{What would be a great fighting choice against e4 for somebody with little time or the desire to study vast amounts of theory? The Scandinavian Defense! Unlike other openings, you will set the tone of the game, and the plans and maneuvers are easy to remember.   Welcome to the Chessable course The Battle-Tested Scandinavian Defense ! The course has two authors – the mastermind of the analysis is my good friend, Ukrainian top GM Igor Kovalenko (career-high 2700 Elo), who is not only feared for his unwillingness to accept draws but is also widely recognized as one of the world's leading experts of the Scandinavian Defense. I'm Arturs Neiksans, co-author of the course. My job was to serve as a moderator of Igor's analysis and record the videos, thus bringing his analytical knowledge to the English-speaking audience.   The course consists of 18 theoretical chapters and is close to a complete repertoire to meet White's e4 – I'm pretty sure we did not miss any significant continuations. Don't be afraid about the amount – the first three chapters are critical as the fate of the Scandinavian Defense depends on their analysis, but the rest are essentially sidelines.   To enhance your understanding, I also wrote a separate chapter about the most typical pawn structures and another about the typical Scandinavian maneuvers, and annotated many games. About the seriousness of the course, all you need to know is this – armed with some powerful cloud engines, Igor did his absolute best to attempt to destroy the Scandinavian Defense with the White color and even tested it in correspondence chess. He devised so many interesting ways to trick Black that you'd be surprised – but the Scandinavian Defense always held its ground. It only proves that it's a serious weapon at a GM level.} 1... d5 {The Scandinavian Defense, described in the poem Scachs d'Amor , is one of the oldest recorded openings in chess. The first-ever game was played in Valencia around 1475 between Francesc de Castellví i de Vic and Narcís Vinyoles – this may be the first recorded game of modern chess. For a long time, the system has been known as the 'Center Counter Defense'.   The name is said to have come from its adoption by Ludvig and Gustav Collijn, two Swedish brothers who played in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.   Half a century later, the Danish chess legend Bent Larsen started to play it occasionally from the 1960s onwards, and in 1979, he defeated World Champion Anatoly Karpov with it. It increased the defense's popularity, and the name gradually switched to 'Scandinavian Defense'. Over time, our opening has become a redoubtable and respected choice at all levels of play.  The psychological aspect of the Scandinavian is also worth noting – many 1.e4 players view it as a terrible opening and often feel compelled to win at any cost. Additionally, it is very difficult for White to accept a minimal advantage in some lines. As a result, players tend to make unobjective decisions, driven more by ambition than a balanced evaluation of the position. This creates numerous practical opportunities for Black, regardless of whether you're playing at amateur or master’s strength.  Enjoy studying, and happy hunting!} *

