1. e4 d5 {The Scandinavian Defense.} 2. exd5 {White has to take. All the other oddities – common at lower rating levels – are discussed in Chapter 18 .} (2. Nc3 dxe4 3. Nxe4 Nc6 ({(Naturally, Black here has complete freedom. If you're feeling funny, you can continue with} 3... Qd5 {and insist on transposing to the main lines, but there's no need.)}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {, and Black has a great version of the Caro-Kann Tartakower variation, as you will see in Chapter 18 .}) 2... Qxd5 3. Nc3 {The move that you will see in 95% of your games. White attacks the queen and wins a tempo for development.} (3. Nf3 {. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempi for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {. This line also showcases some of the sharp ideas of the Scandinavian Defense.} 4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O O-O-O {. The long castle is a very common maneuver in the Scandinavian Defense. The king is positioned on the opposite flank to have complete freedom on the other side.} 6. h3 h5 $1 {is a standard idea after White has castled short. If White doesn't accept the piece immediately, they will consider it for the next several moves.} 7. hxg4 $4 {. Already a losing move, but it's not very obvious.} hxg4 8. Nh2 {. Black wants to connect the queen with the rook to deliver a mate, but it's impossible to do so immediately.} f5 9. Nxg4 Qf7 $1 {, and the queen will get to the h-file no matter what.} 10. d3 Qg6 $1 11. Nh2 Qh7 12. Bf4 g5 {. White's position is collapsing. Check the Chapter 15 for more variations.}) (3. h3 {. This silly-looking move contains a considerable amount of venom, exactly for accelerated time control games, and it's relatively unknown. No worries: we covered it in depth in Chapter 17 .} e5 {It's probably best to enter the Central opening with the colors reversed, as White has an extra tempo on h3 .} 4. Nf3 Bd7 $1 {. If the queenside knight develops first, avoiding pins with the typical Bb5 is necessary.} 5. Nc3 Qe6 6. Be2 Nc6 7. d4 {White hopes to exploit their minor lead in development, but this means that the position is simplifying. Otherwise, White has no other ideas for fighting for an opening advantage.} Nxd4 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Qxd4 Ne7 $1 {, and Black kicks off the white queen targeting the a7 -square so you can castle the long side. For more details, check Chapter 17 .}) (3. d4 {is pretty similar to 3.Nf3 – White wants a position with d4 - c4 and Nc3 , avoiding the typical Scandinavian counterplay against the pawn on d4 .} Nc6 4. Nf3 e5 {, and Black can't allow White to carry out the plan.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 e4 {. This line is quite forcing – Black is doing alright.} 8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ne7 {. Black easily achieves equality, as seen in Chapter 17 .}) 3... Qa5 {This is the classical line, and surprisingly, the black queen stands well here. When the Scandinavian Defense was invented, the black queen was usually retreated to its starting square. Now, White has many choices, but the strongest ones we cover in the first two chapters.   If you ask Igor, 'Why did you choose the classical line of the Scandinavian Defense and not the others?', he would reply:} ({—} 3... Qa5 {was the main choice of Jacques Mieses, the first true Scandinavian specialist – long before any Scandinavian master or computer endorsed it. It’s the most solid option. If you want me to write a '1.e4 repertoire against rare defenses', I’ll explain why there’s no Qd8 or Qd6 in this course. �}) 4. d4 (4. b4 {is a fun gambit that perhaps works best as a surprise or in faster time controls when a quick initiative is important. However, White should normally not achieve more than compensation for the pawn. You still have to know some precise lines.} Qxb4 5. Rb1 Qd6 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. d4 a6 {, and Black takes care of the b5 -square.} 8. Bd3 g6 9. O-O Bg7 {, and Black is doing well, as seen in Chapter 14 .}) (4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 {. White could try to be tricky and not reveal the placement of the kingside knight – it might go to e2 or f3 , mainly depending on what Black chooses.} a6 $1 {Suddenly, Black changes the course of the game and considers positioning the light-squared bishop on b7 – you can do it if White is slow with their decisions.} 6. Bd2 Qc5 7. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {. As soon as the white knight lands on f3 , you can abandon the ... b5 plan and ruin White's pawn structure on the kingside with a known maneuver.} 8. h3 Qh5 {. Including... a6 allows you to deal with any Nb5 jumps, so it's not a waste of time. Check out Chapter 12 for more variations.}) (4. g3 {. You will often meet players who, instead of ‘punishing’ Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {. If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. d4 Nc6 $1 {. As soon as White plays d4 , you meet it with ... Nc6 .} 9. d5 Ne7 {, and Black achieves equality – this and more lines we analyze more in-depth in Chapter 13 .}) 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bd2 c6 6. Bc4 {. White could delay the development of the kingside knight due to different dynamics. One of the reasons is that the white queen can step out very early!} Bf5 7. Ne4 Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 9. Qf3 $5 {. An interesting gambit – White is harassing the light-squared bishop on f5 , which is one of the lines you'd have to know well.} Bxc2 10. Ne2 Bd6 11. Rc1 Bg6 12. h4 h5 {. Black gets a good game with accurate defense, as seen in Chapter 10 .}) 5... c6 ({And not} 5... Bf5 {now. We will explain why this move order is important here .}) 6. Bc4 (6. Bf4 {is a standalone continuation with considerable venom, so study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, weaknesses could arise in their own camp.} Bf5 7. Ne5 Nbd7 8. Nc4 Qd8 9. Ne3 Be6 $1 {. We have played only nine moves, but the position is relatively unexplored, leading to many interesting opportunities for both sides.} 10. a4 {. The most pragmatic choice for White is to play for space advantage.} g6 11. h3 Bg7 12. a5 b5 {. By doing this, you remove White's access to the c4 -square, but also ... b4 might become useful at some point. There are more details in Chapter 7 .}) (6. Ne5 {. White wants to trick you with the move order and avoid playing Bc4 , at least for now.} Be6 $1 {. This move is a powerful alternative to the more popular 6...Bf5 , it's also the top choice of engines. Black also deals with the delayed Bc4 , which now makes little sense.} 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Bd3 g6 {.} ({We're playing in the spirit of the Alekhine defense: e4 Nf6 e5} 8... Nd5 {d4 d6} 9. Nf3 {dxe5} Ne5 {c6 , followed by 6...g6 , with the bishop developing to g7 and the arising Scandinavian structures.})) {Back to our Scandi line: O-O Bg7 Qe1 O-O . Black has completed the development and is looking for the ... c5 -break, which doesn't work yet for tactical reasons. Chapter 8 provides more details about the variation.} 6... Bf5 7. Ne5 {This move is one of the most principled choices and is covered in chapters #1 and #2 .} (7. Bd2 {. What else can be dangerous if White does not want to jump with the knight to e5 , go for entirely forcing lines, and prove they are ambitions against the Scandinavian Defense with radical play? Of course, it's the poisonous plan with Qe2 and O-O-O . We analyze this setup in Chapter 3 .} Nbd7 $1 {Black deals with the Ne5 possibility and ensures that the Nd5 jump is not dangerous.} 8. Qe2 Qc7 $1 {. It is the perfect moment to retreat; White's d5 push is already becoming problematic.} 9. O-O-O e6 {. This setup is the second most important position of the Scandinavian Defense and, in the pre-engine era, was labeled as the most critical choice.   White has two standalone plans: 1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns. 2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black. We analyze everything in Chapter 3 .}) 7... e6 8. g4 {This push is one of the most important lines of Scandinavian Defense, and you must know it by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 $4 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {, and Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {We look at all the critical tries for White in chapters #1 and #2 .    Welcome to the Scandinavian world!} *

