1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. d4 {It is surprising but not something you should be afraid of – this is a dubious gambit, and you have many excellent ways to get a great game. Let's stick to one choice.} dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 g6 {Fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 is a recurring theme in the Scandinavian Defense, but not always. Here, you're indirectly targeting the white pawn on d4 and building an extra layer of defense around your king.} 6. Bg5 Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O c6 {White doesn't have sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn, while Black is planning to get counterplay on the queenside.} *

