1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. e5 {Either your opponent is completely panicking against the Scandinavian Defense, or they mouse-slipped the exd5 move.} c5 3. c3 Nc6 4. d4 a6 ({This idea is similar to the Caro-Kann Defense e4 c6} 4... cxd4 {d5 e5 a6} 5. Nf3 Bg4 {, followed by ... c6 – c5 and ... Nb8 – c6 , but with an extra tempo for Black. The idea is that since we’re playing to pressure the d4 -pawn and eventually capture e5 , the knight on c6 is more effective than White’s potentially bad bishop.   Meanwhile, Black develops his own bishop in one move to target the strongest defender of White’s center – the king’s knight. Therefore, Black’s main plan is to preserve the knight from exchange and hand the move over to White, who often lacks a harmonious setup that prevents Black’s ideas.}) 5. Nf3 Bg4 {You're playing the position as a tremendous French Defense, not committing to a bad light-squared bishop on c8 . Once it is out, secure the center with ... e6 .} *

