1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nf3 ({This move is the most serious alternative to} 3. Nc3 {. White wants to play c4 and only then continue with Nc3 , thus forming a strong pawn center. Of course, there's also a fair chance your opponent will randomly develop the kingside knight first, but they don't know any opening theory.}) 3... Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 {You start so aggressively to talk White out of playing d4 . If you succeed and they do something else, you can castle long and push ... e5 yourself, effectively fighting for advantage.} 5. h3 {Sometimes, White wants to include this move so that you automatically retreat to h5 and then, in some lines, make you suffer, but here, Black has a concrete solution to avoid the suffering.} Bxf3 6. Bxf3 Qe6+ 7. Qe2 Nd4 {White has the bishop pair, but it's about to change.} 8. Qxe6 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 fxe6 {The position is as equal as it gets. You can improvise with the development of your knight but refrain from playing ... e5 to block your bishop.} *

