1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nf3 ({This move is the most serious alternative to} 3. Nc3 {. White wants to play c4 and only then continue with Nc3 , thus forming a strong pawn center. Of course, there's also a fair chance your opponent will randomly develop the kingside knight first, but they don't know any opening theory.}) 3... Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 {You start so aggressively to talk White out of playing d4 . If you succeed and they do something else, you can castle long and push ... e5 yourself, effectively fighting for advantage.} 5. O-O O-O-O 6. h3 h5 {It's a typical sacrifice - keep an eye on it in any position once White has castled short. If White accepts the piece, this will open the h-file you can use to checkmate the white king.} 7. Nc3 Qf5 8. hxg4 {Let's see what happens if White accepts the gift.} ({If} 8. d3 e6 {, Black's attack continues}) 8... hxg4 9. Nh2 e6 10. Bxg4 Qg6 {Black's idea is to stop White from playing Bh3 – the attack is already decisive.} 11. Re1 Nf6 12. Bf3 Bc5 13. Bxc6 Rxh2 14. Bxb7+ Kb8 15. Qf3 Ng4 {We're sure you will enjoy playing these lines!} 16. Ne4 Bd4 17. d3 Rdh8 18. Kf1 Rxg2 19. Qxg2 ({Of course, if} 19. Kxg2 {, then the punishment is immediate,} Ne3# {.}) 19... Nh2+ 20. Kg1 Nf3+ 21. Kf1 Qxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Nxe1+ 23. Kg1 Nxc2 24. Rb1 Kxb7 {After the dust has settled, White is down a pawn with a ruined pawn structure.} *

