1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nf3 ({This move is the most serious alternative to} 3. Nc3 {. White wants to play c4 and only then continue with Nc3 , thus forming a strong pawn center. Of course, there's also a fair chance your opponent will randomly develop the kingside knight first, but they don't know any opening theory.}) 3... Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 {You start so aggressively to talk White out of playing d4 . If you succeed and they do something else, you can castle long and push ... e5 yourself, effectively fighting for advantage.} 5. O-O O-O-O 6. h3 h5 {It's a typical sacrifice - keep an eye on it in any position once White has castled short. If White accepts the piece, this will open the h-file you can use to checkmate the white king.} 7. c3 Nf6 8. d4 e5 {The bishop on g4 is untouchable as long as you can transfer the queen to the h-file in a few moves.} 9. Be3 Qd7 10. Nxe5 {White can quickly get cold feet - this leads to simplifications.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxe2 13. Rxd8+ Kxd8 14. exf6 gxf6 {With equality.} *

