1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nf3 ({This move is the most serious alternative to} 3. Nc3 {. White wants to play c4 and only then continue with Nc3 , thus forming a strong pawn center. Of course, there's also a fair chance your opponent will randomly develop the kingside knight first, but they don't know any opening theory.}) 3... Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 {You start so aggressively to talk White out of playing d4 . If you succeed and they do something else, you can castle long and push ... e5 yourself, effectively fighting for advantage.} 5. d4 {The main move.} O-O-O 6. Be3 e5 7. c4 {This maneuver to push d5 on the next move makes the most sense once Black has committed to ... e5 , preventing you from targeting the d5 -pawn.} Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Bb4 {It is the most straightforward choice, solid, and easy to understand with any time control.} ({The alternative is} 8... Qa6 {, which leads to some very complex lines.}) 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 11. Nc3 Qa6 12. Be2 ({If} 12. b3 {then} Qa5 $1 {, and White will have problems getting rid of the annoying bishop on b4 .}) 12... Nf6 13. O-O Bxc3 {Now, you should know the following trick.} 14. Bxc3 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 Rxd5 {White loses a pawn but still retains reasonable compensation.} 16. Rfe1 Rd7 17. Qxe5 Qxc4 18. Qg3 {White will win back the lost pawn, leading to an equal heavy-piece endgame.} Rhd8 19. Qxg7 Ne4 20. Qxh7 Nxc3 21. bxc3 Qxc3 {Both sides have chances to organize two connected passed pawns – the stronger player will win.} *

