1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. d4 {White wants to trick you and play c4 with Nc3 next, gaining a powerful pawn center. Compared with the immediate Nc3 , the d4 -pawn could be much harder to target in this scenario. You want to respond with ... e5 , but better include ... Nc6 first.} Nc6 4. Nf3 e5 5. Nc3 Bb4 {By doing this, Black keeps the queen in the center. If, at any moment, White takes on e5 , White will lose the opportunity to castle.} 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 e4 {That's why it's important to include ... Nc6 vs Nf3 - Black wins a critical tempo.} 8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ne7 {The position is balanced – Black has multiple ways to maintain equality.} *

