1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. h3 {A rare move that might produce interesting results in blitz games - White stops ... Bg4 ideas, and after Black's ... Bf5 , at some point later, reserves the option to continue with g4 and Bg2 . Instead of a typical Scandinavian Defense here, it is best to transpose to the Central opening.} e5 4. Nc3 Qe6 5. Nf3 Bd7 {The big idea is to delay ... Nc6 ; otherwise, White's Bb5 with immediate pressure on the e5 -pawn will be very unpleasant.} 6. Be2 Nc6 7. O-O O-O-O 8. Re1 f6 {The white pawn on h3 gives Black a good chance to start a kingside pawn assault with ... h5 and ... g5 - g4 .} *

