1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nc3 {Most players will choose this move because it develops a knight and hits the queen.} Qa5 {Objectively, this is the most substantial and logical retreat with the queen. White here has many options.} 4. Bc4 {The light-squared bishop typically goes here. White might be toying with delaying the d4 push or even landing the pawn on d3 to avoid the typical Scandinavian Defense counterplay against it.} Nf6 5. Nf3 {If White keeps delaying the d4 move, position the light-squared bishop on f5 . The tempting ... Bg4 always runs into h3 - g4 plans.} Bf5 6. O-O e6 {Black wants to continue with ... Nbd7 . There's no need to include ... c6 to secure an escape route for the black queen because nobody is attacking it.} 7. d3 Nbd7 8. Bd2 Qb6 9. Be3 Qa5 10. Bd2 Qb6 {Black can already opt to repeat, as seen in the game Pavel Ponkratov (2582) – Shakhriyar Mamedyarov (2747) Casablanca Mohammed op 4th 2023.} *

