1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nc3 {Most players will choose this move because it develops a knight and hits the queen.} Qa5 {Objectively, this is the most substantial and logical retreat with the queen. White here has many options.} 4. Bc4 {The light-squared bishop typically goes here. White might be toying with delaying the d4 push or even landing the pawn on d3 to avoid the typical Scandinavian Defense counterplay against it.} Nf6 5. d3 a6 ({Better than the very tempting} 5... Bg4 {.}) 6. Bd2 Qc5 7. Be3 Qc6 8. Nf3 e6 {As it turns out, the black queen on c6 stands quite well, and after you develop the light-squared bishop on b7 , this forms a powerful battery. The white bishop on c4 doesn't do much and slows White's plan with d3 - d4 - d5 . It also means White can't exploit their lead in development.} 9. a4 b6 {The game remains complex, but White doesn't have the initiative. White is ahead of Black in development, but Black’s bishops are about to reach more advantageous positions. In contrast, White will soon need to transfer their pieces to other areas, which means losing this temporary visual impression of development. Black’s advantage lies in the fact that their pieces will coordinate smoothly, unlike White’s, which may get in each other’s way. Perhaps White should consider sacrifices – but that’s a question for the middlegame.} *

