1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nc3 {Most players will choose this move because it develops a knight and hits the queen.} Qa5 {Objectively, this is the most substantial and logical retreat with the queen. White here has many options.} 4. d4 {The principal choice – White fights for the center.} Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Why do we want to start precisely with} 5... c6 {and not Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 {and ... Bb4 ideas?}) ({First, if White wants to reach the most critical positions against the Scandinavian Defense, they can still meet} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {and so on.}) ({Second, suddenly, White has extra ideas to meet} 5... Bf5 6. Z0 {-- with a future h4 or g4 .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 variation, but you can still be forced to go there if White plays} 6. Bd2 c6 7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 {, and avoiding the principal continuation for Black is more than risky.}) ({That's why we're going for} 5... c6 {. You will have to learn all the main lines anyway, and with this move order, you can meet} 6. Ne5 {with} Be6 {, which is a standalone continuation. Most importantly, the fewer variations for you to study, the fewer chances for your opponents to trick you with the variations and move orders!}) 6. Bf4 {This setup is tricky. White intends to harass your queen with the Ne5 - c4 maneuver and then reposition the knight on e3 , where it's oddly standing great.} Bf5 7. Ne5 Nbd7 ({No need to test if} 7... e6 $2 {works here. It doesn't.} 8. g4 {. No surprises here.} Bg6 9. h4 Nd5 {. Black desperately tries to stay in the game.} ({(} 9... Nbd7 10. Nc4 Qd8 11. h5 {)}) 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Bb4 12. Rh3 $1 {. The h5 push threat remains, and Black has major problems finding a safe place for the light-squared bishop.} Nd7 13. Nxd7 Kxd7 14. h5 Be4 15. Qd2 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Bd5 17. Re3 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 {. To save the bishop, Black will have to give up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 Qd8 9. Ne3 Be6 {It's very tempting to retreat on g6 automatically, but in this line, the e6 -square is the perfect place for the light-squared bishop as it limits the white bishop's activity and slows White's d5 push.} 10. a4 {White plays for space advantage.} g6 11. h3 Bg7 12. a5 b5 {Black has enough counterplay.} 13. Be2 b4 14. Na4 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. O-O e5 17. dxe5 O-O {With this move order, Black completely opens the center, and because of the piece play, the dynamic resources are enough to keep the balance.} *

