chance the position will transpose to the main lines if White now plays Bc4 , but there are other tricks as well.} 7. Ne4 Qd5 {This is stronger than the traditional retreat to c7 .} 8. Nc5 {Probably the strongest move.} b6 9. Nd3 e6 10. c4 Qd8 11. Nde5 Bd6 {Black's next moves are easy, but for White, it makes perfect sense to attempt to exploit the weakened h1 - a8 diagonal.} 12. g3 Qc7 13. Bg2 Nbd7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. O-O Rd8 {This move is a countermeasure against White's Ne5 , which most likely will be incoming soon.} 16. Qe2 h6 17. Rfd1 Bc2 {With this move, Black forces the white rook to a worse square.} 18. Re1 Be4 19. Bc3 {Here are two other scenarios:} ({A.} 19. Rad1 Qb7 20. g4 ({(} 20. b4 O-O 21. Bc3 Rfe8 {)}) 20... c5 21. d5 exd5 22. Nh4 O-O 23. g5 Ne8 $1 {. An accurate move that deprives White of any hope of an advantage.}) ({B.} 19. Bc3 Qb7 20. Bh3 O-O 21. Nd2 Bg6 22. Bg2 a5 $1 23. Qf3 Rc8 24. c5 bxc5 25. Nc4 Bc7 26. dxc5 Nd5 27. Bd4 Rcd8) 19... Qb7 {Black is solid, albeit White does retain some advantage. Black's plan is to castle kingside and prepare ... c6 - c5 – but not immediately, in order to avoid tactical pitfalls White's problem is that after b2 - b4 , Black responds with ... b6 - b5 , gaining control of the important d5 -square.} *

