 reveal their intentions.} Qc7 {The perfect moment to retreat - even if White was not threatening with the Nd5 jump, the d5 push and the capture with the knight is something you never want to miss as well. Don't even look at the pawn on c2 - you have no time for that.} 9. O-O-O e6 {White has two ideas: either play Ne5 and aim for the g4 push and an aggressive kingside attack or play positionally with Nh4 and get a bishop pair for long-term pressure.} 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 {A tempting move, but it might not be the best.} hxg6 {Because of the attack on the h2 -pawn, Black wins a critical tempo.} 12. h4 b5 {A very important move.} 13. Bb3 Nb6 {Black wants to advance on the queenside. With this game plan, Black should keep the king in the center for as long as possible, preserving both castling options. In fact, the king will likely remain in the center for the entire game. We recommend studying the games Grischuk – Kovalenko or Kononenko – Kovalenko , which illustrate the black king's style of play.} *

