1. e4 d5 ({The champion of rare continuations!  The Scandinavian Defense is stronger than} 1... Nf6 {, g6 , Nc6 , and some other fun lines.   In this Quickstarter, we will focus only on the most popular Scandinavian lines, so you can go out and start crushing souls after just one hour of studying the theory.   Once you're ready to dive deeper, begin with the chapters #1 & #2 .}) 2. exd5 {The main move - White wants to punish you for bringing out the queen so early and win some tempos.} Qxd5 3. Nc3 {Most players will choose this move because it develops a knight and hits the queen.} Qa5 {Objectively, this is the most substantial and logical retreat with the queen. White here has many options.} 4. d4 {The principal choice – White fights for the center.} Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Why do we want to start precisely with} 5... c6 {and not Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 {and ... Bb4 ideas?}) ({First, if White wants to reach the most critical positions against the Scandinavian Defense, they can still meet} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {and so on.}) ({Second, suddenly, White has extra ideas to meet} 5... Bf5 6. Z0 {-- with a future h4 or g4 .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 variation, but you can still be forced to go there if White plays} 6. Bd2 c6 7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 {, and avoiding the principal continuation for Black is more than risky.}) ({That's why we're going for} 5... c6 {. You will have to learn all the main lines anyway, and with this move order, you can meet} 6. Ne5 {with} Be6 {, which is a standalone continuation. Most importantly, the fewer variations for you to study, the fewer chances for your opponents to trick you with the variations and move orders!}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 {This is the principal line – you want to know these variations well.} e6 8. g4 {Anything else is not dangerous.} Bg6 9. h4 {White wants to provoke Black into pushing the h-pawn to save their light-squared bishop. Don't fall into the pitfall: it would permanently ruin your pawn structure.} Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {This is a well-known position – now White has some choices.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 {What's the first thing you should remember for Black? First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 - Bc7 and look for the e5 break in the center. Black can castle both ways, depending on the situation.} Bd6 15. Bd2 {According to engines, this is the strongest move, but it won't be self-evident for an unsuspecting player.} Qb6 16. c3 O-O {Accepting the b2 -pawn is dangerous, but you can revisit this idea later. White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 and going after the white king. If White attempts to squeeze Black with f4 , you can reroute your knight to e4 , even if it means a pawn sacrifice. Finally, there's the classical ... a6 - b5  Carlsbad structure idea.} 17. f4 Nf6 18. Qe2 Ne4 {A crucial plan; otherwise, you will end up with no counterplay.} 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Qxe4 Qxb2 {There will be similar moments when also ... f5 generates Black counterplay, sometimes involving a second pawn sacrifice on e6 .} 21. Rfd1 b5 {Black is doing well. Black's strategy consists more of putting pressure on the opponent's weaknesses, and White's game consists of using space.} *

