: it would permanently ruin your pawn structure.} Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {This is a well-known position – now White has some choices.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 {What's the first thing you should remember for Black? First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 - Bc7 and look for the e5 break in the center. Black can castle both ways, depending on the situation.} Bd6 15. Bd2 {According to engines, this is the strongest move, but it won't be self-evident for an unsuspecting player.} Qb6 16. c3 O-O {Accepting the b2 -pawn is dangerous, but you can revisit this idea later. White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 and going after the white king. If White attempts to squeeze Black with f4 , you can reroute your knight to e4 , even if it means a pawn sacrifice. Finally, there's the classical ... a6 - b5  Carlsbad structure idea.} 17. h6 g6 18. Qf3 Bc7 {Exactly this move order! Now you're threatening to take the pawn on b2 for real since the queen is ready to retreat to d6 and form a battery. Also, Black should remember the Bb5 plan – you should always protect the f6 -square.} 19. a4 {Not only threatening a5 but more importantly Bb5} Rae8 {Black should prepare the ... e5 push.} 20. Bb5 Qd6 {Black is in time to defend the knight and create their own threats.} 21. Rfe1 f5 22. g5 Rf7 {With an equal position.} *

