{This is one of the most famous pawn structures of the Scandinavian Defense, which also arises in the Caro-Kann. White has the only pawn in the center, but Black can counter it.    Black's typical ideas are :    1) Go for the ... c5 break. The idea is to destroy White's pawn center and establish a pawn majority on the kingside. This has to be done with caution, especially if White has the bishop pair and a strong light-squared bishop controlling the h1 - a8 diagonal.   2) The ... e5 push is the less popular choice because it results in a fully symmetrical pawn structure. It might be better than ... c5 if White has a bishop pair with a strong light-squared bishop.} 1... g7-g6 ({The plan} 1... b7-b5 {is particularly effective when White has castled long – then Black wants to position their knight from either f6 or a6 to d5 and aggressively push forward the queenside pawns. If White has a pawn on either a3 or c3 , it makes the breakthrough easier. You rarely want to play ... b5 if White has castled short or hasn't castled long just yet.}) 2. g2-g3 {White typically tries to position their kingside pawns on g3 and h4 . Usually, the white king has already castled long, and White is considering the h4 - h5 break to open the h-file. This idea is particularly effective if Black has earlier committed to ... hxg6 since then, you can't easily stop White's h5 push. Be careful about castling short too early.} (2. f2-f4 {— There will be moments when White will castle short and commit to f4 – this might be a future weakness. Now, opening the center with ... c5 might expose the white king on g1 , but the white pawn on f4 will constantly require support.}) (2. c2-c4 {— Another typical sub-structure – White's center can be strong but can also become a target. Consider doubling the rooks on the d-file, position the bishop on f6 or the queen on b6 .} b7-b5 {. This can be an effective weapon if Black has the knight on a6 or c7 . By removing the white pawn from controlling the d5 -square, Black can win a fantastic outpost on d5 for the knight or any other piece.} 3. b2-b3 b5xc4 4. b3xc4 c6-c5 5. d4xc5 {. Black might want to enter such pawn structures, but it depends on what pieces are on the board. White seemingly has a passed c-pawn, but in reality, it's three pawn islands vs two, and for Black, it's easier to play, especially with the a-pawns on the board.}) *

