[GameId "2174210255672030"]

{This pawn structure can frequently appear in the Scandinavian Defense – also with the f6 -pawn standing on f5 , having committed to ... exf5 where your bishop stood. The Tartakower pawn structure comes from a popular line in the Caro-Kann – e4 c6 d4 d5 Nc3 dxe4 Nxe4 Nf6 Nxf6+ exf6 . Typically, White enjoys a slightly better pawn structure and would love to go to a pawn endgame. Then, for White, it's much easier to organize a passed pawn on the queenside while it will block your attempts on the kingside. However, it's easier said than done since Black will always keep at least a few pieces on the board, and then the pawn majority on the queenside is quite irrelevant. The black king mostly will be castled short since the pawn majority allows you to build a better defensive setup.    Let's discuss a few scenarios :    1) White has castled the short side – this means a positional game. You can improve your kingside to better control the squares with ... g6 and ... f5 , or you can consider going aggressive with ... g5 and launching an unexpected kingside attack. For this, you will need quite a few pieces, but if you have two bishops on e6 and d6 and the white knight stands on f3 , a well-timed ... g5 might be an unpleasant surprise to your opponent! In this scenario, you rarely touch the queenside pawns, except for the ... c5 push, perhaps.   2) White has castled the queenside – with your king on the kingside, you will typically look for a queenside pawn minority attack. This will involve pushing the queenside pawns with ... b5 and ... a5 , but the d5 -square is a perfect outpost for a knight. On the kingside be careful playing ... g6 since White will be ready to push h4 - h5 .} 1... g7-g6 2. c2-c4 {This can be a very committal move for White because now the pawn on d4 can become a target by doubling the rooks on the d-file or a typical ... Ne6 . You can fight for the d5 -square with ... b5 and then position on d5 a minor piece.} f6-f5 3. d4-d5 c6xd5 4. c4xd5 {White sometimes wrongly assumes this middlegame position is an improvement, but the d5 -pawn is often difficult to support. Ideally, you'd like to block the d-pawn on d6 with a minor piece and use your pawn majority at the kingside, perhaps for a kingside attack. In practice, the d5 -pawn often falls.} *

