{One of the most famous Carlsbad structures is a frequent guest in many chess openings, but in the Scandinavian Defense, it's mainly present in the first two main chapters. It can happen when you land a minor piece on d5 in the classical pawn structure (could be a knight or a bishop and after a trade), Black almost always recaptures with the c-pawn to keep the e-file closed.    Let's discuss some scenarios :    1) In theory, the most famous idea for both sides is to play the pawn minority attack. Black wants to push ... b5 - b4 and eventually capture on c3 , creating for White more pawn islands and also targets to attack. For White, it's the kingside attack, which the light-squared bishop on d3 often fuels. However, at least in the first chapter, it will rarely work because White will have very far-advanced kingside pawns, and you won't have time to focus on the queenside. Hence, the second scenario.   2) You go for the ... e5 break. This, in particular, is effective when White has advanced the kingside pawns to h5 and g4 (see this line in Chapter 2), but Black is threatening to build a battery of a queen and bishop on d6 and c7 . The game's dynamics require Black to bother the white king and be aggressive.   3) There might be some unusual scenarios for the Carlsbad structure, like White pushing c4 . Normally, this is not great for White since it creates a weak pawn on d4 , but it depends on what pieces are on the board and where Black has positioned the king. If Black has castled short and White has a strong bishop pair, opening up the position with c4 makes a lot of sense.} 1... b7-b5 2. c2-c3 a7-a5 3. a2-a3 b5-b4 4. a3xb4 a5xb4 5. g2-g3 b4xc3 6. b2xc3 {This is Black's dream setup – creating a weakness on c3 to target. As you can see, Black has just one pawn island (a connected chain of pawns), while White has two. In theory, the fewer you have, the better.} *

