12... b5 {Remember this maneuver! This move will be your key idea to organize counterplay on the queenside. Again, it won't work if the white bishop is already on b3 – you'll get a rude awakening with White's d5 push.} 13. Bd3 {It seems that with the bishop on b3 , White only provokes the advancement of Black's queenside pawns.} b4 ({Another accurate move and much stronger than the very tempting} 13... a5 {. If the knight now jumps to a4 , you will proceed with ... Qa5 and ... Nb6 .}) 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bf3 Rb8 {Now it's time to push forward the a-pawn.} *

