16... Rd7 {Once you've castled long, a common idea is to double the rooks on the d-file and target White's d4 -pawn. That's why White sometimes might regret having pushed c4 earlier – then the pawn on d4 might lose some vital support.} 17. Kb1 Rhd8 18. Bf4 Bd6 19. Bc1 Bf8 20. Ne2 c5 {Ultimately, it's all about the counterplay – even if White has the bishop pair and the position is opening up, you can't risk sitting in a passive position at the mercy of your opponent.} *

