8... Be6 {This maneuver is very typical if White for some reason has delayed the Bc4 move. Black's center feels secure, but the dark-squared bishop joins the game via the g7 -square.} (8... Bh5 $2 {. The bishop here is not that well positioned. There might be some exceptions, notably when White has already committed to Bd3 .} 9. g4 Bg6 10. f4 {. Black has huge problems and having the queen on a5 for a potential discovered attack doesn't help.}) 9. f4 g6 {The white knight on h4 stands quite weird.} *

