10... Bxf3 {The most challenging thing to consider in any opening is to move the same piece twice, especially if you've moved it just before. However, chess is very concrete; sometimes, achieving concrete things and avoiding stubbornness is better. White just played Bd2 , weakening the b2 -pawn.} 11. Qxf3 Qb6 {Suddenly, White has to figure out how to protect the pawns.} 12. Qf4 Be7 {While accepting the b-pawn is dangerous, Black successfully forces the white queen to an awkward square.} 13. O-O-O Nd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {And we transpose to the typical Carlsbad structure.} *

