6... h5 {This motif very often features if White starts with the quiet Nf3 . Black is willing to sacrifice a piece to open the h-file that you can use to checkmate the white king. There are many variations with this pattern, but the core idea remains the same: as long as Black can get the queen to the h-file before White organizes counterplay in the center or on the queenside, White can't accept the gift.} 7. hxg4 ({After} 7. Nc3 Qf5 8. d3 e6 {, White should be getting pretty nervous about the kingside attack.}) 7... hxg4 8. Nh2 {It seems that Black has miscalculated, and the queen can't go to h5 because of Bxg4 , but Black has time.} f5 9. Nxg4 Qf7 10. d3 Qg6 {With White being so slow in the center and on the queenside, Black's attack is already decisive.} *

