6... Bg4 {This tempting move once used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, but now it's obsolete for a good reason. But consider the maneuver later, as you will need it in some lines. Just make sure that your opponent can't respond with the aggressive h3 - g4 .} (6... Bf5 {is the correct move.}) 7. h3 {This is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center but retreating with the bishop might run into even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 {To avoid giving up the bishop, Black is forced to make critical pawn structure weaknesses.} *

