10... Nxe5 {Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines - here, it leads to a disaster. Make sure you understand when you can tolerate the knight on e5 ; when the incoming g4 move is a threat and ...tread carefully.} (10... Bb4 {. The most principled continuation for Black – we're getting ready to take on c3 and then push forward the queenside pawns to ignite a queenside attack.}) 11. dxe5 Nd7 {Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {This position might feel very familiar from other lines, but White's f5 push is unstoppable here.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {White crashes through and has a winning attack.} *

