8... Bg6 {In this position and in some of the next few, ensure you never make moves automatically. Although the bishop often retreats to g6 , here this 'automatic' move is a serious inaccuracy.} (8... Nbd7 {. Black remains alert – not only does White want to trade Black's light-squared bishop, but they also aim to push f5 . Black can capture on f5 with the queen.}) (8... Bg4 $6 {. In some other scenarios, this could be a great resource, but here, it backfires.} 9. f3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. f4 {, and Black has no satisfactory response to White's pawn assault.}) 9. f4 Be7 ({Or} 9... Nbd7 {, it doesn't change much.}) 10. f5 exf5 11. Qe2 {White keeps the black king in the center. Together with the Nxf5 idea at the right moment, White secures a large advantage.} *

