3... Nf6 {This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is inaccurate. The move is not a mistake but a significant inaccuracy since you don't get your typical Scandinavian Defense, but all you get is suffering.} (3... Bg4 {. Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} 4. Be2 Nc6 {. If White will now continue with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it.}) 4. d4 {Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for the immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 - b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .} *

