7... h5 {Here, this tactical motif does not work since the black queen already is on d7 and can't easily make it to the h-file.} (7... Bxf3 {is a big decision - many players would automatically retreat with the bishop on h5 to keep some tension and, most importantly, the bishop pair. However, this position once again is concrete, and after the bishop trade, it's a little easier for Black to organize the kingside assault.} 8. Bxf3 Nf6 {. Because of the queenside knight already standing on c3 , White can't reach the desired c3 - d4 setup.} 9. d3 Rg8 {. There's the idea: Black wants to open the kingside by rushing forward with the g-pawn. This idea works if White cannot grab the center or outrun you at the queenside.}) 8. hxg4 hxg4 9. Ng5 Nh6 10. d4 Nxd4 11. Nb5 {White has excellent winning chances.} *

