ough the black king is walking, it feels pretty safe on d7 , and White can't open the position quickly.} 12. c3 Bd6 13. O-O h5 {Typical maneuver to launch a kingside attack.} 14. Re1 Qh4 {Black provokes White to create targets at the kingside so that it's easier to open it for an attack.} 15. g3 Qg4 16. f3 Qg6 17. Be3 {Now Black can immediately force a draw or make an artificial long castle with ... Rd8 and ... Kc8 .} Bxg3 18. hxg3 Qxg3+ 19. Kf1 (19. Kh1 Qh3+ {is also a draw.}) 19... b5 {The simplest way to secure the draw.} 20. Bb3 Bd3+ 21. Qxd3 ({With} 21. Re2 $2 {, White can't continue the game without risking losing.} Qxf3+ 22. Ke1 Qxe2+ 23. Qxe2 Bxe2 24. Kxe2 f6 {. Even though White has two bishops for the rook, Black's passed pawns on the kingside are simply rolling forward.}) 21... Qxf3+ {With a perpetual check – White can't cover from the checks with the bishop.} *

