ormationals of this chapter, you will recognize a familiar problem with the bishop on g6 while the white knight stands on e5 .}) 11. dxe5 Ne4 12. Nxf5 exf5 13. Qe2 {White can't avoid the incoming trades since ... Qa5 + would lead White to lose the e5 -pawn.} Qxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Nxd2 15. Kxd2 Rd8+ 16. Ke2 Bc5 17. c3 Ke7 {There's no need to castle since we're already in a dead-drawn endgame, and the king belongs in the center.} *

