1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do. The move} (6... Bg4 $6 {, which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss. The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. O-O {After this standard move, White initiative is a plain zero, not even talking about the typical engine 'micro plus'.} Nbd7 9. Re1 {It's pretty impressive how White has to be careful not to lose on the spot after this automatic move.} Nxe5 10. Rxe5 Qb4 11. Bb3 O-O-O {The white pawn on d4 is under fire, and the rook on e5 is not where it belongs.} 12. Ne2 Ng4 {The rook is trapped!} 13. Rxf5 (13. c3 Qd6) 13... exf5 14. h3 Nf6 15. Bxf7 {White has a pawn for the lost exchange, a questionable compensation.} Qe7 16. Bb3 g6 17. Nf4 Bh6 {Black is much better.} ({Here's how the game might continue next: Ne6 Bxc1 Nxd8 Bxb2 Nxc6 bxc6 Rb1 . White might consider going for a desperate attack. Ba3 Ba4} 17... Qe4 18. Qf1 Bd6 19. Qa6 Kd7 {. So far, Black's moves are easy.} 20. d5 $5 Ke7 $1 {. Black already has an extra piece; there is no need to add more fuel to White's temporary initiative.} 21. Qxa7 Kf8 22. dxc6 Qe7 23. Qd4 Kg7 {Rb7 Bc7 . The complications have ended, and Black keeps the extra piece – White's scattered three pawns are not enough to compensate for it.}) *

