1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. O-O {After this standard move, White initiative is a plain zero, not even talking about the typical engine 'micro plus'.} Nbd7 9. Re1 {It's pretty impressive how White has to be careful not to lose on the spot after this automatic move.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Qe2 Bc5 {Black's initiative develops itself.} 12. Nd1 O-O-O 13. c3 {The only move for White.} (13. h3 {allows Black to win on the spot.} Rxd1 14. Rxd1 Nxf2 15. Rf1 Ne4+ 16. Kh2 Bd4 $1 {Due to the dark square weaknesses, White can't avoid losing more material.} 17. Bd3 Bxe5+ 18. Bf4 Bxf4+ 19. Rxf4 Qc7 $1 {. The final touch.} 20. g3 Nxg3 $1 21. Kxg3 g5 {, White can safely resign.}) 13... Bb6 {This is stronger than the immediate capture on d1 . There are so many threats - most likely, your opponent will collapse.} 14. Bf4 Rxd1 15. Rexd1 Nxf2 16. Rf1 {The best chance for White.} (16. Rd4 {is not an improvement for the opponent, because after,} Ne4 17. Kh1 Bxd4 18. cxd4 h5 {, and we have an extra pawn and the compensation for it.}) 16... Bg4 17. Qc2 Bd1 {The white queen has nowhere to go to avoid the discovered check; thus, White has to give up the extra material.} 18. Raxd1 Nxd1+ 19. Kh1 {White is close to escaping, but Black can still cause some problems.} Nf2+ 20. Rxf2 Qc5 {Very annoying for White!} 21. Bxe6+ fxe6 22. Bg3 Rd8 {Even though there's a material balance on the board, White's position is difficult.} *

