1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. O-O {After this standard move, White initiative is a plain zero, not even talking about the typical engine 'micro plus'.} Nbd7 9. f4 Rd8 {Black is threatening to destroy White's center with a simple tactic.} 10. Ne2 Bg6 {An improvement compared to some previous suggestions.} ({You can also choose the continuation} 10... Be7 {, as suggested in previous Chessable Scandinavian courses.} 11. c3 O-O 12. Ng3 Bg6 {, Black has achieved a complex game with equal chances.}) 11. c3 Bd6 {The difference is that we'll be positioning the dark-squared bishop on d6 for a more active role.} 12. Qe1 O-O 13. Ng3 Qc7 {Now you can see the difference between positioning the bishop either on e7 or d6 – Black is causing trouble on the b8 - h2 diagonal. White's plan to push f4 - f5 probably won't work, but Black is ready to push ... c5 .} *

