1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. O-O {After this standard move, White initiative is a plain zero, not even talking about the typical engine 'micro plus'.} Nbd7 9. Qe2 {Now that White has protected the knight on e5 , never miss the g4 and f4 push, even though the white king has castled short.} Be7 {Now White's g4 push does not work because of the capture on e5 . Black reserves the opportunity to castle both ways, but for the long castle, the trade on e5 is inevitable.} ({The move} 9... Bd6 {here is a little too ambitious.} 10. g4 Bg6 11. f4 {. White is just better.}) 10. h3 {White's intentions are very clear.} (10. Nxd7 {. Now Black's game is very simple.} Nxd7 11. Ne4 Qc7 12. c3 O-O {. With an equal position – castling long here feels a little adventurous but is possible.}) 10... Nxe5 ({This trade is widespread for the Scandinavian Defense – Black could also explore the logical} 10... Bg6 {.}) 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. g4 {Choice of the engines.} ({After} 12. f4 Nb6 13. Bb3 h5 {, Black makes sure White can't play g4 anymore without seriously weakening their own king.} 14. Ne4 O-O-O {, with equal chances.}) 12... Bg6 13. f4 Bxc2 {An important trick to know.} 14. Be3 {White blunders a pawn but keeps playing to keep the black bishop trapped on c2 .} Nb6 15. Bxb6 {The critical try.} Qxb6+ 16. Kh2 h5 {Albeit White wins the piece, ther position looks very dangerous.} 17. Qxc2 hxg4 18. Kg2 Rxh3 19. Rad1 {Preventing Black from castling long.} Qe3 {With at least a perpetual check.} ({After} 19... Qf2+ {Rh2+ Kxh2 Qh3+ Kg1 , Black has two options: a. Bc5 Qxc5 Qg3+ Kh1 Qh3+= b. g3 Qg2 Bc5+ Rf2 Bxf2+ Kf1 Qg4 Ne2 Rd8 Rxd8+ Kxd8= Black has three pawns for a knight, and there are no problems at all.}) *

