the trade on e5 is inevitable.} ({The move} 9... Bd6 {here is a little too ambitious.} 10. g4 Bg6 11. f4 {. White is just better.}) 10. Bb3 {A sneaky move - be careful when your opponent is seemingly waiting for something. White prepares the g4 push and removes the bishop on c4 from the equation.} Nxe5 {Simple and good.} (10... O-O $4 {. As a rule of thumb – never fall for 'automatic' moves and always keep a close eye on the g4 push .} 11. g4 Bg6 12. h4 {. White is winning.}) 11. dxe5 Nd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 {Now we've reached a typical pawn structure from the French defense / Caro-Kann where Black has no weaknesses.} 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Ba4+ Kf8 15. Bb5 h5 {Everyone who has ever seen games from the closed Caro-Kann will understand how difficult it for White is to exploit the placement of the black king on f8 , while Black's strategic ideas are pretty clear.} *

