1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. Bd2 Nbd7 10. Qe2 Bb4 {White's ideas are more dangerous if he's not mixing several plans into one. It is one of those moments – White starts to attack the black bishop, but then decides to play in the center. Now, it's White who will have to fight for equality.} 11. O-O-O Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd2+ {The more trades, the more obvious the weaknesses in White's pawn structure.} 14. Rxd2 cxd5 15. Bb5+ (15. Bb3 $2 h5 {, and Black is better due to the awkward White's pawn formation.}) 15... Kf8 {Don't fear losing the option to castle – the king feels pretty safe on f8 .} 16. Kb1 h5 {Black finds a creative way to bring the kingside rook into the game.} 17. f3 Rc8 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Rc4 {Objectively equal, but it feels like Black's game is easier.} *

