1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 {It's well known for a long time that this is the continuation that promises White the best chances – White attempts to exploit the vulnerable positioning of our light-squared bishop. However, we will attempt to trick our opponent in a complex game.} (9. Nxg6 $6 hxg6 {, and Black doesn't have any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 $4 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. Rh3 {This older move doesn't promise White anything special.} Bg2 {Before positioning the bishop on d5 , it turns out that forcing the white rook to e3 or g3 is useful.} (12... Bd5 {. If you retreat to d5 immediately, there's a drawback.} 13. Bd3 O-O-O 14. Bd2 {. Black doesn't have the tempo to attack the white rook.}) 13. Rg3 {Probably, most people will play this move without thinking since it comes with a tempo.} Bd5 14. Bxd5 (14. Bd3 Bd6 {, and now the white rook is under attack, which gives Black an important tempo for development.}) 14... cxd5 {White here can easily get worse – the white king on the kingside won't feel safe, but the queenside belongs to Black.} 15. Bd2 Rc8 16. Qe2 ({The rerouting move} 16. Ne2 {doesn't promise White anything. After} Qb6 17. Rb3 Qa6 {, Black is just better, mainly due to the king's safety.}) 16... Be7 17. h6 g6 18. O-O-O {White has castled queenside and secured the king – really?} Nb6 19. Kb1 Nc4 20. Bc1 b5 {Black has the initiative and should be more than fine as long as they don't blunder any counter-ideas with Nxd5 .} *

