ush to expose the black king now would feel quite logical. Black wants to start a swift kingside attack.} (15... Qd8 $6 16. Kg2 $1 {. Unfortunately, Black's ... Qh4 idea here is easily dealt with.}) 16. Kg2 {Probably White needs to include this move sooner than later to protect the kingside pawns better and avoid surprises on h4 or h2 .} Rde8 17. Bd2 Qd8 {Just in time retreating from the incoming c4 push. It is one of those moments where, for White, it's not so easy to play - Black's moves are easier. Think about playing next ... Kb6 , ... g6 , ... e5 or ... Qh4 .} 18. f4 {White attempts to squeeze Black, but there's no turning back after this.} Bc7 {Black starts to rearrange the pieces, bring the king to b8 and eventually land the knight on e4 . The move order may not matter much, but look at the final position.} 19. a4 Kb8 20. b4 g6 21. h6 {Of course, White should keep the kingside closed.} Nb6 22. Bb5 Nc4 23. Bxe8 Rxe8 {Black has more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed exchange.} *

