1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 {It's well known for a long time that this is the continuation that promises White the best chances – White attempts to exploit the vulnerable positioning of our light-squared bishop. However, we will attempt to trick our opponent in a complex game.} (9. Nxg6 $6 hxg6 {, and Black doesn't have any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 $4 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Qf3 {White can land the queen on this square immediately.} O-O-O {Black returns to the idea that opening the center will underline the weakness of the white king and will Black sufficient counterplay.} 16. Be3 {A smart move – White completes the development and not only re-enables the threat of Qxf7 , but also wants to open the queenside with the b4 push.} Kb8 {A cautious response - you want to start a kingside attack, but ignoring the events on the queenside would be unwise.} 17. b4 {Now this is not so strong.} Qc7 18. c4 dxc4 {The black king is gone from the c-file and White will miss some critical tactical ideas.} *

