ng and will Black sufficient counterplay.} 16. Be3 {A smart move – White completes the development and not only re-enables the threat of Qxf7 , but also wants to open the queenside with the b4 push.} Kb8 {A cautious response – you want to start a kingside attack, but ignoring the events on the queenside would be unwise.} (16... g6 {. This logical move here unfortunately does not work.} 17. b4 $1 ({(} 17. h6 {. One of the games at the highest level several years ago continued this way.} Rhf8 18. a3 f5 19. c4 e5 {. With a double-edged game in Alireza Firouzja (2759) – Magnus Carlsen (2847) Aimchess US Rapid Prelim 2021 . )}) 17... Qa4 {. Black can't risk accepting the pawn.} 18. Qxf7 Rde8 19. c4 {. White is faster with generating threats. 17.c3 . White keeps all options open and plays all over the board again.}) 17. Rfe1 {Now White once again is threatening to take on f7 as in some lines the white king is ready to escape to f1 .} e5 {It's time to strike.} 18. Qxf7 e4 {Black cuts off the white queen's escape route.} 19. Be2 Nf6 {Black threatens to trap the guest.} 20. g5 Rhf8 21. Qxg7 Rd7 22. Qh6 {The critical moment – Black seems to be very close, but how to catch the queen?} Qd8 23. gxf6 Rdf7 {A complicated move to find, so best remember it! White can't escape the corner yet since there's always the Rg8 move.} 24. Bf4 {Only move.} Rg8+ {Start of a forcing sequence.} 25. Kh1 (25. Kf1 {is not the way to run!} Rxf6 26. Bxd6+ Qxd6 27. Qe3 Qh2 28. Bb5 Rg2 {, and Black delivers a mate.}) 25... Rxf6 26. Bxd6+ Qxd6 27. Qe3 Rf4 {Black is attacking with three heavy pieces, White is picking up the only moves.} 28. Qh3 Rxf2 29. Rg1 Rxg1+ 30. Rxg1 Rxe2 {The dust has settled, and we have a balance on the board again.} ({Rg8+ . Here's how the game might continue:} 30... Kc7 31. Rg7+ Kb6 32. Rd7 Rh2+ 33. Kg1 Rxh3 34. Rxd6+ {Kb5 Rxd5+ Kc4 Rd7 Rxh5 . With a drawn endgame where Black visually is still pushing.}) *

