 the white king and will Black sufficient counterplay.} 16. Be3 {A smart move – White completes the development and not only re-enables the threat of Qxf7 , but also wants to open the queenside with the b4 push.} Kb8 {A cautious response - you want to start a kingside attack, but ignoring the events on the queenside would be unwise.} 17. c3 {White keeps all options open and plays all over the board again.} e5 18. Be2 Rhf8 {To protect the f-pawn and push it forward.} 19. b4 Qc7 20. Qxd5 Nb6 {White has won the pawn, but Black is very dynamic.} 21. Qf3 e4 {An amazing concept discovered by the engines. Instead of taking back the pawn on c3 , Black sacrifices a second to increase the pressure.} (21... Qxc3 $2 {is an illustration of why you should never 'automatically' take the pawns – we're fighting for the initiative, and this move hands it to White on the platter.} 22. Rac1 Qb2 23. dxe5 Bxe5 24. Bc5 {. White is strategically winning.}) 22. Qxe4 g6 23. c4 {A fierce fight for the initiative.} f5 24. Qh1 ({The automatic retreat} 24. Qg2 $2 {is a mistake. After} Nxc4 25. Rac1 Nxe3 26. fxe3 Qe7 {, and White is losing due to the hopelessly weak king.}) 24... Bf4 {It is possible to take on c4 , which leads to difficult-to-remember lines. This move is simpler.} 25. Bxf4 Qxf4 26. Qh2 {The position is simplifying.} Rxd4 27. Rad1 Qxh2+ 28. Kxh2 Re4 29. Bd3 Rxg4 {Black has restored the material balance and has equal chances.} *

