ng and will Black sufficient counterplay.} 16. a4 {White should play on the queenside, and one of the key elements to generate some play is aggressively pushing forward the pawns.} e5 {Even though this leads to a more complex fight, it makes sense to study it for a better understanding of the lines, and also, something very similar could happen if White had played to 16... g6 17.h6.} 17. Bb5 {One of the critical ideas – the pawn on d5 is not so easy to defend.} a6 18. Qxd5 Qc7 (18... axb5 {fails tactically. After} 19. Qxd6 bxa4 20. Bd2 Qxd2 21. Rxa4 {, Black is busted .}) 19. Be2 exd4 20. Qxf7 g6 {We can stop our analysis here and assess the position as very complex, where Black has great compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} ({Here's how the game might continue from here:} 20... Qc4 {. Trading off the queens makes perfect sense for White. gxh5} 21. g5 h6 $1 {. A temporary pawn sacrifice. Qxc7+ Kxc7} 22. gxh6 Rde8 23. Bxc4 Ne5 24. Bd5 Ng4 {. With balanced chances; one can't help but wonder how White is not getting mated here.}) *

