point – since White is a little invested in the matters on the kingside, you castle away to the queenside.} 17. a4 {The most fighting continuation, but this is playing for all three results possible.} gxh5 {You want to open the kingside.} 18. g5 (18. f4 Nf6 $1 {. From the previous variations, you should be already aware that the knight is heading to e4 , even if it involves a pawn sacrifice.}) 18... f6 19. Rxh5 fxg5 {These moves make the most sense, and now White is interested in keeping the pawn on g5 to shelter thier king.} 20. Qe2 Rde8 21. Rh6 Nf8 22. Bd2 Qc7 23. Rah1 Re7 {White is pushing with all their might, but Black is holding on and does enjoy the extra pawn.} 24. c4 (24. Kf1 Bf4 25. Bb4 Bd6 {leads to a repetition.}) 24... dxc4 25. Rc1 {White switches back to the queenside and the play all over the board.} Kb8 26. Rxc4 Qd8 27. Kf1 Rg8 {The position remains very complex, but as they say, a pawn is a pawn.} *

