ks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} (15... Qd8 {. Going for the straightforward kingside attack this time won't work.} 16. Kg2 Qh4 17. Rh1 Qf6 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 {. White is much better since he has two bishops and can easily organize a play on both flanks, while Black's options are limited. Here ... e5 push only weakens Black's position.}) (15... Qa4 $6 {. You can keep an eye on this move to disrupt White's queenside attack, but it does not achieve the desired effect here.} 16. c3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 {. Again, same story as with the other clickable variation where Black trades queens – White is much better.} g6 18. h6 a6 19. Kg2 {. The position will inevitably open, and the bishop pair promises White better chances.}) 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} (16... O-O-O $2 {. If you're not sure if castling long here is the correct idea (it might be confusing when castling long is good and when it's not), pay attention to White's pawn advancement on the queenside and how quickly it might happen.} 17. a4 Bc7 18. a5 Qd6 19. f4 {. You already know all of these White's maneuvers, so there's no surprise.} a6 20. b4 {, and Black's position is terrible.}) 17. f4 {Without including an earlier a4 and ... Bc7 , this maneuver is not dangerous.} Nf6 {You already know this – the knight is heading to e4 , sometimes involving a positional pawn sacrifice.} 18. Qe2 Ne4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 {Here, it's not even a sacrifice since the pawn on b2 is still hanging.} 20. Qxe4 Qxb2 21. Rfd1 b5 {The position is double-edged, but Black is doing fine.} *

