ional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a