 any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 $4 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} (15... Qd8 {. Going for the straightforward kingside attack this time won't work.} 16. Kg2 Qh4 17. Rh1 Qf6 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 {. White is much better since he has two bishops and can easily organize a play on both flanks, while Black's options are limited. Here ... e5 push only weakens Black's position.}) (15... Qa4 $6 {. You can keep an eye on this move to disrupt White's queenside attack, but it does not achieve the desired effect here.} 16. c3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 {. Again, same story as with the other clickable variation where Black trades queens – White is much better.} g6 18. h6 a6 19. Kg2 {. The position will inevitably open, and the bishop pair promises White better chances.}) 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} (16... O-O-O $2 {. If you're not sure if castling long here is the correct idea (it might be confusing when castling long is good and when it's not), pay attention to White's pawn advancement on the queenside and how quickly it might happen.} 17. a4 Bc7 18. a5 Qd6 19. f4 {. You already know all of these White's maneuvers, so there's no surprise.} a6 20. b4 {, and Black's position is terrible.}) 17. Qf3 {A strong positional move - White slows down Black's ... e5 push, offers the pawn on b2 'for free' and wants to start a kingside attack.} Bc7 {As with every plan, there are pros and cons. If White pushes f4 , Black gets to reroute the knight to e4 . If White does not do it and plays Qf3 instead, Black can build a strong battery on the b8 - h2 diagonal since f4 is not happening.} (17... Qxb2 $2 {. Accepting such pawns at the wrong moment will be costly.} 18. Rfd1 Qb6 19. h6 g6 20. Rab1 Qc7 21. c4 $1 {. The point – this invisible move might be difficult to spot from afar, but Black has no satisfactory response.} dxc4 $2 22. Rxb7 Qc8 23. Rxd7 $1 Qxd7 24. Qf6 {. This is one of White's key ideas you never want to miss.}) 18. Bc2 {White wants to play Qd3 to provoke Black to play ... g6 , so that after Kg2 and Rh1 , White can start a strong attack at the kingside.} Qd6 (18... Qxb2 $2 {. Now you can't take the pawn, but not because the queen would be trapped.} 19. Qd3 g6 20. Kg2 {, White develops a powerful attack at the kingside that might already be winning.}) 19. Rfe1 Rae8 {The check on h2 is tempting but gives nothing at the moment.} 20. Rad1 {White might delay the active operations, wait for you to push e5 , and then exploit the weakened d5 -pawn. Be smart!} Qh2+ 21. Kf1 a6 {Just in case, dealing with a potential Ba4 idea, combined with h6 and Qf6 .} 22. Qg2 Qh4 {Keeping the queens on the board makes sense - the white king is vulnerable.} 23. Re2 b5 24. f3 Nb6 25. b3 Nd7 {It's a cat and mouse game – who will blink first? You are thinking about the e5 push, but if White's strategy is to exploit its weaknesses, then it makes sense to delay it and see what happens.} *

