 move} 17... e5 $2 {is too early here, and this is what White wants.} 18. Bf5 Rad8 19. Qg4 {. White swiftly tosses all of his pieces to the kingside and is ready to start an attack.} Qc6 20. Kg2 g6 $2 {. While this will be our idea later, specifically here, Black walks into a deadly attack.} 21. hxg6 fxg6 {.} ({(Opening the h-file,} 21... hxg6 $4 {, is almost an immediate mate after} 22. Qh3 {. )}) 22. Be6+ Kg7 23. Rh1 {. White's threats are unstoppable.}) 18. Qb3 {This is something you should never forget - White would like to trade queens! Their king is weak; they have two bishops and a considerable space advantage.} (18. Kg2 e5 19. Qb3 e4 {. This transposes to a line covered after 17.Kg2 and only then pushing g5 .}) 18... Qd8 {No, thank you!} 19. f4 f6 {Black starts a counter-offensive on the kingside.} 20. Qc2 Kh8 {As it happens, the move order here is pretty important.} (20... fxg5 $6 21. fxg5 Bf4 {. You might study this idea, but remember – the devil is in the details, as White is not yet committed to the pawn on h7 .} 22. Bxf4 Rxf4 23. Qg2 $1 {. An 'oops' moment – White has a solid advantage since the bishop is stronger than the knight, and Black's weaknesses are more obvious.}) 21. Bxh7 {If White takes the pawn, there's the critical tactical trick that holds Black's position together.} fxg5 22. fxg5 Bf4 {If not for this maneuver, Black is dead lost.} 23. Bxf4 Rxf4 24. Rxf4 Qxg5+ 25. Qg2 Qxf4 {Compared to one of the previous clickables, the black knight can get to f6 , and the white king is more exposed. The position remains balanced.} *

