ional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} 17. g5 {A very tricky move – White boldly pushes forward the king's pawns for a direct attack, removes the option to maneuver the knight to e4 , and literally provokes you to push ... e5 . While that remains one of your key ideas, some important nuances exist.} Bc7 {You can also try this idea, which involves creating a battery with ... Qd6 . It leads to somewhat riskier positions, but judge yourself.} 18. Kg2 Rae8 ({It's pretty obvious that} 18... Qd6 {would be met by} 19. f4 {; thus, the text move is a smarter choice while keeping the ... Qd6 possibility for later.}) 19. f4 {If White does this immediately, a swift counter-attack is vital.} f6 20. Qc2 fxg5 {Don't look back!} 21. Bxh7+ Kh8 22. h6 {Once again, the both camps are engaged in a sharp struggle for the initiative, with the outcome depending on who can seize control of the position.} (22. fxg5 Qd6 {. Here comes the Black queen.}) 22... Re7 23. hxg7+ Rxg7 24. Rh1 gxf4+ 25. Kf2 Rf6 {Black is holding, but you should decide if you like such positions.} 26. Rag1 Nf8 27. Bd3+ Kg8 {We can stop it here – there is no mate; the engine fully supports Black, but ultimately, you're the one who will have to play it.} ({After Kf1 , the game could continue: e5 Rxg7+ Kxg7 dxe5 Bxe5 Qd1 f3 . Who's attacking whom? Bg5 Rf7 Qe1 Nd7 Qh4} 27... Kg8 {Bh6 Bg7 . And so on – the position is balanced, and one mistake from either player will decide the game's fate.}) *

