 any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 $4 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} (15... Qd8 {. Going for the straightforward kingside attack this time won't work.} 16. Kg2 Qh4 17. Rh1 Qf6 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 {. White is much better since he has two bishops and can easily organize a play on both flanks, while Black's options are limited. Here ... e5 push only weakens Black's position.}) (15... Qa4 $6 {. You can keep an eye on this move to disrupt White's queenside attack, but it does not achieve the desired effect here.} 16. c3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 {. Again, same story as with the other clickable variation where Black trades queens – White is much better.} g6 18. h6 a6 19. Kg2 {. The position will inevitably open, and the bishop pair promises White better chances.}) 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} (16... O-O-O $2 {. If you're not sure if castling long here is the correct idea (it might be confusing when castling long is good and when it's not), pay attention to White's pawn advancement on the queenside and how quickly it might happen.} 17. a4 Bc7 18. a5 Qd6 19. f4 {. You already know all of these White's maneuvers, so there's no surprise.} a6 20. b4 {, and Black's position is terrible.}) 17. g5 {A very tricky move - White boldly pushes forward the king's pawns for a direct attack, removes the option to maneuver the knight to e4 , and literally provokes you to push ... e5 . While that remains one of your key ideas, some important nuances exist.} Bc7 {You can also try this idea, which involves creating a battery with ... Qd6 . It leads to somewhat riskier positions, but judge yourself.} 18. Kg2 Rae8 ({It's pretty obvious that} 18... Qd6 {would be met by} 19. f4 {; thus, the text move is a smarter choice while keeping the ... Qd6 possibility for later.}) 19. Rh1 e5 {Compared to the previous version of the e-pawn push, this time, Black is ready for the Bf5 maneuver.} 20. Bf5 Re7 21. Qg4 Qc6 {Black is thinking about the idea of ... e4 and ... g6 or vice-versa to force White to take on d7 or open the f-file for a counter-attack.} 22. Rh4 {Not a forced continuation, but the following idea for Black might come in handy.} g6 23. Bd3 (23. hxg6 $2 fxg6 {. If you remember one of the previous lines, White's key idea of Be6 + here is simply not working.} 24. Bc2 Ref7 {. Suddenly, Black starts a serious offensive on the kingside.}) 23... e4 24. Be2 f5 {Instead of being cautious, suddenly Black can change the game's character – White can't take the pawn en passant.} 25. Qh3 ({If} 25. gxf6 $2 {then} Nxf6 26. Qh3 g5 $1 27. Bxg5 Rg7 {, and Black wins!}) 25... f4 26. Bg4 e3 27. fxe3 gxh5 28. Rxh5 Qg6 {This leads to some crazy complications that the engine, as usual, evaluates as equal.} *

