rd, but the consequences are difficult to evaluate.} exf5 21. hxg7 {White is playing with fire.} Rf7 22. Bh6 Ng4 {The black king feels safer thus it's in White's best interest to trade off the queens.} 23. Qb3 Qxb3 24. axb3 Re6 25. Bd2 Rxg7 26. Kf3 {The only move for White.} Nh2+ 27. Rxh2 Bxh2 28. Rxa7 Rg1 {Black is up an exchange, but White's bishops can become dangerous.} 29. Bf4 Bxf4 30. Kxf4 Rb6 {The position is balanced, but White is making the draw here, not Black. The outside h-pawn might play a vital role.} ({After Bxf5 , the game could continue: Rxb3 Be6+} 30... Kg7 {Bxd5 Rxb2} 31. f3 {. Draw looks like a realistic result.}) *

