1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 9 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves. )}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do. The move} (6... Bg4 $6 {, which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss. The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 {It's well known for a long time that this is the continuation that promises White the best chances – White attempts to exploit the vulnerable positioning of our light-squared bishop. However, we will attempt to trick our opponent in a complex game.} (9. Nxg6 hxg6 {, and Black doesn't have any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} 17. Kg2 {There's a fair chance that the position will transpose from one variation into another. Either way, the Kg2 maneuver generally makes perfect sense since the white king here feels a little safer, can provide better support to the advanced kingside pawns, and also allows to bring the rook on h1 .} Rae8 {Black is reinforcing the idea of pushing e5 but keep your eyes open for extra opportunities.} 18. Rh1 {With this rook move, there's an extra option that you should know.} f5 {Probably there's nothing wrong with sticking to the original plan and pushing... e5 , but then again, after it, White has plenty of choices, including a positional Qb3 , offering the queen trade. The text move is spicier and makes sense since White has committed himself to Rh1 , and with the position opened, the pawn on f2 is weak.} 19. gxf5 {Not a mandatory move, but quite principled. If White closes the kingside with g5 , Black should not rush with the ... e5 push since the pawn on d5 might become vulnerable think Qb3 . Instead, prepare things with moves like ... Re7 , ... a6 , ... Qc6 , and see what happens. If the circumstances are right, push ... e5 ; maybe you will get to reroute the knight to e4 , or even a surprising counterattack on the kingside with ... h6 might look interesting, opening the way for your pieces to start a kingside attack.} Nf6 {Suddenly, the white king starts to feel uneasy. Let's not forget that the white pawn on b2 is still under attack, and to protect it, for White, it will take one extra move.} 20. h6 {White could charge forward, but the consequences are difficult to evaluate.} exf5 21. Qb3 {A very accurate move to trade off the queens - if unprepared, it might not be obvious even for a strong grandmaster.} g6 (21... Qc7 22. Bg5 {. Unfortunately, we can't go here – Black is not in time to trade off the dark-squared bishops. White is much better.}) 22. Qxb6 axb6 {We can stop our analysis here, since the game is not forced. White has a slight advantage, but it's not easy to use it. Black also has ideas like anchoring the knight on e4 and asking White direct questions. It would be great to trade the dark-squared bishops.} ({After Rag1 the game could continue:} 22... Kf7 23. Bc1 Ra8 24. a3 Rfe8 {, looking for the right moment to play ... Ne4 or ways to trade the bishops.}) *

