ks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} (15... Qd8 {. Going for the straightforward kingside attack this time won't work.} 16. Kg2 Qh4 17. Rh1 Qf6 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 {. White is much better since he has two bishops and can easily organize a play on both flanks, while Black's options are limited. Here ... e5 push only weakens Black's position.}) (15... Qa4 $6 {. You can keep an eye on this move to disrupt White's queenside attack, but it does not achieve the desired effect here.} 16. c3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 {. Again, same story as with the other clickable variation where Black trades queens – White is much better.} g6 18. h6 a6 19. Kg2 {. The position will inevitably open, and the bishop pair promises White better chances.}) 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} (16... O-O-O $2 {. If you're not sure if castling long here is the correct idea (it might be confusing when castling long is good and when it's not), pay attention to White's pawn advancement on the queenside and how quickly it might happen.} 17. a4 Bc7 18. a5 Qd6 19. f4 {. You already know all of these White's maneuvers, so there's no surprise.} a6 20. b4 {, and Black's position is terrible.}) 17. Kg2 {There's a fair chance that the position will transpose from one variation into another. Either way, the Kg2 maneuver generally makes perfect sense since the white king here feels a little safer, can provide better support to the advanced kingside pawns, and also allows to bring the rook on h1 .} Rae8 {Black is reinforcing the idea of pushing e5 but keep your eyes open for extra opportunities.} 18. Rh1 {With this rook move, there's an extra option that you should know.} f5 {Probably there's nothing wrong with sticking to the original plan and pushing... e5 , but then again, after it, White has plenty of choices, including a positional Qb3 , offering the queen trade. The text move is spicier and makes sense since White has committed himself to Rh1 , and with the position opened, the pawn on f2 is weak.} 19. gxf5 {Not a mandatory move, but quite principled. If White closes the kingside with g5 , Black should not rush with the ... e5 push since the pawn on d5 might become vulnerable (think Qb3 ). Instead, prepare things with moves like ... Re7 , ... a6 , ... Qc6 , and see what happens. If the circumstances are right, push ... e5 ; maybe you will get to reroute the knight to e4 , or even a surprising counterattack on the kingside with ... h6 might look interesting, opening the way for your pieces to start a kingside attack.} (19. f4 Nf6 $1 {. From the previous variations, you should be already aware that the knight is heading to e4 , even if it involves a pawn sacrifice.}) 19... Nf6 {Suddenly, the white king starts to feel uneasy. Let's not forget that the white pawn on b2 is still under attack, and to protect it, for White, it will take one extra move.} 20. Qb3 {If White tries to include the queen trade in this version, we can reject it.} Qc7 21. h6 Bf4 {A significant move - Black takes over the game.} 22. Qc2 exf5 23. hxg7 Rf7 24. Rag1 Ne4 {Black is pushing.} ({White needs to play very precisely to stay afloat. For example: Bxe4 fxe4 Kf1} 24... Bxd2 25. Qxd2 {e3 Qd3} Qc4 $1 {Qxc4 Rxf2+ Ke1 dxc4 . Black has such a strong rook that White’s only hope of solving the problems is through tactics.} 26. Rf1 {Rxb2 Rxh7! Kxh7 Rf8} Kxg7 {Rxe8 Rxa2 Rxe3 Kf6 Kd1 , and White must settle for a draw.}) *

