1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 10 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves.)}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do.} ({The move} 6... Bg4 {?! , which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 $1 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss.   The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 {It's well known for a long time that this is the continuation that promises White the best chances – White attempts to exploit the vulnerable positioning of our light-squared bishop. However, we will attempt to trick our opponent in a complex game.} (9. Nxg6 $6 hxg6 {, and Black doesn't have any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 $4 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} (15... Qd8 {. Going for the straightforward kingside attack this time won't work.} 16. Kg2 Qh4 17. Rh1 Qf6 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 {. White is much better since he has two bishops and can easily organize a play on both flanks, while Black's options are limited. Here ... e5 push only weakens Black's position.}) (15... Qa4 $6 {. You can keep an eye on this move to disrupt White's queenside attack, but it does not achieve the desired effect here.} 16. c3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 {. Again, same story as with the other clickable variation where Black trades queens – White is much better.} g6 18. h6 a6 19. Kg2 {. The position will inevitably open, and the bishop pair promises White better chances.}) 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} (16... O-O-O $2 {. If you're not sure if castling long here is the correct idea (it might be confusing when castling long is good and when it's not), pay attention to White's pawn advancement on the queenside and how quickly it might happen.} 17. a4 Bc7 18. a5 Qd6 19. f4 {. You already know all of these White's maneuvers, so there's no surprise.} a6 20. b4 {, and Black's position is terrible.}) 17. Kg2 {There's a fair chance that the position will transpose from one variation into another. Either way, the Kg2 maneuver generally makes perfect sense since the white king here feels a little safer, can provide better support to the advanced kingside pawns, and also allows to bring the rook on h1 .} Rae8 {Black is reinforcing the idea of pushing e5 but keep your eyes open for extra opportunities.} 18. g5 e5 {Black continues the original plan – now pushing the f-pawn to f6 or f5 is not optimal since White stands better to meet it.} (18... f6 {would run into} 19. Qc2 {, and the problems with the h7 pawn are considerable, while after...}) (18... f5 {, Black is not generating any threats. Now Black wants to play ... e4 and start a kingside attack.}) 19. Qb3 {Again, one of the key moves – White can't afford to have the queens on the board.} e4 {Giving up the pawn on d5 to keep the queens on the board won't be enough for compensation, at least in this variation.} (19... exd4 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. cxd4 {. White is pushing.}) 20. Bb5 {The principled choice which leads to complications.} Qc7 21. Qxd5 a6 22. Be2 {White can't trade on d7 – the white king is too weak.} b5 23. a4 {This is what engines would play in this position - it might be too much for a human being. We hope you don't spend too much time on this position, but perhaps knowing the idea will help you.} Nb6 24. Qf5 g6 25. Qh3 bxa4 {You want to play ... Nd5 - f4 when the moment will be right.} 26. Be3 {The main idea is to reinforce the c4 push and also perhaps in some lines stop Black from pushing ... e3 .} Kh8 {Black removes the king from any potential checks on the a2 - g8 diagonal and puts White into some zugzwang position where it's difficult to find the next move! It's difficult to push c4 without removing the rook from the a-file, where it attacks two pawns.} (26... Nd5 27. Rxa4 Nf4+ 28. Bxf4 Bxf4 29. Rxa6 Bxg5 {. White is up a pawn after all.}) (26... Re7 $2 {. This human move leads to problems.} 27. c4 Nxc4 28. hxg6 fxg6 29. Rac1 Nxe3+ 30. fxe3 Qb8 31. Rxf8+ Qxf8 32. Rc6 {. The black rook on e7 is weird, and the black king will be coming under some checks – White is just better.}) 27. Rh1 Re7 28. Qh4 {White is building up the pressure on the h-file.} Rb8 29. Rh3 Qc6 30. Rah1 Kg8 {It's time to go back! The c4 push never happened; the position remains very sharp.} *

