er.} Nc4 26. Bb3 Qb7 {Black also has ideas!} (26... Nxd2 $4 {. Ignoring your opponent's ideas has never been a good strategy.} 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Rh1 {.}) 27. Be3 f5 28. hxg6 {Including the trade doesn't promise White anything.} f4 29. Qxh7+ Qxh7 30. gxh7+ Kxh7 31. Rh1+ Kg7 {Black remains alert.} 32. Bc1 Rh8 {Because of the strong central pawns, Black is holding.} ({After Rh6 , this is how the game could continue – the line is quite forcing. Rxh6 gxh6+ Kxh6 a4 , White brings the queenside rook in the game. Kg5 axb5 axb5 Ra6} 32... Bb8 {Black's threat of ... Kg4 and f3 will always give him enough counterplay, maybe even the ... e3 push at the right moment. Rc6} 33. Rh8 {Bxc4 bxc4} f3+ {. White has no choice but to stop the pawn. e3 Rxc4 Bd6 Rc6 Be7 Re6 Bf6 . White has two extra pawns, but they don't matter if Black has such a powerful pawn on e3 . Bxe3 fxe3 Rxe3 Kf4 . The game will end in a draw.}) *

