1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 9 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves. )}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do. The move} (6... Bg4 $6 {, which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss. The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 {It's well known for a long time that this is the continuation that promises White the best chances – White attempts to exploit the vulnerable positioning of our light-squared bishop. However, we will attempt to trick our opponent in a complex game.} (9. Nxg6 hxg6 {, and Black doesn't have any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} 17. Kg2 {There's a fair chance that the position will transpose from one variation into another. Either way, the Kg2 maneuver generally makes perfect sense since the white king here feels a little safer, can provide better support to the advanced kingside pawns, and also allows to bring the rook on h1 .} Rae8 {Black is reinforcing the idea of pushing e5 but keep your eyes open for extra opportunities.} 18. g5 e5 {Black continues the original plan – now pushing the f-pawn to f6 or f5 is not optimal since White stands better to meet it.} (18... f6 {would run into} 19. Qc2 {, and the problems with the h7 pawn are considerable, while after...}) (18... f5 {, Black is not generating any threats. Now Black wants to play ... e4 and start a kingside attack.}) 19. Qb3 {Again, one of the key moves – White can't afford to have the queens on the board.} e4 {Giving up the pawn on d5 to keep the queens on the board won't be enough for compensation, at least in this variation.} (19... exd4 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. cxd4 {. White is pushing.}) 20. Bb5 {The principled choice which leads to complications.} Qc7 21. Qxd5 a6 22. Be2 {White can't trade on d7 – the white king is too weak.} b5 23. Qf5 {The human move – White gives the queen a better role. Black's next moves are easy.} g6 24. Qh3 {If White ever takes on g6 , capture with the f-pawn to open the rook on f8 .} Nb6 {White has to pick up the idea that the light-squared bishop belongs on b3 , but the details can be tricky.} 25. Bd1 {White can also start with the bishop maneuver and keep the Rh1 idea for later.} Nc4 26. Bb3 Qb7 {Black also has ideas!} (26... Nxd2 $4 {. Ignoring your opponent's ideas has never been a good strategy.} 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Rh1 {.}) 27. Be3 f5 28. gxf6 Rxf6 29. hxg6 Rxg6+ 30. Kh1 Qf7 {Black is down a pawn, but the white king is still weak. We can stop our analysis here and congratulate our opponent if they made it this far.} ({After} 30... Rg1+ {, the game could continue. Qf3+ Qxf3 exf3 a4 Kg7 Rae1 Kf7 , Black enables some tactical tricks. axb5 axb5 Ra1} 31. Rxg1+ {Kxg1 Rg8+ Kf1 Bh2 Bxc4+ bxc4 Ra7+ Kg6 Ra5 Rb8 . Probably the correct way to evaluate this position is – it's balanced.}) *

