 to the d6 -square to create a battery of the queen and the bishop.} 19. Rfe1 (19. Rab1 Qd6 20. Rfe1 Rae8 21. Bb5 f5 22. g5 Rf7) 19... Qxb2 {It's time to take the pawn – the black queen is ready to retreat to d6 and create the battery.} 20. Be3 (20. Qg2 e5 $1) 20... a6 {Black deals with the Bb5 - Bd7 threat.} 21. Rab1 {This leads to an equal endgame.} Qxc3 22. Rec1 Qxd3 23. Rb3 Qe4 {This variation is almost forced.} 24. Qxe4 dxe4 25. Rxc7 Nf6 26. Rcxb7 Rfc8 {The final accurate move – you don't want to take the pawn on g4 that would give White huge activity. The rook on c8 also stops White's idea to double the rooks on the 7th rank.} ({With} 26... Nxg4 $6 27. Bg5 {, the problem is that the black knight can't easily get back to d5 , and the knight on g4 is disconnected from the game – White plays for domination.}) 27. Kg2 Nd5 {If you could trade both rooks, you could enter an endgame where the knight will be superior to the bishop.} *

