1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {will mostly transpose to the lines of this chapter or some rare lines from Chapter 9 .}) (5. Bd2 {. The move order can vary – ensure you get to the same final position.} c6 6. Nf3 ({(} 6. Bf4 Bf5 {, another order of the moves. )}) 6... Bf5 {, and we transpose to the main lines.}) 5... c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {All of Black's moves are easy to remember and almost always remain the same against whatever White tries to do. The move} (6... Bg4 $6 {, which used to be the core idea of this Scandinavian variation, is now basically obsolete for a very good reason.} 7. h3 {is the problem – if Black now takes on f3 , White retains a solid advantage by having two bishops and a strong center, but retreating with the bishop might create even greater problems.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 10. Ne5 {. One of White's core ideas is to push h4 - h5 and exploit the unfortunate placement of the black bishop on g6 .} e6 11. h4 h6 {. It is not the best move, but it illustrates the rising problems for Black.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {. Black's pawn structure is terrible, and there's also material loss. The important lesson from this line is to know what you might run into if you position your light-squared bishop on g4 . Mostly, it will go to f5 , but there will be moments when Bg4 will be good. When thinking about it, consider whether White can execute the idea of h3 - g4 , Ne5 , and push h4 - h5 .}) 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {It is one of the most important variations of the Scandinavian Defense that you must know by heart.} Bg6 9. h4 {It's well known for a long time that this is the continuation that promises White the best chances – White attempts to exploit the vulnerable positioning of our light-squared bishop. However, we will attempt to trick our opponent in a complex game.} (9. Nxg6 hxg6 {, and Black doesn't have any positional weaknesses, which is something that you can't say about White. The quick development guarantees Black to take over the game quickly.}) 9... Nbd7 {Starting a forcing sequence – White has to act quickly.} 10. Nxd7 (10. h5 {. White can't do this.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Be3 Be4 {Black has a decisive advantage.} 13. f4 Qa5 14. Rh3 Bb4 {, and Black is winning.}) 10... Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 {Now White has a choice.} 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 {White has no choice but to take – even after the bishop retreat, the trade on d5 will be inevitable since the black bishop is too strong.} cxd5 14. Bd3 {And so we have arrived at the main position of the Scandinavian Defense – the correct evaluation of this position holds the fate of the entire system. The position is very complicated and will require White to play a resourceful play all over the board, which not everybody enjoys since it's difficult to master.   From another point of view, even though White and Black have their standalone ideas, there are various tactical solutions in many move orders. This move order complexity leads to the difficult character of the position, since it's easy to mix up lines for White. Because of this, many grandmasters have stopped playing this variation and are looking for a slightly better game in the variation that Anish Giri recommends. We will look into this line in Chapter 3 .   — What's the first thing someone studying these lines should remember for Black?  — First and foremost, use your pieces effectively: create a battery with ... Qd6 -... Bc7 and look for the ... e5 break in the center.} Bd6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways, but mainly you want to keep your eyes open, what White is planning. If he's aggressively pushing the pawns on the queenside, it's a clear sign that it's not where you want to place your king.} 15. Bd2 {The strongest continuation – White completes the development, does not define the final setup, and keeps the opportunity to play on both flanks. This is a difficult move to play since Black's response seems to ask direct questions.} Qb6 {Even though we're not necessarily thinking about taking either of the pawns, keeping White busy about it already is an achievement.} 16. c3 {White has made two useful moves and keeps the option to play either on the queenside or kingside.} O-O {Now, White can easily mix up things since the choice here is vast. Black's core idea remains pushing ... e5 .} 17. h6 {Either now, a move before or after, but that's a move that White might want to include to create some dark-squared weaknesses around the black king assuming you've castled short} g6 {Your general plans remain the same – mostly, you want to push ... e5 , and if White tries to grab space with f4 , reroute the knight to e4 .} 18. Qf3 {White is back at stopping Black's ... e5 push.} Bc7 {A strong novelty – now in some lines, Black will have access to the d6 -square to create a battery of the queen and the bishop.} (18... Rae8 $6 {is the proposed move in Lifetime Repertoires: Adhiban's 1.e4 ; however, Black is experiencing problems after it.} 19. Rfe1 {. The problem is that capturing the pawn on b2 is risky.} Qxb2 20. Red1 $1 Qb6 ({(} 20... Qa3 $4 21. Bb5 $1 {, and Black's pieces seal the king's fate.} Rd8 22. Bxd7 Rxd7 23. Qf6 {. )}) 21. Rab1 Qc7 22. c4 {. White has some unpleasant tactical motifs at their disposal.}) 19. Rfe1 (19. Rab1 Qd6 20. Rfe1 Rae8 21. Bb5 f5 22. g5 Rf7) 19... Qxb2 {It's time to take the pawn – the black queen is ready to retreat to d6 and create the battery.} 20. Be3 (20. Qg2 e5 $1) 20... a6 {Black deals with the Bb5 - Bd7 threat.} 21. c4 {White continues to play energetically.} Qa3 {That is very precise. It would be best to be careful about opening the position too much. The extra pawn is nice, but don't underestimate White's bishop pair and the annoying pawn on h6 .} 22. Be2 Qd6 23. Kf1 b5 {Black gives up the pawn but limits White's bishops and simultaneously seeks counterplay on the kingside. With this move, we can conclude our analysis of the variation. Now that you have studied the entire chapter judge for yourself how easy it is for White to play. In most variations, to get anything tangible out of the opening, White had to play all over the board with a lot of energetic moves – there are not so many players who like to play like that since it carries a significant risk of backfiring. We find that Black's plans are more straightforward, and there's a great chance that White will get confused in the sea of endless possibilities, even if a great player.} ({After cxb5 , the game could continue: axb5 Bxb5} 23... f5 {. This maneuver you already know.} 24. g5 ({A. f4} 24. Bd2 Bb6 {, Black generates counterplay against White's weaknesses.} 25. Qh3 {Rf5 Bd3 Rxg5 Rxe6 Rh5! Qg4} Nf6 $1 {. One intermezzo move after another – the position is balanced.}) ({B. The line e5 is a very long one where Black gets a draw, but we need to be quite accurate. dxe5 Nxe5} 24. Qf4 {Ng4 Qxd6 Nxe3+ . A necessary intermezzo move to kill White's bishop pair. Rxe3 Bxd6 Bc6 Ra5 Rd1 Bf4 . The position is simplifying. Bxd5+} Kh8 {Re7 Bxg5 Rd7 . Final accuracy – don't allow White to double the rooks on the 7th rank. Rc5 Rb1 Rc1+ Rxc1} {( Kg2 Rcc8 )} 25. Bc1 {a4 Bxh6} a5 {Rf6! Bc4 Bf8 a6 Bc5 a7 Bxa7 Rxa7 Rd6} 26. Kg2 {Rd4 . With a draw.})) *

