1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 {What else can be dangerous if White does not want to jump with the knight to e5 , go for quite forcing lines and with radical play prove their ambitions against the Scandinavian defense? Of course, it's the poisonous plan with Qe2 and O-O-O . In this chapter, we will analyze this system in depth.} (7. Ne5 {is the most principled approach for White. Ne5} e6 8. g4 Bg6 {. It's detailed in Chapter 2 .}) 7... Nbd7 {Black deals with the Ne5 possibility and ensures that the Nd5 jump is not dangerous at the moment.} (7... e6 $6 {. White has already created a threat to jump with the knight to d5 ; thus, ignoring your opponent's threats can't end well.} 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+ {. The point is that with both captures on f6 , Black experiences problems:} ({a. gxf6 does not create any desired dynamics on the g-file.} 9. O-O {Nd7 Re1 White is better, and Black struggles to complete the development. Castling long does not feel safe here, and Black might not even make it.} Qc7 $6 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 {Bxe6! . White can start immediate active operations against the stranded king. fxe6 Rxe6+ Kf7} 11. Qe2 {Nb6 Re1 , and White's attack is decisive.})) {b. Qxf6 Qe2 Nd7 ( Bxc2? . You can't take the pawn due to a typical anti-Scandinavian trick. d5! cxd5 Bb5+ Nc6 Bc3 Qg6 Nd4 There's more than one possibility for White – the point is that Black is suffering everywhere. ) O-O-O . Now Black should watch out for the d5 push. Be7 Bg5 Qg6 Bxe7 Kxe7 . Black will have to survive with an exposed king – maybe with a perfect play, it's possible, but it's not a fun way to play.} 8. Qe2 {This is not the only possible continuation for White, but the only one you should study carefully. In any other variations, Black has no issues whatsoever.} (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Ne3 {is covered in Chapter 4 .}) (8. O-O e6 {is also covered in the next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. Ne5 {Now this jump is less dangerous than in Chapter 1.} (9. Bb3 {. If White is trying to be smart and trick you with the order of the moves, it does not change much.} e6 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. O-O-O {. Transposing to the main lines.}) 9... e6 10. f4 {Looks menacing, but White is not ready to execute the g4 push. It would be best if you thought twice before castling short.} (10. O-O-O {. We can also transpose to the main line of the chapter.} Bb4 {. This happens with a different order of the moves.}) 10... Be7 11. O-O-O (11. g4 Nxe5 {. The key intermezzo move.} 12. fxe5 Nxg4 {. White can voluntary use this setup in some similar lines to aim for some compensation, but not here.}) 11... b5 {Before castling or capturing on e5 here's it's important to define the placement of White's light-squared bishop. If it goes to b3 , you immediately start a queenside attack with ... a5 .} (11... O-O $2 12. g4 {The engines say that Bb3 is a little better, but we'll show this line to prove the point.} Nxe5 13. fxe5 Nxg4 $2 {. Black can get a rook and a couple of pawns for two minor pieces instead.} 14. Rdg1 {. Now White's attack on the kingside is killing.}) 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 {Now White's f4 feels like a waste of time since g4 - g5 is much slower without the light-squared bishop on f5 or g6 .} b4 14. Ne4 {The knight can't block the a-pawn's advancement due to ... Qa5 and ... Nb6 .} a5 {Black is doing great and already can castle short.} *

