1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 {What else can be dangerous if White does not want to jump with the knight to e5 , go for quite forcing lines and with radical play prove their ambitions against the Scandinavian defense? Of course, it's the poisonous plan with Qe2 and O-O-O . In this chapter, we will analyze this system in depth.} (7. Ne5 {is the most principled approach for White. Ne5} e6 8. g4 Bg6 {. It's detailed in Chapter 2 .}) 7... Nbd7 {Black deals with the Ne5 possibility and ensures that the Nd5 jump is not dangerous at the moment.} (7... e6 $6 {. White has already created a threat to jump with the knight to d5 ; thus, ignoring your opponent's threats can't end well.} 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+ {. The point is that with both captures on f6 , Black experiences problems:} ({a. gxf6 does not create any desired dynamics on the g-file.} 9. O-O {Nd7 Re1 White is better, and Black struggles to complete the development. Castling long does not feel safe here, and Black might not even make it.} Qc7 $6 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 {Bxe6! . White can start immediate active operations against the stranded king. fxe6 Rxe6+ Kf7} 11. Qe2 {Nb6 Re1 , and White's attack is decisive.})) {b. Qxf6 Qe2 Nd7 ( Bxc2? . You can't take the pawn due to a typical anti-Scandinavian trick. d5! cxd5 Bb5+ Nc6 Bc3 Qg6 Nd4 There's more than one possibility for White – the point is that Black is suffering everywhere. ) O-O-O . Now Black should watch out for the d5 push. Be7 Bg5 Qg6 Bxe7 Kxe7 . Black will have to survive with an exposed king – maybe with a perfect play, it's possible, but it's not a fun way to play.} 8. Qe2 {This is not the only possible continuation for White, but the only one you should study carefully. In any other variations, Black has no issues whatsoever.} (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Ne3 {is covered in Chapter 4 .}) (8. O-O e6 {is also covered in the next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. O-O-O {The most principled continuation.} e6 {We've reached the second most important position in the Scandinavian Defense, which was considered the most important in the pre-engine era.  The evaluation often varied from 'White has a large advantage' to 'Black is doing completely fine.' In our opinion, White is better, but Black has a clear plan for counterplay. Combined with some dynamic resources, this will allow you to equalize the position and achieve a good game.   However, the amount of tournament wins you will gather in this setup is more important than the engine's evaluation.   Let's talk about some important details. White has two standalone plans:   1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns.   2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black – in this scenario, you won't have either the bishop pair or space. This plan is more dangerous, and it's not a surprise that Anish Giri recommends it. On the positive side, in this plan, you will have to remember less, how to play and keep counterchances.} 10. Ne5 {White attempts to execute plan No. 1 – push forward all kingside pawns.} Bb4 {The most principled continuation for Black is getting ready to take on c3 and then push forward the queenside pawns to ignite a queenside attack. Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from.} (10... h5 $5 {is an interesting resource to stop White's pawn advancement but also quite risky.} 11. h3 $1 h4 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 {The only capture to stop White's d5 push.} 13. Bg5 {Black is still far from solving all the opening problems. Check the sample line.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. d5 $1 {This move is logical with the black king in the center.} exd5 16. Bxd5 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Qf3 $1 {. As it turns out, including earlier moves 11.h3 h4 is in favor of White since Black no longer has the ... Bg4 resource.} Bg6 18. Be4 Kc8 19. Bxg6 Bf4+ {Black is desperately trying to stay in the game.} 20. Kb1 fxg6 21. Qg4+ f5 22. Qxg6 {. There goes a pawn.} Qh7 23. Qf6 Be5 24. Qg5 Qh5 25. Qe3 Kb8 {. Maybe with perfect defense, Black can hold this, but it can't be much fun.}) (10... Nxe5 $2 {. Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines – here, it leads to a disaster.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {. Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. White's f5 push is unstoppable.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {. White crashes through and has a winning attack.}) 11. g4 {At this very moment, this push is harmless for Black.} Nxe5 {The common response – the white pawn on g4 loses the support and also the white bishop on c4 is vital.} 12. gxf5 {What else?} (12. dxe5 Nxg4 {. If Black has not yet castled short, there's no attack for White on the g-file.}) 12... Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 O-O-O {Fighting for more than a draw.} ({Black could also play} 14... Ne4 {and trade remaining minor pieces for a drawn heavy piece endgame.}) 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Rhe1 Rhe8 {White has weaknesses and you have some outposts to exploit – Black is doing great. It makes sense to keep the knight on an outpost vs. the bishop to win the game.} *

