to ignite a queenside attack. Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from.} (10... h5 $5 {is an interesting resource to stop White's pawn advancement but also quite risky.} 11. h3 $1 h4 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 {The only capture to stop White's d5 push.} 13. Bg5 {Black is still far from solving all the opening problems. Check the sample line.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. d5 $1 {This move is logical with the black king in the center.} exd5 16. Bxd5 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Qf3 $1 {. As it turns out, including earlier moves 11.h3 h4 is in favor of White since Black no longer has the ... Bg4 resource.} Bg6 18. Be4 Kc8 19. Bxg6 Bf4+ {Black is desperately trying to stay in the game.} 20. Kb1 fxg6 21. Qg4+ f5 22. Qxg6 {. There goes a pawn.} Qh7 23. Qf6 Be5 24. Qg5 Qh5 25. Qe3 Kb8 {. Maybe with perfect defense, Black can hold this, but it can't be much fun.}) (10... Nxe5 $2 {. Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines – here, it leads to a disaster.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {. Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. White's f5 push is unstoppable.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {. White crashes through and has a winning attack.}) 11. Rhe1 O-O {It's pretty apparent that White is up to no good and is looking for some tactical possibilities concerning the e6 - or f7 -pawns; thus it's time to get the king away from the center. There's no need to rush with the capture on c3 since there's a very good chance White will ask you to do it the next move.} (11... b5 $2 {would be toying with fire. There are moments when Black can afford to keep the king in the center and opt for a quick queenside attack, but this is not one of them.} 12. Bb3 a5 13. Nxd7 {. Also immediately pushing g4 looks dangerous.} Nxd7 14. g4 Bg6 15. h4 {. Now Black can't include the ... h5 defensive resource since Bxe6 is not even a sacrifice – the bishop on g6 will be hanging.} a4 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kf8 18. d5 $1 {. White has a powerful attack.} Nb6 19. h5 Bf7 20. Qxc6 Qxc6 21. dxc6 {. White has three pawns for the minor piece, and Black experiences problems with securing the king.} Nc4 22. a3 Ba5 23. Bg5 h6 24. Be7+ Kg8 25. Bb4 {. White has a large advantage.}) 12. g4 {With the white rook already committed to e1 , this push can cause problems only to White.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 (13. gxf5 $6 {is not difficult to calculate: Nxc4 Qxc4 Bxc3 Qxc3 exf5 . White has no compensation for the missing pawn, but be careful with playing the 'automatic' ... g6 to protect the extra pawn – it would seriously weaken the dark squares around the king.}) 13... Nxg4 14. h3 {This is a pretty sad move, but White can't play Rg1 since the e5 -pawn would be left unguarded.} Nh6 15. Bxh6 gxh6 16. Rg1+ Kh8 17. Qe3 Rad8 {White still has to prove if they have any compensation for the missing pawn.} 18. a3 (18. Qxh6 $2 Rxd1+ 19. Nxd1 Qxe5 {. White's attack looks scary, but there's no follow-up.}) 18... Be7 19. Bd3 (19. Qxh6 $2 Qxe5) 19... Bg6 {The g-file is covered, and from now on, White is fighting to equalize the game.} ({After} 19... Bg6 {, the game could continue: fxg6 Rxd8 Bxd8} 20. Kb1 {. A slow move, but ... Qxh6 would allow Black to pick up the f2 -pawn. Qf7 Qxh6} Kg8 {. White's weaknesses are going nowhere – Black makes sure White doesn't have the Rxg6 maneuver with the king on h8 .} 21. Ne4 {Qf4 Qxf4 Rxf4 Rd1! . White is not in trouble because of this move.} Bh4 {, and Black is pushing.}) *

