White has three pawns for the minor piece, and Black experiences problems with securing the king.} Nc4 22. a3 Ba5 23. Bg5 h6 24. Be7+ Kg8 25. Bb4 {. White has a large advantage.}) 12. a3 {What else? Black is ready to start the queenside attack with ... b5 and ... a5 . White also prepares an escape route for the light-squared bishop to a2 .} Bxc3 13. Bxc3 a5 {An accurate way to start the queenside attack. The key difference is that White is not in time to push g4 .} (13... b5 $6 {is very tempting, but the order of the moves, unfortunately, is not accurate.} 14. Ba2 a5 15. g4 $1 {The big difference.} Bg6 ({(} 15... Nxe5 $4 16. gxf5 {. The problem is that White no longer has the bishop on c4 that you get rid off with the previous move.)}) 16. Bd2 {. The point is that even if Black pushes b4 here, White can ignore it and continue with the kingside attack. White's attack is a little faster.} Nxe5 17. dxe5 Ne4 18. Bf4 {, and White's chances are better.}) 14. g4 Nxe5 {An important detail – the white bishop is under attack, thus White's gxf5 is not a problem.} 15. Qxe5 Qxe5 16. dxe5 Nxg4 17. f3 {An interesting idea – White plans to play for the domination.} Nf2 ({This pesky move is more accurate than the 'automatic'} 17... Nh6 {retreat. Indeed, from f2 -square, it will be easier to give the black knight an active role.}) 18. Rd7 b5 19. Bf1 Nh3 20. Bd2 {Along the way, White could attempt to imprison the knight.} h6 21. Rd6 g5 {Often, there will be moments when it's better to secure your positional benefits rather than holding on to the extra pawn – this rule you will hear in the course many times.} 22. Rxc6 Rfb8 {The position is dynamically balanced.} *

