to ignite a queenside attack. Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from.} (10... h5 $5 {is an interesting resource to stop White's pawn advancement but also quite risky.} 11. h3 $1 h4 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 {The only capture to stop White's d5 push.} 13. Bg5 {Black is still far from solving all the opening problems. Check the sample line.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. d5 $1 {This move is logical with the black king in the center.} exd5 16. Bxd5 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Qf3 $1 {. As it turns out, including earlier moves 11.h3 h4 is in favor of White since Black no longer has the ... Bg4 resource.} Bg6 18. Be4 Kc8 19. Bxg6 Bf4+ {Black is desperately trying to stay in the game.} 20. Kb1 fxg6 21. Qg4+ f5 22. Qxg6 {. There goes a pawn.} Qh7 23. Qf6 Be5 24. Qg5 Qh5 25. Qe3 Kb8 {. Maybe with perfect defense, Black can hold this, but it can't be much fun.}) (10... Nxe5 $2 {. Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines – here, it leads to a disaster.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {. Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. White's f5 push is unstoppable.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {. White crashes through and has a winning attack.}) 11. Rhe1 O-O {It's pretty apparent that White is up to no good and is looking for some tactical possibilities concerning the e6 - or f7 -pawns; thus it's time to get the king away from the center. There's no need to rush with the capture on c3 since there's a very good chance White will ask you to do it the next move.} (11... b5 $2 {would be toying with fire. There are moments when Black can afford to keep the king in the center and opt for a quick queenside attack, but this is not one of them.} 12. Bb3 a5 13. Nxd7 {. Also immediately pushing g4 looks dangerous.} Nxd7 14. g4 Bg6 15. h4 {. Now Black can't include the ... h5 defensive resource since Bxe6 is not even a sacrifice – the bishop on g6 will be hanging.} a4 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kf8 18. d5 $1 {. White has a powerful attack.} Nb6 19. h5 Bf7 20. Qxc6 Qxc6 21. dxc6 {. White has three pawns for the minor piece, and Black experiences problems with securing the king.} Nc4 22. a3 Ba5 23. Bg5 h6 24. Be7+ Kg8 25. Bb4 {. White has a large advantage.}) 12. a3 {What else? Black is ready to start the queenside attack with ... b5 and ... a5 . White also prepares an escape route for the light-squared bishop to a2 .} Bxc3 13. Bxc3 a5 {An accurate way to start the queenside attack. The key difference is that White is not in time to push g4 .} (13... b5 $6 {is very tempting, but the order of the moves, unfortunately, is not accurate.} 14. Ba2 a5 15. g4 $1 {The big difference.} Bg6 ({(} 15... Nxe5 $4 16. gxf5 {. The problem is that White no longer has the bishop on c4 that you get rid off with the previous move.)}) 16. Bd2 {. The point is that even if Black pushes b4 here, White can ignore it and continue with the kingside attack. White's attack is a little faster.} Nxe5 17. dxe5 Ne4 18. Bf4 {, and White's chances are better.}) 14. Bd3 {This move might seem harmless since you could automatically trade the bishop and start the desired queenside attack with seemingly no consequences on the kingside; however, don't underestimate the active white rook.} Nd5 {Don't be afraid to double your pawns – the black pawn on f5 will slow down White's potential kingside attack.} (14... Bxd3 $6 {. There's no need to activate the white rook just like that.} 15. Rxd3 b5 16. Rg3 g6 {Black will have to make this move sooner or later.} 17. Bd2 b4 18. Nxd7 {. White has other good moves as well.} Nxd7 19. h4 {. White's attack is faster, plus White keeps the option to capture on a3 with the rook to keep the b-file closed.}) 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Bd2 b5 {Black is thinking about the attack, but the b5 -pawn also secures the knight on d5 as an outpost.} 17. Qd3 f6 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 {With such a centralized knight, only White can have problems, albeit the engine estimates the position to be equal.} *

