to ignite a queenside attack. Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from.} (10... h5 $5 {is an interesting resource to stop White's pawn advancement but also quite risky.} 11. h3 $1 h4 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 {The only capture to stop White's d5 push.} 13. Bg5 {Black is still far from solving all the opening problems. Check the sample line.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. d5 $1 {This move is logical with the black king in the center.} exd5 16. Bxd5 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Qf3 $1 {. As it turns out, including earlier moves 11.h3 h4 is in favor of White since Black no longer has the ... Bg4 resource.} Bg6 18. Be4 Kc8 19. Bxg6 Bf4+ {Black is desperately trying to stay in the game.} 20. Kb1 fxg6 21. Qg4+ f5 22. Qxg6 {. There goes a pawn.} Qh7 23. Qf6 Be5 24. Qg5 Qh5 25. Qe3 Kb8 {. Maybe with perfect defense, Black can hold this, but it can't be much fun.}) (10... Nxe5 $2 {. Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines – here, it leads to a disaster.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {. Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. White's f5 push is unstoppable.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {. White crashes through and has a winning attack.}) 11. f3 {A standard idea for White – prepare the kingside pawn push and secure the important e4 -square.} h5 {Black cools down White's ambitions on the kingside. It's also possible to take on c3 immediately and proceed with Nd5 afterward, but this would allow White to gain some space on the kingside with g4 .} (11... Nxe5 {. Albeit it feels to be a standard continuation for the setup, specifically in this line, White secures an advantage.} 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. g4 $1 {. The surprise – White doesn't mind ruining their queenside pawn structure.} Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Bg6 {. More accurate than taking on c3 immediately – this would give White the option to push forward the f-pawn instead.} 15. h4 $1 Nxc3 {. If Black delays the capture on c3 , White will eventually retreat with the bishop and keep a solid plus with the bishop pair.} 16. bxc3 h5 17. Rd6 Qa5 18. Qd2 O-O 19. Bb3 {. White is slightly better – the position is playable for Black, but we're looking for more.}) 12. a3 {If White insists on the trade, you'll get something similar to the previous informational line, only with better prospects on the kingside.} Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Nd5 {Best keep the king in the center for a while.} 14. Bd2 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bg6 {Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways or start a queenside attack while keeping the king in the center for the moment.} *

