 17. Rd6 Qa5 18. Qd2 O-O 19. Bb3 {. White is slightly better – the position is playable for Black, but we're looking for more.}) 12. Kb1 {A typical waiting move – White improves the king's placement and waits for Black to define the setup. It also may open the possibility of the knight jump when Black's ... Bxd2 won't be a check anymore.} Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Nd5 {Black's plan is the same – keep the king in the center for the moment and start a queenside attack.} 14. Bd2 b5 15. Bd3 {Retreating on b3 would only fuel Black's queenside initiative.} (15. Bxd5 $6 cxd5 16. Nd3 Rc8 {looks like a strategic disaster for White.}) 15... Nxe5 16. Bxf5 {White can't allow Black to form a powerful outpost in the center.} (16. dxe5 Bxd3 17. cxd3 c5 {. The engine says that the position is still equal, but if someone can get here in trouble, it's only White.}) 16... Nc4 17. Bc1 a5 18. Bd3 Ncb6 {Most likely, Black should proceed by pushing forward the queenside pawns and see what happens, but even a long castle might be an option at some point. For the moment, the king feels safe in the center. Black should aim to preserve the blockaded knight on d5 , under whose cover they can wait on the flank.} *

