to ignite a queenside attack. Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from.} (10... h5 $5 {is an interesting resource to stop White's pawn advancement but also quite risky.} 11. h3 $1 h4 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 {The only capture to stop White's d5 push.} 13. Bg5 {Black is still far from solving all the opening problems. Check the sample line.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. d5 $1 {This move is logical with the black king in the center.} exd5 16. Bxd5 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Qf3 $1 {. As it turns out, including earlier moves 11.h3 h4 is in favor of White since Black no longer has the ... Bg4 resource.} Bg6 18. Be4 Kc8 19. Bxg6 Bf4+ {Black is desperately trying to stay in the game.} 20. Kb1 fxg6 21. Qg4+ f5 22. Qxg6 {. There goes a pawn.} Qh7 23. Qf6 Be5 24. Qg5 Qh5 25. Qe3 Kb8 {. Maybe with perfect defense, Black can hold this, but it can't be much fun.}) (10... Nxe5 $2 {. Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines – here, it leads to a disaster.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {. Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. White's f5 push is unstoppable.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {. White crashes through and has a winning attack.}) 11. f3 {A standard idea for White – prepare the kingside pawn push and secure the important e4 -square.} h5 {Black cools down White's ambitions on the kingside. It's also possible to take on c3 immediately and proceed with Nd5 afterward, but this would allow White to gain some space on the kingside with g4 .} (11... Nxe5 {. Albeit it feels to be a standard continuation for the setup, specifically in this line, White secures an advantage.} 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. g4 $1 {. The surprise – White doesn't mind ruining their queenside pawn structure.} Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Bg6 {. More accurate than taking on c3 immediately – this would give White the option to push forward the f-pawn instead.} 15. h4 $1 Nxc3 {. If Black delays the capture on c3 , White will eventually retreat with the bishop and keep a solid plus with the bishop pair.} 16. bxc3 h5 17. Rd6 Qa5 18. Qd2 O-O 19. Bb3 {. White is slightly better – the position is playable for Black, but we're looking for more.}) 12. Kb1 {A typical waiting move – White improves the king's placement and waits for Black to define the setup. It also may open the possibility of the knight jump when Black's ... Bxd2 won't be a check anymore.} Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Nd5 {Black's plan is the same – keep the king in the center for the moment and start a queenside attack.} 14. Bd2 b5 15. Nxd7 (15. Bxd5 $6 cxd5 16. Nd3 Rc8 {looks like a strategic disaster for White.}) 15... Qxd7 {Simple and good.} 16. Bb3 a5 17. a3 a4 18. Ba2 Qb7 {Black has a good game using the light squares.} ({g4 . Here's one sample line on how the game might continue.} 18... Bg6 {gxh5 Rxh5} 19. Rdg1 {. A very concrete plan.} b4 $1 {Rxg6 bxa3} {( axb4 Qd7! )} 20. axb4 {axb3 Bxb3 fxg6 Qxe6+} Kf8 21. Re1 {. The game continues to be very sharp. Rf5 Qxg6 Rxf3 Ka2} Rb8 {Qh7 . White escapes with a perpetual check: Rxb3 Qh8+ Kf7 Qh5+ Kg8 Re8+ Rxe8 Qxe8+ Kh7 cxb3} 22. Qa6 {Qh5+ . Obviously, this is not a forced line, but it should give you some extra ideas for the possibilities in the position.}) *

