to ignite a queenside attack. Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from.} (10... h5 $5 {is an interesting resource to stop White's pawn advancement but also quite risky.} 11. h3 $1 h4 12. Nxd7 Kxd7 {The only capture to stop White's d5 push.} 13. Bg5 {Black is still far from solving all the opening problems. Check the sample line.} Bd6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. d5 $1 {This move is logical with the black king in the center.} exd5 16. Bxd5 $1 Rae8 $1 17. Qf3 $1 {. As it turns out, including earlier moves 11.h3 h4 is in favor of White since Black no longer has the ... Bg4 resource.} Bg6 18. Be4 Kc8 19. Bxg6 Bf4+ {Black is desperately trying to stay in the game.} 20. Kb1 fxg6 21. Qg4+ f5 22. Qxg6 {. There goes a pawn.} Qh7 23. Qf6 Be5 24. Qg5 Qh5 25. Qe3 Kb8 {. Maybe with perfect defense, Black can hold this, but it can't be much fun.}) (10... Nxe5 $2 {. Do not mix up this trade with some similar lines – here, it leads to a disaster.} 11. dxe5 Nd7 {. Jumping to d5 is hardly better; White would continue with the same plan.} 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. White's f5 push is unstoppable.} Be7 14. f5 exf5 15. e6 {. White crashes through and has a winning attack.}) 11. a3 {White aims for the bishop pair.} Bxc3 {Don't be afraid to give up the dark-squared bishop – White can't use the a3 - f8 diagonal.} 12. Bxc3 Nd5 {More accurate than capturing on c3 first. Black has a simple setup: ... O-O-O , ... Qb6 - c5 , ... h7 - h5 , and then either an exchange of rooks or ... a7 - a5 , aiming to hunt down the bishop. Black’s position is no worse, but at the transition to the middlegame, Black needs to be more precise.} (12... Nxe5 {. If you start with this capture, it gives White an unnecessary extra option.} 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Bd4 {. Black will have to work a little to equalize, since the perspectives of the black queen now are somewhat limited.}) *

