he next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. O-O-O {The most principled continuation.} e6 {We've reached the second most important position in the Scandinavian Defense, which was considered the most important in the pre-engine era.  The evaluation often varied from 'White has a large advantage' to 'Black is doing completely fine.' In our opinion, White is better, but Black has a clear plan for counterplay. Combined with some dynamic resources, this will allow you to equalize the position and achieve a good game.   However, the amount of tournament wins you will gather in this setup is more important than the engine's evaluation.   Let's talk about some important details. White has two standalone plans:   1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns.   2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black – in this scenario, you won't have either the bishop pair or space. This plan is more dangerous, and it's not a surprise that Anish Giri recommends it. On the positive side, in this plan, you will have to remember less, how to play and keep counterchances.} 10. Nh4 Bg6 {The only reasonable move. White will establish the bishop pair, but the question is – what happens then?} ({The tempting move} 10... Bg4 $2 {is borderline losing.} 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. g4 {Watch out for this maneuver – even though it seems to be preparing the more natural f4 - f5 push, White might also be threatening with the immediate g5 push.} Nb6 {The simplest plan.} (11... Bb4 {. If you don't mind having some fun, you can enter some crazy lines that will require you to know a lot of precise moves. With a perfect play, the game should end in a draw, but most likely, in an actual game, you won't be able to remember/pick up the moves. It is not the plan of our repertoire.} 12. Bb3 a5 13. f4 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Be4 {. So far, everything is logical – now Black has to find a series of only moves to make a draw.} 15. g5 a4 {. Important intermezzo.} 16. Bc4 Bxh1 17. gxf6 Bd5 18. fxg7 Rg8 19. Bd3 {. The first part of the forced moves is over, and the fight continues.} b5 $1 20. Rg1 Qd6 $1 21. Nf5 Qa3+ 22. Kd1 Qxa2 23. Ke1 {. White's initiative looks quite scary.} Nf6 24. Qe5 Qb1+ 25. Kf2 Ng4+ $3 {. Nice idea!} 26. Rxg4 Qd1 27. Kg3 h5 $1 {. This isn't easy to explain, but let's follow the engine line.} 28. Rg5 Qxd2 29. Kh3 a3 $1 {. Black is brave and says there is no mate.} 30. Nh6 O-O-O 31. Nxg8 Rxg8 32. Qd6 Kb7 33. Qe7+ Kb6 34. Qf8 e5 $3 {. An impossible move to find if no prior knowledge.} 35. Qxg8 Be6+ 36. f5 Qxg5 37. Qb8+ Ka6 38. g8=Q {White is up a queen!} Bxf5+ 39. Bxf5 Qxf5+ 40. Kg2 Qe4+ {. The game ends with a non-obvious perpetual check.}) 12. Bb3 O-O-O 13. Nxg6 hxg6 {Since Black is threatening to pick up the h-pawn as well, White doesn't have a lot of choices.} 14. g5 Ne8 {Better than positioning the knight on the edge of the board.} 15. h4 Bb4 16. a3 Ba5 {Quite unusual, but White can't do anything about the incoming ... Nd5 move.} 17. Qf3 Nd5 18. Bxd5 cxd5 {Black has excellent chances to win.} *

