g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Bxe6 {This shot you should never miss; it is a recurring theme in similar positions, but it doesn't work here.} fxe6 12. Qxe6+ Be7 13. Rhe1 {This has been known for a long time. Black defends the bishop on e7 with a tempo. The king is ready to escape to f7 if necessary.} Nf8 14. Qe2 {White ensures the black king can't escape f7 .} Bh5 {Before positioning the bishop on f7 to close the e-file with Ne6 , Black takes away from White some extra options.} 15. f3 Bf7 {Since Black wants to play ... Ne6 and castle away from the danger, White has to do something quickly.} 16. d5 {White attempts to keep the initiative going by including more pieces in the attack.} Nxd5 17. Nf5 Ne6 {Black's defensive plan remains the same.} 18. Nxd5 cxd5 19. Nxe7 Qxe7 20. f4 {White's last attempt.} Rc8 {The only move but good enough to ensure Black's advantage.} 21. f5 Rxc2+ 22. Kb1 {White can't take the rook.} (22. Kxc2 $2 Nd4+ {. This line is very forcing and easy to calculate.} 23. Kd3 Nxe2 24. Rxe2 Qxe2+ 25. Kxe2 Bh5+ {, and Black wins more material.}) 22... O-O {It's time to give up the extra material, ensure the king's safety, and go for a counter-attack.} 23. fxe6 Bg6 24. Ka1 Be4 {Black is more active.} 25. Rc1 Rxc1+ 26. Rxc1 Qxe6 {Black has an extra pawn for nothing.} *

