he next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. O-O-O {The most principled continuation.} e6 {We've reached the second most important position in the Scandinavian Defense, which was considered the most important in the pre-engine era.  The evaluation often varied from 'White has a large advantage' to 'Black is doing completely fine.' In our opinion, White is better, but Black has a clear plan for counterplay. Combined with some dynamic resources, this will allow you to equalize the position and achieve a good game.   However, the amount of tournament wins you will gather in this setup is more important than the engine's evaluation.   Let's talk about some important details. White has two standalone plans:   1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns.   2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black – in this scenario, you won't have either the bishop pair or space. This plan is more dangerous, and it's not a surprise that Anish Giri recommends it. On the positive side, in this plan, you will have to remember less, how to play and keep counterchances.} 10. Nh4 Bg6 {The only reasonable move. White will establish the bishop pair, but the question is – what happens then?} ({The tempting move} 10... Bg4 $2 {is borderline losing.} 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Nxg6 {The most popular continuation in the position, after which White will have several interesting continuations at their disposal.} hxg6 12. d5 {For some time, the popular belief was that White here has very good chances for an advantage, but the practice of recent years has proven that Black does well.} cxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be7 {A strong move – Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways.} (14... O-O-O $6 {. One of those moments when the most obvious (and popular) move in the position is a weak choice.} 15. Bg5 $1 {. Very strong – the point is that if Black will retreat with the rook, White can keep the bishop on d5 and do something else, gaining valuable time.}) ({Bf3 is not that dangerous for Black.} 14... Bd6 {½–½ Leinier Domínguez (2758) – Magnus Carlsen (2847), Aimchess US Rapid Prelim chess24.com INT 2021 (8)} 15. Bc3 e5 {Bd5 . White is slightly better, but not much.}) 15. Rhe1 {If White does this, the typical h4 - h5 threat now is much slower since the white rook has left the h-file and Black can safely castle short.} O-O 16. Bf3 {The sacrifice on e6 would not work.} Rac8 17. c3 Nb6 {As you can see, White's h4 - h5 here already might be too slow, since Black will develop an initiative on the queenside.} *

