1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 {What else can be dangerous if White does not want to jump with the knight to e5 , go for quite forcing lines and with radical play prove their ambitions against the Scandinavian defense? Of course, it's the poisonous plan with Qe2 and O-O-O . In this chapter, we will analyze this system in depth.} (7. Ne5 {is the most principled approach for White. Ne5} e6 8. g4 Bg6 {. It's detailed in Chapter 2 .}) 7... Nbd7 {Black deals with the Ne5 possibility and ensures that the Nd5 jump is not dangerous at the moment.} (7... e6 $6 {. White has already created a threat to jump with the knight to d5 ; thus, ignoring your opponent's threats can't end well.} 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+ {. The point is that with both captures on f6 , Black experiences problems:} ({a. gxf6 does not create any desired dynamics on the g-file.} 9. O-O {Nd7 Re1 White is better, and Black struggles to complete the development. Castling long does not feel safe here, and Black might not even make it.} Qc7 $6 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 {Bxe6! . White can start immediate active operations against the stranded king. fxe6 Rxe6+ Kf7} 11. Qe2 {Nb6 Re1 , and White's attack is decisive.})) {b. Qxf6 Qe2 Nd7 ( Bxc2? . You can't take the pawn due to a typical anti-Scandinavian trick. d5! cxd5 Bb5+ Nc6 Bc3 Qg6 Nd4 There's more than one possibility for White – the point is that Black is suffering everywhere. ) O-O-O . Now Black should watch out for the d5 push. Be7 Bg5 Qg6 Bxe7 Kxe7 . Black will have to survive with an exposed king – maybe with a perfect play, it's possible, but it's not a fun way to play.} 8. Qe2 {This is not the only possible continuation for White, but the only one you should study carefully. In any other variations, Black has no issues whatsoever.} (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Ne3 {is covered in Chapter 4 .}) (8. O-O e6 {is also covered in the next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. O-O-O {The most principled continuation.} e6 {We've reached the second most important position in the Scandinavian Defense, which was considered the most important in the pre-engine era.  The evaluation often varied from 'White has a large advantage' to 'Black is doing completely fine.' In our opinion, White is better, but Black has a clear plan for counterplay. Combined with some dynamic resources, this will allow you to equalize the position and achieve a good game.   However, the amount of tournament wins you will gather in this setup is more important than the engine's evaluation.   Let's talk about some important details. White has two standalone plans:   1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns.   2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black – in this scenario, you won't have either the bishop pair or space. This plan is more dangerous, and it's not a surprise that Anish Giri recommends it. On the positive side, in this plan, you will have to remember less, how to play and keep counterchances.} 10. Nh4 Bg6 {The only reasonable move. White will establish the bishop pair, but the question is – what happens then?} ({The tempting move} 10... Bg4 $2 {is borderline losing.} 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Nxg6 {The most popular continuation in the position, after which White will have several interesting continuations at their disposal.} hxg6 12. d5 {For some time, the popular belief was that White here has very good chances for an advantage, but the practice of recent years has proven that Black does well.} cxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be7 {A strong move – Black keeps the opportunity to castle both ways.} (14... O-O-O $6 {. One of those moments when the most obvious (and popular) move in the position is a weak choice.} 15. Bg5 $1 {. Very strong – the point is that if Black will retreat with the rook, White can keep the bishop on d5 and do something else, gaining valuable time.}) ({Bf3 is not that dangerous for Black.} 14... Bd6 {½–½ Leinier Domínguez (2758) – Magnus Carlsen (2847), Aimchess US Rapid Prelim chess24.com INT 2021 (8)} 15. Bc3 e5 {Bd5 . White is slightly better, but not much.}) 15. Bf3 {The most logical move – White anticipates Black's castling either way to determine, how to start a direct attack.} Bf6 {The first thing you want to do is give your bishop the best possible square for activity and keep your eyes open.} 16. h4 O-O-O {Again, Black reacts the same – castle away from the danger.} (16... Rxh4 {. Accepting sacrifices is principled, but it's just dangerous here.} 17. Rxh4 Bxh4 18. Rh1 Be7 19. Rh8+ Bf8 20. a4 {. The engine says that this is somehow still playable for Black, but the risk here is greater than the reward.}) 17. g3 Ne5 18. Bf4 Qc5 {White has a bishop pair in a semi-open position – naturally, you'd like to trade one of them.} 19. Bg2 Nc4 20. c3 e5 {Black should play it out energetically and seek counter-chances. This move also forces White to trade one of the bishops.} 21. Bg5 Bxg5+ 22. hxg5 Rxh1 23. Rxh1 e4 {The most precise move – with the knight on c4 , the white king should feel uneasy.} 24. Bxe4 Qxg5+ 25. f4 Qc5 26. Bc2 Nd6 {Since there's no real attack on the queenside, it's time to fight for the e-file. Black has successfully equalized the game.} *

