derline losing.} 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Nxg6 {The most popular continuation in the position, after which White will have several interesting continuations at their disposal.} hxg6 12. Bb3 {A smart waiting move – White offers a pawn sacrifice on h2 .} Rxh2 {A pawn is a pawn.} (12... b5 $2 {. Unfortunately, you can't do this.} 13. d5 $1 {Now this works.} cxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 {The pawn on b5 is a weakness that Black created himself.} Rb8 16. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Be7 18. Rhe1 {, and White's attack is decisive.}) 13. Bxe6 {This sacrifice works again, but there's an important nuance.} fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Kd8 {A necessary move.} (14... Be7 $2 {. Unfortunately, due to the black rook's placement on h2 , this typical defense does not work here.} 15. Rxh2 Qxh2 16. Re1 {, and Black can't defend the bishop on e7 .}) 15. Rhe1 Rh8 {Black holds everything together.} 16. Bg5 {Black can parry the direct mate threats.} Bb4 17. Qf7 Kc8 {Black walks away from two pins and is ready to consolidate the pieces.} 18. d5 Bxc3 19. bxc3 cxd5 20. Qxg7 Rf8 {Black's defenses are holding.} 21. Re6 (21. Bxf6 Qf4+ $1 {. Remember this check.}) 21... Qxc3 {White has to find the only way to escape with a draw.} 22. Bxf6 Rxf6 23. Qh8+ Kc7 24. Qh2+ Kd8 *

