g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Nxg6 {The most popular continuation in the position, after which White will have several interesting continuations at their disposal.} hxg6 12. g3 {If White slowly improves the piece and pawn coordination on the kingside, you can initiate activity on the queenside. This move also signals that White is not planning a kingside attack, at least not immediately.} b5 13. Bd3 {This is a pattern you should recognize – when White's knight is on and the light-squared bishop on d3 , Black's ... b4 push is pretty effective, as White rarely can play Na4 due to ... Qa5 and ... Nb6 .} b4 14. Ne4 (14. Nb1 {looks too passive to be good.} Qa5 15. Bc4 Nb6 {. Even though White appears to be quite solid, Black has achieved a little more than White has on the kingside.}) 14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bf3 a5 {The position is about balanced, but Black's plan looks pretty clear.} *

