1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 {What else can be dangerous if White does not want to jump with the knight to e5 , go for quite forcing lines and with radical play prove their ambitions against the Scandinavian defense? Of course, it's the poisonous plan with Qe2 and O-O-O . In this chapter, we will analyze this system in depth.} (7. Ne5 {is the most principled approach for White. Ne5} e6 8. g4 Bg6 {. It's detailed in Chapter 2 .}) 7... Nbd7 {Black deals with the Ne5 possibility and ensures that the Nd5 jump is not dangerous at the moment.} (7... e6 $6 {. White has already created a threat to jump with the knight to d5 ; thus, ignoring your opponent's threats can't end well.} 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+ {. The point is that with both captures on f6 , Black experiences problems:} ({a. gxf6 does not create any desired dynamics on the g-file.} 9. O-O {Nd7 Re1 White is better, and Black struggles to complete the development. Castling long does not feel safe here, and Black might not even make it.} Qc7 $6 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 {Bxe6! . White can start immediate active operations against the stranded king. fxe6 Rxe6+ Kf7} 11. Qe2 {Nb6 Re1 , and White's attack is decisive.})) {b. Qxf6 Qe2 Nd7 ( Bxc2? . You can't take the pawn due to a typical anti-Scandinavian trick. d5! cxd5 Bb5+ Nc6 Bc3 Qg6 Nd4 There's more than one possibility for White – the point is that Black is suffering everywhere. ) O-O-O . Now Black should watch out for the d5 push. Be7 Bg5 Qg6 Bxe7 Kxe7 . Black will have to survive with an exposed king – maybe with a perfect play, it's possible, but it's not a fun way to play.} 8. Qe2 {This is not the only possible continuation for White, but the only one you should study carefully. In any other variations, Black has no issues whatsoever.} (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Ne3 {is covered in Chapter 4 .}) (8. O-O e6 {is also covered in the next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. O-O-O {The most principled continuation.} e6 {We've reached the second most important position in the Scandinavian Defense, which was considered the most important in the pre-engine era.  The evaluation often varied from 'White has a large advantage' to 'Black is doing completely fine.' In our opinion, White is better, but Black has a clear plan for counterplay. Combined with some dynamic resources, this will allow you to equalize the position and achieve a good game.   However, the amount of tournament wins you will gather in this setup is more important than the engine's evaluation.   Let's talk about some important details. White has two standalone plans:   1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns.   2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black – in this scenario, you won't have either the bishop pair or space. This plan is more dangerous, and it's not a surprise that Anish Giri recommends it. On the positive side, in this plan, you will have to remember less, how to play and keep counterchances.} 10. Nh4 Bg6 {The only reasonable move. White will establish the bishop pair, but the question is – what happens then?} ({The tempting move} 10... Bg4 $2 {is borderline losing.} 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Nxg6 {The most popular continuation in the position, after which White will have several interesting continuations at their disposal.} hxg6 12. h4 {This is a signature move to start an attack on the kingside. White awaits Black's short castle with the h5 push but keeps the g4 - g5 push on the table.} b5 ({When recommending Bb3 in his course, Anish Giri avoided this plan for Black.} 12... O-O-O {. If you're afraid of mixing something up or don’t remember the details, you can always transpose to the main line.} 13. Bb3 Nb6 14. Bg5 Be7 15. g3 a6 {. It's possible to double the rooks on the d-file immediately. After} 16. Kb1 {, we have reached a position from the main line – Black has no reasons to be unhappy, but if you can play something better earlier, do it.}) 13. Bb3 Nb6 {Please pay attention that with the pawn on b5 , Black has many great opportunities, but the most important one is to fight for the d5 -square.} 14. g4 a5 {Now White faces a choice – should they react to Black's ... a4 threat or charge forward with g5 ?} 15. a4 {A very responsible move, but even for a good player, it's easy to miss Black's next move.} Bb4 {This puts White in a position where they have to prove something immediately.} 16. g5 {A much sharper continuation where the consequences are tough to evaluate.} Nh5 {Jumping to d5 would lead to material losses, but here, Black is eyeing to exploit the weakness on f4 .} 17. Bxe6 Nf4 {As long as you remember that you don't always have to accept the sacrifice on e6 , you're good.} 18. Bxf4 Qxf4+ 19. Kb1 Bxc3 20. bxc3 {White can give a discovered check, but it doesn't achieve much – the black king will feel safe on f8 as well.} O-O 21. h5 Rfe8 {A very cool defense – White has nothing.} 22. Qg4 Qxg4 23. Bxg4 Nxa4 24. Rd3 Rad8 {The position remains double-edged.} *

