g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Nxg6 {The most popular continuation in the position, after which White will have several interesting continuations at their disposal.} hxg6 12. h4 {This is a signature move to start an attack on the kingside. White awaits Black's short castle with the h5 push but keeps the g4 - g5 push on the table.} b5 ({When recommending Bb3 in his course, Anish Giri avoided this plan for Black.} 12... O-O-O {. If you're afraid of mixing something up or don’t remember the details, you can always transpose to the main line.} 13. Bb3 Nb6 14. Bg5 Be7 15. g3 a6 {. It's possible to double the rooks on the d-file immediately. After} 16. Kb1 {, we have reached a position from the main line – Black has no reasons to be unhappy, but if you can play something better earlier, do it.}) 13. Bd3 {Here, the bishop feels safer than on b3 , but White no longer has the sacrifice ideas on e6 . Maybe Bxg6 at some point still could be an option?} b4 {This line is very similar to the one where, instead of h4 , White had played g3 – your response will be the same.} 14. Ne4 {Leaping to a4 would give White problems after ... Qa5 and ... Nb6 .} Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bf3 Rb8 ({It's possible to start also with} 16... a5 {, but the text move feels more precise because Black is bringing the ... Nd5 - c3 maneuver on the table, while the a-pawn push in some lines might be a little slow.}) 17. g4 {White goes for it.} ({Compared to the line with} 17. g3 {, White can start swift action on the kingside.}) 17... Nd5 {White has to be a little careful because Black's plan is very straightforward, and the king in the center feels safe.} 18. h5 {White can also stick to the plan and keep the king on c1 .} gxh5 19. gxh5 Be7 {If you analyze the position a little deeper, you might conclude that it's not so easy for White to come up with the next moves if they don't involve Kb1 .} 20. Q