 to increase the power for the light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, it's scary for White to position the king on a potential x-ray with the black rook. Considering Black's plans to play ... Bf6 and either ... Qa5 or ... a5 - a4 , there might be no choice.} Be7 {Black keeps all options – maybe hit the pawn on h4 , perhaps position the dark-squared bishop on f6 , or go for a queenside attack. Just keeping eyes open.} 19. h5 gxh5 20. gxh5 Nc3+ ({Also} 20... a5 {seriously deserves some attention, but the knight jump is just too tempting.}) 21. Bxc3 bxc3 22. b3 Bf6 23. Qc4 O-O {It's well known that opposite color bishops often feel like an extra piece when there's a direct attack. The white king can become much weaker than the black king.} ({After h6 , here's a sample line of how the game might continue:} 23... g6 {. A typical way to secure the king's safety.} 24. Qxc3 {Rfd8 Qxc6} Qf4 {Qe4 . White has to trade off the queens as quickly as possible. Unfortunately, Black can't keep them, and White is also losing some pawns. Qxe4} 25. Be4 {Rxd4 Rxd4} Bxd4 {. White keeps the extra pawn, but here it's irrelevant. h7+ Kh8} 26. f3 f5 27. Bd3 e5 {. With perfect play from both sides, the game is heading toward a logical and peaceful outcome.}) *

