1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 {What else can be dangerous if White does not want to jump with the knight to e5 , go for quite forcing lines and with radical play prove their ambitions against the Scandinavian defense? Of course, it's the poisonous plan with Qe2 and O-O-O . In this chapter, we will analyze this system in depth.} (7. Ne5 {is the most principled approach for White. Ne5} e6 8. g4 Bg6 {. It's detailed in Chapter 2 .}) 7... Nbd7 {Black deals with the Ne5 possibility and ensures that the Nd5 jump is not dangerous at the moment.} (7... e6 $6 {. White has already created a threat to jump with the knight to d5 ; thus, ignoring your opponent's threats can't end well.} 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Nxf6+ {. The point is that with both captures on f6 , Black experiences problems:} ({a. gxf6 does not create any desired dynamics on the g-file.} 9. O-O {Nd7 Re1 White is better, and Black struggles to complete the development. Castling long does not feel safe here, and Black might not even make it.} Qc7 $6 10. Nh4 $1 Bg6 {Bxe6! . White can start immediate active operations against the stranded king. fxe6 Rxe6+ Kf7} 11. Qe2 {Nb6 Re1 , and White's attack is decisive.})) {b. Qxf6 Qe2 Nd7 ( Bxc2? . You can't take the pawn due to a typical anti-Scandinavian trick. d5! cxd5 Bb5+ Nc6 Bc3 Qg6 Nd4 There's more than one possibility for White – the point is that Black is suffering everywhere. ) O-O-O . Now Black should watch out for the d5 push. Be7 Bg5 Qg6 Bxe7 Kxe7 . Black will have to survive with an exposed king – maybe with a perfect play, it's possible, but it's not a fun way to play.} 8. Qe2 {This is not the only possible continuation for White, but the only one you should study carefully. In any other variations, Black has no issues whatsoever.} (8. Nd5 Qd8 9. Ne3 {is covered in Chapter 4 .}) (8. O-O e6 {is also covered in the next chapter .}) 8... Qc7 {It's time to retreat.} (8... e6 $2 {. Once again, you have to follow your opponent's threats carefully to avoid unpleasant surprises.} 9. d5 $1 {. A widespread move against the Scandi.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 {. Sadly, Black is too exposed on the queenside to enter this position.} 11. b4 Qc8 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 {. Otherwise, Bb5 + will be a big problem.} 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 h5 15. f4 {, and White is almost winning.}) (8... Bxc2 $4 {. Don't even think about taking this pawn, at least very early in the opening phase when your king is in the center. The move has many problems, but in this position, White wins the game on the spot.} 9. Nb5 Qb6 10. Nd6+ {. The rest is just sad.}) 9. O-O-O {The most principled continuation.} e6 {We've reached the second most important position in the Scandinavian Defense, which was considered the most important in the pre-engine era.  The evaluation often varied from 'White has a large advantage' to 'Black is doing completely fine.' In our opinion, White is better, but Black has a clear plan for counterplay. Combined with some dynamic resources, this will allow you to equalize the position and achieve a good game.   However, the amount of tournament wins you will gather in this setup is more important than the engine's evaluation.   Let's talk about some important details. White has two standalone plans:   1) With the white knight on e5 , aggressively move forward kingside pawns.   2) Trade the kingside knight for Black's light-squared bishop and slowly squeeze Black – in this scenario, you won't have either the bishop pair or space. This plan is more dangerous, and it's not a surprise that Anish Giri recommends it. On the positive side, in this plan, you will have to remember less, how to play and keep counterchances.} 10. Nh4 Bg6 {The only reasonable move. White will establish the bishop pair, but the question is – what happens then?} ({The tempting move} 10... Bg4 $2 {is borderline losing.} 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 $1 {. This idea is important to know – the problem is that the jump on d5 now is impossible.} Nh5 14. Bxe6 {. White crashes through.}) 11. Bb3 {This is the recommendation of Anish Giri in his course – Black is in a weird zugzwang where it's difficult to find a good move with a counterplay, but you don't want to enter a 'let's get a slightly worse position, be solid and pray for better times'.} O-O-O {The best that Black can do.} (11... b5 $4 {. Unfortunately, here, this does not work – the white bishop is already on b3 .} 12. d5 {. Black's position is terrible.}) (11... Bb4 {. This line for Black is dangerous.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Kb1 a5 14. d5 {. White can immediately open the center.} cxd5 15. Bxd5 {. Black has no immediate attack on the queenside, White has the bishop pair in a semi-open position, and then there's the h4 –h5 push after the short castle – White is just better.}) 12. Nxg6 hxg6 {Black is slightly worse, but at least there will be clear plans to get a satisfactory game.} 13. h4 {White protects the h-pawn and improves their entire pawn structure.} (13. g3 Nb6 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bg5 Rd7 16. h4 {, follow the model game between Carlos Vila Hernández and Igor Kovalenko played by correspondence in 2024 during the writing of this course's theoretical part.}) 13... Nb6 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Qf3 {White has successfully avoided the complications with the ... b5 push, kept the h-pawn alive, and is planning to improve the position slowly. Blacks must solve the problem of making the 'right' trades. Otherwise, White might suffocate Black.} a6 {Black preps the eventual ... c5 push and secures the b5 -square in advance. It's also possible to start with ... Rd7 .} (15... Nbd5 $6 {. You would love to trade some pieces, but there's a problem.} 16. Ne2 $1 {. White will decline, and Black will start to experience the lack of available space for the pieces.}) 16. g3 Rd7 17. Kb1 (17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Bg5 Be7 {. Since White does not want to trade the bishops, this leads nowhere for them.}) 17... Rhd8 {Black has created some counterplay and is ready to execute the ... c5 push when the time is right.} 18. Bf4 Bd6 19. Bc1 Bf8 {White is back at the question – how to defend the d-pawn? Black could have considered the immediate c-pawn push as well.} 20. g4 {Very energetic.} c5 {A textbook response – Black should meet a flank attack with a counterstrike in the center.} (20... Rxd4 $2 {fails due to a simple tactic:} 21. Rxd4 Rxd4 22. g5 Ne8 {. Jumping on d5 would doom the rook on d4 .} 23. Bxe6+ fxe6 24. Qxf8 {. Black's position is bad – there are too many weaknesses.}) 21. dxc5 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Rxd1 23. Qxd1 Qxc5 {White is slightly pushing, but it's not enough, and with the g4 push, White has committed themself to some weaknesses that won't be easy to fix.} (23... g5 {. Here's how the game might continue. Nfd7 . Jump to d5 here would be a terrible mistake – White would trade on d5 and proceed with Qf3 .} 24. Ne4 {Qf5 Qe2 . White still wants to exploit the f-pawn as a target. Qb5 Qf3 Qf5 . Black is holding.}) *

