1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {A true Scandinavian player is never afraid of White's short castle; however, if White wants to do it, they should do it right now and not after Bd2 .} 7. O-O e6 8. Qe2 Nbd7 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. h3 (10. f4 $6 {. The desire to push f5 and open the light-squared bishop is understandable, but having already committed to Qe2 , here White is unable to accomplish the main idea, which is – to keep the black king in the center.} O-O-O {.}) 10... Be7 11. Bb3 O-O {Since White has no kingside attack, there's no need to postpone the castling or consider going the long way.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bf4 Rad8 {White has absolutely nothing – the bishop pair here doesn't leave any impression.} *

