1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {A true Scandinavian player is never afraid of White's short castle; however, if White wants to do it, they should do it right now and not after Bd2 .} 7. O-O e6 8. Re1 Nbd7 {Black keeps all options open – maybe castle long, consider ... Nb6 and start pressing White's d-pawn.} 9. Ne5 {Here, White's aggressiveness will backfire.} Nxe5 10. Rxe5 (10. dxe5 Ng4 {. White can't exploit the weakened d6 -square and has to deal with his weaknesses first.}) 10... Qb4 11. Bb3 O-O-O 12. Ne2 Qb6 {The white rook on e5 will cause White a lot of headaches.} *

