1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {A true Scandinavian player is never afraid of White's short castle; however, if White wants to do it, they should do it right now and not after Bd2 .} 7. O-O e6 8. Re1 (8. Bd2 Nbd7 {. Most likely, this will transpose to the other lines – the move order is flexible.}) 8... Nbd7 {Black keeps all options open – maybe castle long, consider ... Nb6 and start pressing White's d-pawn.} 9. Ne2 {White plans to reinforce the center with c3 and sets the stage for a potential queenside attack with b4 - a4 , etc. This is a clear sign that castling long isn’t the way to go.} Be7 10. Bd2 Qc7 {One of the best parts about the Scandinavian Defense that often does not work in other openings is that you can toy with castling both ways.} 11. c3 O-O 12. Nh4 Bd6 {If you know something about the Caro-Kann Tartakower variation or the Berlin system in the Ruy Lopez, you should know that doubling the f-pawn here is very much alright for Black.} 13. Nxf5 exf5 14. g3 Rfe8 {Black has a wonderful position.} *

