1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 {A true Scandinavian player is never afraid of White's short castle; however, if White wants to do it, they should do it right now and not after Bd2 .} 7. O-O e6 8. Nh4 {Since Black's light-squared bishop is strong, White would like to deal with it. Watch out for White's hidden threat!} (8. Bd2 Nbd7 {. Most likely, this will transpose to the other lines – the move order is flexible.}) 8... Nbd7 {Black remains alert – not only does White want to trade your light-squared bishop, but also bring the f4 - f5 push on the table.} ({The automatic move} 8... Bg6 $2 {is a serious inaccuracy.} 9. f4 Be7 ({(Or} 9... Nbd7 {, it doesn't change much.)}) 10. f5 $1 exf5 11. Qe2 {, and White keeps the black king in the center. Together with the Nxf5 idea at the right moment, White secures a large advantage.}) (8... Bg4 $6 {. In some other scenarios, this could be a great resource, but here, it backfires.} 9. f3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. f4 {. Black has no satisfactory response to White's pawn assault.}) 9. Nxf5 (9. h3 {. If White plays something slow as this, like Bd2 or Qe2 , then you can retreat with the bishop on g6 since White's f4 –f5 threat will be too slow to stop you from castling.} Bg6 {. White's f4 – f5 idea no longer can keep the black king in the center.}) 9... Qxf5 {Quite an important resource of still having the queen on the 5th rank!} 10. Re1 Bd6 11. g3 Rd8 12. Bd3 Qa5 {Black has a good game. White's two bishops here don't feel significant, and White can't easily finish the development and avoid simplifications at the same time. On top of that, Black can prep either the ... e5 or the ... c5 push, depending on your taste.} *

