1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nh4 e6 {The easiest choice – Black can ignore White's threat and continue the development. If you're looking for some excitement, there's another option!} (8... Bg6 $2 {. This retreat to g6 would be pretty standard, if not for some specific details.} 9. g4 $1 {. Once more, recognize the dangers of White's aggressive pawn pushes on the kingside. The black queen on a5 here is misplaced.} e6 10. g5 {. That's the idea – there's no jump to d5 .} Nh5 $2 11. Be2 {. The black knight is trapped.}) 9. Nxf5 Qxf5 10. Bd3 {Because White is moving with the bishop for a second time, this is not dangerous for Black.} Qa5 11. Qf3 Qb6 12. Qf4 g6 {A worthy idea to know – you don't always have to position your bishop on the standard e7 - or d6 -squares; sometimes it can be pretty powerful on g7 .} 13. O-O-O Bg7 14. h4 h5 {Black is rock solid.} *

