1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nh4 e6 {The easiest choice – Black can ignore White's threat and continue the development. If you're looking for some excitement, there's another option!} (8... Bg6 $2 {. This retreat to g6 would be pretty standard, if not for some specific details.} 9. g4 $1 {. Once more, recognize the dangers of White's aggressive pawn pushes on the kingside. The black queen on a5 here is misplaced.} e6 10. g5 {. That's the idea – there's no jump to d5 .} Nh5 $2 11. Be2 {. The black knight is trapped.}) 9. Nxf5 Qxf5 10. O-O Bd6 11. Bd3 Qg4 {Now there's no ... Qa5 maneuver because Black has committed to ... Bd6 , but there are other retreat squares as well.} 12. Qxg4 Nxg4 13. g3 Ngf6 14. a4 a5 {White has a symbolic edge but nothing more.} *

