1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nh4 Bg4 {This is a sharper continuation.} 9. f3 Qh5 {The point – instead of the automatic retreat on h5 Black hits the knight. Remember this maneuver might be useful in similar positions.} 10. g3 Bh3 {The arising positions are very complex that not everyone might enjoy – Black makes many moves with the queen.} 11. Qe2 {With attempts to trap the black queen, White might castle long.} O-O-O 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. Bd3 {Not an obvious choice. Although sacrificing the d4 -pawn in the Scandinavian Defense is a common idea, White usually exploits the lead in development, not trapping Black's pieces.} Rxd4 14. Qf2 Rxd3 {Since the queen is in danger and the g4 push is a threat, Black has no choice, but this is a great positional sacrifice.} 15. cxd3 Qa5 {If White tries to push g4 to trap the bishop, Black will respond with ... h5 .} 16. Rhe1 e6 17. Kb1 Qa6 {Black has a good game. Even though White has a small material advantage, the outpost on d5 guarantees Black full compensation.} ({After g4 , the game might continue:} 17... h5 {g5 Nfd5} 18. Ne4 {. It might require from White some courage to give up the d-pawn with a check. Qxd3+ Ka1} Qb5 $1 19. Nc3 {Nxc3 Bxc3} Qg5 20. Rg1 Qf4 {. The game remains wild.}) *

