1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nh4 Bg4 {This is a sharper continuation.} 9. f3 Qh5 {The point – instead of the automatic retreat on h5 Black hits the knight. Remember this maneuver might be useful in similar positions.} 10. g3 Bh3 {The arising positions are very complex that not everyone might enjoy – Black makes many moves with the queen.} 11. Be2 {White prepares the f4 push to harass the black queen.} h6 {Wonders of the engines. Black ignores White's idea and preps a future ... g5 push, but it makes more sense with the queen gone from the h5 -square so you're not self-trapping the queen.} 12. f4 Qa5 13. Ne4 Qd5 14. Nf2 g5 ({Now you see the purpose of h6 .} 14... Nb6 $6 {would allow White to tighten the grip and claim some space advantage.} 15. Bf3 Qe6+ 16. Qe2 Qxe2+ 17. Bxe2 Be6 18. b3 Rd8 19. c3 {. Black is getting suffocated – that's the scenario you want to avoid.}) 15. fxg5 hxg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. Nxh3 Qh6 {Black has an interesting game for the sacrificed pawn, but it's up to you to decide if it's worth a pawn.} *

