1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. O-O {White's short castle combined with the humble Bd2 can't give him hope for an advantage.} e6 {The black queen can remain on a5 since no notable discovered attacks exist.} 9. Nh4 Bg4 {Here, you can also retreat on g6 since White's g4 - g5 threat is not as dangerous as before – White has already committed to the short castle. The text move is a little more ambitious.} 10. Qe1 {This idea is borrowed from the Exchange Caro-Kann to continue with f3 and Qg3 , but Black can successfully counter it.} Qb6 {Provoking the bishop on e3 where it will limit the scope of the white queen.} 11. Be3 Qc7 {Black takes away White's Qg3 plan and can castle both ways.} *

