1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. O-O {White's short castle combined with the humble Bd2 can't give him hope for an advantage.} e6 {The black queen can remain on a5 since no notable discovered attacks exist.} 9. Nh4 Bg4 {Here, you can also retreat on g6 since White's g4 - g5 threat is not as dangerous as before – White has already committed to the short castle. The text move is a little more ambitious.} 10. f3 Bh5 (10... Qh5 $4 {. Unfortunately, here, this intermezzo move is a terrible mistake.} 11. Qe1 {or Be1 – White is not obliged to play g3 .}) 11. g4 {If White has already castled short and Black has not, this can only be dangerous to White.} Bg6 12. g5 {White is harassing the knight and stops it from landing on d5 – we've seen this idea before, but now Black has a powerful idea.} Qb6 {With this trick Black re-enables the Nd5 jump.} (12... Nh5 13. f4 {, and Black has some problems.}) 13. Be1 Nd5 14. Bxd5 cxd5 15. f4 Be4 {Black is alright, while White has committed to many weaknesses on the kingside.} ({After the move Bf2 , the game might continue.} 15... Qc6 16. Ne4 dxe4 17. Qe2 h6 18. c4 hxg5 19. fxg5 Be7 {. The white king is starting to feel some heat.} 20. d5 exd5 21. Nf5 Ne5 {. The game is very complex but objectively equal.}) *

