1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nd5 {That's the jump you should expect at any moment if your queen is still on a5 . White might also include the d5 push and capture with the knight.} Qd8 9. Nxf6+ {This trade is not dangerous because Black gets more space for the other pieces, and one of White's core ideas against the Scandinavian Defense is to claim space advantage.} Nxf6 10. Bb3 e6 11. Qe2 a5 {Typical claim for some extra space on the queenside, but there's also a deeper idea that White can easily miss.} 12. a4 Bg4 {Black could also continue the development with 12... Bd6 , and if White castles the long way, fire up the queenside with ... b5 , even if it costs a pawn.} 13. c3 {Now you see the point of including ... a5 – White might have some problems with the b-pawn.} Bd6 {A little more precise than the immediate ... Qb6 . The point is that White will have to sacrifice the b-pawn and then use the b-file for some counterplay. That's why it's better to continue development and keep the idea of ... Qb6 for a better moment.} 14. h3 Bxf3 {Now Black has no choice, but also White has committed to the h3 move, which might just be useless.} 15. Qxf3 Qb6 16. Bc2 {White could protect the bishop with Qd1 , but his piece coordination would be awkward.} Qxb2 17. Rc1 Qb6 {White has compensation for the pawn but nothing more, and he'll have to prove it with active play. Black castles short and plays rock-solid chess.} *

