1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nd5 {That's the jump you should expect at any moment if your queen is still on a5 . White might also include the d5 push and capture with the knight.} Qd8 9. Ne3 {It might seem that the white knight on e3 stands a little awkward, but it does support pushing forward the pawns.} Bg6 {It is possible to retreat with the bishop to the usual g6 -square, but White always gets some advantage in all lines.} 10. Qe2 e6 11. O-O-O Qc7 12. h4 {That is a very annoying idea. If Black blocks the pawn with ... h5 , it weakens the g5 -square and creates an outpost for the white knight.} O-O-O {It's necessary.} (12... h6 {. We're getting some Caro-Kann vibes, but this line is perilous for Black and thus not playable. A. Ne5! Nxe5 ( Bh7?? loses, but the winning idea for White is charming. Nxf7! Kxf7 Bxe6+! Kxe6 Nd5+! .The black king is dragged out in the open. Kxd5 c4+ Kd6 Bf4+ . The show is over.) dxe5 Qxe5 f4! , and Black is walking a tightrope to survive.) B. Ng5 h5 Rhe1 . White has a pleasant advantage, and there's no easy way for Black to equalize. Nd5 g3 Nxe3 Bxe3 Bb4 c3 Bd6 Bd3 Bxd3 Rxd3 Nf6 c4 , and White continues pushing.}) 13. Ng5 h5 14. Rhe1 {White has a pleasant advantage, and there's no easy way for Black to equalize.} Nd5 15. g3 Nxe3 16. Bxe3 Bb4 17. c3 Bd6 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Nf6 20. c4 {White continues pushing.} *

