1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nd5 {That's the jump you should expect at any moment if your queen is still on a5 . White might also include the d5 push and capture with the knight.} Qd8 9. Ne3 {It might seem that the white knight on e3 stands a little awkward, but it does support pushing forward the pawns.} Be4 {Specifically here, it's the best move.} (9... Bg6 {. It is possible to retreat with the bishop to the usual g6 -square, but White always gets some advantage in all lines. See here .}) 10. O-O {If White is slow with his actions, you can secure an escape route for your light-squared bishop on h7 and also deal with any future Ng5 ideas.} h6 11. a4 (11. Ne5 e6 12. f4 Bd6 {. It's not clear if White wants to go this route since Black has kept the strong bishop on e4 .}) 11... e6 12. Re1 Be7 {A little more precise than ... Bd6 since White might be prepping Bf1 idea to reroute the e3 -knight via c4 to e5 .} 13. Bf1 O-O 14. Nc4 c5 {Black immediately starts active operations in the center and has a great game.} *

