1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {Black acknowledges the X-ray of White's dark-squared bishop, but it's not dangerous here.} 8. Nd5 {That's the jump you should expect at any moment if your queen is still on a5 . White might also include the d5 push and capture with the knight.} Qd8 9. Ne3 {It might seem that the white knight on e3 stands a little awkward, but it does support pushing forward the pawns.} Be4 {Specifically here, it's the best move.} (9... Bg6 {. It is possible to retreat with the bishop to the usual g6 -square, but White always gets some advantage in all lines. See the line.}) 10. Ng5 {Of course. Be very careful here!} e6 {Black deals with the hidden threats and gives up the light-squared bishop for a solid game.} (10... Bd5 $6 11. Bd3 $1 {. Black has problems with the bishop. Most likely, Black will have to get rid of the knight from g5 and return with the bishop on e4 , which loses time.}) ({The automatic} 10... Bg6 $2 {is losing, but the lines are very nice.} 11. f4 $1 e6 12. f5 $1 {. Suddenly, Black has no satisfactory moves!} Bh5 ({(} 12... exf5 13. Nxf5 $1 {. The point.} Bxf5 14. Bxf7+ Ke7 15. Qe2+ Kd6 16. Bf4+ {, with a brutal mate. )}) 13. fxe6 $1 Bxd1 {. Ends the game immediately, but Black is doomed anyway.} 14. exf7+ Ke7 15. Nf5# {, with Legal's mate on the board!}) 11. O-O Bd6 {Here, positioning the bishop on g7 would be too slow since the White has not yet committed to Nxe4 , and there are tactical motifs connected with the e6 - and f7 - pawns.} (11... h6 $2 {would be just a mistake – White wants to take on e4 anyway. On top of that, there's a tactical problem.} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Qh5+ {. Oops.} Ke7 15. Bb4+ {. This sneaky side check is easy to miss from afar.} Nd6 16. Nc4 Nf6 17. Qe5 Nfe8 18. Rfe1 Kd7 19. Qxe6+ Kc7 20. Ne5 {. Perhaps Black is not lost yet, but the position looks so terrible that no one will enjoy playing it.}) 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bc1 {If White wants to get the bishop pair, this is the best version since Black could not fianchetto the bishop to g7 .} O-O 14. g3 Nef6 15. c3 Re8 {White has a small advantage due to the bishop pair and some space advantage; however, Black has an easy game in the center, and it will take a Capablanca to win this for White.} *

