1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will discuss what to do if White tries to trick you by avoiding positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 .} 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Nh4 {A rare move but not as harmless as it may seem.} (7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 Qc7 {will transpose to the main lines of Chapter 3 .}) 7... Bg4 {A principled choice.} (7... Bg6 $6 8. Bc4 {. White's plan has worked – now, in all of the transpositions to the main lines, Black won't have the best setup.} ({(} 8. Qf3 $5 e6 9. Ne4 {also looks interesting for White, Black is slightly worse. )}) 8... e6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nxg6 {. That's the difference – White gets the bishop pair immediately and avoids a lot of tricky sidelines.} hxg6 12. c3 Nd7 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {. White has a solid advantage due to the bishop pair and the center.} Nb6 15. Bb3 Rd7 ({(} 15... Bd6 16. g3 Rh3 17. Bc2 {. White keeps pressing. )}) 16. f4 Nd5 17. g3 {. Black is getting suffocated, but opening the position with ... c5 will increase the power of White's bishop pair.}) 8. Be2 {This would be toothless and not in the spirit of Nh4 .} Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Qa6 {Black removes the queen from the X-ray and offers a favorable queen trade.} 10. Qf3 e6 11. O-O-O Nbd7 12. Rhe1 O-O-O {Jan Timman (2630) – Alexander Beliavsky (2665), Ubeda 1997. Black has solved all opening problems, while White needs to devise a decent plan.} *

