1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will discuss what to do if White tries to trick you by avoiding positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 .} 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Nh4 {A rare move but not as harmless as it may seem.} (7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 Qc7 {will transpose to the main lines of Chapter 2 .}) 7... Bg4 {A principled choice.} (7... Bg6 $6 8. Bc4 {. White's plan has worked – now, in all of the transpositions to the main lines, Black won't have the best setup.} ({(} 8. Qf3 $5 e6 9. Ne4 {also looks interesting for White, Black is slightly worse. )}) 8... e6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nxg6 {. That's the difference – White gets the bishop pair immediately and avoids a lot of tricky sidelines.} hxg6 12. c3 Nd7 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {. White has a solid advantage due to the bishop pair and the center.} Nb6 15. Bb3 Rd7 ({(} 15... Bd6 16. g3 Rh3 17. Bc2 {. White keeps pressing. )}) 16. f4 Nd5 17. g3 {. Black is getting suffocated, but opening the position with ... c5 will increase the power of White's bishop pair.}) 8. f3 Be6 {There's White's disadvantage of not positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 ! Black can position their bishop on e6 and fianchetto the other bishop on g7 .} 9. g4 {An interesting way to complicate matters.} Qb6 {Before fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop, Black can ask White some unpleasant questions.} 10. Ng2 Na6 (10... Qxd4 {. Of course, taking on b2 runs into Rb1 , but accepting the central pawn right away is dangerous.} 11. Qe2 Nd5 12. O-O-O Nd7 13. Be1 {. White develops a strong initiative, and Black has problems completing the development.} Qe5 $1 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {. Necessary – after the queen trade, the Nc7 intermezzo check is unpleasant.} 15. Qd3 {. White's position looks very promising.}) 11. Bxa6 {Normally, this would be a bad trade for White, but the position is pretty concrete here.} Qxa6 12. Nf4 Bd5 {Black wants to play ... e6 and secure the bishop on d5 ; thus, White has to act quickly.} 13. g5 Nd7 14. Nfxd5 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Qc4 {Because of this trick, Black wins back the lost pawn.} 16. Nc3 Qxd4 17. f4 {White stops the annoying ... Qh4 +.} O-O-O 18. Qe2 Nb6 19. O-O-O Nc4 {Black is about to simplify the game into an equal endgame.} 20. Be1 Qxf4+ 21. Kb1 Rxd1+ 22. Nxd1 Nd6 {Of course, White has a great compensation for the missing pawn, but nothing more than that, and Black has excellent resources to have a good game.} ({After Rg1 , the game might continue:} 22... e6 {Rg4 Qf5} 23. Ne3 {Qb5 Nc4 Qd5! , Black inevitably completes the development. a4} Be7 24. Bf2 {Nxc4 Rxc4+} Kb8 {Rd4 Qc6 Qe5+ Ka8 Qxg7 . White wins back the pawn, but Black is now active. Rc8 Rd2 Qh1+ Ka2 Qe4 Qxf7 Qxa4+ Kb1 Bxg5 Qxe6 . The position is equal.}) *

