1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will discuss what to do if White tries to trick you by avoiding positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 .} 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Nh4 {A rare move but not as harmless as it may seem.} (7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 Qc7 {will transpose to the main lines of Chapter 2 .}) 7... Bg4 {A principled choice.} (7... Bg6 $6 8. Bc4 {. White's plan has worked – now, in all of the transpositions to the main lines, Black won't have the best setup.} ({(} 8. Qf3 $5 e6 9. Ne4 {also looks interesting for White, Black is slightly worse. )}) 8... e6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nxg6 {. That's the difference – White gets the bishop pair immediately and avoids a lot of tricky sidelines.} hxg6 12. c3 Nd7 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {. White has a solid advantage due to the bishop pair and the center.} Nb6 15. Bb3 Rd7 ({(} 15... Bd6 16. g3 Rh3 17. Bc2 {. White keeps pressing. )}) 16. f4 Nd5 17. g3 {. Black is getting suffocated, but opening the position with ... c5 will increase the power of White's bishop pair.}) 8. f3 Be6 {There's White's disadvantage of not positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 ! Black can position their bishop on e6 and fianchetto the other bishop on g7 .} 9. g4 {An interesting way to complicate matters.} Qb6 {Before fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop, Black can ask White some unpleasant questions.} 10. Ng2 Na6 (10... Qxd4 {. Of course, taking on b2 runs into Rb1 , but accepting the central pawn right away is dangerous.} 11. Qe2 Nd5 12. O-O-O Nd7 13. Be1 {. White develops a strong initiative, and Black has problems completing the development.} Qe5 $1 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {. Necessary – after the queen trade, the Nc7 intermezzo check is unpleasant.} 15. Qd3 {. White's position looks very promising.}) 11. Nf4 Nc7 {Black is in time to protect the bishop on e6 . Ensure you don't blunder Na4 , which would trap the queen. The ... Qxd4 resource is the only way to do this!} 12. Qe2 Qxd4 {Compared to the previous clickable variation on move 10 by Black, you can take the pawn here. The difference is that the white knight already stands on f4 , and after the planned ... g6 and ... Bg7 , there's no Bh6 discovered attack. Also, the knight on c7 conveniently defends the e6 -square and, from afar, also the g7 -square.} 13. O-O-O g6 {Black is about to complete their development, and White must show something fast.} 14. g5 Nfd5 15. Ncxd5 Bxd5 16. c3 Qb6 17. Be3 (17. Qe5 {. White's initiative evaporates after this move, and Black's moves are easy.} Rg8 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Bh3 Bg7 20. Qe4 Kf8 21. f4 e6 {. A pawn is a pawn – Black's position feels pretty safe.}) 17... Qa5 18. Bd4 {White keeps pushing, but luckily, the moves are not difficult to find.} Rg8 19. c4 Be6 20. Qe5 c5 {That's the advantage of having an extra pawn – you can always sell it back for the right price, and here it's avoiding trouble. Trading the queens would land Black in a terrible endgame.} 21. Bc3 {White keeps the foot on the gas pedal.} (21. Qxc5 {. Now the position simplifies to equality:} Qxc5 22. Bxc5 Bf5 {. White has no threats, and Black will have enough time to regroup their pieces.}) 21... Qb6 22. Qe3 Bg7 23. Bxg7 Rxg7 24. h4 Rd8 {White has compensation for the missing pawn but nothing more.} *

