1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will discuss what to do if White tries to trick you by avoiding positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 .} 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Nh4 {A rare move but not as harmless as it may seem.} (7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 Qc7 {will transpose to the main lines of Chapter 2 .}) 7... Bg4 {A principled choice.} (7... Bg6 $6 8. Bc4 {. White's plan has worked – now, in all of the transpositions to the main lines, Black won't have the best setup.} ({(} 8. Qf3 $5 e6 9. Ne4 {also looks interesting for White, Black is slightly worse. )}) 8... e6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nxg6 {. That's the difference – White gets the bishop pair immediately and avoids a lot of tricky sidelines.} hxg6 12. c3 Nd7 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {. White has a solid advantage due to the bishop pair and the center.} Nb6 15. Bb3 Rd7 ({(} 15... Bd6 16. g3 Rh3 17. Bc2 {. White keeps pressing. )}) 16. f4 Nd5 17. g3 {. Black is getting suffocated, but opening the position with ... c5 will increase the power of White's bishop pair.}) 8. f3 Be6 {There's White's disadvantage of not positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 ! Black can position their bishop on e6 and fianchetto the other bishop on g7 .} 9. Bd3 Qb6 {This maneuver is typical – you walk away from a discovered attack, and even though you might not be threatening to take either of the white pawns, at least you will keep your opponent busy thinking about it.} 10. Qe2 g6 {Probably you can take the pawn as well, but it feels safer to complete the development.} *

