1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will discuss what to do if White tries to trick you by avoiding positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 .} 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Nh4 {A rare move but not as harmless as it may seem.} (7. Bc4 Nbd7 8. Qe2 Qc7 {will transpose to the main lines of Chapter 2 .}) 7... Bg4 {A principled choice.} (7... Bg6 $6 8. Bc4 {. White's plan has worked – now, in all of the transpositions to the main lines, Black won't have the best setup.} ({(} 8. Qf3 $5 e6 9. Ne4 {also looks interesting for White, Black is slightly worse. )}) 8... e6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nxg6 {. That's the difference – White gets the bishop pair immediately and avoids a lot of tricky sidelines.} hxg6 12. c3 Nd7 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {. White has a solid advantage due to the bishop pair and the center.} Nb6 15. Bb3 Rd7 ({(} 15... Bd6 16. g3 Rh3 17. Bc2 {. White keeps pressing. )}) 16. f4 Nd5 17. g3 {. Black is getting suffocated, but opening the position with ... c5 will increase the power of White's bishop pair.}) 8. f3 Be6 {There's White's disadvantage of not positioning the light-squared bishop on c4 ! Black can position their bishop on e6 and fianchetto the other bishop on g7 .} 9. f4 {A logical follow-up.} g6 {You have to stop the f-pawn, plus Black can fianchetto the dark-squared bishop to g7 .} (9... Nbd7 {. Entering this line is risky.} 10. f5 $1 {. Oops! You can't take the pawn.} Bd5 ({(} 10... Bxf5 $4 11. b4 {)}) 11. Bd3 {. Because of the white pawn on f5 , Black is now forced to open up the position.} e5 12. fxe6 Bxe6 13. O-O Qb6 14. Kh1 {White has a strong initiative, and Black will have to play very accurately to stay alive.} Qxd4 15. Nf5 Qb6 16. a4 $1 a5 17. Qe1 {. If Black wants to castle long, there's always the pressure on the a5 -pawn.} O-O-O 18. Ne4 Bb4 19. c3 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Bf8 21. b4 {. Even with a naked eye, it's self-evident that you're not enjoying such an extra pawn – achieving a draw will be a huge success for Black.} Re8 $1 22. Be3 Qd8 23. Qe2 $1 {. Legendary mate threat incoming!} Bxf5 $1 24. Bxf5 g6 25. Bxd7+ Qxd7 26. Qf2 {. Black has traded some pieces, but the danger to the king remains.}) 10. f5 {White can't beat Black with brute force.} Bxf5 11. Ne4 Qd5 12. Nxf6+ {Now, the position simplifies a bit.} exf6 13. Nxf5 Qxf5 14. Qe2+ Qe6 {White has the center and two bishops, but where's the pawn?} 15. O-O-O Nd7 16. Re1 Qxe2 17. Bxe2 O-O-O 18. Bc4 c5 {Black gives up the extra pawn and easily equalizes the game.} ({After dxc5 , the game might continue.} 18... Ne5 19. Re4 Bc5 20. Bc3 Rhe8 {. White will win back the sacrificed pawn, but this will cost them the bishop pair.} 21. Rhe1 Re7 {Bxe5 fxe5} 22. Rxe5 Rxe5 23. Rxe5 Bd6 {, with a drawn endgame.}) *

