ck.} Re8 $1 22. Be3 Qd8 23. Qe2 $1 {. Legendary mate threat incoming!} Bxf5 $1 24. Bxf5 g6 25. Bxd7+ Qxd7 26. Qf2 {. Black has traded some pieces, but the danger to the king remains.}) 10. Bd3 Bg4 {Good move – Black remains alert to the f5 threat. Now, White has several choices.} (10... Nbd7 {leads to a tactical firefight in semi-forced lines, but the outcome is a worse middlegame for Black.} 11. Qe2 Qb6 12. f5 $1 gxf5 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 {. Black has no choice and can forget about castling short.} 14. Bxf5 O-O-O 15. O-O-O e6 16. Be4 Qxd4 {. If not accepting the pawn, Black suffers for no reason.} 17. Be3 Qe5 18. Bxc6 $1 Bc5 ({(} 18... bxc6 $4 {leads to Black's quick demise.} 19. Qa6+ Kb8 20. Bxa7+ Kc7 21. Bd4 Qf4+ 22. Kb1 Rb8 23. Rhf1 {, and Black's position collapses under multiple threats. )}) 19. Bxd7+ {. White initiates some simplifications.} Nxd7 20. Rd3 Nb6 21. Bxc5 Qxc5 22. Ne4 Qe7 23. Rhd1 {. In all variations, Black has to play very carefully to keep the balance, while White has many options to create problems for Black.}) 11. Nf3 {Now, the f5 push is no longer a problem, and Black can complete the development.} Nbd7 12. h3 Bf5 13. Bc4 {If White would take on f5 , capturing with the pawn would give Black more dynamics than with the queen.} h5 {An important move – White's g4 push had to be stopped.} 14. Qe2 Qc7 {It's time to retreat!} (14... e6 $2 {Keeping the black queen on a5 for too long can have consequences.} 15. d5 {a push Black should never miss.} cxd5 16. Nxd5 Qc5 17. Bb4 {. There's simply no good square for the black queen!}) 15. O-O-O e6 {The position is double-edged. Black can castle long or keep the king in the center and also consider starting a queenside assault with the pawn push.} *

