1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Ne4 {Quite a popular continuation in the position – White moves the queenside knight for a second time to get a different pawn structure on the queenside. Many players don't feel comfortable with the constant Scandinavian pressure on the d4 -pawn, which is a way to solve it.} Qc7 {By far the most played move in the position – the queen typically retreats here in most Scandinavian positions.} 8. Ng3 {It might feel very familiar for the Caro-Kann fans.} (8. Nxf6+ exf6 $5 {. It looks like the Tartakower variation from the Caro-Kann.} ({( Practice in Caro-Kann has proven that the capture} 8... gxf6 $2 {is dubious.} 9. g3 $1 {. There's no real pressure on the g-file, and the white king will always feel more secure on the kingside than the black king on the queenside. )}) 9. Bc4 Bd6 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. O-O-O Qxe2 12. Bxe2 Nd7 13. c4 g5 $5 {. White is slightly better, but the position is complex enough, and Black has his advantages.}) 8... Bg6 9. h4 Nh5 {Not a maneuver you'll see in the Caro-Kann because the knight is still on g8 .} 10. Ne2 {This is a sharper choice, but it doesn't pose Black any big problems.} (10. Nxh5 Bxh5 11. Be2 Nd7 12. Ng5 {. Top choice of the engine.} Bxe2 13. Qxe2 h6 14. Nf3 e6 15. O-O-O Bd6 16. Kb1 O-O-O {. Black has completed the development, and we've arrived at the classical variation of the Caro-Kann that has the reputation of being slightly passive. From one side, Black does not have space advantage problems, and there's no incoming direct attack, but you'll have to fight for equality the entire game to achieve a draw. These prospects don't seem to be a good strategy for our repertoire.}) 10... Nd7 11. g4 Nhf6 12. h5 Be4 13. Ng3 h6 {A great move – Black stops the g-pawn where it is and is ready to retreat with the bishop to h7 .} 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Be3 e6 {Black is calmly continuing the development and will castle long.} 16. Qd3 Nef6 17. Rg1 O-O-O {Compared to the classical lines of the Caro-Kann, White has committed to Rg1 and g4 .} *

