1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Ne4 {Quite a popular continuation in the position – White moves the queenside knight for a second time to get a different pawn structure on the queenside. Many players don't feel comfortable with the constant Scandinavian pressure on the d4 -pawn, which is a way to solve it.} Qd5 {This rare continuation allows Black to lead the game in a direction that White might not be ready for.} (7... Qc7 {is by far the most played move in the position – the queen typically retreats here in most Scandinavian positions.} 8. Nxf6+ exf6 $5 {. It looks like the Tartakower variation from the Caro-Kann.} ({(Practice in Caro-Kann has proven that the capture} 8... gxf6 $2 {is dubious.} 9. g3 $1 {. There's no real pressure on the g-file, and the white king will always feel more secure on the kingside than the black king on the queenside. )}) 9. Bc4 Bd6 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. O-O-O Qxe2 12. Bxe2 Nd7 13. c4 g5 $5 {. White is slightly better, but the position is complex enough, and Black has his advantages.}) 8. Ng3 Bg4 {Now, with the queen on d5 , Black suddenly has different ideas!} 9. c3 Bxf3 10. gxf3 e6 11. Qb3 {White doesn't mind the doubled f-pawns as long as Black opens the a-file for his rook.} Nbd7 {More fun than the queen trade, which also is good for Black.} 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 c5 {The position is pretty wild, and it might be not so easy for White to come up with the next moves.} *

