1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Ne4 {Quite a popular continuation in the position – White moves the queenside knight for a second time to get a different pawn structure on the queenside. Many players don't feel comfortable with the constant Scandinavian pressure on the d4 -pawn, which is a way to solve it.} Qd5 {This rare continuation allows Black to lead the game in a direction that White might not be ready for.} (7... Qc7 {is by far the most played move in the position – the queen typically retreats here in most Scandinavian positions.} 8. Nxf6+ exf6 $5 {. It looks like the Tartakower variation from the Caro-Kann.} ({(Practice in Caro-Kann has proven that the capture} 8... gxf6 $2 {is dubious.} 9. g3 $1 {. There's no real pressure on the g-file, and the white king will always feel more secure on the kingside than the black king on the queenside. )}) 9. Bc4 Bd6 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. O-O-O Qxe2 12. Bxe2 Nd7 13. c4 g5 $5 {. White is slightly better, but the position is complex enough, and Black has his advantages.}) 8. Nxf6+ exf6 {Compared to the traditional c7 -square, the black queen on d5 stands much more active.} 9. c4 {Logical but also a very committal move – the pawn on d4 might later become a target.} Qd7 {The queen here stands perfectly as the queenside knight has another route into the game.} 10. Be2 Na6 {This maneuver is well known in the Caro-Kann Tartakower variations.} 11. O-O Be7 12. Re1 O-O 13. Bc3 Rfe8 {As you can see, Black has an easy development.} 14. Nh4 Be6 15. Qd2 Rad8 {The game is complex. You're thinking about pressing the pawn on d4 also ... Nc7 with the ... b5 push to fight for the d5 -square comes to mind.   Typical for the Tartakower variation, Black can be pretty aggressive on the queenside and with the ... g5 push initiate interesting complications on the kingside.   It's probably a good idea to avoid unnecessary trades – White's dream is to use the extra pawn on the queenside in a dry endgame.} *

