lem.} 15. Nh4 Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Qf3 Rc8 18. O-O-O {. White has too much freedom with the development, Black has not started the counterplay in the center with the ..c5 push, and castling short is very dangerous due to h4 - h5 . That's why entering this particular line is bad for Black.}) 15. Ne5 {White could immediately attempt to exploit the black queen's placement on d7 .} Bxe5 16. dxe5 Ne4 17. Be3 Qc7 {Even if you're not seriously considering grabbing the e5 -pawn, at least let White worry about it.} 18. O-O Rd8 (18... Qxe5 $4 {, keeping the king in the center, walking into a million pins – it just can't end well.} 19. g4 Bg6 20. f4 Qf6 21. f5 {. Game over.}) 19. Qe2 O-O 20. g4 Bg6 21. f4 f5 {A very important resource. Due to the bishop pair, White's position seems better optically, but realistically, they have nothing.} 22. exf6 Nxf6 {If White had the g-pawn on g3 and the dark-squared bishop on c3 , we could talk about an advantage for White. It's impossible to achieve it here; White's kingside has weaknesses.} 23. Rad1 c5 24. Bc1 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 26. b3 Rxd1+ 27. Qxd1 Kf7 {We're approaching an equal endgame.} *

