1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Ne4 {Quite a popular continuation in the position – White moves the queenside knight for a second time to get a different pawn structure on the queenside. Many players don't feel comfortable with the constant Scandinavian pressure on the d4 -pawn, which is a way to solve it.} Qd5 {This rare continuation allows Black to lead the game in a direction that White might not be ready for.} (7... Qc7 {is by far the most played move in the position – the queen typically retreats here in most Scandinavian positions.} 8. Nxf6+ exf6 $5 {. It looks like the Tartakower variation from the Caro-Kann.} ({(Practice in Caro-Kann has proven that the capture} 8... gxf6 $2 {is dubious.} 9. g3 $1 {. There's no real pressure on the g-file, and the white king will always feel more secure on the kingside than the black king on the queenside. )}) 9. Bc4 Bd6 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. O-O-O Qxe2 12. Bxe2 Nd7 13. c4 g5 $5 {. White is slightly better, but the position is complex enough, and Black has his advantages.}) 8. Nc5 {The best move, also a novelty.} b6 {Now White has some choices.} 9. c4 {The white knight is heading to d3 , so White pushes back the black queen while the bishop still guards the c4 -square.} Qd8 10. Nd3 e6 {White is slightly better, but Black has created a different game that not everybody who plays 1.e4 might appreciate.} 11. Nde5 Bd6 12. g3 Qc7 ({It's possible to start with the knight move} 12... Nbd7 {, since you can sacrifice the c6 -pawn.} 13. Nxc6 Qc7 14. Nb4 O-O 15. Be2 Bh3 {, and White has problems completing the development.}) 13. Bg2 Nbd7 {Best include this move earlier before castling short to clarify White's intentions.} 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 {A necessary accuracy – keep an eye on White's Nh4 .} (14... Nxd7 $2 {is a positional mistake – please ensure you understand when Nh4 is and isn't a problem.} 15. Nh4 Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Qf3 Rc8 18. O-O-O {. White has too much freedom with the development, Black has not started the counterplay in the center with the ..c5 push, and castling short is very dangerous due to h4 - h5 . That's why entering this particular line is bad for Black.}) 15. Qe2 Rd8 {Black removes the rook from the h1 - a8 diagonal and delays White's Ne5 plan.} 16. O-O h6 {Before castling short, it's a good idea to prepare an escape route for the light-squared bishop, should White think about Nh4 .} 17. b4 {White stops Black from pushing c5 .} O-O (17... c5 $2 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. b5 {. This is the problem – White forms a much better pawn structure on the queenside. You might remember seeing something similar before in this chapter, but White had an awkward knight on d3 .}) 18. Rfd1 Bc2 {Black uses the same maneuver to remove the white rook from the d-file.} 19. Re1 Be4 20. Bc3 Qb7 {You can't rule out the ... c5 push – keep your eyes open.} 21. a4 Rfe8 {Black preps to play ... b5 and fight for the light squares in the center.} ({After h4 , the line might continue – you're warned that the variations will be crazy!} 21... b5 $5 22. d5 $1 {will happen if White is inclined to test your calculation skills, but these attempts won’t succeed as long as Black responds accurately.}) *

