lem.} 15. Nh4 Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Qf3 Rc8 18. O-O-O {. White has too much freedom with the development, Black has not started the counterplay in the center with the ..c5 push, and castling short is very dangerous due to h4 - h5 . That's why entering this particular line is bad for Black.}) 15. Qe2 Rd8 {Black removes the rook from the h1 - a8 diagonal and delays White's Ne5 plan.} 16. O-O h6 {Before castling short, it's a good idea to prepare an escape route for the light-squared bishop, should White think about Nh4 .} 17. Rfd1 Bc2 {An important intermezzo move to push the white rook away from the ideal square.} 18. Re1 Be4 {After pushing back the white rook, it's time to improve your bishop.} 19. Bc3 {This move comes with two ideas – threaten to play Ne5 and avoid the light-squared bishop trade by pushing your bishop away from the center.} Qb7 {Ignoring Ne5 would not be smart, especially considering that White's dark-squared bishop no longer stands on d2 .} 20. Bh3 {White can proceed with the other idea.} O-O 21. Nd2 Bg6 22. Bg2 {And the white bishop is back. It's unclear if White has achieved a lot since Black's bishop on g6 is quite active. Still, we can assume that White's bishop is somewhat better since it targets the pawn on c6 .} a5 {Black slows down White's plan to push b4 and is ready to organize some counterplay on the queenside, involving ... b5 push or ... Bb4 – we can conclude our analysis.} ({After Qf3 , the game might continue:} 22... Rc8 23. c5 {, and White radically changes the course of the game.} bxc5 24. Nc4 Bc7 25. dxc5 Nd5 26. Bd4 Rcd8 {. It doesn't seem that White has achieved a clear advantage – the game remains sharp.}) *

