1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bf4 {This is a standalone continuation with considerable venom; thus, you should study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, you could create weaknesses in your camp. For the moment, White takes control of the c7 -square.} (6. Ne5 Be6 $5 {gives Black an extra opportunity. Of course, there's nothing wrong with the normal Bf5 as well.}) 6... Bg4 {You should be already aware that this move is risky.} 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 {You should avoid these positions in general – White controls the center and has the bishop pair. There's an extra trick for you to know.} 9. a3 Nd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bc4 {White controls the critical d5 -square.} ({If the sequence} 11. Bxc3 $6 Qd5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {happens, Black is doing pretty much alright since White has problems completing the development while trading the queens, which would have made Black's task to equalize easier.}) 11... Nd7 12. Bxc3 Qc7 13. O-O-O {A long defense and battle for equality is ahead for Black – you're worse.} Be7 {Here's how the game might continue.} ({h4} 13... Nf6 14. Bd2 O-O-O 15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Bg5 {. Of course, White avoids any trades since they are enjoying space advantage and the bishop pair.} Be7 17. Kb1 h6 18. Bf4 Bd6 19. Bc1 Nd5 20. Bb3 b5 21. Bd2 {. White is about to break the c-file open while Black lacks any counterplay.}) *

