1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bf4 {This is a standalone continuation with considerable venom; thus, you should study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, you could create weaknesses in your camp. For the moment, White takes control of the c7 -square.} (6. Ne5 Be6 $5 {gives Black an extra opportunity. Of course, there's nothing wrong with the normal Bf5 as well.}) 6... Bf5 {Black continues to play according to the general guidelines.} ({You should be already aware that the move} 6... Bg4 $6 {is risky.} 7. h3 Bxf3 ({(} 7... Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {. White starts a dangerous kingside attack, and winning the pawn on g4 makes things shaky.} Nxg4 10. h5 Bf5 11. Nd2 $1 e6 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Qf3 {White is very much ahead in development – it can't end well for Black. )}) 8. Qxf3 e6 {. You should avoid these positions in general – White controls the center and has the bishop pair. There's an extra trick for you to know.} 9. a3 Nd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bc4 $1 {. White controls the critical d5 -square. Bxc3?!} Qd5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {. If this happens, Black is doing pretty much alright since White has problems completing the development while trading the queens, which would have made Black's task to equalize easier.}) 7. Qd2 {A pretty logical move – White safeguards the e1 - a5 diagonal and is thinking about castling long, but again, it doesn't create any threats to Black.} e6 {Black is threatening with ... Bb4 and ... Ne4 .} (7... Nbd7 {. If interested, you can toy with the move order.} 8. Nh4 {, because Black has not started with ... e6 , now there's no ... Bb4 maneuver.} Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 {. But even this position shows that Black has no problems fighting against White's two bishops.}) 8. Ne5 (8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 {. Why did White lose a tempo with 7.Qd2 ?}) (8. O-O-O $4 Bb4 {-+} 9. a3 Ne4 $1 {, and the white queen is lost.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Nc4 Qd8 10. Nd6+ {One of the common misunderstandings of this and very similar positions in the Scandinavian defense is that White can trade the knight for the dark-squared bishop and then control the dangerous a3 - f8 diagonal. In reality, it's impossible to use it.} Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Nb6 12. Bc5 Nbd5 {The point is that Black is not obliged to castle short at all – there's also the long castle, and then the white bishop, either on c5 or a3 , doesn't do much.} ({After Nxd5} 12... Ne4 $1 {is quite an unusual intermezzo move.} 13. Qe3 Nxc5 {Nc3 Nd7 . Black can also consider castling short.}) *

