1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bf4 {This is a standalone continuation with considerable venom; thus, you should study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, you could create weaknesses in your camp. For the moment, White takes control of the c7 -square.} (6. Ne5 Be6 $5 {gives Black an extra opportunity. Of course, there's nothing wrong with the normal Bf5 as well.}) 6... Bf5 {Black continues to play according to the general guidelines.} ({You should be already aware that the move} 6... Bg4 $6 {is risky.} 7. h3 Bxf3 ({(} 7... Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {. White starts a dangerous kingside attack, and winning the pawn on g4 makes things shaky.} Nxg4 10. h5 Bf5 11. Nd2 $1 e6 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Qf3 {White is very much ahead in development – it can't end well for Black. )}) 8. Qxf3 e6 {. You should avoid these positions in general – White controls the center and has the bishop pair. There's an extra trick for you to know.} 9. a3 Nd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bc4 $1 {. White controls the critical d5 -square. Bxc3?!} Qd5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {. If this happens, Black is doing pretty much alright since White has problems completing the development while trading the queens, which would have made Black's task to equalize easier.}) 7. Be2 {White could opt for continuing simple development.} Nbd7 8. O-O e6 9. Nh4 {If White doesn't go after the bishop and delays the maneuver, you can consider including also ... h6 .} (9. a3 Be7 10. b4 Qd8 11. b5 Nd5 $1 {. White's pseudo-aggression on the queenside only leads to pawn weaknesses. White must now think about maintaining equality.}) (9. Ne5 {(with the idea of Nc4 - d6 )} Nxe5 10. Bxe5 ({(} 10. dxe5 $6 Nd7 {– the e5 -pawn is weak and Black is already a little better. )}) 10... O-O-O 11. a3 Bd6 12. b4 Qc7 {. White doesn't have time to pose problems for Black, and they themselves risk getting a complex of weak pawns.}) 9... Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. a3 Be7 {White has the bishop pair, but there's no danger. Please note that without the white pawn on c4 , it's impossible to create real problems for Black. Our plans could include ... O-O , ... Nf6 - d5 , followed by a later ... c6 - c5 or the exchange of a couple of minor pieces, after which the space advantage will no longer be significant.} *

