1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bf4 {This is a standalone continuation with considerable venom; thus, you should study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, you could create weaknesses in your camp. For the moment, White takes control of the c7 -square.} (6. Ne5 Be6 $5 {gives Black an extra opportunity. Of course, there's nothing wrong with the normal Bf5 as well.}) 6... Bf5 {Black continues to play according to the general guidelines.} ({You should be already aware that the move} 6... Bg4 $6 {is risky.} 7. h3 Bxf3 ({(} 7... Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {. White starts a dangerous kingside attack, and winning the pawn on g4 makes things shaky.} Nxg4 10. h5 Bf5 11. Nd2 $1 e6 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Qf3 {White is very much ahead in development – it can't end well for Black. )}) 8. Qxf3 e6 {. You should avoid these positions in general – White controls the center and has the bishop pair. There's an extra trick for you to know.} 9. a3 Nd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bc4 $1 {. White controls the critical d5 -square. Bxc3?!} Qd5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {. If this happens, Black is doing pretty much alright since White has problems completing the development while trading the queens, which would have made Black's task to equalize easier.}) 7. a3 {A tricky move with concrete ideas – don't underestimate it.} Nbd7 {Black often starts with this move and not ... e6 . White might still go after the more aggressive Ne5 and Nc4 - e3 or the g4 push.} (7... e6 {is playable but gives White one more option.} 8. Ne5 Nbd7 9. Nc4 Qd8 10. Ne3 {. White creates a carousel with the knight.} Bg6 $6 {. The engine suggest leaving the bishop on f5 and proceed with ... Nb6 . For illustration, check what happens if Black retreats automatically.} 11. h4 h6 12. Qf3 Nb6 13. Be5 Be7 14. O-O-O O-O 15. Bd3 {White's attack looks very serious.}) 8. b4 Qd8 9. d5 {A standalone idea in the standalone variation! White wants to disrupt your typical way of development.} (9. Bc4 $6 e6 10. O-O Be7 11. h3 O-O {(witht the idea of Nb6-d5 and a5...) White's с4-bishop is caught by Black's tempi.}) ({If} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. O-O Be7 12. Na4 {. There are no reasonable alternatives with a clear game plan – everything else just marks time.} O-O 13. c4 a5 {.}) 9... g6 {Luckily for you, there are always other options.} 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Ba6 Bg7 12. O-O Nh5 13. Bd2 Qc7 {Black has a great game.} *

