ive up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices. White could attempt to demolish Black on the spot, but it doesn't work. You must study these lines carefully.} 9. d5 cxd5 10. Ne3 {White improves the Nxd5 threat.} Be6 {A very stubborn move! The dark-squared bishop will develop to g7 .} (10... Be4 {. It's possible to rely on the e-pawn push like in a similar line, but at the end of the line, White keeps pressing.} 11. f3 e5 12. Bg5 d4 $1 {. Fancy but necessary.} 13. Nxe4 dxe3 14. c3 Qb6 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Nxe4 17. fxe4 {. The position has simplified. White has two bishops, but the black pawn on e3 is still alive.} Bc5 18. Ke2 a6 19. b4 Bb6 20. Kf3 f6 21. Bxe3 Bxe3 22. Kxe3 Ke7 23. Ra5 {. White is slightly pushing due to the better bishop vs the knight, who is struggling to find a good place.} Rac8 24. Be2 Nb6 25. b5 {. And so on – Black is defending, and White plays with no risk.}) 11. Nexd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qa5+ 13. Nc3 g5 ({It's possible to explore also the quiet} 13... g6 {, but this move comes with a tempo.}) 14. Bd2 Bg7 {Black is alright. The position is tactical, making it difficult to offer any general guideline. It’s crucial for Black to respond to an attack with a counterattack and not hesitate to sacrifice a pawn in exchange for initiative along the central diagonals and files.} *

