ive up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices. White could attempt to demolish Black on the spot, but it doesn't work. You must study these lines carefully.} 9. d5 cxd5 10. Ne3 {White improves the Nxd5 threat.} Be6 {A very stubborn move! The dark-squared bishop will develop to g7 .} (10... Be4 {. It's possible to rely on the e-pawn push like in a similar line, but at the end of the line, White keeps pressing.} 11. f3 e5 12. Bg5 d4 $1 {. Fancy but necessary.} 13. Nxe4 dxe3 14. c3 Qb6 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Nxe4 17. fxe4 {. The position has simplified. White has two bishops, but the black pawn on e3 is still alive.} Bc5 18. Ke2 a6 19. b4 Bb6 20. Kf3 f6 21. Bxe3 Bxe3 22. Kxe3 Ke7 23. Ra5 {. White is slightly pushing due to the better bishop vs the knight, who is struggling to find a good place.} Rac8 24. Be2 Nb6 25. b5 {. And so on – Black is defending, and White plays with no risk.}) 11. Qd2 {A smart play – White treats that the d-pawn is going nowhere and instead opts for development.} Qa5 12. O-O-O g5 {White can't take on g5 .} 13. Bg3 (13. Bxg5 $4 d4 14. Bxf6 dxe3 {. The point – White loses a piece.}) 13... d4 {Since the d-pawn is gone anyway, better give it up under your terms.} (13... Rc8 $6 {. This is how one top-level game continued – White quickly got a large advantage.} 14. Bb5 Bg7 15. Be5 $1 {. Around here, Black probably realized that they couldn't castle short due to Bxd7 and Nxd5 threat.} Rc5 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 {. As seen in Viswanathan Anand (2764) – Shakhriyar Mamedyarov (2765), Paris GCT rapid 2019. Black managed to trick White and even win the game, but the position was perilous.} 17. Ncxd5 $1 Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2 Ne8 19. Bg3 {. White is borderline winning.}) 14. Qxd4 Bg7 {The point is that the white queen on d4 does not stand that great after all.} 15. Ned5 Rc8 16. Bb5 {White goes forward with huge forces, but Black is holding.} Kf8 17. Nxe7 Rxc3 {A key idea – White's bishop on b5 now is hanging.} (17... Kxe7 $4 {would end with a brutal knockout.} 18. Bxd7 Bxd7 19. Qd6+ Ke8 20. Rhe1+ Be6 21. Rxe6+ {. Pretty thematic.} fxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kf8 23. Bd6# {.}) 18. Bxd7 Nxd7 19. Qd6 Rxc2+ 20. Kxc2 Qxa2 {White's discovered checks look terrifying but only lead to a perpetual check. White has to go for it since their king is very weak.} 21. Ng6+ Kg8 22. Ne7+ Kf8 {With a draw. There is no smothered mate, in case you were wondering!} *

