1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bf4 {This is a standalone continuation with considerable venom; thus, you should study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, you could create weaknesses in your camp. For the moment, White takes control of the c7 -square.} (6. Ne5 Be6 $5 {gives Black an extra opportunity. Of course, there's nothing wrong with the normal Bf5 as well.}) 6... Bf5 {Black continues to play according to the general guidelines.} ({You should be already aware that the move} 6... Bg4 $6 {is risky.} 7. h3 Bxf3 ({(} 7... Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {. White starts a dangerous kingside attack, and winning the pawn on g4 makes things shaky.} Nxg4 10. h5 Bf5 11. Nd2 $1 e6 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Qf3 {White is very much ahead in development – it can't end well for Black. )}) 8. Qxf3 e6 {. You should avoid these positions in general – White controls the center and has the bishop pair. There's an extra trick for you to know.} 9. a3 Nd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bc4 $1 {. White controls the critical d5 -square. Bxc3?!} Qd5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {. If this happens, Black is doing pretty much alright since White has problems completing the development while trading the queens, which would have made Black's task to equalize easier.}) 7. Ne5 {The most principled continuation – most continuations give Black some freedom of choice.} Nbd7 ({No need to test if} 7... e6 $2 {works here. It doesn't.} 8. g4 {. No surprises here.} Bg6 9. h4 Nd5 {. Black desperately tries to stay in the game.} ({(} 9... Nbd7 10. Nc4 Qd8 11. h5 {)}) 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Bb4 12. Rh3 $1 {. The h5 push threat remains, and Black has major problems finding a safe place for the light-squared bishop.} Nd7 13. Nxd7 Kxd7 14. h5 Be4 15. Qd2 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Bd5 17. Re3 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 {. To save the bishop, Black will have to give up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices. White could attempt to demolish Black on the spot, but it doesn't work. You must study these lines carefully.} 9. d5 cxd5 10. Ne3 {White improves the Nxd5 threat.} Be6 {A very stubborn move! The dark-squared bishop will develop to g7 .} (10... Be4 {. It's possible to rely on the e-pawn push like in a similar line, but at the end of the line, White keeps pressing.} 11. f3 e5 12. Bg5 d4 $1 {. Fancy but necessary.} 13. Nxe4 dxe3 14. c3 Qb6 15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Nxe4 17. fxe4 {. The position has simplified. White has two bishops, but the black pawn on e3 is still alive.} Bc5 18. Ke2 a6 19. b4 Bb6 20. Kf3 f6 21. Bxe3 Bxe3 22. Kxe3 Ke7 23. Ra5 {. White is slightly pushing due to the better bishop vs the knight, who is struggling to find a good place.} Rac8 24. Be2 Nb6 25. b5 {. And so on – Black is defending, and White plays with no risk.}) 11. Qd2 {A smart play – White treats that the d-pawn is going nowhere and instead opts for development.} Nh5 {This could be interesting to explore.} 12. Bg3 g6 13. Ncxd5 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bg7 {The position is complex, and Black will have to find some accurate moves, but their chances are not worse.} ({O-O-O . Here's an illustration of the required accuracy:} 14... a6 15. Nf4 Qb6 16. Nc4 Bxc4 17. Qxd7+ {Kf8 . If White takes on c4 , it ends with a perpetual check. b3 Bxf1 Rhxf1 e6 . Black ultimately survives, but the moves are difficult.}) *

