ive up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices.} 9. Bd3 {White attempts to accelerate their development by trading off the light-squared bishops.} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 {Again, Black should not fear the Nd6 + since you can always cast long.} 11. O-O-O (11. Nd6+ {is played relatively often at amateur level. Black needs to react by} Bxd6 12. Bxd6 Nf8 $1 {– Otherwise there will be big exchanges and the king does not need castling. Alternatively, White will not be able to hold the king – it will be either O-O-O or O-O ;} 13. Ba3 Ng6 14. O-O-O Qc7 15. g3 O-O-O {.}) ({If} 11. O-O {, then} Nb6 12. Ne5 Bd6 13. Rfe1 Qc7 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bd2 O-O 16. Qg3 Kh7 {.}) 11... Nd5 ({More accurate than the tempting} 11... Nb6 {. In general, it's important not only to find an interesting game with chances of counterplay, but also a position where the cost of the move is not much higher than for your opponent.}) ({Be mindful of situations where the} 11... Nb6 {maneuver doesn't work* as in the following line. If} 12. Ne5 {, then,} Nbd5 13. Nxd5 {, and even if the take} Qxd5 {is an important idea in the Scandinavian Defense – attacking White's pawns on g2 and a2 – White has the very energetic} 14. c4 $1 {. And after} Qxg2 15. Rde1 {, the black queen is in trouble. Moreover, Black is behind in development – not a good position to choose.} ({∗ Mostly, it works well if the white king is still in the center. For example, instead of the earlier long castle, White played} 15. h4 {, and you're forcing your opponent to castle short to decrease the temperature of the position. However, with the king already castled long, this can backfire.   In other words, if the white king castles queenside, Black can afford to centralize and fix a piece in the center. But if the king stays in the center, this setup deprives Black of quick counterplay. For that reason, we don’t recommend playing ... Nd5 in response to a flank pawn advance.})) 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Nd6+ {Let's look again at what happens if White goes for the tempting check,} Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Nf6 15. Ba3 Qc7 {Black is safely castling long, and it's unclear what White's bishop is doing on a3 .} ({After Qe3 , the game might continue: O-O-O Rd3} 15... Ne4 $1 16. f3 Nd6 {, and White runs out of ideas.}) *

