ive up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices.} 9. Qe2 {This idea is borrowed from the open Sicilian – White wants to castle long, delay the development of the light-squared bishop, and cause havoc in the center. BTW, don't miss the mate-in-one threat!} e6 {Simple and good – you already know that Nd6 + here is not dangerous.} (9... Be6 $5 {One GM game here continued differently – it only shows that Black often has more than one opportunity to get an interesting game.} 10. Ne5 g6 11. O-O-O Bg7 12. h4 Qa5 {. Black got a dynamic game in Anton Shomoev (2561) – Viktor Láznička (2666); Ho Chi Minh City HD Bank op-A 6th 2016. The black king can now remain in the center.}) 10. O-O-O Nb6 11. Ne3 Nbd5 {The simplest way to deal with White's creative ideas.} 12. Ncxd5 Nxd5 {With balanced chances.} ({After Nxf5 , the game might continue: Nxf4 Qg4} 12... g5 $5 {. Why not? The black knight stands well on f4 . Ne3 h5} 13. Qf3 {Qf6 Ba6!} Rb8 14. Bc4 Bg7 {. Black is at least not worse.}) *

