d badly means that if there is a tactical firefight, Black's chances are not worse. You will have to look for dynamic resources to equalize the game. The biggest threat is White's space advantage.} (11... Qa5 {. There's an important nuance of why this continuation is not the best here.} 12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Qf5 14. Bh2 {. Now you can't trade off White's bishop.} Qe6+ 15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Bg7 17. a5 {. Black has a solid worse endgame with no counterplay.}) 12. a5 {White is trying to squeeze Black in earnest.} b5 {Black can respond with the same! Doing this takes control of the c4 -square, and... b4 might become useful at some point.} 13. Qd2 {If White plays an 'empty' move like this, Black can solve all of their opening problems with simple moves.} a6 14. Be2 Bd5 15. Ncxd5 cxd5 {Black has progressed by improving the pawn structure.} 16. Bf3 e6 17. b3 Nb8 18. c4 Nc6 {White has nothing better than to go for simplifications.} ({After cxd5 , the game might continue: Nxd5 Nxd5 exd5} 18... O-O 19. O-O {Bg5 Bf6 . The position is liquidating into a draw. Bxf6 Qxf6 Bxd5 Rfd8 Bxc6 Qxc6 Rfd1 Rd5 Rac1} Qd6 {. White's extra pawn won't hold.}) ({Of course, c5? would leave the d4 -pawn very weak after} 18... Ne4 {.}) *

