ive up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices.} 9. Ne3 {The main move – Black needs to remain careful.} Be6 {We have played only nine moves, but the position is relatively unexplored, leading to many interesting opportunities for both sides.} ({A. The automatic retreat} 9... Bg6 $6 {is a mistake:} 10. h4 h6 11. h5 Bh7 12. d5 $5 {. The problem is Black can no longer opt for fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 .} Bd3 {.} ({� a1. One high-level GM blitz game continued like this and promised White a significant advantage:} 12... Bd3 13. Qxd3 e6 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Kb1 b5 16. g4 {. White was faster with his threats and ultimately won. Mustafa Yılmaz (2604) – Viktor Láznička (2648), Wch Blitz Moscow 2019.}) ({� a2.} 12... e5 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Bd3 {, and White is better.}) ({� a3.} 12... Ne4 $2 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 {. This happened in Vasif Durarbayli (2615) – Valentin Dragnev (2535) EU-ch Blitz Katowice 2021.} 15. Qd4 Qa5+ 16. c3 Nf6 17. Nc4 Qd5 18. Qe3 {. White's lead in development is decisive.}) ({B.} 12... e6 {does not fully solve Black's problems.} 13. Nf5 exf5 14. Bd3 g6 15. O-O Be7 16. Qd2 {. White is better, and there are some direct problems.} O-O 17. Bxh6 Re8 18. Bxf5 {. With a simple tactic, White wins a pawn.} Bf8 19. Bxf8 Nxf8 20. Bh3 Qb6 {. Black has some compensation for the missing pawn, but not enough.} 21. b3 Rad8 22. Rad1 gxh5 {. A pawn is a pawn.})) 10. a4 {The most pragmatic choice for White – play for a space advantage.} g6 11. h3 {White defends against the positional ... Nh5 threat.} Bg7 {Black has completed the development and is ready to formulate the plan for counterplay. The fact that none of Black's pieces stand badly means that if there is a tactical firefight, Black's chances are not worse. You will have to look for dynamic resources to equalize the game. The biggest threat is White's space advantage.} (11... Qa5 {. There's an important nuance of why this continuation is not the best here.} 12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Qf5 14. Bh2 {. Now you can't trade off White's bishop.} Qe6+ 15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Bg7 17. a5 {. Black has a solid worse endgame with no counterplay.}) 12. a5 {White is trying to squeeze Black in earnest.} b5 {Black can respond with the same! Doing this takes control of the c4 -square, and... b4 might become useful at some point.} 13. Be2 {White continues the development and hopes to exploit the weakness on c6 by playing Bf3 . Now Black has two interesting continuations, both feel completely different.} b4 {Black attempts to use the momentum and push forward the b-pawn to gain access to the d5 -square. It looks a little more lively than the alternative line.} 14. Na4 Nd5 15. Bg3 {This would change the pawn structure, but it's not clear if it's in White's favor.} O-O 16. O-O Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bd5 {Once again, Black is thinking about ... e5 .} *

