d badly means that if there is a tactical firefight, Black's chances are not worse. You will have to look for dynamic resources to equalize the game. The biggest threat is White's space advantage.} (11... Qa5 {. There's an important nuance of why this continuation is not the best here.} 12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Qf5 14. Bh2 {. Now you can't trade off White's bishop.} Qe6+ 15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Bg7 17. a5 {. Black has a solid worse endgame with no counterplay.}) 12. a5 {White is trying to squeeze Black in earnest.} b5 {Black can respond with the same! Doing this takes control of the c4 -square, and... b4 might become useful at some point.} 13. Be2 {White continues the development and hopes to exploit the weakness on c6 by playing Bf3 . Now Black has two interesting continuations, both feel completely different.} b4 {Black attempts to use the momentum and push forward the b-pawn to gain access to the d5 -square. It looks a little more lively than the alternative line.} 14. Na4 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. O-O e5 {A temporary pawn sacrifice. This move order is the most precise way, since White wants to push c4 and capture on c3 with the knight. If you start with a short castle and then push ... e5 , none of Black's ideas will work anymore because the light-squared bishop will be under attack.} ({Accepting the pawn is possible} 16... Qxa5 $5 {, but White will win it back quickly.} 17. c4 bxc3 18. Nxc3 Qb4 19. Bb5 $1 {. White stops Black from castling.} Bb3 $1 20. Qf3 {. White wins back the pawn. There's a long line at the end of which Black achieves a draw, but the question is – do you need it?}) 17. Bd2 O-O {There's no time to protect the pawn – Black has to play energetically.} 18. Bxb4 Qg5 19. Bf3 e4 {White has two options to retreat with the bishop.} 20. Be2 Rfb8 21. Bd6 e3 22. Bf3 Re8 {Black is down a pawn, but the initiative looks pretty serious and should result in winning it back.} 23. fxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 Bxf3 {The position starts to simplify.} 25. Qxf3 Qxf3 26. Rxf3 Bxd4 27. Rd1 Bg7 {Black is good.} *

