1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({We don’t go for} 5... Bf5 {at this point in the repertoire – here ’s a quick reminder of why this move order matters.}) 6. Bf4 {This is a standalone continuation with considerable venom; thus, you should study it carefully. If Black mixes up the order of the moves, there's a risk of getting suffocated, and to break through, you could create weaknesses in your camp. For the moment, White takes control of the c7 -square.} (6. Ne5 Be6 $5 {gives Black an extra opportunity. Of course, there's nothing wrong with the normal Bf5 as well.}) 6... Bf5 {Black continues to play according to the general guidelines.} ({You should be already aware that the move} 6... Bg4 $6 {is risky.} 7. h3 Bxf3 ({(} 7... Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {. White starts a dangerous kingside attack, and winning the pawn on g4 makes things shaky.} Nxg4 10. h5 Bf5 11. Nd2 $1 e6 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Qf3 {White is very much ahead in development – it can't end well for Black. )}) 8. Qxf3 e6 {. You should avoid these positions in general – White controls the center and has the bishop pair. There's an extra trick for you to know.} 9. a3 Nd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bc4 $1 {. White controls the critical d5 -square. Bxc3?!} Qd5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {. If this happens, Black is doing pretty much alright since White has problems completing the development while trading the queens, which would have made Black's task to equalize easier.}) 7. Ne5 {The most principled continuation – most continuations give Black some freedom of choice.} Nbd7 ({No need to test if} 7... e6 $2 {works here. It doesn't.} 8. g4 {. No surprises here.} Bg6 9. h4 Nd5 {. Black desperately tries to stay in the game.} ({(} 9... Nbd7 10. Nc4 Qd8 11. h5 {)}) 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Bb4 12. Rh3 $1 {. The h5 push threat remains, and Black has major problems finding a safe place for the light-squared bishop.} Nd7 13. Nxd7 Kxd7 14. h5 Be4 15. Qd2 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Bd5 17. Re3 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 {. To save the bishop, Black will have to give up a pawn and play a hopeless endgame.}) 8. Nc4 {The main idea behind Bf4 – White reroutes the knight to e3 for some interesting dynamics.} (8. g4 {. Here, it's not dangerous.} Nxe5 {You also can explore the option of retreating with the bishop to e6 .} 9. gxf5 Ned7 10. Bd3 g6 {. If somebody can get worse here, it's only White.}) 8... Qd8 {Now White has some choices.} 9. Ne3 {The main move – Black needs to remain careful.} Be6 {We have played only nine moves, but the position is relatively unexplored, leading to many interesting opportunities for both sides.} ({A. The automatic retreat} 9... Bg6 $6 {is a mistake:} 10. h4 h6 11. h5 Bh7 12. d5 $5 {. The problem is Black can no longer opt for fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 .} Bd3 {.} ({� a1. One high-level GM blitz game continued like this and promised White a significant advantage:} 12... Bd3 13. Qxd3 e6 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Kb1 b5 16. g4 {. White was faster with his threats and ultimately won. Mustafa Yılmaz (2604) – Viktor Láznička (2648), Wch Blitz Moscow 2019.}) ({� a2.} 12... e5 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Bd3 {, and White is better.}) ({� a3.} 12... Ne4 $2 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 {. This happened in Vasif Durarbayli (2615) – Valentin Dragnev (2535) EU-ch Blitz Katowice 2021.} 15. Qd4 Qa5+ 16. c3 Nf6 17. Nc4 Qd5 18. Qe3 {. White's lead in development is decisive.}) ({B.} 12... e6 {does not fully solve Black's problems.} 13. Nf5 exf5 14. Bd3 g6 15. O-O Be7 16. Qd2 {. White is better, and there are some direct problems.} O-O 17. Bxh6 Re8 18. Bxf5 {. With a simple tactic, White wins a pawn.} Bf8 19. Bxf8 Nxf8 20. Bh3 Qb6 {. Black has some compensation for the missing pawn, but not enough.} 21. b3 Rad8 22. Rad1 gxh5 {. A pawn is a pawn.})) 10. a4 {The most pragmatic choice for White – play for a space advantage.} g6 11. h3 {White defends against the positional ... Nh5 threat.} Bg7 {Black has completed the development and is ready to formulate the plan for counterplay. The fact that none of Black's pieces stand badly means that if there is a tactical firefight, Black's chances are not worse. You will have to look for dynamic resources to equalize the game. The biggest threat is White's space advantage.} (11... Qa5 {. There's an important nuance of why this continuation is not the best here.} 12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Qf5 14. Bh2 {. Now you can't trade off White's bishop.} Qe6+ 15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Bg7 17. a5 {. Black has a solid worse endgame with no counterplay.}) 12. a5 {White is trying to squeeze Black in earnest.} b5 {Black can respond with the same! Doing this takes control of the c4 -square, and... b4 might become useful at some point.} 13. Be2 {White continues the development and hopes to exploit the weakness on c6 by playing Bf3 . Now Black has two interesting continuations, both feel completely different.} b4 {Black attempts to use the momentum and push forward the b-pawn to gain access to the d5 -square. It looks a little more lively than the alternative line.} 14. Na4 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. O-O e5 {A temporary pawn sacrifice. This move order is the most precise way, since White wants to push c4 and capture on c3 with the knight. If you start with a short castle and then push ... e5 , none of Black's ideas will work anymore because the light-squared bishop will be under attack.} ({Accepting the pawn is possible} 16... Qxa5 $5 {, but White will win it back quickly.} 17. c4 bxc3 18. Nxc3 Qb4 19. Bb5 $1 {. White stops Black from castling.} Bb3 $1 20. Qf3 {. White wins back the pawn. There's a long line at the end of which Black achieves a draw, but the question is – do you need it?}) 17. dxe5 O-O {This position is not easy to play for both sides since White and Black have weaknesses.} 18. c4 {A logical attempt to bring either the white knight in the game or push back the active black bishop.} Be6 {Better keep the white knight where it is.} 19. a6 {This pawn later in the game could prove to be very strong.} Nxe5 20. b3 (20. Qxd8 {. We'll also leave here the other lines we looked at, but we'd be amazed if your opponents made it this far.} Rfxd8 21. b3 Nd3 22. Be3 $5 {. White can go for a positional exchange sacrifice.} Bxa1 23. Rxa1 h5 24. Rd1 ({(} 24. Bxd3 Rxd3 25. Nc5 Rdd8 26. Ra4 Rd1+ 27. Kh2 Bc8 28. h4 {, and Black is holding.)}) 24... Ne5 25. Rxd8+ Rxd8 26. Bxa7 Ra8 {leads to a crazy sequence where both sides exchange blows and ends with a draw.} 27. Bd4 Nd7 28. a7 c5 29. Nxc5 Rxa7 30. Nxe6 Ra2 31. Nf4 g5 {. This part is pretty forcing – Black wants to collect back the extra material.} 32. c5 Nb8 33. Bf3 gxf4 34. Kf1 Ra3 35. Bd5 Na6 {. White has a nice compensation, but not more.} 36. c6 Ra5 37. Bf3 Ra3 38. Ke2 Rxb3 39. Bxh5 Rb1 40. Kd2 b3 41. Bf3 Nc7 42. Be5 Nb5 43. c7 Nxc7 44. Bxc7 Rb2+ 45. Kd3 Rxf2 46. Be5 b2 47. Bxb2 Rxb2 {. We hope you'll forgive us for not asking you to study this line. �}) 20... Qc7 21. Qc1 c5 22. Qe3 Rac8 {We can stop our analysis here because Igor wrote some more. :) Black has enough resources to hold the balance.} ({After Rad1 , the game might continue:} 22... Rfe8 23. Rfe1 Bd7 24. Bg4 f5 25. Bf3 Nxf3+ 26. Qxf3 Qc6 27. Qxc6 {Rxc6 Be3} Bd4 28. Kf1 {Rxa6 . As usual, all the pieces find ways to disappear from the board. Nxc5 Bxc5 Bxc5} Rxe1+ 29. Kxe1 Bxc6 {Rd8+ Kf7 Rh8 Ra1+} 30. Kd2 {a5 Rxh7+ Kg8 Rc7} Bxg2 {, and the game is leading to a perfect draw.}) *

