[White "8) The Impetuous 6.Ne5 without Bc4"]
[Black "Impetuous 6.Ne5: 7.Be2 with 8.Nxd7"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B01"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2174210256262100"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Perhaps you are wondering why we are starting with} 5... c6 {and not with Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {?}) ({First, if White wants to go to the main lines, they can meet the move} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 {, and Black has nothing better than} c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {, and everything that we discuss in Chapter 2 .}) ({Second, after} 5... Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 {, White suddenly has some extra interesting options like} 7. h4 $5 {or g4!? .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the variation of Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 , but White can still force them to go there with the following move order –} 6. Bd2 {с6 Bc4} Nbd7 7. Qe2 {, because rejecting this for Black is more than risky.}) ({Considering everything above, that's why we're recommending} 5... c6 {. You will have to study the main lines anyway, and if White starts to be tricky with} 6. Ne5 {, there's the} Be6 {option. There are fewer variations for you to study and fewer opportunities for your opponent to catch you in some lines.}) 6. Ne5 (6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {is the main line of Chapter 2 .}) 6... Be6 ({A powerful alternative to the more popular} 6... Bf5 {. The fact that back in 1995, Vishy Anand played this variation in the world championship match against Garry Kasparov speaks volumes about the line. Kasparov did not get anything with White and even found himself in a worse position. In the current digital age, many young masters choose this move, probably because it's also the top choice of engines.}) 7. Be2 {This is slow, with no ambitions, and gives Black freedom with choices.} ({After} 7. Bd3 {, we play the logical} Nbd7 8. f4 {, and we transpose to another line .}) 7... Nbd7 {The white knight on e5 is under fire.} 8. Nxd7 Bxd7 9. O-O g6 ({You can also play} 9... Bf5 {followed by ... e6 , to reach the classical setup.}) 10. Bf3 Bg7 {Black got dynamic chances in the game Dmitry Andreikin (2726) – Andrey Esipenko (2682), Chess.com, Titled Tuesday intern op June 9th, 2020.} *

