on f4 , preventing White’s rook and bishop on d2 from becoming active. The damage to our pawn structure isn’t dangerous – the key factor is the blockade on the white squares.} 12. Bc4 e6 {Black has a great game, as White's immediate g4 push does not work.} ({g4?? . In one blitz game, White did decide to try it.} 12... Nxe5 13. fxe5 Ng4 14. Ne4 Bxe4 15. Qxg4 Bf5 {. White had no compensation for the lost pawn in the game Graham Horobetz – Andrey Esipenko (2682), Chess.com, Titled Tuesday intern op, May 19th 2020.}) *

