1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Perhaps you are wondering why we are starting with} 5... c6 {and not with Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {?}) ({First, if White wants to go to the main lines, they can meet the move} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 {, and Black has nothing better than} c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {, and everything that we discuss in Chapter 2 .}) ({Second, after} 5... Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 {, White suddenly has some extra interesting options like} 7. h4 $5 {or g4!? .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the variation of Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 , but White can still force them to go there with the following move order –} 6. Bd2 {с6 Bc4} Nbd7 7. Qe2 {, because rejecting this for Black is more than risky.}) ({Considering everything above, that's why we're recommending} 5... c6 {. You will have to study the main lines anyway, and if White starts to be tricky with} 6. Ne5 {, there's the} Be6 {option. There are fewer variations for you to study and fewer opportunities for your opponent to catch you in some lines.}) 6. Ne5 (6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {is the main line of Chapter 2 .}) 6... Be6 ({A powerful alternative to the more popular} 6... Bf5 {. The fact that back in 1995, Vishy Anand played this variation in the world championship match against Garry Kasparov speaks volumes about the line. Kasparov did not get anything with White and even found himself in a worse position. In the current digital age, many young masters choose this move, probably because it's also the top choice of engines.}) 7. Nc4 {It's strange to retreat with the knight that nobody is bothering, but it's still a move.} Qd8 {If you want, you can also explore retreating with the queen to c7 , provoke White to play either g3 or Qf3 with Bf4 , and then retreat to d8 .} 8. Ne3 {The knight here seemingly stands well to support the d5 push, but Black counter-arguments are convincing.} (8. Bf4 {is more played by amateurs. Black plays in the same way as in the Bf4 variation, but without developing the knight to d7 .} g6 9. Be2 Bg7 {. Doing so, we have more options along the d-file.} 10. O-O O-O {.}) ({After} 8. Bg5 {, we play a classic Scandinavian setup.} Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bxc4 10. Bxc4 {, here, we see that the Bg5 move doesn’t make sense, as the bishop exchange favors Black.} e6 11. O-O Be7 {.}) 8... g6 9. g3 Bg7 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Na6 12. d5 {White carried out their idea to open the long diagonal only to meet an unpleasant surprise.} Bd7 {Black doesn't have to take on d5 ! Now the white knight on e3 feels a little awkward.} 13. Qe2 Nb4 14. dxc6 Nxc6 {Black had equalized in Maksim Chigaev (2644) – José Carlos Ibarra Jeréz (2538), Chess24 Banter Blitz Cup chess24.com, November 6th, 2019.} *

