1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Perhaps you are wondering why we are starting with} 5... c6 {and not with Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {?}) ({First, if White wants to go to the main lines, they can meet the move} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 {, and Black has nothing better than} c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {, and everything that we discuss in Chapter 2 .}) ({Second, after} 5... Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 {, White suddenly has some extra interesting options like} 7. h4 $5 {or g4!? .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the variation of Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 , but White can still force them to go there with the following move order –} 6. Bd2 {с6 Bc4} Nbd7 7. Qe2 {, because rejecting this for Black is more than risky.}) ({Considering everything above, that's why we're recommending} 5... c6 {. You will have to study the main lines anyway, and if White starts to be tricky with} 6. Ne5 {, there's the} Be6 {option. There are fewer variations for you to study and fewer opportunities for your opponent to catch you in some lines.}) 6. Ne5 (6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {is the main line of Chapter 2 .}) 6... Be6 ({A powerful alternative to the more popular} 6... Bf5 {. The fact that back in 1995, Vishy Anand played this variation in the world championship match against Garry Kasparov speaks volumes about the line. Kasparov did not get anything with White and even found himself in a worse position. In the current digital age, many young masters choose this move, probably because it's also the top choice of engines.}) 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Bd3 g6 {Notice that with the bishop on e6 , Black often does not try to remove it to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game.} ({Instead, we're playing in the spirit of the Alekhine defense e4 Nf6 e5} 8... Nd5 {d4 d6} 9. Nf3 {dxe5} Ne5 {c6 , followed by 6...g6 with developing the bishop to g7 and the arising Scandinavian structures. You should remember this idea since it also works here!}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Kh1 {This is what Kasparov played against Anand back in 1995.} c5 {White's center is collapsing.} (10... Bf5 $6 {. Kasparov and Anand committed inaccuracies in the game.} 11. Bc4 $6 {. The World champion underestimated the power of the black bishop.} e6 12. Be2 h5 {. Since White's g4 push was never working, Black kept his beautiful bishop on f5 . See the model game Garry Kasparov (2795) – Viswanathan Anand (2725), PCA-World-ch, 1995.}) 11. Be3 cxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O 13. Qf3 Nc5 {Black's dynamics look convincing to give them equal chances.} *

