asparov played against Anand back in 1995.} c5 {White's center is collapsing.} (10... Bf5 $6 {. Kasparov and Anand committed inaccuracies in the game.} 11. Bc4 $6 {. The World champion underestimated the power of the black bishop.} e6 12. Be2 h5 {. Since White's g4 push was never working, Black kept his beautiful bishop on f5 . See the model game Garry Kasparov (2795) – Viswanathan Anand (2725), PCA-World-ch, 1995.}) 11. f5 {Maybe this is what Anand didn't like or could not evaluate.} gxf5 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. d5 {White has a compensation for the pawn but not more than that.} e6 14. Bg5 O-O {Black can also castle long and make things even more interesting.} 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Bxf5 {White wins back the sacrificed pawn thanks to a small trick.} exf5 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. Qxd7 Rf7 {Black has a weak pawn on f5 but a stronger bishop.} 19. Qd5 Rd8 20. Qf3 Qb4 {The position is balanced.} *

