1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Perhaps you are wondering why we are starting with} 5... c6 {and not with Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {?}) ({First, if White wants to go to the main lines, they can meet the move} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 {, and Black has nothing better than} c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {, and everything that we discuss in Chapter 2 .}) ({Second, after} 5... Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 {, White suddenly has some extra interesting options like} 7. h4 $5 {or g4!? .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the variation of Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 , but White can still force them to go there with the following move order –} 6. Bd2 {с6 Bc4} Nbd7 7. Qe2 {, because rejecting this for Black is more than risky.}) ({Considering everything above, that's why we're recommending} 5... c6 {. You will have to study the main lines anyway, and if White starts to be tricky with} 6. Ne5 {, there's the} Be6 {option. There are fewer variations for you to study and fewer opportunities for your opponent to catch you in some lines.}) 6. Ne5 (6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {is the main line of Chapter 2 .}) 6... Be6 ({A powerful alternative to the more popular} 6... Bf5 {. The fact that back in 1995, Vishy Anand played this variation in the world championship match against Garry Kasparov speaks volumes about the line. Kasparov did not get anything with White and even found himself in a worse position. In the current digital age, many young masters choose this move, probably because it's also the top choice of engines.}) 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Bd3 g6 {Notice that with the bishop on e6 , Black often does not try to remove it to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game.} ({Instead, we're playing in the spirit of the Alekhine defense e4 Nf6 e5} 8... Nd5 {d4 d6} 9. Nf3 {dxe5} Ne5 {c6 , followed by 6...g6 with developing the bishop to g7 and the arising Scandinavian structures. You should remember this idea since it also works here!}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. f5 {This is too straightforward – Black has done nothing wrong to get overrun in the opening like this.} gxf5 11. Bxf5 Nxe5 {If somebody is playing here for more, it's only Black.} 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. Bf4 Qc5+ {The simplest choice that requires no calculation.} (14... Qh5 {. This is more interesting but requires more calculations.} 15. Qe1 Ng4 {, starting a tactical firefight.} 16. Rd1 $1 ({(} 16. Qxe6 Qc5+ 17. Kh1 Nf2+ 18. Rxf2 Qxf2 19. Re1 $1 Bf8 $5 20. Qe5 Rg8 21. Bg3 Rxg3 22. hxg3 O-O-O {, Black ends up with a better position. )}) 16... O-O 17. h3 Qc5+ 18. Kh1 e5 {. Black tries to hold on to the pawn.} 19. Bg3 Rxf1+ 20. Qxf1 Rf8 21. Qe2 Nf2+ 22. Bxf2 Qxf2 23. Qd3 {. Ultimately, the position simplifies, and the extra pawn doesn't seem meaningful. White is about to cement the e4 -knight.}) 15. Kh1 e5 16. Bg3 e4 17. Qe2 O-O {White may win back the pawn on e4 , but their queenside pawns will be exposed.} *

