1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Perhaps you are wondering why we are starting with} 5... c6 {and not with Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {?}) ({First, if White wants to go to the main lines, they can meet the move} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 {, and Black has nothing better than} c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {, and everything that we discuss in Chapter 2 .}) ({Second, after} 5... Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 {, White suddenly has some extra interesting options like} 7. h4 $5 {or g4!? .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the variation of Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 , but White can still force them to go there with the following move order –} 6. Bd2 {с6 Bc4} Nbd7 7. Qe2 {, because rejecting this for Black is more than risky.}) ({Considering everything above, that's why we're recommending} 5... c6 {. You will have to study the main lines anyway, and if White starts to be tricky with} 6. Ne5 {, there's the} Be6 {option. There are fewer variations for you to study and fewer opportunities for your opponent to catch you in some lines.}) 6. Ne5 (6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {is the main line of Chapter 2 .}) 6... Be6 ({A powerful alternative to the more popular} 6... Bf5 {. The fact that back in 1995, Vishy Anand played this variation in the world championship match against Garry Kasparov speaks volumes about the line. Kasparov did not get anything with White and even found himself in a worse position. In the current digital age, many young masters choose this move, probably because it's also the top choice of engines.}) 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Bd3 g6 {Notice that with the bishop on e6 , Black often does not try to remove it to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game.} ({Instead, we're playing in the spirit of the Alekhine defense e4 Nf6 e5} 8... Nd5 {d4 d6} 9. Nf3 {dxe5} Ne5 {c6 , followed by 6...g6 with developing the bishop to g7 and the arising Scandinavian structures. You should remember this idea since it also works here!}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Qe1 {A prophylactic move against the ... c5 break. For White, holding the outpost on e5 is important.} O-O {Black has completed their development. Here, White has three major choices.} (10... c5 $2 {. Make sure not to rush with this move!} 11. d5 $1 Bxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxe1 13. Nc7+ {. An intermezzo check often changes everything.} Kd8 14. Rxe1 Kxc7 15. Nxf7 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. f5 {White can charge forward, but it won't give them more than a perpetual check.} Bxf5 12. Nc4 {White can include this intermezzo move to avoid the upcoming knight trade, but there are drawbacks to the plan.} Qd8 13. Bxf5 gxf5 14. Rxf5 b5 15. Ne3 {Going back to e5 now doesn't make much sense.} e6 16. Rf3 b4 17. Ne2 {White's pieces are pushed back.} c5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Qxb4 Nfe4 {Black has a fantastic initiative for the sacrificed pawn.} *

