 move against the ... c5 break. For White, holding the outpost on e5 is important.} O-O {Black has completed their development. Here, White has three major choices.} (10... c5 $2 {. Make sure not to rush with this move!} 11. d5 $1 Bxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxe1 13. Nc7+ {. An intermezzo check often changes everything.} Kd8 14. Rxe1 Kxc7 15. Nxf7 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. h3 {White is preparing the g4 push and hopes for f5 .} Bf5 {Black is not afraid of doubling the pawns, as long as it gives them control of the e4 -square.} ({Of course, make sure to check if} 11... c5 $2 {push works. Here, it doesn't.} 12. d5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxe1 14. Nxe7+ {. Another intermezzo move. With the white queen on e1 , you can forget about ... c5 .}) 12. Bxf5 gxf5 {Black has a slightly weakened king, allowing you to control the e4 -square better.} 13. Be3 e6 14. Kh1 Rfe8 {We're transposing to the main lines.} *

