1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 ({Perhaps you are wondering why we are starting with} 5... c6 {and not with Bf5 – with an idea to meet} 6. Bc4 {with} e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 {?}) ({First, if White wants to go to the main lines, they can meet the move} 5... Bf5 {with} 6. Ne5 {, and Black has nothing better than} c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {, and everything that we discuss in Chapter 2 .}) ({Second, after} 5... Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 {, White suddenly has some extra interesting options like} 7. h4 $5 {or g4!? .}) ({And third, Black plays} 5... Bf5 {to avoid the variation of Bc4 - Bd2 - Qe2 , but White can still force them to go there with the following move order –} 6. Bd2 {с6 Bc4} Nbd7 7. Qe2 {, because rejecting this for Black is more than risky.}) ({Considering everything above, that's why we're recommending} 5... c6 {. You will have to study the main lines anyway, and if White starts to be tricky with} 6. Ne5 {, there's the} Be6 {option. There are fewer variations for you to study and fewer opportunities for your opponent to catch you in some lines.}) 6. Ne5 (6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {is the main line of Chapter 2 .}) 6... Be6 ({A powerful alternative to the more popular} 6... Bf5 {. The fact that back in 1995, Vishy Anand played this variation in the world championship match against Garry Kasparov speaks volumes about the line. Kasparov did not get anything with White and even found himself in a worse position. In the current digital age, many young masters choose this move, probably because it's also the top choice of engines.}) 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Bd3 g6 {Notice that with the bishop on e6 , Black often does not try to remove it to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game.} ({Instead, we're playing in the spirit of the Alekhine defense e4 Nf6 e5} 8... Nd5 {d4 d6} 9. Nf3 {dxe5} Ne5 {c6 , followed by 6...g6 with developing the bishop to g7 and the arising Scandinavian structures. You should remember this idea since it also works here!}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Qe1 {A prophylactic move against the ... c5 break. For White, holding the outpost on e5 is important.} O-O {Black has completed their development. Here, White has three major choices.} (10... c5 $2 {. Make sure not to rush with this move!} 11. d5 $1 Bxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxe1 13. Nc7+ {. An intermezzo check often changes everything.} Kd8 14. Rxe1 Kxc7 15. Nxf7 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. Kh1 {White, just in case, removes the king from the g1 - a7 diagonal and is better equipped to push g4 if the circumstances require it.} Bf5 {An important trade – Black will have enough counterplay using the light squares in the center.} 12. Bxf5 gxf5 13. Be3 e6 14. g4 {This is the only dangerous plan for White – open the g-file and try to checkmate the black king. The good news is – you have enough resources to counter it.} fxg4 {You can't take on g4 with the knight since the knight on d7 would be left hanging.} (14... Nxe5 $2 {. It's very tempting to use an existing idea from other Scandinavian lines to collect the pawn on g4 with the knight, but specifically here, it's a mistake.} 15. fxe5 Nxg4 16. Bf4 {. The problem is that White wants to play h3 , Qh4 and Rg1 and have a killing attack. Black can delay it, but not for too long.} c5 17. d5 Qc7 18. Qg3 Kh8 19. Rae1 {. White is just in time for everything.} exd5 20. Nxd5 Qc6 21. c4 b5 22. b3 bxc4 23. bxc4 {. Things look very bad for Black.}) 15. Rg1 Rfe8 {An important maneuver – Black clears the f8 -square for the knight; thus, White's Qh4 plan here loses power.} 16. h3 Nf8 {Black is ready to close the g-file with the knight. Thus, White has to switch to a positional game.} 17. hxg4 Nd5 18. Ne4 Qxe1 {Without the queens on the board, the black king is safe.} 19. Raxe1 Ng6 {The minor weaknesses on the kingside don't matter – the remaining Black's pieces stand on ideal squares, plus Black is ready to push back White's pieces from the center by using the f- and c-pawns.} *

