 move against the ... c5 break. For White, holding the outpost on e5 is important.} O-O {Black has completed their development. Here, White has three major choices.} (10... c5 $2 {. Make sure not to rush with this move!} 11. d5 $1 Bxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxe1 13. Nc7+ {. An intermezzo check often changes everything.} Kd8 14. Rxe1 Kxc7 15. Nxf7 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. Kh1 {White, just in case, removes the king from the g1 - a7 diagonal and is better equipped to push g4 if the circumstances require it.} Bf5 {An important trade – Black will have enough counterplay using the light squares in the center.} 12. Bxf5 gxf5 13. Be3 e6 14. g4 {This is the only dangerous plan for White – open the g-file and try to checkmate the black king. The good news is – you have enough resources to counter it.} fxg4 {You can't take on g4 with the knight since the knight on d7 would be left hanging.} (14... Nxe5 $2 {. It's very tempting to use an existing idea from other Scandinavian lines to collect the pawn on g4 with the knight, but specifically here, it's a mistake.} 15. fxe5 Nxg4 16. Bf4 {. The problem is that White wants to play h3 , Qh4 and Rg1 and have a killing attack. Black can delay it, but not for too long.} c5 17. d5 Qc7 18. Qg3 Kh8 19. Rae1 {. White is just in time for everything.} exd5 20. Nxd5 Qc6 21. c4 b5 22. b3 bxc4 23. bxc4 {. Things look very bad for Black.}) 15. Rg1 Rfe8 {An important maneuver – Black clears the f8 -square for the knight; thus, White's Qh4 plan here loses power.} 16. Nxg4 Nxg4 17. Rxg4 f5 {An important move to stop White from building a battery of three heavy pieces on the g-file.} 18. Rg2 Kh8 {If White now puts the queen in front of the two rooks, it won't be as effective as vice versa.} 19. d5 {White still has some tactical ideas; thus, Black needs to be accurate.} Qb4 ({Albeit playable, the move} 19... exd5 {would be a risky choice.} 20. Rxg7 Kxg7 21. Bd4+ Kf8 {, and after,} 22. Qh4 Qb4 {is the only move not to lose on the spot.} 23. Rg1 Qxd4 24. Qxh7 Qxg1+ {. Black has no choice.} 25. Kxg1 Nf6 26. Qxb7 Re1+ 27. Kg2 Rae8 28. Qxc6 Kg7 {. The position is equal, but Black had to make some difficult moves to get here.}) 20. a3 Qe7 {Now White has no tricks.} 21. dxc6 bxc6 22. Qf2 Rg8 23. Rag1 c5 {Black's pawn structure is slightly worse, but the white pawn on f4 makes it a potential target. Black has a well-coordinated army, which means we have a dynamic balance on the board.} *

