1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. Be2 {It's a move! Of course, it would stand better on c4 , but also on e2 , the bishop is not that bad.} Bf5 7. O-O e6 {As you can see, Black has no issues completing the development.} 8. Nh4 Bg6 9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. a3 Be7 {The engine here gives White a small edge due to the bishop pair, but you have nothing to be worried about. White pieces don't stand on optimal squares, and it will take time to regroup them. In the meantime, Black can finish their development and look for counterplay with the ... c5 push.} *

