1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. h3 {White stops ... Bg4 , but that wasn't your plan.} Bf5 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Qa6 {A little more precise than starting with ... e6 since you force the queens off the board or stop White from castling short.} 9. Qxa6 Nxa6 10. Bd2 e6 {A typical Scandinavian / Caro-Kann endgame where Black is rock solid. If White wants to claim something out of the opening, they would need the c-pawn on c4 , not c2 .} *

