1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. h3 {White stops ... Bg4 , but that wasn't your plan.} Bf5 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 {Of course, you can also opt for simple development.} 9. O-O Be7 10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 O-O 12. c4 Nd7 {The knight goes to f6 , and Black either pressures the d4 -pawn by doubling the rooks on the d-file or seeks counterplay with ... c5 .} *

