1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. a3 {Some people like such moves, but realistically, the most White will get out of this position is the two-bishop advantage, having committed to a3 instead of developing a piece.} Bf5 7. Nh4 {There's White's idea – he's trying to trade off the bishop and get the bishop pair where the a3 move is useful.} Bg4 8. Qd2 Nbd7 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 {White will get the bishop pair, but at the same time, there will be some weaknesses on the kingside.} 11. Bg2 e6 12. O-O Qc7 ({It's possible to start also with} 12... Be7 {.}) 13. f4 Be7 {White can't trap the bishop on g6 . If they tried to pin the dark-squared bishop on the e-file, there's always the ... Nb6 resource.} 14. f5 exf5 15. Qe2 Nb6 16. Nxf5 Bxf5 17. Rxf5 O-O {White has the bishop pair, but the king is weak. Naturally, Black would like to keep the queens on the board.} *

