1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. Bd3 {This is the only move in this chapter requiring extra attention. No wonder some strong players have also been testing it.} Bg4 {Normally, you don't put the bishop on g4 , but this variation is an exception. The reason is that White's h3 - g4 and Ne5 are not as good as they are in the classical variation.} (6... Bf5 $6 {. White's idea reveals in this variation.} 7. b4 $1 {The point.} Qxb4 {Black has to accept the pawn.} 8. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qc4 10. Bd3 Qe6+ 11. Kf1 {. For the sacrificed pawn White has a dangerous initiative.}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O {White can also play it out positionally.} e6 9. a3 Bd6 {If White does anything else, Black takes the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 Bg6 {Black has a healthy position.} 13. Re1 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 O-O 15. Bd2 Qh5 {The position is just equal.} *

