1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. Bd3 {This is the only move in this chapter requiring extra attention. No wonder some strong players have also been testing it.} Bg4 {Normally, you don't put the bishop on g4 , but this variation is an exception. The reason is that White's h3 - g4 and Ne5 are not as good as they are in the classical variation.} (6... Bf5 $6 {. White's idea reveals in this variation.} 7. b4 $1 {The point.} Qxb4 {Black has to accept the pawn.} 8. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qc4 10. Bd3 Qe6+ 11. Kf1 {. For the sacrificed pawn White has a dangerous initiative.}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O {White can also play it out positionally.} e6 9. Bf4 {White stops Black from landing the dark-squared bishop on the ideal d6 -square.} Qd8 {Black preps the dark-squared bishop trade.} 10. g4 Bg6 11. Bxg6 hxg6 12. Qe2 {Typical engine move, but it contains a trap that might be useful to know.} Bd6 (12... Rxh3 $2 {. Accepting the pawn is dangerous:} 13. Kg2 Rh8 14. Rh1 {. White will use the h-file against you, and the extra pawn doesn't feel.}) 13. Bg3 {It will take the most optimistic person in the world to take on h3 . Our advice is to be realistic.} Qe7 ({There's no need to open the f-file for the white rook. If} 13... Bxg3 $6 14. fxg3 Rxh3 $2 15. Kg2 Rh8 16. g5 {, and the white knights dominate the center and the black king is in trouble.}) 14. a4 Nbd7 15. a5 O-O 16. Ne5 Rac8 {The c5 push is incoming – perhaps Black can prepare it first with moves like ... a6 and ... Rfd8 .} *

