1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. Bd3 {This is the only move in this chapter requiring extra attention. No wonder some strong players have also been testing it.} Bg4 {Normally, you don't put the bishop on g4 , but this variation is an exception. The reason is that White's h3 - g4 and Ne5 are not as good as they are in the classical variation.} (6... Bf5 $6 {. White's idea reveals in this variation.} 7. b4 $1 {The point.} Qxb4 {Black has to accept the pawn.} 8. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qc4 10. Bd3 Qe6+ 11. Kf1 {. For the sacrificed pawn White has a dangerous initiative.}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. Bd2 {Clear indication that White is thinking about castling long.} Nbd7 9. g4 (9. Qe2 e6 10. g4 Bg6 {. This will transpose to later lines.}) 9... Bg6 10. Qe2 e6 {So far, so good. White will likely castle long, but might consider including trade on g6 first.} 11. Bxg6 {This trade looks anti-positional since it opens the h-file for the black rook, but it also might give White an option to anchor the knight on g5 , which is difficult to chase away.} hxg6 12. O-O-O Bb4 {Black wants to eliminate the white knight and control the light squares by playing ... Qb5 next. The white pawn on a2 serves as a good distraction.} 13. Kb1 ({Or} 13. a3 {, your response will be the same.}) 13... Bxc3 {Best take it immediately.} (13... O-O-O $6 {. If Black wants to win an extra tempo and capture on c3 after White's 'waste of time' a3 , then castling long might not be the best choice.} 14. a3 Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Qc7 ({(Also the idea of} 15... Qb5 $2 {no longer works.} 16. Qxb5 cxb5 17. Ng5 Rhf8 18. Bb4 {, and Black can resign. )}) 16. Ng5 Nb6 17. Qe5 {. That's why the Bxg6 is not such a silly idea after all – White here is much better.}) 14. Bxc3 Qb5 15. Qxb5 {White has to take. Otherwise, Black can start active operations on the queenside with ... a5 and keep the king in the center.} cxb5 16. d5 {A necessity, or the black knight on d5 , will dominate the bishop.} Nxd5 17. Bxg7 Rg8 18. Bh6 Rh8 {Pushing the bishop away from the h8 - a1 diagonal is important.} 19. Bc1 Rc8 {The position remains double-edged.} *

