1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. Bd3 {This is the only move in this chapter requiring extra attention. No wonder some strong players have also been testing it.} Bg4 {Normally, you don't put the bishop on g4 , but this variation is an exception. The reason is that White's h3 - g4 and Ne5 are not as good as they are in the classical variation.} (6... Bf5 $6 {. White's idea reveals in this variation.} 7. b4 $1 {The point.} Qxb4 {Black has to accept the pawn.} 8. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qc4 10. Bd3 Qe6+ 11. Kf1 {. For the sacrificed pawn White has a dangerous initiative.}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. Bd2 {Clear indication that White is thinking about castling long.} Nbd7 9. g4 (9. Qe2 e6 10. g4 Bg6 {. This will transpose to later lines.}) 9... Bg6 10. Qe2 e6 {So far, so good. White will likely castle long but might consider including trade on g6 first.} 11. O-O-O {Most players who will get here probably won't take on g6 .} Bb4 12. a3 {If White forces you to take on c3 , there's an important nuance.} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 ({If you play} 14. Qb5 {right here, it will run into the familiar motif of the queen trade and White's d5 push, leaving Black with a worse pawn structure on the kingside. However, you have another resource, since White has not yet played Kb1 .}) 14... Qd5 {Black's ... Qa2 threat gives you enough time to regroup.} 15. Kb1 Qe4 16. Rhe1 Qxd3 17. Rxd3 Nd5 18. Bd2 b5 {Black feels safe.} *

