1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 {In this chapter, we will look at some harmless continuations and what to do if your opponent develops their pieces like the 'Fritz 5' chess engine or is a big fan of online bullet games.} 6. Bd3 {This is the only move in this chapter requiring extra attention. No wonder some strong players have also been testing it.} Bg4 {Normally, you don't put the bishop on g4 , but this variation is an exception. The reason is that White's h3 - g4 and Ne5 are not as good as they are in the classical variation.} (6... Bf5 $6 {. White's idea reveals in this variation.} 7. b4 $1 {The point.} Qxb4 {Black has to accept the pawn.} 8. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qc4 10. Bd3 Qe6+ 11. Kf1 {. For the sacrificed pawn White has a dangerous initiative.}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. Bd2 {Clear indication that White is thinking about castling long.} Nbd7 9. g4 (9. Qe2 e6 10. g4 Bg6 {. This will transpose to later lines.}) 9... Bg6 10. Qe2 e6 {So far, so good. White will likely castle long but might consider including trade on g6 first.} 11. O-O-O {Most players who will get here probably won't take on g6 .} Bb4 12. Kb1 O-O {You shouldn't be afraid of the advanced pawns on the kingside – it's not easy for White to come up with the next move. Remember, you still want to take on d3 , trade on c3 and play ... Qb5 .} (12... Bxd3 $6 {. Unfortunately, you can't replicate the idea from the variation if White had traded the light-squared bishops on g6 .} 13. Qxd3 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Qb5 15. Qxb5 cxb5 {. This line would be fantastic if not for White's next move.} 16. d5 $1 Nxd5 17. Bxg7 Rg8 18. Bh6 {. Black's pawn structure on the kingside is significantly worse than in the similar line.}) 13. g5 Nh5 {The safe choice – if you will jump to d5 , White might already take on g6 and push h4 - h5 .} 14. h4 {White's idea is to break your blockade to proceed with the kingside attack or play positionally and force you to play without the knight on h5 .} Rfd8 {A multi-purpose move; there's no need to force things just yet.} ({It makes sense to eliminate the white knight before it reaches the target} 14... Bxc3 {, but there are other problems:} 15. Bxc3 Qc7 16. Bd2 Rfd8 17. Qe3 {White can prep an idea to trap the black knight on h5 with moves like Be2 , Ne5 , Bg4 , and Qf3 or even a more sinister idea – play for positional domination and shut out the black knight from the game forever.} Nb6 {. It seems that White won't make it but...} 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Ne5 Nd5 20. Qf3 {... White's incoming c4 is a big problem, and Black can't stop it.} b5 $2 21. Ba5 $1 {. Ouch.}) 15. a3 {White might attempt to get something very similar to the informational line, but by doing this, White also creates a potential 'hook' on the queenside – the pawn on a3 .} Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Qc7 17. Bd2 b5 {White has the bishop pair and some space advantage, but Black now has a straightforward game.} ({If White tries to trap the knight on h5 Qe3 , Black is faster on the queenside.} 17... a5 {Be2?} 18. b4 a4 {c5 , and Black is already much better.}) *

