1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bd3 {This move order is rare, but the idea is interesting – White removes the ... Bf5 as an option since it would run into a familiar trick. From White's perspective, it has been the choice of Garry Kasparov, Lenier Dominguez Perez, and other strong grandmasters.} Bg4 {The light-squared bishop has to be developed, so g4 -square is the only good option.} (6... Bf5 $4 7. b4 $1 {. That's why!}) 7. f3 {This was once the choice of Dominguez.} Bh5 8. Nge2 Nbd7 9. Nf4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {In a typical Scandinavian fashion, Black 'gave up the bishop pair to solve all of their opening problems'. It may sound funny, but that's how it is very often.} 11. Qe2 e6 12. Ne4 Bb4 13. c3 {Otherwise, White's strategy makes no sense.} Be7 14. g3 Nxe4 15. fxe4 Bg5 {Black found a cute way to eliminate White's bishop pair in Leinier Domínguez (2725) – Vasyl Ivanchuk (2764), Capablanca Memorial Elite 47th Havana 2012.} *

