1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bd3 {This move order is rare, but the idea is interesting – White removes the ... Bf5 as an option since it would run into a familiar trick. From White's perspective, it has been the choice of Garry Kasparov, Lenier Dominguez Perez, and other strong grandmasters.} Bg4 {The light-squared bishop has to be developed, so g4 -square is the only good option.} (6... Bf5 $4 7. b4 $1 {. That's why!}) 7. Ne4 {An interesting idea – White invites Black to skip the middlegame and go right to the endgame. This move is more poisonous than it may seem in the beginning.} Bxd1 (7... Qh5 $2 {would work with the white knight on f3 perhaps.} 8. f3 {. The black queen on h5 is poorly placed.}) (7... Nxe4 {would be the easy way out, accepting a slightly worse position but solid enough.} 8. Bxa5 Bxd1 9. Rxd1 Nf6 10. c4 {, and White has the center and the bishop pair.}) 8. Nxf6+ exf6 {Here, this 'automatic' capture only leads to problems.} 9. Bxa5 Bh5 {Black thought that they would get a good game with the inevitable ... Bg6 , but this is when things suddenly became crystal clear.} (9... Bg4 10. Ne2 {, and White has a better middlegame with easy plans.}) 10. f4 {Typical energetic response by Kasparov – Black can't trade the bishops.} Bd6 11. f5 g6 {Garry Kasparov (2812) – Loek van Wely (2636) Hoogovens 5' Wijk aan Zee blitz 1999.} 12. Nh3 O-O 13. O-O {White would have kept a significant advantage.} *

