1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bd3 {This move order is rare, but the idea is interesting – White removes the ... Bf5 as an option since it would run into a familiar trick. From White's perspective, it has been the choice of Garry Kasparov, Lenier Dominguez Perez, and other strong grandmasters.} Bg4 {The light-squared bishop has to be developed, so g4 -square is the only good option.} (6... Bf5 $4 7. b4 $1 {. That's why!}) 7. Ne4 {An interesting idea – White invites Black to skip the middlegame and go right to the endgame. This move is more poisonous than it may seem in the beginning.} Bxd1 (7... Qh5 $2 {would work with the white knight on f3 perhaps.} 8. f3 {. The black queen on h5 is poorly placed.}) (7... Nxe4 {would be the easy way out, accepting a slightly worse position but solid enough.} 8. Bxa5 Bxd1 9. Rxd1 Nf6 10. c4 {, and White has the center and the bishop pair.}) 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 {That's a move you normally don't play in these setups, but this position is a unique exception!} 9. Bxa5 Bh5 10. f4 {Continuing in the same spirit as in the Kasparov – Van Wely game. Otherwise, Black will play ... e6 and ... Bg6 with a good position.} e6 11. f5 c5 {The main difference is that Black has the g-file for enough counterplay. Black can achieve a good game with very energetic play.} 12. Bc3 (12. d5 $5 Bd6 $1) 12... Nc6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black is not holding onto the pawn but seeks activity.} 14. Nh3 {White might also opt for the development, considering that Black can't play ... e5 due to White's Nf2 and the light-squared bishop on h5 eventually is doomed.} Ne5 15. Nf4 {Now the position will simplify a little – Black loses a pawn but will get the bishop pair.} Nxd3+ 16. cxd3 Bg4 17. fxe6 fxe6 {Black eventually will have full compensation for the missing pawn – we can stop our analysis here, since the game is not forced.} ({After Rf1 , here's how the game might continue if White picks up many of the best (and non-obvious) moves:} 17... h5 18. h3 Bf5 19. Nd5 $1 Rd8 $1 {. Black gives up a pawn and even more!} 20. Nxf6+ Ke7 21. Nd5+ Kd6 $1 22. Bxh8 Kxd5 {. This position is unbelievable since White has an extra exchange and a pawn, but Black is doing alright!} 23. Bc3 Rg8 $1 24. O-O-O Rxg2 {. Black is simply too active.} 25. Rde1 Bd6 {Rg1} 26. Rh2 Rg7 {Bf4+} 27. Kd1 Kc6 {, and Black is ready to take over the game.}) *

