1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Ne4 {If White goes for the discovered attack via the e4 -square instead of d5 , it gives Black an extra option.} Qc7 ({It's possible to go} 7... Qd8 {as well.} 8. Nxf6+ exf6 {. This will transpose to the main line of the chapter.}) 8. Nxf6+ exf6 {Black's logic makes sense – the queen on c7 stands better than on d8 .} 9. Qe2+ Be7 10. O-O-O {The principled continuation – now Black has to be a little careful.} b5 {Now this is necessary – if Black would castle short instead, White's g4 and h4 would make a big difference. It's important to remind White as quickly as possible that castling long can have consequences.} 11. Bb3 a5 12. g4 Bc8 {There's no need to fuel White's attack with ... Bg6 since their incoming h4 - h5 will happen.} 13. a3 O-O 14. Nf3 {Not an easy move to make since White gives up the g-pawn. The problem is – if you accept it, it will accelerate White's attack, and Black immediately goes into defense. White's idea also is to push g5 .} b4 {We also considered this, but here, Black is too slow. Still, study the line for some extra ideas!} 15. Rhe1 Bd6 16. g5 (16. a4 Nd7 17. g5 Ba6 {transposes to the same line.}) 16... Nd7 17. a4 Ba6 18. Qe3 c5 {Now we're entering a crazy line where White could easily get cold feet.} 19. gxf6 c4 20. fxg7 Rfc8 21. Ba2 b3 {Black is pushing forward everything they have!} 22. Bb1 c3 23. Qxc3 bxc2 24. Bxc2 Qb6 25. Qe3 (25. Qxa5 $4 Rxc2+ $1 26. Kxc2 Bd3+ {is easy to miss.}) 25... Rab8 26. Bc3 Bb4 {Black is down three pawns, but the practical compensation is interesting. White can claim an advantage only with precise play.} 27. Kd2 Nf6 28. Ne5 Rxc3 29. bxc3 Rc8 {Black plays with a great imagination, and now White has to pick up some tough moves.} (29... Nd5 $4 30. Bxh7+ {. The black king is also weak.}) 30. Rb1 Rxc3 31. Rxb4 axb4 32. Nd7 {The key move – White wins.} Nxd7 33. Qe8+ Kxg7 34. Rg1+ Kf6 35. Qxd7 Bc8 36. Qd5 Ke7 37. Qg5+ Qf6 38. Qxf6+ Kxf6 39. Rg3 {That's too bad – this was such a fun line!} *

