1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Qe2 {It's important to note that if White starts with this move, you must immediately retreat with the queen since there's a trick you don't want to miss.} Qc7 (7... Nbd7 $4 {. Black defends from Nd5 but misses another threat.} 8. Nb5 {. The trouble arrived from a different angle.}) 8. Nf3 e6 ({With} 8... Nbd7 {, you can also transpose to the variations from Chapter 2 .} 9. O-O-O e6 {, and so on.}) 9. Bb3 Bb4 {In this version, starting with this move is a little more precise.} 10. O-O-O Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Nbd7 {Black can castle both ways. If you're wondering why you were unable to play like this in Chapter 3 with an early ... e6 and ... Bb4 , you'll see that the move order to get to the position matters.} *

