1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nge2 {White can attempt to go after the light-squared bishop.} e6 8. Ng3 Nbd7 ({More precise than the automatic} 8... Bg6 {– White will trade your bishop anyway; thus, best focus on development. Think like this: it took White three moves with the knight to capture your bishop, who had only moved once.}) 9. d5 {An interesting attempt to exploit the x-ray, but Black is holding.} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Avoid giving White a freeroll with the bishop pair.} (11... Nxf6 12. Qe2 {. The point is that now Black is unable to preserve the bishop.} Bg6 $2 13. Bb5+ {, and Black is in trouble.}) 12. Qe2 Bg6 {The difference is that now Bb5 doesn't come with a check, and Black is ready to castle long.} *

