1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nge2 {White can attempt to go after the light-squared bishop.} e6 8. Ng3 Nbd7 ({More precise than the automatic} 8... Bg6 {– White will trade your bishop anyway; thus, best focus on development. Think like this: it took White three moves with the knight to capture your bishop, who had only moved once.}) 9. Nxf5 Qxf5 10. O-O Bd6 11. f4 {White could attempt to squeeze Black.} O-O 12. Kh1 Qa5 {The black queen doesn't feel particularly well on f5 ; thus, best move it back to the queenside.} 13. a3 Qb6 14. Qe2 {White correctly assumes that accepting the pawn on b2 is risky for Black – the Rab1 threat is serious.} Rfe8 15. Rad1 Rad8 {Black keeps eyes open on what White will do. You could position the knight on d5 or play ... g6 and fianchetto the bishop to g7 to pressure the d4 -pawn.} *

