1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nf3 Nbd7 {transposes to the lines  from Chapter 4.}) 7... Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 ({We did not seriously consider} 8... gxf6 {since it's dubious and White has several ways to get a considerable advantage, starting with} 9. Qf3 $5 {. We've once again reached the Tartakower setup from the Caro-Kann, where the evaluation some time ago was unanimous – White is better. But is it so? Compared to a known line in the Caro-Kann, White has an extra tempo while Black controls the important b1 - h7 diagonal. Black has some problems, but there's no reason to evaluate the arising positions as clearly worse for Black. White has the initiative, but Black's game is straightforward with clear attacking plans, which most people today value highly in accelerated time control games.}) 9. Qf3 {A very serious gambit – White uses the fact that the kingside knight has not blocked the queen yet and attempts to use the loose black bishop to accelerate the initiative.} Bxc2 {A principled response.} 10. Ne2 (10. Rc1 {will transpose to the variation with a different move order.} Bg6 11. h4 h5 12. Ne2 Bd6 13. Bf4 {, and so on.}) 10... Bd6 11. Rc1 Bg6 12. h4 h5 {The only move. Now you're racing to get the knight to d5 , and you must do it before castling short.} (12... Qe7 $2 {Black can't ignore White's threats.} 13. h5 Be4 14. Qg4 Nd7 15. f3 {. White had already achieved a winning advantage in Alexey Kislinsky (2479) – Dmitrijs Tokranovs (2325), Pardubice Czech op-A 28th 2017.} Bd5 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Qxg7 {. The safety of the black king is a decisive factor.}) 13. O-O {This would allow Black to regroup just in time.} Nd7 14. Bf4 Nb6 {Black is ready to castle short – you'll see why!} 15. Bb3 O-O 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Nf4 Nd5 {That's why! Black is just in time to block the strong light-squared bishop and doesn't have to commit to ... Kh7 .} *

