1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nf3 Nbd7 {transposes to the lines  from Chapter 4.}) 7... Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 ({We did not seriously consider} 8... gxf6 {since it's dubious and White has several ways to get a considerable advantage, starting with} 9. Qf3 $5 {. We've once again reached the Tartakower setup from the Caro-Kann, where the evaluation some time ago was unanimous – White is better. But is it so? Compared to a known line in the Caro-Kann, White has an extra tempo while Black controls the important b1 - h7 diagonal. Black has some problems, but there's no reason to evaluate the arising positions as clearly worse for Black. White has the initiative, but Black's game is straightforward with clear attacking plans, which most people today value highly in accelerated time control games.}) 9. Qf3 {A very serious gambit – White uses the fact that the kingside knight has not blocked the queen yet and attempts to use the loose black bishop to accelerate the initiative.} Bxc2 {A principled response.} 10. Ne2 (10. Rc1 {will transpose to the variation with a different move order.} Bg6 11. h4 h5 12. Ne2 Bd6 13. Bf4 {, and so on.}) 10... Bd6 11. Rc1 Bg6 12. h4 h5 {The only move. Now you're racing to get the knight to d5 , and you must do it before castling short.} (12... Qe7 $2 {Black can't ignore White's threats.} 13. h5 Be4 14. Qg4 Nd7 15. f3 {. White had already achieved a winning advantage in Alexey Kislinsky (2479) – Dmitrijs Tokranovs (2325), Pardubice Czech op-A 28th 2017.} Bd5 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Qxg7 {. The safety of the black king is a decisive factor.}) 13. Bf4 {Precise move order – Black now has difficulty bringing the knight into the game.} Bb4+ {This enables the ... Nd7 move. It's also best to keep the king in the center for a while since it's unclear if castling short is not causing greater problems.} (13... O-O $6 14. O-O Na6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Nf4 {. Black has some problems with the light-squared bishop. People usually castle to bring the king to safety – is this the case here?}) 14. Kf1 Nd7 {The knight is heading to d5 .} 15. Qb3 {That's the drawback of having the bishop on b4 ... The knight maneuver will have to wait.} Qb6 16. Rh3 Be7 {A precise move – Black wants to get queens off the board.} 17. Qd1 {White decides to keep the queens on the board.} Qd8 {Black once again re-enables the ... Nb6 maneuver, best not castle short just yet.} 18. Rg3 Nb6 19. Rxg6 {Very creative! White must know this maneuver in advance because finding it over the board is nearly impossible, at least evaluating the complications.} fxg6 20. Be6 g5 {Black gains some space but, more importantly, frees the h6 -square for the rook.} 21. Qd3 Rh6 22. Bd2 Qd6 23. Qe4 Kf8 {White has the compensation, but don't forget that you have an exchange and a pawn for your suffering.} 24. Rc3 Re8 25. Rb3 f5 {It's a good idea to bring the rook on h6 in the game, even if it costs you the extra pawn.} 26. Bxf5 Nc4 27. Bc1 g4 {The cosmic lines are over; we can conclude our analysis and assess that the position is equal!} 28. Rxb7 (28. Bxh6 $2 Qxh6 {, and Black takes over the game.}) (28. Qd3 Rf6 29. Bf4 Qd5 30. Bg6 b5 {. You shouldn't mind to give up your extra material to normalize the position.} 31. Bxe8 Kxe8 32. Bg5 Rf7 {, with equality.}) 28... Bxh4 29. Qc2 Rf6 30. Nf4 Qxd4 31. Ng6+ Rxg6 32. Bxg6 Rd8 {And somehow, this will end in a draw – congratulations to White if they made it this far.} *

