the variation with a different move order.} Bg6 11. h4 h5 12. Ne2 Bd6 13. Bf4 {, and so on.}) 10... Bd6 11. Rc1 Bg6 12. h4 h5 {The only move. Now you're racing to get the knight to d5 , and you must do it before castling short.} (12... Qe7 $2 {Black can't ignore White's threats.} 13. h5 Be4 14. Qg4 Nd7 15. f3 {. White had already achieved a winning advantage in Alexey Kislinsky (2479) – Dmitrijs Tokranovs (2325), Pardubice Czech op-A 28th 2017.} Bd5 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Qxg7 {. The safety of the black king is a decisive factor.}) 13. Bf4 {Precise move order – Black now has difficulty bringing the knight into the game.} Bb4+ {This enables the ... Nd7 move. It's also best to keep the king in the center for a while since it's unclear if castling short is not causing greater problems.} (13... O-O $6 14. O-O Na6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Nf4 {. Black has some problems with the light-squared bishop. People usually castle to bring the king to safety – is this the case here?}) 14. Kf1 Nd7 {The knight is heading to d5 .} 15. Qb3 {That's the drawback of having the bishop on b4 ... The knight maneuver will have to wait.} Qb6 16. Rh3 Be7 {A precise move – Black wants to get queens off the board.} 17. Re3 Qxb3 {Now it's a little easier – even if you misremember something, you're not getting checkmated.} 18. Bxb3 Kf8 19. d5 {While there are others, this is the most forcing continuation – even without the queens, White keeps charging forward, and Black still has to be cautious.} Ne5 {It's time to give something back. Now, the position will simplify.} 20. Bxe5 fxe5 21. dxc6 bxc6 22. Rxc6 Bxh4 23. Rxe5 Bd8 {The last accurate move – Black stops White from doubling the rooks on the 7th rank.} ({After Nf4 , here's how the game might continue:} 23... Rh6 {Nxg6+} 24. Rxg6 Rxg6 {fxg6 , and Black is holding.}) *

