ght feel like a blunder.} 11. Bxf7+ {Indeed! Did Black miss this? However, Black just sold the pawn to accelerate their development, and the king on d8 will feel just fine.} Kd8 12. Bb3 Re8+ 13. Be3 Be4 14. Ne2 {White responds energetically, but also Black doesn't have to take the pawn on g2 .} a5 {Black plays like nothing happened, and White has to figure out where to position the king.} 15. Kd2 {Wonders of the engine.} a4 {There's more than one way to continue to get a rich counterplay – this line is just an example.} 16. Bc2 g6 17. Qh4 Bxc2 18. Kxc2 Qf7 19. Nc1 Nd7 20. Nd3 Ra5 {Black has the positional compensation, but as they say, a pawn is a pawn. Hence, this continuation is for adventurous souls.} *

