move and gives White some advantage but doesn't present any further moves.} ({If} 11. Qxe7+ {, here 's how continued one of the games of the variation. You probably don't have to study it move by move, but at least going through some ideas wouldn't hurt.}) 11... Qxe2 {We will look at this line a little deeper.} 12. Nxe2 Be6 {The point – if White now trades on e6 , White can't hope for any advantage, since just one semi-weakness is not enough. The question is – how will White protect the bishop?} 13. Bb3 Na6 {Or take on b3 immediately, but it's already clear that White won't take on e6 themselves.} 14. Bf4 Bxb3 15. axb3 O-O-O {Both bishops will disappear from the board, but White's chances for an advantage are minimal.} 16. Rhe1 Nc7 17. Bxd6 Rxd6 18. b4 Nd5 {Objectively, the position is just equal.} *

