1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nf3 Nbd7 {transposes to the lines  from Chapter 4.}) 7... Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 ({We did not seriously consider} 8... gxf6 {since it's dubious and White has several ways to get a considerable advantage, starting with} 9. Qf3 $5 {. We've once again reached the Tartakower setup from the Caro-Kann, where the evaluation some time ago was unanimous – White is better. But is it so? Compared to a known line in the Caro-Kann, White has an extra tempo while Black controls the important b1 - h7 diagonal. Black has some problems, but there's no reason to evaluate the arising positions as clearly worse for Black. White has the initiative, but Black's game is straightforward with clear attacking plans, which most people today value highly in accelerated time control games.}) 9. Nf3 {The most played move in the position. Even though the white knight on f3 doesn't appear to be doing much, White might hint at Nh4 ideas later.} Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nh4 {White goes after the bishop.} Bc8 {This is more fighting – Black wants to play ... Na6 - c7 and then see what happens. Maybe position the knight on d5 , or go back with ... Be6 ideas and recapture with the knight.} 12. Re1 Na6 13. Bxa6 {A committal move – White ruins Black's pawn structure but gives Black the bishop pair.} bxa6 14. c4 Be6 15. Qa4 Qd7 {Black gets very creative on the kingside – it's unclear if White can even take the pawn without consequences.} ({Bc3 . Here's how the game might continue – at least it will give you the directions.} 15... Re8 {. Now rushing with ... g5 and ... Bg4 would be too early.} 16. Qxa6 Bc7 17. Qa4 h5 {. Once again, Black plays like nothing happened – fine, positional chess.} 18. Nf3 Bg4 {Nd2 Be2 Nf1} 19. h4 {d5} Rc8 {dxc6 Qf5} 20. Qxa7 {h3 . This is just one of the lines – White has collected many pawns but will have to be very careful on the kingside. The engine gives here equality.}) *

