1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nf3 Nbd7 {transposes to the lines  from Chapter 4.}) 7... Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 ({We did not seriously consider} 8... gxf6 {since it's dubious and White has several ways to get a considerable advantage, starting with} 9. Qf3 $5 {. We've once again reached the Tartakower setup from the Caro-Kann, where the evaluation some time ago was unanimous – White is better. But is it so? Compared to a known line in the Caro-Kann, White has an extra tempo while Black controls the important b1 - h7 diagonal. Black has some problems, but there's no reason to evaluate the arising positions as clearly worse for Black. White has the initiative, but Black's game is straightforward with clear attacking plans, which most people today value highly in accelerated time control games.}) 9. Qe2+ {Smart check! White uses the fact that Black can't trade the queens without consequences.} Be7 (9... Qe7 $2 {. Unfortunately, this is a serious mistake.} 10. O-O-O {. The problem is that Black has to take on e2 since White can decline the queen trade at any moment and threaten to include Re1 .} Qxe2 11. Nxe2 Bd6 {. Black is significantly behind in development with a worse pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Rhe1 Kd7 {. If only Black was able to complete the development...} 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nh5 Rg8 16. Bh6 $1 {, and Black will lose something.}) 10. Nf3 {Before defining which way to castle, White develops the knight first.} O-O {Now, the pawn on c2 is under attack.} (10... b5 {. If you start with the queenside attack immediately, you're telling White to castle short:} 11. Bb3 O-O 12. Nh4 Bd7 13. O-O {. White is just better, and Black's setup on the queenside is weird.}) (10... Bxc2 $4 {. The problem is, you can't take the pawn.} 11. Bh6 $1 gxh6 12. Qxc2 {. Black's position is horrible. The main problem is that you can't secure your king.}) 11. O-O-O {Quite a principled choice. The game has a good chance of heating up, and the king's safety will be a huge factor.} Bd6 {Black uses the moment to improve the dark-squared bishop and threatens with ... Re8 to take the e-file. Once again, White has some choices, but the two main ones are Rhe1 and Rde1 . Please pay close attention to the difference and understand why your response will differ against both.} 12. g4 {This would be a nice idea, if not work the intermezzo move.} Re8 13. Qf1 Be4 14. Qh3 b5 {Black starts first. Thus, their chances are to be preferred. White can't retreat to d3 without completely ruining their queenside pawn structure.} *

