1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nf3 Nbd7 {transposes to the lines  from Chapter 4.}) 7... Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 ({We did not seriously consider} 8... gxf6 {since it's dubious and White has several ways to get a considerable advantage, starting with} 9. Qf3 $5 {. We've once again reached the Tartakower setup from the Caro-Kann, where the evaluation some time ago was unanimous – White is better. But is it so? Compared to a known line in the Caro-Kann, White has an extra tempo while Black controls the important b1 - h7 diagonal. Black has some problems, but there's no reason to evaluate the arising positions as clearly worse for Black. White has the initiative, but Black's game is straightforward with clear attacking plans, which most people today value highly in accelerated time control games.}) 9. Qe2+ {Smart check! White uses the fact that Black can't trade the queens without consequences.} Be7 (9... Qe7 $2 {. Unfortunately, this is a serious mistake.} 10. O-O-O {. The problem is that Black has to take on e2 since White can decline the queen trade at any moment and threaten to include Re1 .} Qxe2 11. Nxe2 Bd6 {. Black is significantly behind in development with a worse pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Rhe1 Kd7 {. If only Black was able to complete the development...} 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nh5 Rg8 16. Bh6 $1 {, and Black will lose something.}) 10. Nf3 {Before defining which way to castle, White develops the knight first.} O-O {Now, the pawn on c2 is under attack.} (10... Bxc2 $4 {. The problem is, you can't take the pawn.} 11. Bh6 $1 gxh6 12. Qxc2 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. O-O-O {Quite a principled choice. The game has a good chance of heating up, and the king's safety will be a huge factor.} Bd6 {Black uses the moment to improve the dark-squared bishop and threatens with ... Re8 to take the e-file. Once again, White has some choices, but the two main ones are Rhe1 and Rde1 . Please pay close attention to the difference and understand why your response will differ against both.} 12. Rhe1 {A logical move – White takes over the e-file but keeps the other rook on d1 for some potential action in the center. Black must be accurate since White's kingside attack might still be happening.} b5 {Normally, this would be your move – if the bishop retreats to b3 , you continue with the queenside assault; after Bd3 , you should trade it and fight for the weakened light squares on the queenside. However, White has an unpleasant intermezzo move.} 13. Nh4 Bd7 {You don't have any better squares since retreating on g6 will result in the light-squared bishop trade; White will continue with Bd3 and start a kingside attack with h4 - h5 .} ({Here, the move} 13... Bc8 $2 {is a heavy mistake – make sure you don't mix up the sides of Rhe1 and Rde1 !} 14. Bd3 Na6 15. d5 $1 {is precisely why White kept the rook on d1 .} Nc5 16. dxc6 Qb6 17. Bxb5 $1 Rb8 18. Be3 $1 {If the white rook was not on d1 , this would be impossible.}) 14. Bd3 g6 (14... Na6 $4 {. Black has no time to develop the queenside.} 15. Qh5 g6 16. Nxg6 fxg6 17. Bxg6 {. The problem is – Black has no way to defend the pawn on h7 since the bishop on d7 blocks the queen.}) 15. g4 Na6 16. Nf5 {A mighty move that engines initially don't even consider. Black can't take the knight.} Re8 {Black has got no choice.} (16... gxf5 $4 {is not obvious, but White develops a killing attack.} 17. gxf5 Kh8 18. Qh5 Rg8 19. Re4 $1 {. Very powerful.} Rg2 20. Bf1 $1 Rg1 21. Be2 $1 Rg2 22. Bf3 $1 {. A precise sequence found by the engine.} Rxh2 23. Qxf7 Bxf5 24. Re8+ $1 Qxe8 25. Qxf6+ Kg8 26. Qxd6 {. White is down a rook but wins because of two impossible-to-parry threats.}) 17. Qf3 Rxe1 (17... gxf5 {. Once again, you can't take the knight.} 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 19. Re1 Qc8 20. gxf5 {. Even if White doesn't have a direct killing shot, Black has major difficulties organizing a defense against the kingside attack.} Kh8 21. Rg1 Nb4 22. Be4 Nd5 23. Qh5 Nf4 24. Qf3 Nd5 25. Kb1 $1 {. According to the engine, White can afford to execute even such slow moves and still win. Just don't go here.}) 18. Nh6+ Kg7 19. Rxe1 {White has the attack while Black hasn't even started his.} Nb4 20. Be4 Qc7 21. g5 f5 22. a3 {A powerful move, forcing Black's hand.} Nd5 23. Bxd5 cxd5 24. Qxd5 Bc6 25. Qb3 {White is up a pawn and is still attacking.} Rc8 26. Bc3 Be4 27. d5+ Kf8 28. Ng4 {It already feels that Black is borderline losing.} b4 {Last chance to complicate matters.} 29. axb4 Bxc2 30. Qxc2 fxg4 31. Re4 Bf4+ 32. Kb1 Bxg5 33. Qd1 {White keeps a large advantage.} *

