queen trade at any moment and threaten to include Re1 .} Qxe2 11. Nxe2 Bd6 {. Black is significantly behind in development with a worse pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Rhe1 Kd7 {. If only Black was able to complete the development...} 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nh5 Rg8 16. Bh6 $1 {, and Black will lose something.}) 10. Nf3 {Before defining which way to castle, White develops the knight first.} O-O {Now, the pawn on c2 is under attack.} (10... Bxc2 $4 {. The problem is, you can't take the pawn.} 11. Bh6 $1 gxh6 12. Qxc2 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. O-O-O {Quite a principled choice. The game has a good chance of heating up, and the king's safety will be a huge factor.} Bd6 {Black uses the moment to improve the dark-squared bishop and threatens with ... Re8 to take the e-file. Once again, White has some choices, but the two main ones are Rhe1 and Rde1 . Please pay close attention to the difference and understand why your response will differ against both.} 12. Rhe1 {A logical move – White takes over the e-file but keeps the other rook on d1 for some potential action in the center. Black must be accurate since White's kingside attack might still be happening.} Qc8 {A smart waiting move, anticipating White's Nh4 . Black delays the queenside attack for one move.} (12... b5 $6 {. Normally, this would be your move – if the bishop retreats to b3 , you continue with the queenside assault; after Bd3 , you should trade it and fight for the weakened light squares on the queenside. However, White has an unpleasant intermezzo move. See the informational variation here .}) 13. Nh4 ({The idea} 13. g4 $2 {is tempting, but it does not work once again.} Bxg4 14. Rg1 Re8 $1 {. It matters where the other white rook stands. If it were on e1 , this entire idea would not work. White's attack on the kingside is failing.}) 13... Bg4 {That's the idea – you want to close the d1 - h5 diagonal for the white queen.} 14. f3 Bd7 {Now, no matter what happens, the white queen can't easily join the kingside attack, and the Black can focus on their matters on the queenside.} 15. g4 Na6 16. Bd3 Re8 17. Be4 g6 {You will need this move to stop Nf5 . White can't do it here since you will accept the piece and eliminate the annoying f5 -pawn immediately. That's one of the perks of having the queen on c8 .} 18. Qg2 Qc7 19. Nf5 Bf4 {You already know that Black can't capture the knight on f5 .} 20. Rg1 {White hopes for the g-file to open at some point, but you can ignore the white knight for now.} Be6 21. Kb1 Rad8 22. c3 Kh8 {Even if White has slightly better chances, Black has an excellent counterplay and an easy plan on the queenside. At all times, White must ensure that you won't change your mind and will still grab the knight.} *

