queen trade at any moment and threaten to include Re1 .} Qxe2 11. Nxe2 Bd6 {. Black is significantly behind in development with a worse pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Rhe1 Kd7 {. If only Black was able to complete the development...} 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nh5 Rg8 16. Bh6 $1 {, and Black will lose something.}) 10. Nf3 {Before defining which way to castle, White develops the knight first.} O-O {Now, the pawn on c2 is under attack.} (10... Bxc2 $4 {. The problem is, you can't take the pawn.} 11. Bh6 $1 gxh6 12. Qxc2 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. O-O-O {Quite a principled choice. The game has a good chance of heating up, and the king's safety will be a huge factor.} Bd6 {Black uses the moment to improve the dark-squared bishop and threatens with ... Re8 to take the e-file. Once again, White has some choices, but the two main ones are Rhe1 and Rde1 . Please pay close attention to the difference and understand why your response will differ against both.} 12. Rde1 {White has to take control of the e-file but keep the kingside rook for a potential attack against the black king. It, however, takes away from White options to react decisively in the center if an opportunity arises.} b5 ({This move was a serious inaccuracy after Rhe1 , but here it works. Make sure you understand the nuances!} 12... Qc8 $6 {. If you're trying to play it in the same spirit as with 12.Rhe1 , there is a major difference.} 13. g4 $1 {. This move was unavailable in that line, but is here.} Bxg4 14. Rhg1 {. First, Black does not have the defensive resource of ... Re8 , and second, the white rook on e1 has avoided the nasty pin. This position for Black is perilous.}) 13. Nh4 {An important intermezzo move characteristic of these lines.} Bc8 {It's important to keep the 7th rank open in case White is ready to sacrifice 'everything that moves' on g6 – you will need to connect your queen.} (13... Bd7 {is very risky.} 14. Bd3 g6 ({(} 14... Na6 $4 15. Qh5 g6 16. Nxg6 {. This problem you already should know - you can't protect the kingside.)}) 15. g4 Na6 16. Nf5 {. This sacrifice is covered already in another informational line, and the bottom line is the same – you can't accept it.} Re8 17. Qf3 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Bf8 19. Ne3 Rc8 20. Be4 {. White's plan is much clearer than Black's.}) 14. Bd3 Na6 {Black is hinting at ... Nb4 .} 15. Qh5 {Let's look at the variation if White goes for a double sacrifice.} ({White can carry out this breakthrough} 15. d5 {like in the line with 12.Rhe1 , but with the white rook on d1 missing, it's nowhere near as effective as in that line.} Nc5 16. dxc6 Qb6 {. Since White can't take the pawn on b5 because of ... Rb8 and White is missing the rook on d1 , Black has a fantastic position.}) 15... g6 16. Nxg6 fxg6 17. Bxg6 Qc7 {That's why you had to play ... Bc8 earlier.} (17... hxg6 $4 {. It goes without saying that you can't accept the second piece.} 18. Qxg6+ Kh8 19. Re4 {, and the engine announces mate in 10.}) 18. Bh6 {White keeps pushing.} hxg6 {Now you can take it!} 19. Qxg6+ Kh8 20. Bxf8 (20. Re4 $4 Qh7 21. Qh5 Bf5 {, and White's attack fails.}) 20... Bxf8 21. Re8 (21. Re4 $4 Qg7 {. It may look scary, but White has exactly one check on h4 , but the attack is officially over. Black's two minor pieces for the rook are too strong.}) 21... Qg7 22. Rxf8+ (22. Qh5+ $4 Kg8 23. Rhe1 Bg4 {. The engine says that ... Nc7 is even stronger but you have to see the point – White's initiative is over.}) 22... Qxf8 23. Re1 Nc7 24. Re3 {White is desperately using all of their last resources – Black is holding.} Qg7 25. Qxg7+ Kxg7 26. Re7+ Kg6 27. Rxc7 {The outcome is that White wins back one of the sacrificed pieces for a bunch of pawns, but as they say, a piece is a piece.} Be6 28. Rxc6 Bd5 29. Rc3 Rh8 30. h3 b4 31. Rg3+ Kf7 {White has four pawns for the bishop; objectively, the position is equal. However, White's pawns seem to be static; thus, it feels that Black's practical chances should be rated higher.} *

