queen trade at any moment and threaten to include Re1 .} Qxe2 11. Nxe2 Bd6 {. Black is significantly behind in development with a worse pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Rhe1 Kd7 {. If only Black was able to complete the development...} 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nh5 Rg8 16. Bh6 $1 {, and Black will lose something.}) 10. Nf3 {Before defining which way to castle, White develops the knight first.} O-O {Now, the pawn on c2 is under attack.} (10... Bxc2 $4 {. The problem is, you can't take the pawn.} 11. Bh6 $1 gxh6 12. Qxc2 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. O-O-O {Quite a principled choice. The game has a good chance of heating up, and the king's safety will be a huge factor.} Bd6 {Black uses the moment to improve the dark-squared bishop and threatens with ... Re8 to take the e-file. Once again, White has some choices, but the two main ones are Rhe1 and Rde1 . Please pay close attention to the difference and understand why your response will differ against both.} 12. Rde1 {White has to take control of the e-file but keep the kingside rook for a potential attack against the black king. It, however, takes away from White options to react decisively in the center if an opportunity arises.} b5 ({This move was a serious inaccuracy after Rhe1 , but here it works. Make sure you understand the nuances!} 12... Qc8 $6 {. If you're trying to play it in the same spirit as with 12.Rhe1 , there is a major difference.} 13. g4 $1 {. This move was unavailable in that line, but is here.} Bxg4 14. Rhg1 {. First, Black does not have the defensive resource of ... Re8 , and second, the white rook on e1 has avoided the nasty pin. This position for Black is perilous.}) 13. Nh4 {An important intermezzo move characteristic of these lines.} Bc8 {It's important to keep the 7th rank open in case White is ready to sacrifice 'everything that moves' on g6 – you will need to connect your queen.} 14. Bd3 Na6 {Black is hinting at ... Nb4 .} 15. a3 {Even if White stops the knight from jumping to b4 , this decision can backfire because the white pawn on a3 can soon become a target.} Nc7 {Black finds another way to bring the knight to d5 . It's tempting to play 15... g6 and stop White from playing Nf5 , but this comes with other problems.} (15... g6 16. f4 Nc7 {. The point is – if Black plays ... f5 now, the white knight will make it to the e5 square, which might be even worse.} 17. f5 Nd5 18. Rhf1 Bd7 19. Be4 {, and White's initiative on the kingside feels more real.}) 16. Qf3 {Let us illustrate one potential line for how Black can open up the queenside.} b4 17. axb4 {If White doesn't take it and moves past with the a-pawn to keep the queenside closed, you can push either ... b3 or ... Nd5 first and then push the b-pawn.} a5 18. bxa5 Nd5 {Exchange sacrifice is on the horizon.} 19. c4 Bb4 {Another powerful move – now White has no choice.} 20. cxd5 Bxd2+ 21. Kxd2 Qxa5+ {Now White has to walk a tightrope to survive the next moves.} 22. Kc1 {Not an obvious difference between Kc2 and Kc1 .} (22. Kc2 $6 Qa4+ 23. Kc1 cxd5 {. Black has a terrific attack and an extra option of ... Qxd4}) (22. Ke2 $4 Re8+ 23. Kd1 Qa1+ {, and White loses the rook.}) 22... cxd5 {The engine keeps the position level but in no lines White feels safe.} ({Re3 . Here's how the game might continue:} 22... Bd7 23. Bb1 Qa1 {Rhe1 Rab8} 24. Re2 g5 {. Just as White seemingly defends everything, the knight on h4 can be standing awkwardly. Rc3 . White can't jump to f5 due to ... Rfc8 +, and everything is starting to fall apart. Rfe8 . The knight on h4 isn't going anywhere.} 25. Re8 {Rxe8 Re3} Rc8 {Rc3 Re8 , with a repetition.}) *

