1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White delays or avoids playing Nf3 .} Nf6 5. Bd2 {When Indian grandmaster Parimarjan Negi quit his professional career, he recommended exactly this move in his full repertoire for White.} ({If White will start with the move} 5. Bc4 {first, most likely it will transpose to some of the lines.} c6 6. Bd2 Bf5 {, and so on.}) 5... c6 6. Bc4 {If White wants to avoid Nf3 and try to make some shortcuts, what else is here? White threatens Nc3 - d5 and attempts to stop Black from following standard development with ... Bf5 and ... Nbd7 . But perhaps this threat is not so dangerous after all...} Bf5 {Black sticks to the strategy – the fewer standalone variations with unique pawn structures to study, the better.} ({It would be interesting to consider} 6... Bg4 7. f3 Bd7 {, but this leads to a different kind of game where Black sometimes will have to play like an engine.}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nf3 Nbd7 {transposes to the lines  from Chapter 4.}) 7... Qd8 8. Nxf6+ exf6 ({We did not seriously consider} 8... gxf6 {since it's dubious and White has several ways to get a considerable advantage, starting with} 9. Qf3 $5 {. We've once again reached the Tartakower setup from the Caro-Kann, where the evaluation some time ago was unanimous – White is better. But is it so? Compared to a known line in the Caro-Kann, White has an extra tempo while Black controls the important b1 - h7 diagonal. Black has some problems, but there's no reason to evaluate the arising positions as clearly worse for Black. White has the initiative, but Black's game is straightforward with clear attacking plans, which most people today value highly in accelerated time control games.}) 9. Qe2+ {Smart check! White uses the fact that Black can't trade the queens without consequences.} Be7 (9... Qe7 $2 {. Unfortunately, this is a serious mistake.} 10. O-O-O {. The problem is that Black has to take on e2 since White can decline the queen trade at any moment and threaten to include Re1 .} Qxe2 11. Nxe2 Bd6 {. Black is significantly behind in development with a worse pawn structure.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Rhe1 Kd7 {. If only Black was able to complete the development...} 14. Bxe6+ fxe6 15. Nh5 Rg8 16. Bh6 $1 {, and Black will lose something.}) 10. Nf3 {Before defining which way to castle, White develops the knight first.} O-O {Now, the pawn on c2 is under attack.} (10... Bxc2 $4 {. The problem is, you can't take the pawn.} 11. Bh6 $1 gxh6 12. Qxc2 {, and Black's position is horrible.}) 11. O-O-O {Quite a principled choice. The game has a good chance of heating up, and the king's safety will be a huge factor.} Bd6 {Black uses the moment to improve the dark-squared bishop and threatens with ... Re8 to take the e-file. Once again, White has some choices, but the two main ones are Rhe1 and Rde1 . Please pay close attention to the difference and understand why your response will differ against both.} 12. Rde1 {White has to take control of the e-file but keep the kingside rook for a potential attack against the black king. It, however, takes away from White options to react decisively in the center if an opportunity arises.} b5 ({This move was a serious inaccuracy after Rhe1 , but here it works. Make sure you understand the nuances!} 12... Qc8 $6 {. If you're trying to play it in the same spirit as with 12.Rhe1 , there is a major difference.} 13. g4 $1 {. This move was unavailable in that line, but is here.} Bxg4 14. Rhg1 {. First, Black does not have the defensive resource of ... Re8 , and second, the white rook on e1 has avoided the nasty pin. This position for Black is perilous.}) 13. Nh4 {An important intermezzo move characteristic of these lines.} Bc8 {It's important to keep the 7th rank open in case White is ready to sacrifice 'everything that moves' on g6 – you will need to connect your queen.} 14. Bd3 Na6 {Black is hinting at ... Nb4 .} 15. a3 {Even if White stops the knight from jumping to b4 , this decision can backfire because the white pawn on a3 can soon become a target.} Nc7 {Black finds another way to bring the knight to d5 . It's tempting to play 15... g6 and stop White from playing Nf5 , but this comes with other problems.} (15... g6 16. f4 Nc7 {. The point is – if Black plays ... f5 now, the white knight will make it to the e5 square, which might be even worse.} 17. f5 Nd5 18. Rhf1 Bd7 19. Be4 {, and White's initiative on the kingside feels more real.}) 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 g6 {Now it's a good moment to include ... g6 and secure some squares around the king. Better include this move sooner than later since White wants to play h4 - h5 anyway, and then something like Qd3 with pressure on the h7 -pawn might cost Black more.} 18. Be4 {A little more aggressive than Bd3 .} Ne6 {An important resource – you can't miss White's Qf3 .} 19. c3 Rc8 {You want to proceed with ... a5 and ... b4 but maybe there will be opportunities to push ... b4 immediately. For example, if White retreats with the bishop to c2 to reposition it on b3 .} 20. Kb1 a5 {The arising position is complex enough, where both sides have their ideas.} 21. h4 {The race is on.} f5 22. Bxc6 {An interesting resource!} Rxc6 23. d5 Bf4 {Black would be in trouble without this move. The next moves are forcing.} 24. dxc6 Qxd2 25. Qxd2 Bxd2 26. Re5 b4 {Black is at least not worse.} ({After cxb4 , here's how the game might continue: axb4} 26... a4 {( axb4 Bxb4 Rb5 Be7 b4 Rc8 . Black can give up the bishop for the two connected passed pawns on the queenside and a fortress on the kingside or be ambitious and attempt to block the pawns to collect them later. ) Rc8} 27. Rxb5 {Rxc6 Rd1} Bh6 28. Rb4 {. A good question is – how to properly evaluate this position? The white pawns on the queenside are not easily moving forward as long as Black keeps the rook on the board. Since the pawn movement stops, it's logical to assume that Black can set up a solid defense and then attempt to go after the pawns. Ra6 Rc4 Ra5 Kc2} Bg7 {Rc8+ Bf8 Ra1 Kg7 . Let's evaluate this as balanced – the better player will win.}) *

