1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 {In this short chapter we will examine some interesting alternatives from White's perspective that shouldn't cause you headaches but still could be important to know.} 5. Bd3 {This setup makes more sense with the black queen on d6 , a very popular Scandinavian Defense variation. Then White can continue with ideas like Nb5 or Ne4 . It leaves the pawn on d4 unattended – you can exploit it.} Nc6 6. Nge2 ({White already needs to be careful since} 6. Nf3 {would run into} Bg4 {and the pawn on d4 loses support.}) 6... Bf5 {Please notice that White doesn't have the b4 push here – your knight on c6 conveniently takes care of the threat.} 7. O-O O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the pawn on d4 and is also thinking about ... Nb4 .} 8. a3 Bxd3 {Obviously, you can't win the d4 -pawn immediately due to a simple discovered check.} 9. Qxd3 e6 10. Bf4 a6 {You can also live without this move, but it provokes White to play b4 . It makes sense to immediately lift the queen to f5 or continue simple development as ... Bd6 – Black has many good moves.} 11. b4 Qf5 {If White doesn't trade the queens, you will proceed with moves like ... Bd6 or ... Nd5 . White's queenside attack does not seem to be ready.} 12. Qxf5 exf5 13. Rad1 Bd6 {White might regret committing to b4 .} *

