1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 {In this short chapter we will examine some interesting alternatives from White's perspective that shouldn't cause you headaches but still could be important to know.} 5. Be2 {Another move, directed against ... Bg4 , which gives Black some freedom of choices.} Nc6 {If you want to gamble or this is an accelerated time control game and you need a quick initiative, you can attempt to punish White for their opening choices – there's a fair chance that he won't pick up the most ambitious moves.} 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. h3 {Anything else and Black castles short with an immediate pressure on the d-pawn.} Bh5 {Taking on f3 , followed by the long castle, would release the tension; if somebody had to be careful, it's Black.} 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 e5 {This leads to some sharp lines.} 10. Nxe5 {White attempts to win the bishop on g6 , but it's not so simple.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. f4 {There's the idea.} Qe7 13. f5 O-O-O {The bishop is trapped, but the white king is vulnerable.} 14. Kf1 Qd7 15. fxg6 {This is probably the best White can do; otherwise, Black's initiative is very scary.} Qxd2 16. Qxd2 Rxd2 17. gxf7 Bb4 18. Re1 Rf8 19. Bc4 c6 {Black will win back the lost pawn and restore the balance.} *

