1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 {In this short chapter we will examine some interesting alternatives from White's perspective that shouldn't cause you headaches but still could be important to know.} 5. a3 {White enables the b4 push idea and, just in case, takes care of the b4 -square.} Bg4 {Normally, you want to position the bishop on f5 , which is something that you might decide to explore if you get too many games in the following semi-forced lines, but as a general thought – since here you have an option to develop the bishop with a tempo, why not!} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {This would allow Black to pressure the d4 -pawn immediately. It also initiates a long sequence of moves, and if White picks up a lot of not obvious moves, it ends with a draw.} 7. Bb5 Ne4 ({Or} 7... Nd5 {, it doesn't matter much.}) ({It's also interesting to consider long castling, which forces White to take on c6 , leading to roughly balanced chances:} 7... O-O-O $5 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. h3 Qh5 $1 {. This is a typical Scandi idea and an important one to know.}) 8. Qd3 {White could protect the knight and the bishop on b5 , but this leads to massive simplifications.} Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxf3 10. gxf3 O-O-O ({Not forced – Black could also play} 10... e6 {, or a6 , and then castle short.}) 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {The point is that White can't exploit the weakened black king since their monarch is in trouble. Castling short allows Black to play... e6 , ... Bd6 , and ... Qh5 or a kingside attack.} *

