{Ke1 Re4+ . Not the worst draw!} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 {In this short chapter we will examine some interesting alternatives from White's perspective that shouldn't cause you headaches but still could be important to know.} 5. a3 {White enables the b4 push idea and, just in case, takes care of the b4 -square.} Bg4 {Normally, you want to position the bishop on f5 , which is something that you might decide to explore if you get too many games in the following semi-forced lines, but as a general thought – since here you have an option to develop the bishop with a tempo, why not!} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {This would allow Black to pressure the d4 -pawn immediately. It also initiates a long sequence of moves, and if White picks up a lot of not obvious moves, it ends with a draw.} 7. Bb5 Ne4 ({Or} 7... Nd5 {, it doesn't matter much.}) ({It's also interesting to consider long castling, which forces White to take on c6 , leading to roughly balanced chances:} 7... O-O-O $5 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. h3 Qh5 $1 {. This is a typical Scandi idea and an important one to know.}) 8. b4 {A tough move to find.} Nxc3 9. bxa5 Nxd1 10. a6 {Otherwise, White is just worse.} O-O-O 11. axb7+ Kxb7 12. Bxc6+ {Again, the only move.} Kxc6 13. Ne5+ Kb7 {The point is that the white pawn on d4 remains attacked.} 14. Nxf7 Rxd4 15. Nxh8 {Essentially agreeing to a draw.} Re4+ 16. Kd2 Rd4+ *

