{After Kf3 , White is still slightly better. Judge yourself how easy it will be for White to pick all of this up!} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 {In this short chapter we will examine some interesting alternatives from White's perspective that shouldn't cause you headaches but still could be important to know.} 5. Be2 {Another move, directed against ... Bg4 , which gives Black some freedom of choices.} Nc6 {If you want to gamble or this is an accelerated time control game and you need a quick initiative, you can attempt to punish White for their opening choices – there's a fair chance that he won't pick up the most ambitious moves.} 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. h3 {Anything else and Black castles short with an immediate pressure on the d-pawn.} Bh5 {Taking on f3 , followed by the long castle, would release the tension; if somebody had to be careful, it's Black.} 8. g4 Bg6 9. Bd2 e5 {This leads to some sharp lines.} 10. dxe5 Nd7 {Now you can't take on e5 , at least not immediately.} (10... Nxe5 $4 11. Bb5+ {. This intermezzo check should not be missed.} Nc6 12. Nd5 {, and Black loses material.}) 11. Bb5 O-O-O 12. Qe2 {White is about to consolidate the position and castle away from the center, where Black can unleash a surprising idea.} Ndxe5 13. Nxe5 Nd4 {The game remains very sharp.} 14. Nc4 Qb4 15. a3 Qc5 16. b4 Nxc2+ 17. Kf1 Qe7 {This entire sequence for White is the best, but the moves are not obvious.} 18. Ra2 {The most accurate move.} (18. Qxe7 Bxe7 19. Rc1 Nxa3 20. Nxa3 Rxd2 {, and Black will collect a third pawn on b4 .}) 18... c6 (18... Bd3 19. Nb6+) 19. Ne5 Rxd2 {The only move.} 20. Qxd2 Qxe5 21. f4 {Initiating a forcing sequence.} Ne3+ 22. Ke2 Qxf4 23. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Kxe3 cxb5 25. Nxb5 {The position has simplified – White has an exchange for a pawn, but Black still has the bishop pair.} a6 26. Rd2 Be7 27. Nd6+ Kb8 *

