1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 {In this short chapter we will examine some interesting alternatives from White's perspective that shouldn't cause you headaches but still could be important to know.} 5. a3 {White enables the b4 push idea and, just in case, takes care of the b4 -square.} Bg4 {Normally, you want to position the bishop on f5 , which is something that you might decide to explore if you get too many games in the following semi-forced lines, but as a general thought – since here you have an option to develop the bishop with a tempo, why not!} 6. f3 Bd7 {The bishop on d7 stands well, especially because White can no longer opt for the active Nf3 - e5 plan. After the automatic ... Bh5 or ... Bf5 , White could attempt to start an improvised pawn assault.} ({After} 6... Bf5 {, White has now interesting ideas to consider.} 7. g4 Bg6 8. b4 Qb6 9. g5 {. Sadly, Black doesn't have the ... Nd5 resource.} Nh5 10. f4 {. Even though White has committed to multiple weaknesses and is playing all over the board, you have to admit that Black is squeezed pretty well.}) 7. b4 Qb6 8. Bc4 e6 {It may seem that the bishop on d7 is passive, but also White's setup is far from ideal. Compared to the variations with Bd2 , Black can immediately attempt to exploit White's weaknesses on the queenside.} 9. Rb1 {Defensive action against Black's plan to push ... a5 . It allows Black to explore another idea – solve the problem of the passive light-squared bishop in a very creative way.} a6 10. Nge2 ({White could attempt to stop it with} 10. Qd3 {, but after} Bc6 {, the light-squared bishop will also be well-placed on c6 , followed by} 11. Z0 Nbd7 {.}) 10... Bb5 11. Ba2 {White's most ambitious response – to exploit the placement of the black queen.} Be7 12. Be3 O-O 13. Qd2 {The incoming d5 push has to be dealt with.} Bxe2 14. Nxe2 Qd6 {Black is about to set up a perfect blockade on the light squares.} 15. c4 b5 {After Black secures the d5 -square as an outpost, this should give Black a good game.} *

