1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. Nf3 c6 {While it makes sense to start with ... c6 and then decide whether to position the light-squared bishop on f5 or g4 , there's a problem with this move order.} 6. Qe2 {Smart move comes with a trick.} (6. d3 {. If White would play like this, Black could use one of the Scandinavian tricks to equalize the game.} Bg4 7. h3 Qh5 {. White can't return with the bishop to e2 to keep the pawn structure intact.}) 6... Bf5 (6... Bg4 $4 {might seem like a good idea, especially considering that after} 7. h3 {,} Qh5 {seemingly once again works, but there's a different problem.} 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. Ne5+ {. This basic trick you should know by heart.}) 7. d3 {White can avoid positioning the pawn on d4 . There are some perks – quite similar to the Grünfeld Defense, Black misses an immediate counterplay against it, and the pawn on d3 limits the scope of Black's light-squared bishop.} Nbd7 8. Bd2 Qc7 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. f4 {The problem is that with the white pawn on d3 for Black, it will be more difficult to organize proper counterplay while White's plan is straightforward.} e6 11. f5 Bh5 12. Nf3 O-O-O 13. fxe6 fxe6 14. O-O-O {Black is left with a major weakness on e6 .} *

