1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. Nf3 Bf5 {We're sticking to the same approach.} ({A.} 5... Bg4 $6 {is the most played move in the position, but is simply weak. It can be easily answered by} 6. h3 $1 {. See the informational variation .}) ({B. We also considered ambitions to fight for the d4 -square with} 5... Nc6 {immediately, but there are issues as well after} 6. h3 {. See the variation here .}) ({C. While it makes sense to start with} 5... c6 {and then decide whether to position the light-squared bishop on f5 or g4 , there's a problem with the move order. See the reason why here .}) 6. Qe2 e6 {It might be a good idea to keep an option to play more aggressively if White wants to carry out the plan of Nh4 - f4 - f5 immediately.} 7. h3 {White is aiming for the Nh4 idea and first secures the control of the g4 -square, should Black respond with ... Bg4 .} c6 8. d3 {White can start also with Nh4 right away.} Bg6 9. Bd2 Qc7 {Here, the move order is not strict, as long as you get to this position.} 10. Nh4 Nbd7 11. f4 {It's safe to assume that including the moves h3 - e6 clearly favors Black.} b5 12. Bb3 a5 {Black can afford to start a queenside attack since White's f5 push is not yet a threat.} 13. a4 (13. f5 $2 Qg3+ {. Another downside of the h3 move.}) 13... Nc5 {As they say, you close some doors and always open new ones. White avoided the d4 push but no longer controls the c5 -square.} 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. axb5 {White doesn't have anything better than accepting the pawn sacrifice.} Nxb3 16. cxb3 cxb5 17. Qe5 Bd6 18. Qxb5+ Ke7 {White's extra doubled b-pawn doesn't even feel while the weaknesses at White's position are here to stay.} *

