1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. Nf3 Bf5 {We're sticking to the same approach.} ({A.} 5... Bg4 $6 {is the most played move in the position, but is simply weak. It can be easily answered by} 6. h3 $1 {. See the informational variation .}) ({B. We also considered ambitions to fight for the d4 -square with} 5... Nc6 {immediately, but there are issues as well after} 6. h3 {. See the variation here .}) ({C. While it makes sense to start with} 5... c6 {and then decide whether to position the light-squared bishop on f5 or g4 , there's a problem with the move order. See the reason why here .}) 6. O-O e6 7. d3 Nbd7 {More accurate than the tempting ... c6 , the move order matters here.} (7... c6 $6 {. Lifetime Repertoires: Scandinavian by Robert Ris offers this move, but here it's slow.} 8. Nh4 Nbd7 9. Bd2 Bg6 10. f4 {. White gets to carry out the idea.} O-O-O 11. Kh1 Qc7 12. h3 {. There will be a similar line later in the course where the white knight stands on g3 with the same plan to push f5 . It is a big difference, since Black can organize counterplay with ... h5 - h4 . Here, the white knight on h4 conveniently blocks this opportunity.} Kb8 13. a4 Bd6 14. a5 a6 15. Qf3 {. Black is slightly worse, which might still be acceptable but with no counterplay whatsoever, which is dangerous.}) 8. Nh4 {White might attempt to go after the bishop or the f4 - f5 idea.} O-O-O 9. Bd2 Ne5 10. Bb3 Bg6 {The difference is that Black has avoided the ... c6 move, which should favor Black.} 11. f4 Nc6 12. Kh1 Qb6 13. f5 exf5 14. Nxf5 Kb8 {Black has active ideas like ... h5 with ... Ng4 or trading the knight on f5 with ... Nd4 to follow.} *

