1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. Nge2 Bf5 {Again, it's a good idea to pay attention to the details, where to place the light-squared bishop. While the f5 -square will be available to you most of the time, you want to check what happens after the more ambitious ... Bg4 .} ({The problem with} 5... Bg4 $6 {is Black will lose time by moving the bishop and might end up giving it up anyway.} 6. O-O e6 ({(} 6... Nc6 {. The aggressive move here won't work.} 7. h3 Bh5 8. Bb5 {. White has not committed to d4 and will create the weaknesses 'for free'.)}) 7. h3 Bh5 8. d3 c6 9. Qe1 {. An idea, borrowed from exchange Caro-Kann – White escapes the pin and is starting to hunt the light-squared bishop.} Nbd7 10. f4 {. Black faces an uneasy decision – position the bishop on g6 and allow White to eventually carry out Ng3 with f4 - f5 while already committed to ... c6 , which restricts Black's counterplay with ... Ne5 - c6 - d4 that we discussed in other lines, or take on e2 and play a slightly worse position.}) 6. O-O e6 {Black continues the development and, for the moment, refrains from ... c6 since nobody is bothering the black queen.} 7. d3 c6 {You're committing to ... c6 in the variations where White is planning to play Ng3 and f4 - f5 but here circumstances are different. First, Black has no choice since White's Bd2 and Nd5 threats are unpleasant; thus, it is best to prepare an escape route while you can.} 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. Bf4 {This feels quite unambitious and doesn't create Black any problems.} Nbd7 10. Re1 Bb4 11. a3 Bxc3 {There's nothing wrong with accepting the pawn.} (11... Be7 $6 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Nd5 {. White achieved a solid advantage in Sergei Movsesian (2649) – Viktor Gazik (2502), EU-ch Online KO Final Chess.com INT 2020.}) 12. bxc3 Qxc3 13. a4 O-O {White does have the b-file open, but it's not enough to have full compensation for the missing pawn.} 14. Qb1 b6 15. Ne2 Qa5 16. Nd4 Qc5 {Black is better.} *

