1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. d3 {White tries to be smart and not reveal the placement of the kingside knight – it might go to e2 or f3 , mostly depending on what Black will choose.} a6 {Suddenly, Black changes the course of the game and is considering positioning the light-squared bishop on b7 – you can do it if White is slow with their decisions. However, you might have to change your approach depending on how White will respond. Be on your guard, and don't treat the fianchettoing the bishop on b7 as mandatory!} (5... Bg4 {. Some Chessable courses recommend bringing out the bishop according to classical motives. The problem is this is what White wants.} 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 {. As it turns out, the bishop on h5 is not positioned well.} 9. Bd2 c6 10. Kh1 Qc7 11. a3 $5 {White has an easy initiative, while Black struggles to find counterplay.}) 6. Bd2 Qc5 {Black has several interesting continuations, but this seems to be the most logical because the black queen also takes care of the d4 -square. You do want to push ... b5 and ... Bb7 to follow, but keep your eyes open for better opportunities.} (6... b5 $4 {. Of course, paying attention to your opponent's last move is a good idea.} 7. Nd5 {, and Black loses immediately.}) 7. Qe2 {A tricky move – White might reconsider switching to the d4 plans; thus, you'll have to alter your approach.} Nc6 {Black exploits the white queen's placement.} (7... b5 $6 {is not the best choice.} 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. Nf3 e6 10. d4 {. Suddenly Black has to deal with the incoming d5 push and position the queen on an awkward square.} Qd6 {. Positioning the queen on e7 is hardly better.} 11. O-O-O Nbd7 12. Rhe1 Be7 13. Bg5 {, and White has a pretty serious initiative.}) 8. Be3 (8. Nf3 {allows} Bg4 {.}) 8... Qf5 {The position is even, and White's d4 - d5 push no longer seems to be that dangerous. You're thinking about playing ... b5 and eliminate White's light-squared bishop with ... Na5 .} 9. d4 Nb4 10. O-O-O Be6 {Black successfully blocks the d-pawn and can already castle long.} *

