[GameId "2174210256540720"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. d3 {White tries to be smart and not reveal the placement of the kingside knight – it might go to e2 or f3 , mostly depending on what Black will choose.} a6 {Suddenly, Black changes the course of the game and is considering positioning the light-squared bishop on b7 – you can do it if White is slow with their decisions. However, you might have to change your approach depending on how White will respond. Be on your guard, and don't treat the fianchettoing the bishop on b7 as mandatory!} (5... Bg4 {. Some Chessable courses recommend bringing out the bishop according to classical motives. The problem is this is what White wants.} 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 {. As it turns out, the bishop on h5 is not positioned well.} 9. Bd2 c6 10. Kh1 Qc7 11. a3 $5 {White has an easy initiative, while Black struggles to find counterplay.}) 6. Bd2 Qc5 {Black has several interesting continuations, but this seems to be the most logical because the black queen also takes care of the d4 -square. You do want to push ... b5 and ... Bb7 to follow, but keep your eyes open for better opportunities.} (6... b5 $4 {. Of course, paying attention to your opponent's last move is a good idea.} 7. Nd5 {, and Black loses immediately.}) 7. Nf3 Bg4 {As soon as the white knight lands on f3 , you can abandon the ... b5 plan and instead ruin White's pawn structure on the kingside with a known maneuver.} 8. h3 Qh5 {The inclusion of ... a6 allows you to deal with any Nb5 jumps so it's not a waste of time.} *

