1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. d3 {White tries to be smart and not reveal the placement of the kingside knight – it might go to e2 or f3 , mostly depending on what Black will choose.} a6 {Suddenly, Black changes the course of the game and is considering positioning the light-squared bishop on b7 – you can do it if White is slow with their decisions. However, you might have to change your approach depending on how White will respond. Be on your guard, and don't treat the fianchettoing the bishop on b7 as mandatory!} (5... Bg4 {. Some Chessable courses recommend bringing out the bishop according to classical motives. The problem is this is what White wants.} 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 {. As it turns out, the bishop on h5 is not positioned well.} 9. Bd2 c6 10. Kh1 Qc7 11. a3 $5 {White has an easy initiative, while Black struggles to find counterplay.}) 6. Bd2 Qc5 {Black has several interesting continuations, but this seems to be the most logical because the black queen also takes care of the d4 -square. You do want to push ... b5 and ... Bb7 to follow, but keep your eyes open for better opportunities.} (6... b5 $4 {. Of course, paying attention to your opponent's last move is a good idea.} 7. Nd5 {, and Black loses immediately.}) 7. Nge2 {With the white knight on e2 , the possible d4 - d5 push doesn't seem to be threatening, so you can proceed with the idea of fianchettoing the bishop on b7 .} b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. Be3 {If White wants to close the h1 - a8 diagonal with f3 , this has to be the move.} Qd6 {Not forcing - Black also has many other interesting retreats, but the d6 -square seems to suit well for Scandinavian positions in general.} 10. f3 e6 {Black wants to play ... c5 and if possible, keep the pawn on b5 for a better control of the queenside square.} 11. a4 {A concrete solution – Black is not in time to play ... c5 and ... Qb6 .} Be7 {A good trick to know. It's not wrong to play ... b4 and to protect the pawn, but if you can avoid forming unnecessary weaknesses, do it.} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 {White can't take on b5 due to a simple trick.} 14. Qa1 Bc6 {The position is equal.} ({Qa5 . White can't win the b-pawn.} 14... O-O 15. O-O Nbd7 {. Now ... Ra8 is a problem and Nxb5 is still met by ... Qe5 .}) *

