1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine some sidelines if White decides to avoid the d4 move – because of this, Black might be missing out the typical counterplay against White's center.} 5. d3 {White tries to be smart and not reveal the placement of the kingside knight – it might go to e2 or f3 , mostly depending on what Black will choose.} a6 {Suddenly, Black changes the course of the game and is considering positioning the light-squared bishop on b7 – you can do it if White is slow with their decisions. However, you might have to change your approach depending on how White will respond. Be on your guard, and don't treat the fianchettoing the bishop on b7 as mandatory!} (5... Bg4 {. Some Chessable courses recommend bringing out the bishop according to classical motives. The problem is this is what White wants.} 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 {. As it turns out, the bishop on h5 is not positioned well.} 9. Bd2 c6 10. Kh1 Qc7 11. a3 $5 {White has an easy initiative, while Black struggles to find counterplay.}) 6. Bd2 Qc5 {Black has several interesting continuations, but this seems to be the most logical because the black queen also takes care of the d4 -square. You do want to push ... b5 and ... Bb7 to follow, but keep your eyes open for better opportunities.} (6... b5 $4 {. Of course, paying attention to your opponent's last move is a good idea.} 7. Nd5 {, and Black loses immediately.}) 7. Be3 Qc6 {An unusual retreat, but it has a concrete idea – Black hits the pawn on g2 and considerably slows White's d3 - d4 - d5 idea.} 8. Nf3 e6 {It may seem that Black is falling behind in terms of development, but White has difficulties exploiting this because carrying out the d-pawn push-up to d5 will take time.} (8... b5 $4 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Ne5+ {. Don't try this at home!}) (8... Bg4 $6 {. It's tempting to solve the opening problems with a common maneuver, but White has a more promising position.} 9. Bxf7+ $1 {. This shot should never be a surprise.} Kxf7 10. Ne5+ Kg8 11. Nxg4 Qxg2 {. Because of this resource, Black is still in the game, but the complications are in White's favor.} 12. Nxf6+ exf6 13. Kd2 Nd7 14. Ne4 Qh3 $1 15. Rg1 {. White has all the fun – their king is much more secure than Black's.}) 9. O-O {Should White proceed with standard development, Black will have the necessary time to bring their pieces into play.} b5 10. Bb3 Bb7 11. d4 Bb4 {Better remove White's option to play d5 right away.} 12. Ne2 {The d5 push accomplishes nothing – Black collects it with a pawn.} O-O 13. Nf4 Bd6 {The black queen on c6 is not positioned that badly after all – the battery of the queen and the bishop can create some interesting possibilities.} 14. Ne5 Qe4 {White's piece coordination could be better.} *

