e a surprise.} Kxf7 10. Ne5+ Kg8 11. Nxg4 Qxg2 {. Because of this resource, Black is still in the game, but the complications are in White's favor.} 12. Nxf6+ exf6 13. Kd2 Nd7 14. Ne4 Qh3 $1 15. Rg1 {. White has all the fun – their king is much more secure than Black's.}) 9. a4 b6 {It's important to build the battery of the queen and bishop first - White can't play Ne5 because the g2 -pawn is hanging.} (9... Bb4 $6 {. If Black starts with the wrong move order, White will claim the better position.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Qd6 12. f4 Nbd7 13. d4 {. Suddenly, Black is quite cramped.} b6 14. Na2 {. The bishop on b4 is in trouble, plus White's Qf3 threat is looming.}) 10. O-O Bb7 {Just in time – now Ne5 is not happening.} 11. Nb5 {The move looks fancy with some tricks, but if Black stays alert, this gives White nothing.} Be7 12. Bf4 {Since White positioned the knight on b5 , it makes sense to continue. Otherwise, Black will castle short, and the white knight from b5 will have to retreat.} O-O {Very strong and possibly unexpected for White – do they want to take the pawn on c7 and possibly trap the knight?} 13. Nbd4 Qc5 {As long as you're not missing some tactical shots on e6 , Black will complete the development.} 14. c3 Bd6 {An accurate move to defend the c7 -pawn against the b4 threat.} 15. Bg5 {White is still threatening to play b4 .} a5 16. Re1 Nbd7 {Black has completed the development. The black queen on c5 might feel weird, but White can't possibly exploit it.} ({h3 . Here's how the game might continue. Ne5 . Black simplifies the position. Nxe5} 16... Be5 17. Be3 Qe7 {Nf3 Bd6 . Black is ready to fight for the initiative on the kingside – the light-squared bishop on b7 is very strong.}) *

