1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nge2 {This is an interesting move since White keeps two options: go for the d4 or f4 push.} Nc6 {The move order matters – this move feels very active as Black is fighting for the d4 -square, but now the queen on a5 might feel disconnected from the game.} 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 O-O 9. Rb1 {Suddenly, White is harassing the black queen, and the knight on c6 stops Black from having a better escape route.} Qc5 10. d3 a6 11. h3 {This was played in Eltaj Safarli (2593) – Vladimir Oblamski (2088), Minsk Kupreichik Memorial rapid 2019. It seems that Black is doing alright, but in reality, Black is suffering with the coordination between the pieces, and you will have to wait for White to initiate some action.} *

