1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nge2 {This is an interesting move since White keeps two options: go for the d4 or f4 push.} Bd6 {The most solid response – Black secures the pawn on e5 and is ready to meet both White's d4 and f4 .} (6... Nc6 $6 {. Move order matters: the knight on c6 may block the queen's best escape route. See the informational variation .}) 7. O-O O-O {Now White needs to choose which pawn they want to push.} 8. d3 {This signals that White wants to play f4 . The idea is to establish a pawn majority on the queenside and also use the semi-open f-file. The downside is that it weakens the white king.} c6 {Black limits the activity of White's light-squared bishop and preps for the f4 push.} 9. h3 {It makes sense to take care of the g4 square first. Otherwise, Black is seriously considering moves like ... Bg4 or ... Qb6 + and ... Ng4 to follow.} Re8 10. f4 {White carries out the f-pawn push, but it doesn't accomplish much.} exf4 11. Bxf4 Bxf4 12. Rxf4 Be6 {Black continues a simple development and monitors White's potential exchange sacrifice on f6 . That's why the queenside knight best stands on d7 .} 13. Qd2 Nbd7 14. Rf2 Re7 15. g4 Rae8 {With an equal position.} *

