1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nge2 {This is an interesting move since White keeps two options: go for the d4 or f4 push.} Bd6 {The most solid response – Black secures the pawn on e5 and is ready to meet both White's d4 and f4 .} (6... Nc6 $6 {. Move order matters: the knight on c6 may block the queen's best escape route. See the informational variation .}) 7. O-O O-O {Now White needs to choose which pawn they want to push.} 8. d4 Nc6 {Once again, as soon as White plays d4 , Black can bring out the knight. It's interesting to consider also 8... c6 but then Black slightly stays behind in development.} 9. Bg5 {If White would continue pushing forward the d-pawn, ... Ne7 is a nice retreat.} exd4 10. Bxf6 dxc3 11. Bxc3 Qh5 {As seen in Viswanathan Anand (2720) – Vasyl Ivanchuk (2695), PCA/Intel-GP London rapid 1994. The position is equal.} *

