1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nge2 {This is an interesting move since White keeps two options: go for the d4 or f4 push.} Be7 {This is a worthy alternative – the bishop protects the knight and doesn't jump under any threats while keeping the d-file open for the black rook.} (6... Nc6 $6 {. Move order matters: the knight on c6 may block the queen's best escape route. See the informational variation .}) 7. O-O O-O 8. d4 {As seen in Eduardas Rozentalis (2578) – Franz Wiedermann (2119), Liechtenstein op 25th Triesen 2007. Now, Black could have opted for a more aggressive approach.} Nc6 {Since White has committed to d4 , now this move comes with perfect timing.} ({It's tempting to pin the d-pawn with} 8... Rd8 $2 {, but White has a powerful response.} 9. Bd2 $1 {. Suddenly, Black is in trouble. For the Scandinavian players, missing White's Bd2 and Nd5 maneuvers should be unforgivable.} exd4 $2 10. Nd5 Qc5 11. Bb4 {Black can resign.}) 9. d5 Nb4 10. a3 Bf5 {Black is threatening to take over the game, and White will have to use some imagination to keep the game level.} 11. Bd2 Nxc2 12. Rc1 Nd4 {At the moment, Black has a healthy extra pawn.} 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qe2 {Not a very obvious move.} Bd8 15. Nb5 d3 16. Bxa5 dxe2 17. Rfe1 c5 {The position remains balanced.} *

