1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. d3 {If White starts with this move, he's considering following up with Bd2 and bothering the black queen. Best make sure you can retreat if this happens.} c6 7. Nf3 (7. Bd2 Qc7 8. Nf3 Bd6 {, White only took away the opportunity Nf3 - d2 - c4 , and everything else is the same as in other lines.}) ({If White plays} 7. Nge2 {, we respond just as we would against 6.Nge2 .}) 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O {White seems slightly ahead in the development, but not enough to claim an advantage.} 9. Re1 h6 {Black preps ... Be6 and ... Nbd7 to follow and ensures that White can't follow up with Ng5 .} 10. Nd2 Be6 11. Nc4 Bxc4 12. dxc4 Qc7 {Black keeps the balance.} *

