1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. d4 ({The good and popular} 8. d3 {is met by} c6 {, and we transpose to the previous variation .}) 8... Nc6 {This approach is easy to remember – as soon as White plays d4 , you meet it with ... Nc6 .} 9. d5 {Not a very obvious move for White because now the d5 -pawn is seemingly in trouble.} ({Exchanging} 9. dxe5 {is slightly inferior for White} Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 {.}) 9... Ne7 10. Bd2 {The trickiest move order – now you must know a few precise moves.} Nexd5 11. Nxe5 {With this trick, White hopes to exploit the placement of the black queen on a5 .} Ne3 {An important intermezzo move – you want to capture on e5 with the queen.} 12. Nc6 {Before White captures the knight on e3 , they want to ruin your pawn structure.} Qxc3 {Another powerful move.} 13. Bxe3 Qxb2 14. Nxa7 Bf5 {Black has achieved a good middlegame.} *

