1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. d4 ({The good and popular} 8. d3 {is met by} c6 {, and we transpose to another line .}) 8... Nc6 {This approach is easy to remember – as soon as White plays d4 , you meet it with ... Nc6 .} 9. d5 {Not a very obvious move for White because now the d5 -pawn is seemingly in trouble.} ({Exchanging} 9. dxe5 {is slightly inferior for White} Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 {.}) 9... Ne7 10. Re1 Nexd5 11. Bd2 {Another temporary pawn sacrifice – the pawn on e5 is difficult to protect, so best focus on your development.} Bg4 12. Qc1 Bxf3 {With simplifications incoming.} 13. Bxf3 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Qb6 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 Rfe8 {Black has achieved full equality.} *

