1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. Re1 {White doesn't reveal the cards, are they going to play d3 or d4 ?} Re8 {Black should do the same.} ({If you rush with} 8... Nc6 {, White will continue with} 9. d3 {, and the queen on a5 feels awkward.}) 9. d4 Nc6 {As soon as White plays d4 , Black plays ... Nc6 , nothing changes.} 10. d5 {The difference with some similar lines is that the retreat to e7 is impossible in this variation, but luckily, there are other options as well.} Nb4 11. Nd2 {This is a move that you should never miss – White is threatening to play either Nc4 or Nb3 to harass your queen. Here, this does not work because you're controlling the g4 -square. If White had included h3 , then Nd2 would be a big problem.} Bg4 {Important move to weaken the g1 - a7 diagonal.} (11... Bf5 $2 {would be premature.} 12. Nc4 Qc5 13. Ne3 Bg6 14. a3 Na6 15. Bd2 {. Black has massive problems to find a safe place for the queen.)}) 12. f3 Bf5 13. Nb3 {Now White's Nc4 - e3 idea no longer works because Black can pick up the pawn on c2 because of a pin.} Qa6 14. Bf1 Bxc2 {Another important resource.} 15. Bxa6 Bxd1 16. Bxb7 Bxf3 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 {Black dominates the position with the bishop pair.} *

