1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. Re1 {White doesn't reveal the cards, are they going to play d3 or d4 ?} Re8 {Black should do the same.} ({If you rush with} 8... Nc6 {, White will continue with} 9. d3 {, and the queen on a5 feels awkward.}) 9. d4 Nc6 {As soon as White plays d4 , Black plays ... Nc6 , nothing changes.} 10. d5 {The difference with some similar lines is that the retreat to e7 is impossible in this variation, but luckily, there are other options as well.} Nb4 11. Bd2 Nbxd5 12. Nxe5 {White resorts to a trick you've seen before. Now, Black has to be a little accurate.} Bxe5 13. Nxd5 Qa4 {The only move, but it's enough if it holds the position.} 14. Bc3 Bg4 {Another important move – Black deals with the backrank weakness and develops the remaining piece with tempo. Simplifications are incoming.} 15. Qd2 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Qb5 {White has nothing.} *

