1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. Re1 {White doesn't reveal the cards, are they going to play d3 or d4 ?} Re8 {Black should do the same.} ({If you rush with} 8... Nc6 {, White will continue with} 9. d3 {, and the queen on a5 feels awkward.}) 9. h3 {Another smart move – White takes control of the g4 -square and postpones the push of the d-pawn. Again, if Black will prematurely play ... Nc6 , White will respond with d3 , and the black queen on a5 does not stand well, and if Black will play ... c6 , then White will push d4 since you no longer can meet it with ... Nc6 . So you need a good waiting move that improves your position.} Bd7 {Finally, White has to reveal their cards.} (9... c6 10. d4 {, and Black is worse.}) 10. d3 {White is thinking about Nd2 - c4 so ... Bd7 actually helps Black quite a bit.} Bc6 11. Bd2 Nbd7 {This is quite characteristic of the Scandinavian Defense. White can try a discovered attack, but none of the moves seem to accomplish anything.} 12. a3 Qa6 {Black would like to rearrange the queen to b7 for a strong battery.} 13. Na2 {Such moves are rarely good, but this is an exception since the idea is very concrete. White is not only threatening with Nb4 but possibly also pushing forward the queenside pawns.} Bc5 14. b4 Bf8 15. c4 b5 16. c5 Qb7 {Black stops White's threats just in time. We can stop our analysis here and conclude that Black has a fully satisfactory game.} ({After Bc3 , the game might continue:} 16... g6 {Bb2 Bg7 . Black starts by improving the dark-squared bishop.} 17. Nc1 {a5 Now it's time to activate the queenside rook. Nb3 axb4 axb4 Rxa1 Bxa1} Bd5 {, dealing with the Na5 threat. Na5 Qa8} 18. c6 {. Good try, but it gives White nothing.} Bxc6 {Nxc6 Qxc6} 19. Nxe5 {Qd6 , and Black remains rock solid.}) *

