1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. Re1 {White doesn't reveal the cards, are they going to play d3 or d4 ?} Re8 {Black should do the same.} ({If you rush with} 8... Nc6 {, White will continue with} 9. d3 {, and the queen on a5 feels awkward.}) 9. h3 {Another smart move – White takes control of the g4 -square and postpones the push of the d-pawn. Again, if Black will prematurely play ... Nc6 , White will respond with d3 , and the black queen on a5 does not stand well, and if Black will play ... c6 , then White will push d4 since you no longer can meet it with ... Nc6 . So you need a good waiting move that improves your position.} Bd7 {Finally, White has to reveal their cards.} (9... c6 10. d4 {, and Black is worse.}) 10. d4 {White pushes d4 but because of the included h3 , now there are some important nuances.} Nc6 {Once again, Black plays ... Nc6 at the right moment.} 11. d5 Nd4 {Another solution to the d5 push – in other lines this did not quite work because the black rook on e8 was not well defended.} ({Once again,} 11... Ne7 {drops the pawn on e5 ,} 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Rxe5 {.}) ({But after Black's} 11... Nd4 {, jumping on d4 here} 12. Nxd4 {would be a big mistake for White (see next variation ). Make sure you don't mix up this position with different versions, and pay close attention to where you should retreat with the knight (see the variations 6.Nf3 with 8.d4  #1 & #2 ).} ({Nb4? no longer works.} 12. Nd2 $1 {. Black is in big trouble since there is no ... Bg4 move to weaken the g1 –a7 diagonal.} Bf5 13. Nc4 Qc5 14. Ne3 {. Very strong – Black has no choice.} Bg6 15. a3 {Na6 Bd2 . Black's queen is in trouble.})) 12. Bg5 {One of the two tempting moves – White wants to destroy Black's pawn structure on the kingside since the knight has seemingly nowhere to go.} Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 e4 {Very strong. If White doesn't take the pawn now, Black will proceed with Be5 and keep it.} 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 {The dust is about to settle.} 15. Rxe4 Rxe4 16. Qxe4 Re8 17. Qd3 Bc5 {Black is down a pawn but has a wonderful piece activity for full compensation.} 18. c3 Qb6 19. Qd2 h6 {Black wins back the lost pawn.} 20. Bf4 g5 21. b4 {White doesn't have anything better.} Bxf2+ 22. Qxf2 gxf4 23. Qxb6 axb6 24. gxf4 {White is up a pawn, but Black is to move!} Re3 25. Rc1 Rd3 {It's possible to take the pawn on h3 immediately, but this move feels more active since ... Rd2 is a big positional threat.} 26. c4 Bxh3 {The endgame is just equal.} *

