1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. Re1 {White doesn't reveal the cards, are they going to play d3 or d4 ?} Re8 {Black should do the same.} ({If you rush with} 8... Nc6 {, White will continue with} 9. d3 {, and the queen on a5 feels awkward.}) 9. h3 {Another smart move – White takes control of the g4 -square and postpones the push of the d-pawn. Again, if Black will prematurely play ... Nc6 , White will respond with d3 , and the black queen on a5 does not stand well, and if Black will play ... c6 , then White will push d4 since you no longer can meet it with ... Nc6 . So you need a good waiting move that improves your position.} Bd7 {Finally, White has to reveal their cards.} (9... c6 10. d4 {, and Black is worse.}) 10. d4 {White pushes d4 but because of the included h3 , now there are some important nuances.} Nc6 {Once again, Black plays ... Nc6 at the right moment.} 11. d5 Nd4 {Another solution to the d5 push – in other lines this did not quite work because the black rook on e8 was not well defended.} ({Once again,} 11... Ne7 {drops the pawn on e5 ,} 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Rxe5 {.}) ({But after Black's} 11... Nd4 {, jumping on d4 here} 12. Nxd4 {would be a big mistake for White (see next variation ). Make sure you don't mix up this position with different versions, and pay close attention to where you should retreat with the knight (see the variations 6.Nf3 with 8.d4  #1 & #2 ).} ({Nb4? no longer works.} 12. Nd2 $1 {. Black is in big trouble since there is no ... Bg4 move to weaken the g1 –a7 diagonal.} Bf5 13. Nc4 Qc5 14. Ne3 {. Very strong – Black has no choice.} Bg6 15. a3 {Na6 Bd2 . Black's queen is in trouble.})) 12. Nd2 {Engines choice which for humans might be difficult to make since it leaves the knight on d4 which can severely backfire. Watch out for White's idea to play Nce4  c3 .} Qb6 {It's time to retreat with the queen, and b6 seems to be the safest square.} ({If} 12... Qa6 {, this invites White to probe things with} 13. Bf1 {.} ({It would also make sense to consider Bf5 to hit the pawn on c2 , but White wants to proceed with} 13. Nce4 {and c3 anyway; thus ... Bf5 feels like a waste of time.})) 13. g4 {White is threatening to trap the knight with g5 and also improves the Nce4 idea so that the knight from d4 can't escape to f5 .} c6 {The only move but it's good enough.} 14. Nce4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 cxd5 {Now the position is about to simplify.} 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. c3 Nc6 18. Qxd5 Qc7 {White has a small edge because of the bishop pair, but the king is weak.} 19. Be3 Be6 20. Qb5 Rac8 {We can stop our analysis here – Black has a great position. You might consider pushing ... f5 or ... h5 to attack the white king or look for ways to trade off the light-squared bishops.} *

