1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. g3 {You will often meet players who instead of 'punishing' Black for choosing the Scandinavian Defense, will want to opt for an easy game. In this chapter, we will talk about everything g3 -related.} Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 {If White doesn't care about the center, you should! Black attempts to play out the opening more aggressively.} 6. Nf3 {The most logical move – White opts for quick development.} Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White has a choice between opening the position with d4 or applying pressure against the e5 -pawn with Re1 .} 8. Re1 {White doesn't reveal the cards, are they going to play d3 or d4 ?} Re8 {Black should do the same.} ({If you rush with} 8... Nc6 {, White will continue with} 9. d3 {, and the queen on a5 feels awkward.}) 9. d3 {White is playing some slow chess and hopes that their clear plan gives them a good game. But what about Black? Strangely, previous Chessable courses don't pay enough attention to this strong plan.} c6 {Black limits the scope of White's light-squared bishop on g2 and prepares an escape route for the queen.} 10. h3 {A good move – most of the time, the control of the g4 -square will be important.} h6 {Black can respond with the same logic. Controlling the g5 -square enables the ... Be6 move, followed by ... Nbd7 .} ({If Black plays} 10... Be6 {now, then} 11. Ng5 {threatens to win the bishop pair for no compensation.}) 11. d4 {Albeit White has lost a tempo, Black has committed to ... c6 and can't meet this move with the typical ... Nc6 . However, a tempo is a tempo.} Nbd7 {More logical, but it also involves a temporary pawn sacrifice.} (11... exd4 {. Opening the position is a little risky, but still might be playable. The pawn structure is symmetrical, but White's development is better.} 12. Rxe8+ Nxe8 13. Nxd4 Nd7 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Ne4 {. White is pushing, but with a careful defense, Black should be able to hold this.}) 12. a4 {The engine suggests ignoring the pawn and focusing on pushing on the queenside.} Bf8 13. Bd2 exd4 {Black is running out of reasonable moves; thus, this move is necessary.} 14. Rxe8 Nxe8 15. Nxd4 Ndf6 {Black needs to figure out where to position the light-squared bishop.} 16. Nb3 Qc7 17. a5 a6 18. Bf4 Qe7 19. Qe1 Bf5 {Black is alright and should be able to hold this without much problem.} *

