1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. a3 {White wants to make a hybrid of all plans with this move. It's interesting, but that's all it is.} c6 ({You can start with} 4... Nf6 {, but with this move order, you completely neutralize White's ideas of b4 .}) (4... Nf6 5. d4 Bg4 {. There's one nuance you should know - if White has not yet positioned his knight on f3 , maybe he never will.} 6. f3 {. Precisely the point.} Bd7 7. b4 {. Black would have enjoyed having access to ... Qc7 .} Qb6 8. Bc4 e6 9. Nge2 Be7 10. Rb1 O-O 11. O-O {. Black is slightly squeezed with an awkward queen on b6 that might be subject to losing more tempos.}) 5. d4 Nf6 {The difference with the move order is that now you will get more information from your opponent about which setup they intend to choose. Black's ... c6 , in general, is a good addition.} 6. Bd3 Bg4 {You can't place the bishop on f5 due to a common trick with b4 .} 7. Nf3 ({If White would now play} 7. f3 {, you could retreat the bishop to h5 and then to g6 , since White has already committed to Bd3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 9. Qe2 {If White considers castling long, there's a problem.} (9. Bd2 e6 10. Qe2 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qb6 {transposes to a line , covered later.}) 9... e6 10. Bd2 {This allows Black to ask White some difficult-to-answer questions about the central pawn.} Bxf3 {This feels like a waste of time after committing to an earlier ... Bh5 , but there is a concrete idea.} 11. Qxf3 Qb6 12. Qf4 {White can ignore the b-pawn, but losing the central pawn might be too much.} Be7 {It makes sense to explore fianchettoing the bishop on g7 .} 13. O-O-O Nd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {This is one of the classical positions of the Scandinavian Defense. It's a Carlsbad pawn structure. White has two bishops, but Black can castle on either side.} 15. g4 a6 16. g5 Bd6 17. Qe3 O-O-O {Probably the safest choice – the king will find shelter on b8 .} *

