1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Qe2 {White might go for some early tricks, but this is pretty easy to parry.} a6 {With this simple move, Black takes away a critical square for White's pieces.} 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nd4 {Black can immediately ask White some direct questions.} 7. Qd3 {White is stubborn!} e5 8. Nge2 Bf5 9. Ne4 O-O-O {Black is speedy with the development while something has gone wrong with White's strategy.} 10. c3 ({After} 10. Nxd4 {, the take} exd4 {is necessary, otherwise the bishop on f5 is lost.} 11. Qe2 Ne7 12. O-O {. Just as White is about to complete development with d3 , now comes the dagger.} d3 $1 13. cxd3 Nc6 {. Black is much better due to the development and White's weak pawn on d3 .}) 10... Qb5 {Nice and accurate.} (10... Nb3 $6 {. It's very tempting to win the game on the spot, but the consequences are far from clear.} 11. axb3 Qxa1 12. Nd6+ {. This trick, unfortunately, is still there.} Bxd6 13. Qxf5+ Kb8 14. Qxf7 {. White has full compensation for the minimal material losses.}) 11. Qxb5 Nxb5 12. O-O Nf6 {It's becoming apparent that if somebody is fighting for an advantage here, it's Black.} 13. Ng5 Bd3 {A strong and energetic choice!} 14. Nxf7 Bc5 15. Nxh8 Rxh8 {Black is down an exchange and a pawn, but their pieces completely dominate the board.} ({After Re1 , the game might continue:} 15... Ng4 16. Bh3 Bxf2+ {Kf1 Rf8!! Bxg4+ Kb8 . White has an extra rook, but they are dead lost. Rd1 Bc5+} 17. Kg2 {Rf2+ Kh3} Nd6 {. White is completely tied up!}) *

