1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. b4 {This is a fun gambit that may work best as a surprise weapon or in faster time controls, where a quick initiative is important. However, under normal circumstances, White should not get more than just enough compensation for the pawn. Still, knowing some precise lines is essential.} Qxb4 {Challenge accepted – after all, it's a pawn.} 5. Nb5 {This comes with a cute trick, but if you're aware of it, then White is down a pawn for nothing.} Qa5 6. Bc4 Nf6 {Simple and good way to deal with White's tricks.} (6... c6 $2 {. After all, why not? Well, there's a tactical problem!} 7. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 8. Qh5+ {. And no matter what Black will respond next, the queen is lost.} g6 9. Nd6+ exd6 10. Qxa5 {. Black is just lost.}) 7. Bb2 a6 8. Bc3 Qb6 9. Nd4 {White has to fall back.} c5 10. Ndf3 e6 {Black calmy continues the development. With the b-file open, leaving your light-squared bishop on the 'passive' c8 -square makes sense instead of seeking the usual activity with ... Bf5 .} 11. Nh3 Qc7 12. a4 Nc6 {Black has an extra pawn and the compensation for it.; their pieces are well-placed and full of potential; and, White's knight on the rim is poorly placed, making it hard to fight for the center. Altogether, Black stands better and has realistic chances of a decisive result.} *

