1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. b4 {This is a fun gambit that may work best as a surprise weapon or in faster time controls, where a quick initiative is important. However, under normal circumstances, White should not get more than just enough compensation for the pawn. Still, knowing some precise lines is essential.} Qxb4 {Challenge accepted – after all, it's a pawn.} 5. Rb1 Qd6 {Here, the queen will stand better than the typical a5 -square – after all, White could gain access to some unpleasant Rb5 ideas. As you will see, Black's setup against the gambit is simple.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Bc4 {White can again delay the development of the d-pawn and rush with the king away from the center.} a6 {With the idea of ... b5 , ... c5 and ... c4 . White has no compensation for the pawn – Black stands better.} 8. O-O {If White reacts with the 8.a4 move, Black can continue by fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on b7 with ... b6 .} (8. Ng5 $4 Qe5+) 8... b5 9. Bb3 c5 10. a4 {White hopes that Black has over-extended their pawns and wants to prove that their better development will give them better chances once the position opens up.} c4 11. Ba2 b4 12. Ne2 {White has nothing better.} Bb7 {A good moment to sell back the extra pawn.} 13. Bxc4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 e6 15. c3 Qc7 16. d3 Nc6 {Although White is slightly ahead in development, their pawn structure is terrible, and they can't stop Black from castling short.} *

