1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. b4 {This is a fun gambit that may work best as a surprise weapon or in faster time controls, where a quick initiative is important. However, under normal circumstances, White should not get more than just enough compensation for the pawn. Still, knowing some precise lines is essential.} Qxb4 {Challenge accepted – after all, it's a pawn.} 5. Rb1 Qd6 {Here, the queen will stand better than the typical a5 -square – after all, White could gain access to some unpleasant Rb5 ideas. As you will see, Black's setup against the gambit is simple.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. d4 a6 {Black takes care of the b5 -square. Now, White has some choices to explore.} (7... g6 $5 {. If you're looking for some variety, you can start with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 and then decide what to do with the queenside – there will be many options.}) 8. Bd3 {White wants to proceed with Ne4 , trade off the knights, and pressure the b7 -pawn. It's good to remember that you got a free pawn from accepting the gambit!} g6 {This maneuver should always be on your radar – the idea is to apply some extra pressure against White's center.} (8... e6 $6 {This would be slightly passive.} 9. O-O Be7 10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 {. White has excellent compensation for the pawn while Black will struggle to show some signs of activity.}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Nd7 {Black is flexible with the ideas like pushing ... c5 , or ... Nf6 , or even protecting the b-pawn with ... Rb8 . It's a good idea not to underestimate your opponent's activity, but objectively, Black's position looks safe.} *

