1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. b4 {This is a fun gambit that may work best as a surprise weapon or in faster time controls, where a quick initiative is important. However, under normal circumstances, White should not get more than just enough compensation for the pawn. Still, knowing some precise lines is essential.} Qxb4 {Challenge accepted – after all, it's a pawn.} 5. Rb1 Qd6 {Here, the queen will stand better than the typical a5 -square – after all, White could gain access to some unpleasant Rb5 ideas. As you will see, Black's setup against the gambit is simple.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. d4 a6 {Black takes care of the b5 -square. Now, White has some choices to explore.} (7... g6 $5 {. If you're looking for some variety, you can start with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 and then decide what to do with the queenside – there will be many options.}) 8. g3 {White wants to position their bishops on two strong diagonals to apply some serious pressure.} (8. Bc4 $6 {is not particularly good, and we already looked at this with a different move order.} b5 9. Bb3 c5 $1 10. dxc5 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 e6 {, and White will lose the c5 -pawn.}) 8... Qc6 {Powerful – White is quite not in time to carry out their threats.} 9. Bd2 {This might feel like an automatic move since White's Bg2 with the discovered attack is seemingly incoming. However, the position is very concrete.} e5 {Surprise! Black uses the fact that White can't take the pawn with the knight.} 10. Qe2 {If White decides to pin the pawn, you can reverse the roles and play the gambit yourself. By the way, all you're giving up is the extra pawn.} Bd6 11. dxe5 O-O {Very energetic – now ... Bxe5 with ... Re8 to follow is a big threat.} 12. exd6 {Scary, but what else?} Re8 13. Be3 Qxc3+ 14. Qd2 Qc6 {Black should decline the queen trade since White has not yet completed their development.} 15. Bg2 Ne4 {Black is slightly better, but perhaps White's bishop pair will allow them to avoid even greater trouble.} *

