1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. b4 {This is a fun gambit that may work best as a surprise weapon or in faster time controls, where a quick initiative is important. However, under normal circumstances, White should not get more than just enough compensation for the pawn. Still, knowing some precise lines is essential.} Qxb4 {Challenge accepted – after all, it's a pawn.} 5. Rb1 Qd6 {Here, the queen will stand better than the typical a5 -square – after all, White could gain access to some unpleasant Rb5 ideas. As you will see, Black's setup against the gambit is simple.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. d4 a6 {Black takes care of the b5 -square. Now, White has some choices to explore.} (7... g6 $5 {. If you're looking for some variety, you can start with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 and then decide what to do with the queenside – there will be many options.}) 8. g3 {White wants to position their bishops on two strong diagonals to apply some serious pressure.} (8. Bc4 $6 {is not particularly good, and we already looked at this with a different move order.} b5 9. Bb3 c5 $1 10. dxc5 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 e6 {, and White will lose the c5 -pawn.}) 8... Qc6 {Powerful – White is quite not in time to carry out their threats.} 9. Qd3 {If White will spot that you're planning on pushing ... e5 , this move seems to be necessary.} Be6 {As usual, you close some doors and always open new ones. Now White can't easily fianchetto the bishop on g2 since ... Bc4 is a problem.} 10. Bg2 Bc4 {This can lead to some crazy lines – White has an interesting opportunity to sacrifice a rook, but if you're ready, there's no danger to you.} 11. Ne5 {A beautiful idea, even though the concept from the beginning is somewhat flawed.} Qxg2 {Of course, it's possible to take the queen on d3 as well, but show us someone who won't accept a free rook!} 12. Qxc4 Qxh1+ 13. Ke2 Qg2 {The simplest choice – Black defends against White's Bd2 and, depending on White's choices, wants to continue either with ... e6 or ... Nbd7 .} ({The engine also offers} 13... Nc6 {and try to hold on to the material, but White develops an unpleasant initiative, and even if Black finds all the best moves, the final position is hard to evaluate.}) 14. Qxf7+ ({After} 14. Qxc7 $4 Nc6 $1 {is the only move.} 15. Rxb7 Nxd4+ 16. Kd3 Ne6 {. White's initiative is over – the critical d7 - and c6 -squares are protected.} 17. Rb8+ Rxb8 18. Qxb8+ Nd8 {, White needs just one deadly diagonal check, but there is no such thing.}) 14... Kd8 15. Qc4 Nbd7 {This is a tough move, as nobody wants to give up a free extra rook, but every other option is much more complicated.} 16. Nf7+ Kc8 17. Nxh8 e5 {Now we once again have a material balance on the board, but due to the stranded white knight on h8 , Black is better.} 18. Be3 b6 {We can conclude our analysis here and assess that Black's chances are better. You want to continue with ... exd4 , ... Kb7 , and ... Re8 , developing a strong initiative, and the only way White can stop it is by closing the center.} ({After d5 , here's how the game might continue:} 18... Bc5 {Black is also threatening with the very annoying ... b5 . Bxc5 Nxc5} 19. Nf7 Qxh2 {. Time to simplify the position. d6 Qh5+} 20. Ke1 Ne4 $1 {. Nice resource.} 21. Nxe4 Qh1+ 22. Ke2 Qxe4 {Qxe4 Nxe4 Ke3} 23. Nd6+ {Nxe5 Kb7 . After the dust has settled, Black has a healthy extra pawn.}) *

