1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. b4 {This is a fun gambit that may work best as a surprise weapon or in faster time controls, where a quick initiative is important. However, under normal circumstances, White should not get more than just enough compensation for the pawn. Still, knowing some precise lines is essential.} Qxb4 {Challenge accepted – after all, it's a pawn.} 5. Rb1 Qd6 {Here, the queen will stand better than the typical a5 -square – after all, White could gain access to some unpleasant Rb5 ideas. As you will see, Black's setup against the gambit is simple.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. d4 a6 {Black takes care of the b5 -square. Now, White has some choices to explore.} (7... g6 $5 {. If you're looking for some variety, you can start with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 and then decide what to do with the queenside – there will be many options.}) 8. g3 {White wants to position their bishops on two strong diagonals to apply some serious pressure.} (8. Bc4 $6 {is not particularly good, and we already looked at this with a different move order.} b5 9. Bb3 c5 $1 10. dxc5 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 e6 {, and White will lose the c5 -pawn.}) 8... Qc6 {Powerful – White is quite not in time to carry out their threats.} 9. Qd3 {If White will spot that you're planning on pushing ... e5 , this move seems to be necessary.} Be6 {As usual, you close some doors and always open new ones. Now White can't easily fianchetto the bishop on g2 since ... Bc4 is a problem.} 10. Bg5 {Engine suggests that White should first trade the bishop and only then play Bg2 , but from White's perspective, it doesn't make much sense unless they have a profound understanding of some of the nuances.} Nbd7 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Bg2 {The point is that Black can't play the very tempting... Bc4 !} Rd8 {The pawn on b7 is falling, and there's nothing Black can do about it – best focus on your development.} (12... Bc4 $2 {Please ensure you don't mix this line with the position where White's dark-squared bishop is still on c1 .} 13. Ne5 $3 {Again, the same cut tactic, but here it works wonders.} Qxg2 14. Qxc4 Qxh1+ 15. Ke2 {. The difference is that the black queen is immediately under attack, and Black is missing the queenside knight to cover some critical squares.} Qg2 16. Qxf7+ Kd8 17. Qe6 Ke8 18. d5 {. Black could have used a knight on b8 .}) 13. Nh4 Qd6 14. Bxb7 g6 {Black is about to bring the king to the safety, and White should do the same.} 15. O-O Bg7 16. Qxa6 {Now it's White who is up a pawn.} Qxa6 17. Bxa6 O-O 18. Nf3 Nd5 {The engine suggests that the position is equal, but due to the bishop pair and clear targets, Black's position is much easier to play.} *

