1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. O-O {Big decision – now Black can think about a direct kingside attack.} O-O-O {Already, the fact that both kings are on opposite flanks suggests some fireworks! White doesn't have much time because Black is about to grab the center with ... e5 and claim a better position.} 6. Nc3 {It's tempting but not necessarily good – now White can't play the original idea of d4 , c4 , and put the knight behind the pawns. The white knight on c3 restricts White some important options.} Qd7 7. h3 Bxf3 {A big decision – many players would automatically retreat with the bishop on h5 to keep some tension and, most importantly, the bishop pair. However, this position once again is concrete, and after the bishop trade, it's a little easier for Black to organize the kingside assault. Here, the tactical motif} (7... h5 $2 {does not work since the black queen already is on d7 and can't easily make it to the h-file.} 8. hxg4 hxg4 9. Ng5 Nh6 10. d4 $1 Nxd4 11. Nb5 $1 {, and White has excellent winning chances.}) 8. Bxf3 Nf6 {Because of the queenside knight already standing on c3 , White can't reach the desired c3 - d4 setup.} 9. d3 Rg8 {There's the idea - Black wants to open the kingside by rushing forward with the g-pawn. This idea works if White cannot grab the center or outrun you on the queenside.} 10. Be3 g5 11. Ne4 Ne5 {Black is very fast with his threats.} ({After Nxf6 , here's how quickly White can get into trouble: exf6 Bxa7 Bd6 Be3} 11... g4 12. hxg4 {Nxf3+ Qxf3} Rxg4 {. White's extra pawn is irrelevant, which you can't say about Black's initiative.}) *

