1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. O-O {Big decision – now Black can think about a direct kingside attack.} O-O-O {Already, the fact that both kings are on opposite flanks suggests some fireworks! White doesn't have much time because Black is about to grab the center with ... e5 and claim a better position.} 6. h3 h5 {A common motif – White does not want to open the h-file since the odds are that it will lead to a swift checkmate.} (6... Bxf3 $6 {. The problem with this move order is that White has not yet committed to Nc3 .} 7. Bxf3 Qd7 {. You'd think that Black can still proceed with ... Nf6 , ... Rg8 and push forward the g-pawn, but here White is more flexible with the queenside plans than with the knight standing already on c3 .} 8. c3 $1 {. Very strong – White grabs a lot of space in the center.} Nf6 {.} ({(In case you're wondering, it is possible to push} 8... e5 {, but in this position, Black is missing the light-squared bishop to cover the weakened light squares.)}) 9. d4 Rg8 10. Nd2 {. Another powerful move – White is ready to meet Black's kingside attack with a solid play in the center, textbook response. It's also interesting to enter a race with b4 –b5.} g5 11. Re1 g4 12. hxg4 Nxg4 13. Ne4 {. Already here, it starts to feel that Black's attack is unprepared.} Qf5 14. Qe2 Qh5 15. Bf4 {, and White is strategically winning.}) 7. Nc3 {White could develop the queenside knight as well before accepting the bishop – very logical.} Qf5 {A good square for the black queen – Black is eyeing the h3 -pawn for potential sacrifices, but if White accepts the sacrifice, the queen is ready to connect with the rook on h8 for a devastating effect.} 8. d3 {Another version of accepting the bishop's sacrifice.} e6 {It's possible that Black might be already considering the ... Bxh3 sacrifice idea, but it's best not to rush with it and bring more pieces in the game first. Around here White should be feeling pretty nervous.} 9. hxg4 {It does not work here.} hxg4 10. Ng5 {White stops the immediate ... Qh5 , but as long as you know that the queen can get to the h-file a few moves later, everything is still under control.} (10. Nh2 Qh7 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. Qc1 g5 {, and Black's attack is crushing.}) 10... Nf6 11. Nxf7 Bc5 {The material balance (to be precise, White's extra rook on a1 ) here does not matter – Black's threats are too powerful.} *

