– White grabs a lot of space in the center.} Nf6 {.} ({(In case you're wondering, it is possible to push} 8... e5 {, but in this position, Black is missing the light-squared bishop to cover the weakened light squares.)}) 9. d4 Rg8 10. Nd2 {. Another powerful move – White is ready to meet Black's kingside attack with a solid play in the center, textbook response. It's also interesting to enter a race with b4 –b5.} g5 11. Re1 g4 12. hxg4 Nxg4 13. Ne4 {. Already here, it starts to feel that Black's attack is unprepared.} Qf5 14. Qe2 Qh5 15. Bf4 {, and White is strategically winning.}) 7. Nc3 {White could develop the queenside knight as well before accepting the bishop – very logical.} Qf5 {A good square for the black queen – Black is eyeing the h3 -pawn for potential sacrifices, but if White accepts the sacrifice, the queen is ready to connect with the rook on h8 for a devastating effect.} 8. hxg4 {Once again, the bishop is poisoned.} hxg4 9. Nh2 e6 {Quite similar to one of the previous lines – even if White wins the g-pawn, Black's initiative on the h-file is deadly.} 10. Bxg4 Qg6 {Very accurate – make sure that you remember this move! Now White can't play Bh3 .} (10... Qh7 $2 {. Here this is too straightforward, and White can close the h-file.} 11. Bh3 {, and Black does not have sufficient compensation for the lost piece.}) 11. Ne2 {White brings more pieces to the defense.} Bd6 12. Ng3 Nf6 13. Bh3 {White has managed to survive at the moment but at what cost?} Nd4 {Black keeps attacking.} 14. c3 Nc2 15. Rb1 {Now it's time to strike.} Bxg3 16. fxg3 Rxh3 17. gxh3 Ne3 {White's position falls apart.} *

