ng, it is possible to push} 8... e5 {, but in this position, Black is missing the light-squared bishop to cover the weakened light squares.)}) 9. d4 Rg8 10. Nd2 {. Another powerful move – White is ready to meet Black's kingside attack with a solid play in the center, textbook response. It's also interesting to enter a race with b4 –b5.} g5 11. Re1 g4 12. hxg4 Nxg4 13. Ne4 {. Already here, it starts to feel that Black's attack is unprepared.} Qf5 14. Qe2 Qh5 15. Bf4 {, and White is strategically winning.}) 7. hxg4 {Let's check what happens if White immediately accepts the piece.} hxg4 {Black wants to build a powerful battery of the queen and rook on the h-file and deliver a brutal checkmate.} 8. Nh2 {White might decide that because of the Bxg4 threat, Black's ... Qh5 is delayed, and thus White will prevail. However, even if it will take Black a few moves to get the queen to the h-file, White's position is perilous, if not already losing.} f5 9. Nxg4 Qf7 {It's possible to accept the knight and continue playing the position with a normal attack, but this move is stronger.} 10. d3 {Preventing ... Qh5 .} ({If} 10. Ne3 $2 g5 {or g6 with the idea of} 11. Z0 Qh7 {.}) 10... Qg6 ({If} 10... Qh5 $4 {, White can launch a discovered attack with} 11. Nh6 $1 Qh4 {, and after the sacrifice} 12. Bg5 Qxg5 {, they win the rook after} 13. Nf7 {– fork.}) 11. Nh2 Qh7 12. Bf4 g5 13. Bg3 f4 {Black wins back the piece but the deadly attack continues.} *

