ng, it is possible to push} 8... e5 {, but in this position, Black is missing the light-squared bishop to cover the weakened light squares.)}) 9. d4 Rg8 10. Nd2 {. Another powerful move – White is ready to meet Black's kingside attack with a solid play in the center, textbook response. It's also interesting to enter a race with b4 –b5.} g5 11. Re1 g4 12. hxg4 Nxg4 13. Ne4 {. Already here, it starts to feel that Black's attack is unprepared.} Qf5 14. Qe2 Qh5 15. Bf4 {, and White is strategically winning.}) 7. c3 {This is a strong setup – White wants to play d4 and fight for some space advantage in the center. There are also some options to accept the piece and then bring the queen to b3 to trade the queens – don't underestimate White's plans.} Nf6 ({Starting with} 7... e5 {might be too much – White will accept the piece.}) 8. d4 e5 {Now this is different. White can take the bishop but will have to give up the material immediately.} 9. Be3 {A smart player will continue developing and correctly assess that accepting the bishop on g4 is too dangerous.} Qd7 {The queen, in general, stands better on d7 since you want to continue with moves like ... Bd6 and also throw in the ... Bxh3 as an option.} 10. Nxe5 {This leads to simplifications.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Bxd1 Bxd1 13. exf6 gxf6 {The dust has settled – the position is materially balanced; Black has two bishops but a slightly worse pawn structure.} 14. Bd4 Be2 15. Re1 Re8 {An important resource – Black defends against two threats simultaneously.} 16. Nd2 Rg8 17. Bxf6 Bd6 {White has won the pawn, but Black still has the bishop pair and the open g-file, guaranteeing Black full compensation for the lost pawn.} ({Nf1 . Here's how the game might continue.} 17... Re6 18. Bh4 Bf3 {Ng3 Rxe1+ Rxe1 Bc6 . Black wants to push forward the f-pawn as far as it goes.}) *

