l players feel comfortable entering such sharp positions where they might get checkmated on the spot.} 10. b5 {. White should not accept the g-pawn; otherwise, the opened g-file will guarantee Black a strong initiative.} Ne7 11. Qa4 Kb8 12. Bc4 Qd7 13. Ne5 Qc8 14. Qb3 {. White is faster with his threats. It doesn't mean this position is not playable for Black – know the risk.}) 6. Bxf3 Qe6+ {Also, Black does not have a great choice – if you keep the queens, White will proceed with c3 - d4 , and Black's ... e5 plan feels soft without the light-squared bishop on the board.} 7. Kf1 {A strange moment to become ambitious, but at least this way White preserves the light-squared bishop (which might last for a few moves anyway).} O-O-O {Now ... Nd4 once again is on the table since the b7 -pawn is protected.} 8. d3 Qd7 {Black removes the queen and is about to advance the e-pawn. There are many alternatives, including the ... Nd4 move.} (8... g6 {. This is a position where Black can improvise with the plans. Also, positioning the dark-squared bishop on g7 seems reasonable since the e-pawn is blocked.} 9. Nc3 Nd4 10. Be3 Bg7 11. g3 Nxf3 {. Black felt that White is ready to retreat with the bishop to g2 .} 12. Qxf3 Nf6 13. Re1 Qf5 14. Kg2 Qxf3+ 15. Kxf3 {. The position looked quite equal in Jonathan Rowson (2569) – Vladimir Kramnik (2793), London Classic Gp-B 5th rapid 2013.}) 9. Nd2 e5 10. Nc4 Nge7 {The position can become sharp quickly – Black's game lies on the kingside.} ({After g3 , the game might continue:} 10... f5 {Kg2 Qe6 Re1 e4} 11. Kg1 g5 $1 {. Why not? To accept the pawn is quite dangerous for White.} 12. Bxg5 $2 {Qg6} Be7 13. Bxe7 {Bg2 Bc5 , and Black has a strong initiative.}) *

