1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. h3 {This is super unambitious – White does not want to compete in opening theory and avoids Scandinavian tactics. While pushing back the bishop and only then castle short makes sense, Black's 'refutation' of the plan is already well documented.} Bxf3 {It seems that also the queen trade is inevitable.} (5... Bh5 $6 {is a dangerous choice, but you might keep it as an adventurous option or for some faster time controls if you feel your opponent won't pick up the critical moves.} 6. d4 e6 ({(} 6... O-O-O $2 7. c4 {. Black doesn't have the critical f5 square for the queen since h3 and ... Bh5 are included. This position is borderline losing for Black. )}) 7. O-O Nf6 {. White proceeds with the strongest setup.} 8. c3 $1 O-O-O 9. b4 $1 g5 $5 {. The race is on. Objectively, White should be faster, but not all players feel comfortable entering such sharp positions where they might get checkmated on the spot.} 10. b5 {. White should not accept the g-pawn; otherwise, the opened g-file will guarantee Black a strong initiative.} Ne7 11. Qa4 Kb8 12. Bc4 Qd7 13. Ne5 Qc8 14. Qb3 {. White is faster with his threats. It doesn't mean this position is not playable for Black – know the risk.}) 6. Bxf3 Qe6+ {Also, Black does not have a great choice – if you keep the queens, White will proceed with c3 - d4 , and Black's ... e5 plan feels soft without the light-squared bishop on the board.} 7. Qe2 {A worthy try to keep the bishop pair.} Nd4 {This is the strongest continuation but also leads to a dead draw.} 8. Qxe6 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 fxe6 {This is one of those positions where, even for Magnus Carlsen, it will be tough to outplay an average titled player. Black should avoid pushing ... e5 – this would close the dark-squared bishop and limit the rook lifts on the 5th rank.} 10. Nc3 {The best that White can come up with.} g6 {No matter what White throws at you, this is the move that you want to start. Black remains flexible with the knight's development, but the dark-squared bishop can go to h6 as well.} (10... Nh6 $6 {. Even if the position is quite dry, Black has to remain accurate. This move allows Black to occupy the f5 square, but drawbacks exist.} 11. Ne4 Nf5 12. c3 e5 {. That's the thing – you don't want to play this move because it blocks your bishop and the rook mobility on the 5th rank. However, White's d4 was a problem.} 13. d3 g6 14. Ke2 Bg7 15. Be3 b6 16. a4 {. White achieved a pleasant edge in Denis Kadrić (2547) – Aleksandr Rakhmanov (2629) , EU-ch 20th Skopje 2019. The black knight on f5 stands pretty, but apart from that, Black doesn't have any active prospects, while White can advance on the queenside. Black will have to fight for the draw for a long time.}) 11. Ne4 {White threatens with Nc5 , but now there's an important nuance for Black.} (11. d3 {. White could continue a simple development, but now Black can trade the bishops.} O-O-O 12. h4 Bh6 13. h5 Bxc1 14. Rxc1 Nf6 15. hxg6 hxg6 {. The position is equal.}) 11... Bh6 {White's bishop did not make it to e3 to meet the bishop trade by fixing their pawn structure, which means White can't easily cover their weaknesses.} (11... Nf6 {. It's also possible to proceed with a standard development.} 12. d3 O-O-O 13. Be3 Nh5 14. b4 Bg7 15. Rb1 {. The position is equal, but White has developed a little initiative at the queenside. Black should not have any real problems}) 12. Nc5 {Everything else leads to simplifications – White might want to win a pawn.} O-O-O 13. Nxe6 Rd6 14. Nc5 Nf6 {Black has full compensation and will win back the lost pawn.} *

