1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. h3 {This is super unambitious – White does not want to compete in opening theory and avoids Scandinavian tactics. While pushing back the bishop and only then castle short makes sense, Black's 'refutation' of the plan is already well documented.} Bxf3 {It seems that also the queen trade is inevitable.} (5... Bh5 $6 {is a dangerous choice, but you might keep it as an adventurous option or for some faster time controls if you feel your opponent won't pick up the critical moves.} 6. d4 e6 ({(} 6... O-O-O $2 7. c4 {. Black doesn't have the critical f5 square for the queen since h3 and ... Bh5 are included. This position is borderline losing for Black. )}) 7. O-O Nf6 {. White proceeds with the strongest setup.} 8. c3 $1 O-O-O 9. b4 $1 g5 $5 {. The race is on. Objectively, White should be faster, but not all players feel comfortable entering such sharp positions where they might get checkmated on the spot.} 10. b5 {. White should not accept the g-pawn; otherwise, the opened g-file will guarantee Black a strong initiative.} Ne7 11. Qa4 Kb8 12. Bc4 Qd7 13. Ne5 Qc8 14. Qb3 {. White is faster with his threats. It doesn't mean this position is not playable for Black – know the risk.}) 6. Bxf3 Qe6+ {Also, Black does not have a great choice – if you keep the queens, White will proceed with c3 - d4 , and Black's ... e5 plan feels soft without the light-squared bishop on the board.} 7. Qe2 {A worthy try to keep the bishop pair. ⭕ Alternative} Qxe2+ {If Black wants to play on (the opponent is significantly weaker and not very good at endgames), then this is a great choice. It's often a typical strategy for stronger players to avoid drawing lines by entering a slightly worse endgame and slowly outplaying the less experienced opponent.} 8. Bxe2 Nd4 9. Bd1 {Still, the bishop pair is something you should never underestimate.} e5 10. c3 Ne6 11. Bc2 O-O-O 12. d3 g6 {If you can trade one of the bishops, do it.} 13. Nd2 Bh6 14. Nf3 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 f6 16. g3 Nh6 {Black has eliminated White's bishop pair, and now we have an approximately equal position where the stronger player will win most of the time.} *

