1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this and the next chapter, we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. h3 {Super unambitious - White does not want to compete in opening theory and avoids any Scandinavian tactics. While pushing back the bishop and only then castle short makes sense, Black's 'refutation' of the plan is already well documented. ⭕ Alternative} Bh5 ({Objectively, this is a dangerous choice, but you might want to consider it if your opponents are constantly leading you to the dry endgame with} 5... Bxf3 {. If White chooses the setup of Nf3 and Be2 , typically they want a long, quiet game without any risk. Suddenly, after Bh5 , they are forced to play a very complex middlegame where White will have to calculate variations with no margin for error to prove an advantage.   Know the risk you're taking!}) 6. g4 {The attempt to fight for space advantage doesn't promise White anything real.} Bg6 7. d4 e6 8. c4 Qd6 {White has to play with a great determination; otherwise, the created weaknesses in their own setup are here to stay.} 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. Be3 h5 11. c5 Qd7 12. g5 Nge7 {The black knight has some promising prospects.} 13. Qa4 Nd5 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Rhg1 a6 {Albeit the game remains complex, Black has nothing to complain about.} *

