1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this and the next chapter, we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. h3 {Super unambitious – White does not want to compete in opening theory and avoids any Scandinavian tactics. While pushing back the bishop and only then castle short makes sense, Black's 'refutation' of the plan is already well documented.} Bh5 ({Objectively, this is a dangerous choice, but you might want to consider it if your opponents are constantly leading you to the dry endgame with} 5... Bxf3 {. If White chooses the setup of Nf3 and Be2 , typically they want a long, quiet game without any risk. Suddenly, after Bh5 , they are forced to play a very complex middlegame where White will have to calculate variations with no margin for error to prove an advantage.   Know the risk you're taking!}) 6. d4 {The standard plan.} e6 {Before everything else, you need to stop White's c4 - d5 idea.} (6... O-O-O $2 7. c4 {. Black doesn't have the critical f5 -square for the queen since h3 and ... Bh5 are included. This position is borderline losing for Black.}) 7. O-O Nf6 (7... O-O-O $6 {is too early.} 8. Be3 Nf6 9. c4 $1 Qf5 10. Qb3 {, and White is much better.}) 8. c3 {Objectively, the strongest setup for White.} (8. Nc3 {doesn't look very menacing.} Qd7 9. Be3 Bb4 {, and Black gets a satisfactory game without mind-boggling experiences.}) 8... O-O-O 9. b4 g5 {That's a move you want to throw at White, basically after any of their last moves.   Now we're heading for a very sharp game, which is something that White might not be ready for. Objectively, White should be faster with their own attack, but not all players feel comfortable entering such sharp positions where they might get checkmated on the spot. A perfect choice in the blitz or rapid format!} 10. b5 {White should not accept the g-pawn; otherwise, the opened g-file will guarantee Black a strong initiative.} (10. Nbd2 {would allow Black to carry out the plan.} g4 11. hxg4 Bxg4 12. b5 $1 Na5 13. Ne5 {. White aims to punish Black's initiative by playing positionally.} Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Bd6 $1 15. Nxf7 Rhg8 {. White already needs to be careful.} 16. Nxd6+ cxd6 17. f3 Rg6 18. Rf2 Kb8 {, and White's extra pawn doesn't play any role – Black has a practical compensation.}) 10... Ne7 11. Ne5 {It will take all the willpower in the world for White NOT to choose this move! After all, it seems that Black is just dropping the pawn on f7 .} Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Rg8 {Black can ignore it.} 13. Nxf7 Re8 14. Ne5 h5 {White has the pawn, Black has the initiative.} 15. Be3 Nf5 16. c4 {Already a necessity; otherwise, Black's initiative on the kingside starts to look very serious.} Nxd4 17. Qb2 Qxe5 18. Bxd4 Qf5 {Black temporarily sacrifices a piece.} 19. Bxf6 e5 20. Nd2 Qxf6 21. Ne4 {After a forcing line White gets a beautiful knight on e4 but Black has enough dynamic resources to keep the game balanced.} Qb6 22. Qe2 g4 23. Rad1 {Typical engine move, but it's the best choice for White.} gxh3 24. Qxh5 Rxg2+ 25. Kh1 Qe6 {The game remains very sharp.} *

