1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. c4 ({This has to be one of the principal ideas – it's also the most played move in the position, closely followed by} 6. Be3 {.}) 6... Qf5 {Here, the queen stands better than the usual h5 -square. White needs to decide whether to give up the pawn on d4 for some initiative or protect it.} 7. Nc3 {This fails tactically.} Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 9. Bg4 {It seems that Black blundered something.} Nc2+ {But no – White does not have a satisfactory continuation.} 10. Qxc2 Qxg4 {Black is winning.} *

