1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. c4 ({This has to be one of the principal ideas – it's also the most played move in the position, closely followed by} 6. Be3 {.}) 6... Qf5 {Here, the queen stands better than the usual h5 -square. White needs to decide whether to give up the pawn on d4 for some initiative or protect it.} 7. d5 {It's been known for a long time why this move is a mistake.} e6 8. Nc3 Nf6 {White has big problems to defend the d5 -pawn.} 9. Qa4 {The best that White can do under the circumstances.} (9. Bd3 $2 {. This line does not deserve any special study because White is forcing Black to pick up the only moves and then win the game.} Bxf3 10. Bxf5 Bxd1 11. dxc6 exf5 12. cxb7+ Kxb7 13. Nxd1 Bb4+ {. So far, these were forcing captures; this check is very logical.} 14. Ke2 Rhe8+ {Black has a winning attack.}) (9. h3 {Similarly to 9.Bd3 , Black's moves are obvious.} Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Ne5 11. Be2 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 {. The only trick worth knowing, but Black also has other good moves.} 13. Nxd5 Qe4 14. O-O Rxd5 15. Qb3 Bc5 {, and White has no compensation for the lost pawn.} 16. Bg5 $1 {. It's interesting that this is the only move after which White doesn't lose immediately.} Bb6 {. Black's extra pawn and the centralized pieces give them very good winning chances.}) 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Ne5 11. Qxa7 Bc5 {A good trick to know – White can't take the bishop due to the fork on d3 .} 12. Qa8+ Kd7 13. Qxb7 {If White accepts the second pawn, Black's initiative immediately becomes deadly.} Rb8 14. Qa6 Nd3+ 15. Kf1 exd5 {The position is opening up quickly, and the white king is more vulnerable than Black's.} 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Rhe8 {Black's threats are very difficult to stop.} 18. Be3 Rxe3 19. fxe3 Rxb2 20. Qc6+ Kd8 {Black's attack is already decisive.} *

