1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. c4 ({This has to be one of the principal ideas – it's also the most played move in the position, closely followed by} 6. Be3 {.}) 6... Qf5 {Here, the queen stands better than the usual h5 -square. White needs to decide whether to give up the pawn on d4 for some initiative or protect it.} 7. Be3 {White wants to reinforce the center, but Black has an effective way to destroy it.} Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Qe6+ {An essential check – don't forget, White might still play Bg4 !} 10. Be2 {The only move – everything else costs White the game.} c5 {We find this paradoxical move much simpler than 10...Qe4 .} ({The move} 10... Qe4 {is recommended in some previous Chessable courses.} 11. Qa4 Qxd4 12. O-O e6 {, Black needs to complete the development carefully.} ({(} 12... e5 $4 {. Sometimes, too much activity is too much.} 13. Rd1 Qc5 14. Bg4+ Kb8 15. Rxd8# {.)}) 13. Nc3 a6 {The lines continue, but for White, it's still easier to play, especially in faster time controls.} 14. Bf3 {White is still attacking.} Qc5 ({(} 14... Qd7 {is also possible, but now Black has to remember a lot of precise moves to stay in the game.} 15. Nb5 $1 Kb8 16. Rfd1 Bd6 17. Qb3 $1 {. White is attacking with great imagination.} axb5 18. c5 Ne7 19. a4 $1 b4 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. a5 d5 {. Black continues making the only moves.} 22. Qxb4 Qd6 $1 23. Qc3 e5 24. a6 b6 25. a7+ {. White's initiative continues.} Ka8 26. Rxd5 Nxd5 27. Rd1 Qe6 28. Qc4 Kxa7 29. Bxd5 Rxd5 {. The bishop is too strong, and thus, better eliminate it.} 30. Rxd5 Rc8 31. Qa4+ Kb7 32. Rd7+ Rc7 33. Qe4+ Qc6 34. Rxc7+ Kxc7 35. Qxe5+ Qd6 {, with equality. Judge yourself if this is worth it. )}) 15. b4 $1 {. Very logical – White fires up the queenside.} Qxb4 16. Qc2 Qxc4 17. Rab1 b5 {. The engine here gives a minor advantage to Black, but visually, Black's position is perilous.} 18. Rfc1 Ba3 19. Be2 Qf4 20. g3 Qd2 21. Nxb5 Qxc2 {. Finally, Black gets the queens off the board.} 22. Na7+ Kd7 23. Rxc2 Ne7 24. Bxa6 {. With a balanced game.}) 11. Qa4 {White proceeds with the typical way of seeking action on the queenside.} ({If White castles short} 11. O-O {, Black can delay the capture on d4 since the bishop is not going anywhere. You can decide later whether to take with the pawn or the rook.} Nf6 12. Qa4 cxd4 13. Qxa7 Qa6 {. This transposes to the lines, covered with a different move order.}) 11... cxd4 12. Qxa7 Nf6 (12... d3 {, Black can win a piece, but the complications will be difficult to evaluate.} 13. Nc3 dxe2 14. Qa8+ Kd7 15. Qxb7+ Ke8 16. Qb5+ Qd7 17. a4 {. The key idea – White doesn't mind trading the queens, but this will form a chain of powerful pawns on the queenside.} Nf6 18. Kxe2 Qxb5 19. axb5 e5 20. Rhd1 {. White's position seems more straightforward to play, albeit engines insist that the position is equal.}) 13. O-O {If White offers you the bishop on e2 , you can gamble and enter some crazy lines, but the text move is simpler as this will be your response pretty much against anything that White throws at you in this sideline.} Qa6 14. Qxa6 bxa6 15. Bd3 e5 {We have a material balance on the board, and Black dreams about pushing forward the central pawns.} ({Nd2 . Here's how the game might continue: Bb4} 15... Ne4 {Nxe4} 16. Bxe4 g6 {. Black wants to push ... f5 and ... e4 .} 17. a3 {Be7 Rfe1} f5 18. Bd5 {Bf6 . Somehow, Black's pawns are running forward faster.}) *

