this will form a chain of powerful pawns on the queenside.} Nf6 18. Kxe2 Qxb5 19. axb5 e5 20. Rhd1 {. White's position seems more straightforward to play, albeit engines insist that the position is equal.}) 13. Na3 Qa6 {Again, Black's response is the same.} 14. Qc5+ {If White traded the queens, the knight on a3 would be misplaced.} Qc6 15. Qe5 e6 16. Nb5 (16. O-O $2 {. If White castles away from the center, their position rapidly deteriorates.} Bxa3 17. bxa3 Qc7 $1 18. Qb5 Ne4 {, and Black takes over the game.}) 16... Bb4+ 17. Kd1 ({If} 17. Kf1 {, we go for the same} Qc5 {.}) 17... Qc5 {The simplest move – Black forces the queen trade since White can't walk away because of the incoming ... d3 and ... Qxc4 threat.} ({Keeping queens on the board with} 17... Qb6 {leads to a much more complex game.}) 18. Qxc5+ Bxc5 19. Bd3 Ng4 ({Stronger than the tempting} 19... e5 {– don't allow the white king easily to get to the c2 -square where it will feel secure.}) 20. Ke2 Rhe8 {If White will now push back the black knight, they will also create weaknesses at the dark squares.} 21. a3 g6 22. b4 Bf8 23. Rad1 e5 24. h3 Nf6 25. f3 Nh5 {Black effectively is taking over the game – the white king is in the crossfire.} *

