1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. c4 ({This has to be one of the principal ideas – it's also the most played move in the position, closely followed by} 6. Be3 {.}) 6... Qf5 {Here, the queen stands better than the usual h5 -square. White needs to decide whether to give up the pawn on d4 for some initiative or protect it.} 7. Qb3 {A clever way to protect the pawn and escape some pins.} e5 {It's obvious that if somebody is interested in complicating matters, it's Black – White has not castled yet.} (7... Nxd4 $2 {does not work:} 8. Nxd4 Rxd4 9. f3 Bh5 10. g4 {, and Black will lose something.}) (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 $4 9. Qxb7+ {. That's why White played Qb3 in the first place – to make sure that Black can't do this.}) 8. d5 Bxf3 {Simple and good – Black secures the d4 -square for the knight.} 9. Qxf3 Qxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 11. Bd1 f5 {Black has a great position and a beautiful knight on d4 , but White does have the bishop pair.} *

