1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. c4 ({This has to be one of the principal ideas – it's also the most played move in the position, closely followed by} 6. Be3 {.}) 6... Qf5 {Here, the queen stands better than the usual h5 -square. White needs to decide whether to give up the pawn on d4 for some initiative or protect it.} 7. Nbd2 {White keeps the pawn on d4 , but the queenside knight on d2 feels weird, and White's dark-squared bishop is blocked.} e6 {A great move – not only does Black continue the development, but you also keep a close eye on the d4 -pawn.} (7... Nxd4 $4 {. By now, you should already know that you can't take the pawn.} 8. Nxd4 Rxd4 9. f3 {.}) 8. h3 {White forces matters. If they would castle short, Black could revisit the idea to capture on d4 after all or proceed with the typical ... h5 idea.} Bxf3 9. Nxf3 Qa5+ {A vital check to which White has no satisfactory answer.} 10. Kf1 ({If} 10. Bd2 $4 Bb4 {, White's pawn on d4 will drop.}) 10... Qb6 11. Qb3 {The best that White can do.} Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qe5 {If White had castled short, this would be a fantastic position for them. Now, they will have to waste several tempos to connect the rooks.} 14. Bf3 ({Of course, after} 14. Bxa7 $4 {the bishop is trapped:} b6 {.}) 14... c6 {You want to get the dark-squared bishops off the board as quickly as possible; otherwise, White will get serious compensation and attacking chances on the queenside.} 15. g3 (15. Bxa7 $6 Bc5 16. Re1 Qd4 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 {. White wins back the pawn, but now Black dominates the dark squares.}) 15... Nh6 {Our proposed improvement – the black knight is heading to the f5 - and d4 -squares for a great effect.} (15... Nf6 {is recommended in Lifetime Repertoires: Scandinavian Defense .} 16. Bf4 Qc5 17. Kg2 Bd6 18. Be3 Qa5 {. The given evaluation here is that Black is slightly better, while actually, it's not so simple if White continues to play aggressively.} 19. Qc2 Bc5 20. b4 $1 Bxb4 21. Rab1 {, and White has a very obvious compensation for the sacrificed material.}) (15... Qa5 {Black can also go for the straightforward ... Bc5 plan.} 16. Kg2 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. Qc3 Nf6 19. b4 {. White's initiative continues, even if Black has traded the bishops.} Qd4 20. Qc2 Qd3 21. Qa4 Kb8 22. b5 Ne4 {. The engine tries to convince us that this is holding.} 23. Rhd1 Nd2 24. Rxd2 Qxd2 25. bxc6 Qb2 26. c5 {, and according to Stockfish, it's equal.}) 16. Kg2 {This move is a big mistake.} Nf5 17. Bxa7 Rd2 {Suddenly, White doesn't have a satisfactory defense against the blatant ... Qxg3 threat!} 18. Bg4 Bc5 {Black's attack is already crushing.} *

