Nxd4 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Rxd4 {Black has won a pawn and now White has to show something for it.} 10. Be3 Rd7 {The difference why the rook stands better on d7 than on d8 is that in some lines, you avoid the Qg4 + and can double the rooks one move faster.} 11. c5 {An interesting idea – White wants to demolish Black's defenses with the c6 push.} Qd3 ({If the black rook would stand on d8 , this would give White an interesting option of} 11... Qg4 {, followed by c6 .}) 12. Qf3 Qd5 {Of course, White can't trade the queens.} 13. Qf4 Kb8 {A prudent move – watch out for White's Qa4 .} (13... e5 $2 {. This hasty but very logical move gives White a powerful attack.} 14. Qa4 a6 15. Nc3 Qc6 16. Qa5 $1 {. Suddenly, Black has no defense against White's queenside pawn assault.}) 14. Nc3 e5 {The only move, but it's enough!} 15. Qa4 {If White trades off the queens, the position is equal.} Qc6 16. Qa5 {With this move order, White's attack does not work since Black is not committed to ... a6 .} Nf6 17. Rad1 (17. b4 Qa6 {. Trading off the queens guarantees Black safety while White will have to work hard to prove the compensation for the missing pawn.}) 17... Nd5 ({Also} 17... Be7 {looks reasonable, keeping the idea of ... Qa6 . The text move, however, is stronger.}) 18. Nxd5 Rxd5 19. b4 {Now, White's b5 is unstoppable, but it alone does not guarantee White any success.} f5 20. b5 Qe6 21. c6 Bc5 {Just in time.} 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 23. Rd7 Qxc6 {Precise – for White, it's time to seek equality.} 24. bxc6 Rxa5 25. cxb7 Rxa2 26. Rc1 Rb2 27. Rxg7 Rxb7 {White is fighting for a draw.} *

