Nxd4 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Rxd4 {Black has won a pawn and now White has to show something for it.} 10. Be3 Rd7 {The difference why the rook stands better on d7 than on d8 is that in some lines, you avoid the Qg4 + and can double the rooks one move faster.} 11. c5 {An interesting idea – White wants to demolish Black's defenses with the c6 push.} Qd3 ({If the black rook would stand on d8 , this would give White an interesting option of} 11... Qg4 {, followed by c6 .}) 12. Qe1 {A new move – White threatens with the immediate Qa5 , and the c6 push is still there.} e6 {Black should race to complete the development.} 13. Nc3 {If White does not go for the c6 breakthrough, the queenside attack is destined to fail.} Nf6 14. a4 a6 {A risky move but it's necessary to stop Nb5 .} 15. b4 Ng4 16. Rd1 Qc4 17. Rxd7 Kxd7 18. Qd2+ Kc8 19. Bg5 {White improves the Rd1 idea.} (19. Rd1 {. White wants to deliver a quick checkmate, but you can easily parry it.} Be7 20. Qd7+ Kb8 21. Qxe7 Nxe3 22. fxe3 Qxc3 {, and Black keeps the extra pawn.}) 19... f6 20. Rd1 Bxc5 {The only move, but it's again good enough.} 21. bxc5 fxg5 22. Qd7+ Kb8 23. Qxg7 Rc8 24. h3 e5 {A significant move; otherwise, White is doing pretty well.} 25. hxg4 Qxc3 {Black keeps the extra pawn and some winning chances.} *

