1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. O-O {White sacrifices the d4 -pawn – a common motif of the Scandinavian Defense.} Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Qxd4 {White can't trade the queens, but what's the proper way to avoid it?} 8. Nd2 {The best that White can come up with.} Ne5 {It's in Black's best interest to trade White's strong, light-squared bishop as quickly as possible. If it retreats to e2 , White might have difficulties continuing development. Think about original ideas like ... Qa4 and White can't easily get the queen to the queenside attack.} ({The following line, starting with} 8... Qd7 {, will illustrate what type of game White would like to get.} 9. c3 Ne5 10. Qb3 Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 e6 12. Be3 {. Even though Black has traded off the strong light-squared bishop, White's lead in the development and direct attacking ideas on the queenside guarantee him a lasting initiative at a minimum material cost.} a6 13. Rfd1 Qe8 14. Rxd8+ Qxd8 15. Rd1 {. Black needs to play this very carefully, but objectively, the position is fine.}) 9. Qe2 e6 {It's important to bring the dark-squared bishop in the game first.} (9... Nf6 {. This move order creates unnecessary complications for Black.} 10. Re1 Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 {. White is not only thinking about the Ne5 idea but also organizes a kingside attack.}) 10. Bxb7+ {The only resource to keep the balance – it's a complicated move to find, and basically, White has to know it.} ({Trying to chase the queen with} 10. c3 {is suboptimal. Black responds with} Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 Qa4 12. b3 Qc6 13. Ne5 $6 {, a human move,} Qe8 14. Be3 {, threatening Bxa7 .} f6 {. Black counterattack and after} 15. Nc4 Kb8 {, they defend the pawn.} 16. Rfd1 Ne7 {.}) 10... Kxb7 11. Nb3 Qd5 12. Bf4 Ng6 13. Be3 {White is down a full piece, but the strong initiative at the queenside and Black's lack of development guarantees them equality, but not more.} Qe5 {Black walks away from the Rd1 threat first.} 14. f4 Qf5 15. g4 {White has to kick away the black queen protecting the b5 -square.} Qe4 16. Rad1 Rd5 {Now it's Black's turn to make the only move – everything else loses!} 17. Rxd5 exd5 18. Na5+ Kc8 19. Qa6+ {White forces a perpetual check.} Kd7 20. Qb5+ Kc8 {The game should end in a draw – White can't risk to continue.} *

