1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. c3 {This might be a typical reaction of somebody surprised by the sudden Black's aggressiveness – it's important to keep pushing.} e5 {If unprepared, White should be feeling pretty uncomfortable. Capture on e5 already leads White to a much worse position.} 7. c4 {White attempts to counter-attack and position the pawn on d5 since Black has already committed to ... e5 and won't be able to target the white pawn. It is not dangerous for Black since White loses a tempo.} Qe4 {Not only the d4 pawn is hanging, but also Black is threatening to take on f3 and ruin White's hopes for a safe castling short.} 8. Nc3 Bb4 9. d5 {The only reasonable thing that White can do.} Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qg6 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Na5 {The position remains equal, but playing with Black is easier. Both knights have clear targets and outposts to employ, while White has to figure out where to hide the king. On top of this, White risks ending up in a strategically bad position due to the pawn structure.} 13. Qa4 b6 14. Be3 f5 (14... Ne7 {also deserves attention.}) 15. c5 {White proceeds with a queenside attack.} f4 {It's important to push back the bishop.} 16. cxb6 axb6 17. Bd2 Rxd5 18. c4 {The forcing line continues – Black wins a pawn but now has to give up an exchange to secure the king.} Rxd2 19. Kxd2 Nf6 20. c5 {White tries to make something work before Black can reorganize their pieces.} Nd7 21. cxb6 Nc5 {Suddenly, things get very sharp.} 22. Qb4 Nab3+ 23. Ke1 {After every other retreat, Black can consider keeping the knight on b3 for attacking purposes.} Nxa1 24. Qxc5 Qxb6 25. Qxb6 cxb6 26. Bd1 Rd8 {The dust has settled – Black has an extra pawn, but the knight on a1 needs to get liberated.} ({After Rg1 , the game might continue:} 26... g6 {Rg5 Rd5} 27. h4 {Rc5 . Obviously, there are other moves, like activating the king first. Kd2 Rd5+ Kc1 Rd3 Rxe5} Nb3 {Kc2 Rd2+ Kxb3 Rxd1 . Draw seems to be the likely outcome.}) *

