1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. Nc3 {The moment to play this move feels quite awkward because it doesn't solve the problem of the d4 pawn.} Qf5 {Retreating to a5 also looks interesting, but the text move is easier to remember since this is where you will retreat with the queen in similar positions most of the time. Again, White faces the question – protect the d4 pawn or give it up for some compensation?} 7. h3 {This is pretty smart because if Black is not careful, you might mix up this position with a line where White has just made a mistake.} Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nf6 {You can't take on d4 due to the Bg4 threat! There are similar lines in this chapter where Black proceeds with ... Nxd4 and wins a pawn due to the ... Nxc2 +, but not here. Now ... Nxd4 once again is a threat.} (8... Nxd4 $4 9. Bg4 Nxc2+ 10. Qxc2 {, and Black can't capture on g4 anymore.}) 9. Bxc6 Qe6+ {An important resource – Black avoids ruining the pawn structure.} 10. Qe2 Qxc6 11. O-O a6 {You can't take on d4 because of the Nb5 trick; thus ... a6 reinforces the threat.} 12. Be3 e6 {Black is very much safe and is ready to consider starting a kingside attack with ... Rg8 and push forward the g-pawn.} *

