1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. Nc3 {The moment to play this move feels quite awkward because it doesn't solve the problem of the d4 pawn.} Qf5 {Retreating to a5 also looks interesting, but the text move is easier to remember since this is where you will retreat with the queen in similar positions most of the time. Again, White faces the question – protect the d4 pawn or give it up for some compensation?} 7. d5 {White is over-extended.} Bxf3 {The most precise way to punish White for their strategy.} 8. Bxf3 Nf6 {Black doesn't have to rush anywhere – complete the development, and the d5 pawn most likely will fall anyway since White can't easily dodge the pin. However, don't put the plans to conquer the d5 pawn over the integrity of your position.} 9. Be3 e6 10. Qe2 Ne5 {A GM-level move. Black values the activity above the extra pawn!} (10... exd5 11. O-O-O {is not so clear – White has some compensation for the missing pawn.} Bb4 $2 12. Nxd5 {Good trick to know. (Black should play} Kb8 {or h5 to avoid any Bg4 skewer.)}) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Rd1 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Bb4 {White is solidly worse.} *

