1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. Nc3 {The moment to play this move feels quite awkward because it doesn't solve the problem of the d4 pawn.} Qf5 {Retreating to a5 also looks interesting, but the text move is easier to remember since this is where you will retreat with the queen in similar positions most of the time. Again, White faces the question – protect the d4 pawn or give it up for some compensation?} 7. Be3 Nf6 {An important accuracy – before pushing ... e5 , better extra secure the bishop on g4 against any unexpected Nh4 jumps. White's d-pawn isn't going anywhere.} 8. O-O (8. h3 $2 {Talking Black into executing their main idea is not a good strategy.} Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 e5 {. White is not losing but is worse.}) 8... e5 9. d5 Nb4 {The opening should give you the feeling that Black will destroy White very quickly. Notice that you're not threatening to play ... Nxc2 due to Bd3 .} 10. h3 Bxf3 ({Probably the smart move, but the alternative with} 10... h5 {looks very appealing and, most of the time, probably will give you a crushing attack.}) 11. Bxf3 Kb8 {Black improves the ... e4 threat and defends the a7 pawn.} 12. Qe2 Nxc2 13. Be4 {This only trick allows White to avoid greater trouble.} Nxe4 14. Qxc2 Nd6 15. Bxa7+ {Nice trick – Black can't take the poisoned bishop due to the Nb5 + and the knight can't be touched since the queen on f5 would be left defenseless.} Ka8 16. Qa4 Qd7 {This also means that White's attack is over, and Black gets a very nice position.} 17. Qxd7 Rxd7 18. Bc5 b6 {Black has slightly better chances in the endgame.} *

