1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. Be3 {A reasonable choice.} e5 {Here, lighting up the center is important. Whenever you're studying these lines, make sure that you understand the difference, when it's a good idea to push ... e5 right away, and when you can afford to include a developing move like ... Nf6 .} (6... Nf6 $6 {. If you mix up the move order, you transpose to a position where Black has committed to ... Nf6 too early.} 7. c4 Qf5 8. Nc3 {. The position is playable for Black, but White has the better chances.}) 7. Nc3 Qa5 {White once again experiences some discomfort with the pressure on the d-file and has to liquidate into an equal position to avoid trouble.} 8. Nxe5 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 {This leads to a completely symmetrical position where White's development is not better.} 11. Qc4 Nf6 12. Rd1 Rxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Bd6 {It's possible to protect the pawn on f7 with ... Qe6 , but the text move gives Black some dynamic chances if White accepts it.} 14. Qxf7 {If White doesn't take the pawn, you can play the next move ... Qe6 . After the queen trade, White will have a slightly better pawn structure, but it's impossible to convert it.} Bb4 15. Qc4 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qd5+ 17. Kc1 Rd8 {Black plays very dynamically, and it will result in winning back the lost pawn.} 18. Rg1 Qxa2 19. b3 Qa3+ {The position remains equal.} *

