most logical continuation also requires us to study fewer lines, which is our course's ambition.} (8... Qa6 $5 {is also interesting, but it leads to a huge fight and complex lines that you must remember flawlessly. If you wish you can study the informational variation here .}) 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 {The position has clarified a bit – White has the bishop pair, but Black has anchored a knight on d4 , and the black king on the queenside feels pretty safe.} 11. a3 {This leads to an equal endgame, but White will have opportunities to stumble and get a worse position.} Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 f5 13. b4 Qa6 14. Be2 {An accurate move – the immediate castling short lands White into a worse position due to ... e4 .} Nf6 15. Nb3 Rhe8 {Because of the stuck white king in the center and the pin on f1 - a6 diagonal, ... Nxd5 move seems to be impossible to parry.} 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. O-O Nxd5 18. cxd5 {White has no choice.} Qxe2 19. Qxd4 g6 20. Qxa7 Qa6 {White is temporarily up a pawn, but the d5 -pawn will fall.} 21. Qd4 Qd6 22. Rfd1 Re5 23. Qa7 Qa6 {Draw seems to be very close.} *

