most logical continuation also requires us to study fewer lines, which is our course's ambition.} (8... Qa6 $5 {is also interesting, but it leads to a huge fight and complex lines that you must remember flawlessly. If you wish you can study the informational variation here .}) 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 {The position has clarified a bit – White has the bishop pair, but Black has anchored a knight on d4 , and the black king on the queenside feels pretty safe.} 11. Nc3 Qa6 {Black doesn't allow White to catch a breath and pressures the c-pawn before the white king can leave the center.} 12. Be2 {This leads to a complex game where Black must know several important tactical ideas.} Nf6 13. O-O {If White castles short, Black wins the pawn on d5 .} Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 Rxd5 16. Rfe1 {Earlier courses suggest that White here keeps a small edge, but it's unclear how White can create anything remotely close to an initiative.} Rd7 {The best place for the black rook.} (16... Rc5 17. b3 Re8 18. Qd2 {. This is not so clear, the black rook on c5 is misplaced.}) (16... Rd6 $6 {. Here the rook will be targeted by the white bishop.} 17. Qxe5 Qxc4 18. Qg3 Rhd8 19. Be5 $1 {Exactly because of this move White secures a lasting initiative.}) 17. Qxe5 (17. Bxe5 Re8 {will lead to many trades.}) 17... Qxc4 18. Qg3 {White will win back the sacrificed pawn, but Black is trading the minor pieces and leads the position to an equal heavy piece endgame.} Rhd8 19. Qxg7 Ne4 20. Qxh7 {White doesn't have a choice.} Nxc3 21. bxc3 Qxc3 {Both sides have chances to organize two connected passed pawns in front of their kings; thus, the position is equal – the stronger player will win this with either color most of the time.} *

