most logical continuation also requires us to study fewer lines, which is our course's ambition.} (8... Qa6 $5 {is also interesting, but it leads to a huge fight and complex lines that you must remember flawlessly. If you wish you can study the informational variation here .}) 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 {The position has clarified a bit – White has the bishop pair, but Black has anchored a knight on d4 , and the black king on the queenside feels pretty safe.} 11. Nc3 Qa6 {Black doesn't allow White to catch a breath and pressures the c-pawn before the white king can leave the center.} 12. Be2 {This leads to a complex game where Black must know several important tactical ideas.} Nf6 13. a3 Rhe8 {An important idea to know!} (13... Bxc3 {If you initiate trades right away, White will have the better position.} 14. Bxc3 Nxe2 ({(The line} 14... Rhe8 {no longer works.} 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. O-O {. The black pawn on d4 is weak.} Nxd5 $4 17. Bg4+ {. Oops. )}) 15. Qxe2 Rhe8 16. Rc1 {. That's the point – White doesn't have to rush with the short castle and fall under ... Nxd5 or ... Rxd5 tricks.} c6 17. dxc6 Qxc6 18. O-O {. White is slightly better due to the stronger bishop and Black's more exposed king.}) 14. Rc1 {White might avoid the tactical skirmishes and force Black to take on c3 , but now the extra tempo should help your cause.} Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Kb8 {A good move – Black stops White from castling short since there's always the capture on d5 . With the king on b8 , White no longer has surprise checks on the h3 - c8 diagonal.} 16. Bd3 e4 17. Be2 Nf3+ {Quite ambitious – White can't accept the knight for obvious reasons.} (17... Nxe2 {may be simpler.} 18. Qxe2 Nd7 19. O-O Nc5 {. This is also good for Black.}) 18. Kf1 Ne5 {Black has the initiative, and White has to figure out how to secure the king.} *

