[Black "Quiet 3.Nf3: 4.Be2 with 6.Be3 #12"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B01"]
[PlyCount "46"]
[GameId "2174210256737433"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In this chapter we will discuss the positions that arise if White develops the kingside knight first. White wants to play d4 , c4 , and only then Nc3 – using the queen to win some tempos for the development, but not immediately.} Bg4 {Naturally, you don't want to give White such freedom; thus, it's best to play more aggressively here.} (3... Nf6 {. This sample line will illustrate what kind of game White wants to achieve if Black is not accurate.} 4. d4 {. Now Black doesn't have any immediate active countermeasures in the center, like the ... e5 push.} Bg4 5. Be2 c6 6. c4 Qa5+ {. We're setting up the classical Scandinavian position and should not complain about anything, but the white pawn standing on c4 instead of c2 makes quite a difference.} 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bf4 {. Because of the white pawn on c4 , Black loses some active plans that involve ... Nd5 . Also, for White, it's easier to go for immediate d5 push plans or advance on the queenside with b4 – b5 . This position for Black would be very much acceptable with the pawn on c2 .}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {If White continues with d4 and c4 , Black is ready for it. White is at a crossroads.} 5. d4 {For a good reason, there's a rule that whoever controls the center controls the game. If White won't grab the center, Black will.} O-O-O {Black immediately starts hammering the center – now White has several choices.} 6. Be3 {A reasonable choice.} e5 {Here, lighting up the center is important. Whenever you're studying these lines, make sure that you understand the difference, when it's a good idea to push ... e5 right away, and when you can afford to include a developing move like ... Nf6 .} (6... Nf6 $6 {. If you mix up the move order, you transpose to a position where Black has committed to ... Nf6 too early.} 7. c4 Qf5 8. Nc3 {. The position is playable for Black, but White has the better chances.}) 7. c4 {Seems to be necessary – White wants to close the center with d5 .} Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Bb4 {The most logical continuation also requires us to study fewer lines, which is our course's ambition.} (8... Qa6 $5 {is also interesting, but it leads to a huge fight and complex lines that you must remember flawlessly. If you wish you can study the informational variation here .}) 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 {The position has clarified a bit – White has the bishop pair, but Black has anchored a knight on d4 , and the black king on the queenside feels pretty safe.} 11. Nc3 Qa6 {Black doesn't allow White to catch a breath and pressures the c-pawn before the white king can leave the center.} 12. Be2 {This leads to a complex game where Black must know several important tactical ideas.} Nf6 13. a3 Rhe8 {An important idea to know!} (13... Bxc3 {If you initiate trades right away, White will have the better position.} 14. Bxc3 Nxe2 ({(The line} 14... Rhe8 {no longer works.} 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. O-O {. The black pawn on d4 is weak.} Nxd5 $4 17. Bg4+ {. Oops. )}) 15. Qxe2 Rhe8 16. Rc1 {. That's the point – White doesn't have to rush with the short castle and fall under ... Nxd5 or ... Rxd5 tricks.} c6 17. dxc6 Qxc6 18. O-O {. White is slightly better due to the stronger bishop and Black's more exposed king.}) 14. axb4 {Challenge accepted!} Qxa1 15. Qxa1 Nc2+ 16. Kf1 Nxa1 17. Bd1 c6 {White was hoping to trap the black knight on a1 , but after this precise move, the position is balanced.} 18. Ke2 b5 {With this incredible resource, the black knight will receive a helping hand from the pawns.} 19. dxc6 bxc4 20. Ba4 Nb3 {The knight escapes!} 21. Bxb3 cxb3 22. Ra1 Re7 23. Be3 Nd5 {The position remains very complex, but most likely, it will liquidate into something peaceful a couple of moves later.} ({After Nb5 , the game might continue: Nxe3 fxe3} 23... Rd5 24. Ra5 Rb5 {, Black gives up the extra exchange to secure the king.} 25. Rxb5 Re6 26. Rb7 Rxc6 27. Rxf7 {Rc2+ . The rook endgame is just equal.}) *

