most logical continuation also requires us to study fewer lines, which is our course's ambition.} (8... Qa6 $5 {is also interesting, but it leads to a huge fight and complex lines that you must remember flawlessly. If you wish you can study the informational variation here .}) 9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 {The position has clarified a bit – White has the bishop pair, but Black has anchored a knight on d4 , and the black king on the queenside feels pretty safe.} 11. Nc3 Qa6 {Black doesn't allow White to catch a breath and pressures the c-pawn before the white king can leave the center.} 12. Be2 {This leads to a complex game where Black must know several important tactical ideas.} Nf6 13. a3 Rhe8 {An important idea to know!} (13... Bxc3 {If you initiate trades right away, White will have the better position.} 14. Bxc3 Nxe2 ({(The line} 14... Rhe8 {no longer works.} 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. O-O {. The black pawn on d4 is weak.} Nxd5 $4 17. Bg4+ {. Oops. )}) 15. Qxe2 Rhe8 16. Rc1 {. That's the point – White doesn't have to rush with the short castle and fall under ... Nxd5 or ... Rxd5 tricks.} c6 17. dxc6 Qxc6 18. O-O {. White is slightly better due to the stronger bishop and Black's more exposed king.}) 14. axb4 {Challenge accepted!} Qxa1 15. Qxa1 Nc2+ 16. Kf1 Nxa1 17. Bd1 c6 {White was hoping to trap the black knight on a1 , but after this precise move, the position is balanced.} 18. Ba4 b5 {Same trick.} 19. cxb5 cxd5 20. Ke2 {White is almost trapping the knight...} d4 {Because of the d-pawn, Black keeps the material balance.} 21. Rxa1 dxc3 22. bxc3 Re7 23. c4 Ne4 {As seen in the game Pierre Barbot (2271) – Nad-Titus Petre (2362), Avoine op 27th 2012, the position remains balanced, but Black's priority should be trading one of White's bishops.} ({Be3 . Here's how the game might continue: Nc3+ Ke1 Nxa4 Rxa4} 23... Rc7 24. c5 Rb7 {Ra5 Rd5! Ke2 f5} 25. g3 g6 {. None of the sides can make progress.}) *

