1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. h3 {Despite that it looks pretty ridiculous, this is a very tricky move to stop any pins on g4 , thus also securing the pawn on d4 . If Black plays a typical Scandinavian Defense, you will get an unpleasant pin of the knight on c6 , or White will get to execute c4 and only then position the knight on c3 . In 2023, Igor Kovalenko faced this continuation many times online – this contains considerable venom for accelerated time control games.} Nf6 {White's ideas will work like a charm if Black will play with the typical Scandinavian approach.} (3... c5 {. We also looked at other opportunities to fight for the center.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qd8 6. Bb5 {.} ({(Also,} 6. b3 {looks interesting with some fresh positions.)}) 6... Bd7 7. O-O e6 8. Re1 Nf6 9. a4 Rc8 10. d3 {. White looks more active.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {Black might also decide to develop the queenside knight, but there are different sets of problems.} (4... Bf5 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. g4 {. White has made perfect use of the 3.h3 move.} Bg6 7. Bg2 c6 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Qe2 e6 10. Bd2 {. White is better positioned while Black struggles to determine their counterplay.}) 5. Nc3 Qd6 6. d4 {Black has committed to ... Nc6 while White has made sure there is no ... Bg4 .} Bf5 7. g4 {Another use of the move h3 .} Bg6 8. Bg2 O-O-O 9. O-O e5 (9... Nxd4 $4 {. Black can't take the pawn.} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Qe2 {, and White already has a decisive attack.}) 10. Nxe5 Nxd4 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Be3 {White's bishop pair in the open position looks pretty impressive.} c6 13. g5 Ne8 14. Ne4 {White is better.} *

