1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. h3 {Despite that it looks pretty ridiculous, this is a very tricky move to stop any pins on g4 , thus also securing the pawn on d4 . If Black plays a typical Scandinavian Defense, you will get an unpleasant pin of the knight on c6 , or White will get to execute c4 and only then position the knight on c3 . In 2023, Igor Kovalenko faced this continuation many times online – this contains considerable venom for accelerated time control games.} e5 {Probably it's best to enter the Central Game with colors reversed, where White has an extra tempo on h3 .} 4. Nf3 (4. Nc3 {. White can also start with this move order – all you must remember is a small nuance.} Qe6 5. Nf3 Bd7 $1 {. Exactly the bishop move, not the typical ... Nc6 . It transposes to the variations, had White started with 4.Nf3 .}) 4... Bd7 {This is a significant move you should remember. If the queenside knight develops first, it's necessary to avoid any pins with the typical Bb5 .} (4... Nc6 $6 {This logical move is not accurate and only leads to self-inflicted problems.} 5. Nc3 Qd6 {. A better retreat square than on e6 .} ({(} 5... Qe6 $6 {. This would be in the spirit of the old line of the Central opening, but unfortunately, here it's a big mistake.} 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. O-O O-O-O 8. Re1 {. White has positioned his pieces on the most active squares, and Black is already experiencing big problems.} Bc5 9. d3 Nf6 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 {. Comparing with the Central Game＊ – with colors reversed – the white pawn stands on h3 ; thus, Black does not have the resource 11... Ng4 12.Re1 f5 13.h3 h5 which leads to a complex position. Now Black is losing the e5 -pawn for nothing.) ✱ Note: please compare with} e4 {e5} 12. d4 {exd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3 Nf6 , Center Game: Berger Variation, Nc3 Bb4 Bd2 O-O O-O-O Re8 Bc4 d6 Nf3 Be6 Bxe6 Rxe6 Ng5 . The point we are discussing. Re8 a3 Ba5 Qg3} h6 13. h4 {.}) 6. Bc4 {. There's the problem – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. Bb5 {A sneaky move – trading the bishops allows White to activate the knight while ... Nc6 transposes to a bad line. It would help if you had something else.} a6 {Probably a fitting response to h3 in general – Black immediately solves all opening problems.} 7. Bxd7+ Nxd7 8. O-O O-O-O 9. d4 {White could attempt to open the position to exploit the minor development lead, but it doesn't work.} exd4 10. Qxd4 Ne7 {The white queen can jump to a7 and even a8 , but it's more likely that it will lead to a loss of the queen rather than checkmating Black.} 11. Ng5 Qg6 12. Qe4 Nf5 {The only move to keep the balance, but it's good enough.} 13. g4 Nd6 14. Qxg6 hxg6 15. Bf4 {White is pressing a little, but it's temporary.} Be7 16. Kg2 Bxg5 17. Bxg5 f6 {Black has achieved full equality.} *

