m – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. Bb5 {A sneaky move – trading the bishops allows White to activate the knight while ... Nc6 transposes to a bad line. It would help if you had something else.} a6 {Probably a fitting response to h3 in general – Black immediately solves all opening problems.} 7. Bxd7+ Nxd7 8. O-O O-O-O 9. Re1 {It's very logical but this also allows Black to be a little ambitious.} f5 10. d4 e4 11. d5 Qg6 {Black controls the initiative even if the position is objectively equal.} 12. Ng5 Ngf6 13. Ne6 Bd6 {A very strong exchange sacrifice that should catch White completely off-guard.} 14. Ne2 {White can accept the exchange immediately, but engines insist that this move order is slightly more accurate. From Black's perspective, nothing changes – you're looking for a kingside attack.} Nb6 15. Nxd8 Rxd8 16. Nf4 Qf7 17. Be3 Nbxd5 {Simple and good.} 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 {We can stop our analysis here and conclude that for the minimum sacrificed material, Black has a good chance to organize a successful kingside attack. Thus, you have sufficient compensation.} *

