m – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the 3.h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. Bd3 {This odd move comes with an idea to immediately pressure the e5 -pawn.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O-O 8. Re1 {Compared to Be2 , here White is immediately attacking the e5 -pawn.} f6 {... f5 would be too aggressive as Black's development is not strong enough to support it.} 9. Be4 Nge7 10. d4 {This is White's big plan.} Qf7 {And this is Black's refutation!} 11. dxe5 Bxh3 12. Qe2 Bg4 {White achieved nothing; their king looks more vulnerable than Black's.} *

