m – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. g3 {In this variation, Black has to know one more precise move. Either way, it's hard to believe that White can include both g3 and h3 in the first six moves and still get an advantage.} Nc6 7. Bg2 O-O-O 8. O-O Nd4 {Otherwise, White will continue with Re1 and perhaps play d4 themself – now this is impossible.} 9. Re1 ({Slightly more challenging than} 9. d3 {, but Black's response is straightforward.}) 9... Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Bc6 11. Qe3 {Now what?} Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Ne7 {Nice! As it turns out, Black is not obliged to defend the pawns.} 13. Qxe5 Qxe5 14. Rxe5 Nc6 {White has good practical chances to land into a worse endgame.} *

