n the first six moves and still get an advantage.} Nc6 7. Bg2 O-O-O 8. O-O Nd4 {Otherwise, White will continue with Re1 and perhaps play d4 themself – now this is impossible.} 9. Re1 ({Slightly more challenging than} 9. d3 {, but Black's response is straightforward.}) 9... Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Bc6 11. Qe3 {Now what?} Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Ne7 {Nice! As it turns out, Black is not obliged to defend the pawns.} 13. Qxa7 {What could be wrong with grabbing a free pawn that exposes the enemy king with threats to grab another?} Qc6+ 14. Kg1 Nf5 {White's problem is that Black develops a powerful initiative – Black's ... Nd4 is very difficult to counter.} 15. Ne2 Bc5 16. Qa8+ Kd7 17. Qa5 Rhe8 18. d3 b6 19. Qc3 Re6 {We can stop our analysis here – Black has too many threats, and White can't meet them all. On top of the cake is a cherry – a wonderful trick that, for White, is easy to miss.} ({b4?? is a logical move to force the queen trade, but it meets a swift end.} 19... Nxg3 $3 20. Nxg3 Bxf2+ {. White drops the queen.}) *

