m – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. g3 {In this variation, Black has to know one more precise move. Either way, it's hard to believe that White can include both g3 and h3 in the first six moves and still get an advantage.} Nc6 7. Bg2 O-O-O 8. O-O Nd4 {Otherwise, White will continue with Re1 and perhaps play d4 themself – now this is impossible.} 9. Nxd4 (9. d3 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Bc6 {. This looks pretty easy to remember – Black equalizes with no problems.}) 9... exd4 10. Re1 {White attempts to grab some free tempos, but it's not enough to claim an advantage.} Qg6 {It's important not to allow the white knight to jump to e4 . Here, it's impossible because White would immediately blunder the knight with ... f5 .} 11. Nd5 (11. Ne2 {. This is the same route for the knight, only a different execution.} Bc6 12. Nf4 Qd6 {, and we transpose to the present line with 11.Nd5 .}) 11... Bc6 12. Nf4 Qd6 13. d3 Ne7 {Black has no issues since the white knight on f4 feels awkward. Even more – White should be a little more careful because of Black's space advantage.} *

