1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. h3 {Despite that it looks pretty ridiculous, this is a very tricky move to stop any pins on g4 , thus also securing the pawn on d4 . If Black plays a typical Scandinavian Defense, you will get an unpleasant pin of the knight on c6 , or White will get to execute c4 and only then position the knight on c3 . In 2023, Igor Kovalenko faced this continuation many times online – this contains considerable venom for accelerated time control games.} e5 {Probably it's best to enter the Central Game with colors reversed, where White has an extra tempo on h3 .} 4. Nf3 (4. Nc3 {. White can also start with this move order – all you must remember is a small nuance.} Qe6 5. Nf3 Bd7 $1 {. Exactly the bishop move, not the typical ... Nc6 . It transposes to the variations, had White started with 4.Nf3 .}) 4... Bd7 {This is a significant move you should remember. If the queenside knight develops first, it's necessary to avoid any pins with the typical Bb5 .} (4... Nc6 $6 {This logical move is not accurate and only leads to self-inflicted problems.} 5. Nc3 Qd6 {. A better retreat square than on e6 .} ({(} 5... Qe6 $6 {. This would be in the spirit of the old line of the Central opening, but unfortunately, here it's a big mistake.} 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. O-O O-O-O 8. Re1 {. White has positioned his pieces on the most active squares, and Black is already experiencing big problems.} Bc5 9. d3 Nf6 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 {. Comparing with the Central Game＊ – with colors reversed – the white pawn stands on h3 ; thus, Black does not have the resource 11... Ng4 12.Re1 f5 13.h3 h5 which leads to a complex position. Now Black is losing the e5 -pawn for nothing.) ✱ Note: please compare with} e4 {e5} 12. d4 {exd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3 Nf6 , Center Game: Berger Variation, Nc3 Bb4 Bd2 O-O O-O-O Re8 Bc4 d6 Nf3 Be6 Bxe6 Rxe6 Ng5 . The point we are discussing. Re8 a3 Ba5 Qg3} h6 13. h4 {.}) 6. Bc4 {. There's the problem – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. Be2 {The main move – White is preparing the d4 push.} Nc6 7. O-O {If White includes the castling, Black will achieve equality with a different trick.} O-O-O 8. d4 Nxd4 {Best start capturing with the knight to avoid any extra options if White decides not to capture on d4 immediately.} 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Qxd4 Bb5 11. Bg4 ({A better choice than} 11. Qg4 {– Black would trade the queens and retreat with the bishop back on d7 . Here, at least, White slightly damages Black's pawn structure.}) (11. Qxa7 $2 {fails tactically:} Bxe2 12. Re1 Qa6 $1 {, and White loses a piece.}) 11... Rxd4 12. Bxe6+ fxe6 13. Nxb5 Rb4 {With this move, Black makes sure that White can't take on a7 without self-trapping the knight.} 14. a4 a6 15. Nc3 Nf6 {Unfortunately for White, just one weakness on e6 is insufficient to claim an advantage.} 16. Re1 Rb6 17. Ne2 e5 18. Kf1 Bc5 {Black is pretty safe.} *

