1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. h3 {Despite that it looks pretty ridiculous, this is a very tricky move to stop any pins on g4 , thus also securing the pawn on d4 . If Black plays a typical Scandinavian Defense, you will get an unpleasant pin of the knight on c6 , or White will get to execute c4 and only then position the knight on c3 . In 2023, Igor Kovalenko faced this continuation many times online – this contains considerable venom for accelerated time control games.} e5 {Probably it's best to enter the Central Game with colors reversed, where White has an extra tempo on h3 .} 4. Nf3 (4. Nc3 {. White can also start with this move order – all you must remember is a small nuance.} Qe6 5. Nf3 Bd7 $1 {. Exactly the bishop move, not the typical ... Nc6 . It transposes to the variations, had White started with 4.Nf3 .}) 4... Bd7 {This is a significant move you should remember. If the queenside knight develops first, it's necessary to avoid any pins with the typical Bb5 .} (4... Nc6 $6 {This logical move is not accurate and only leads to self-inflicted problems.} 5. Nc3 Qd6 {. A better retreat square than on e6 .} ({(} 5... Qe6 $6 {. This would be in the spirit of the old line of the Central opening, but unfortunately, here it's a big mistake.} 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. O-O O-O-O 8. Re1 {. White has positioned his pieces on the most active squares, and Black is already experiencing big problems.} Bc5 9. d3 Nf6 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 {. Comparing with the Central Game＊ – with colors reversed – the white pawn stands on h3 ; thus, Black does not have the resource 11... Ng4 12.Re1 f5 13.h3 h5 which leads to a complex position. Now Black is losing the e5 -pawn for nothing.) ✱ Note: please compare with} e4 {e5} 12. d4 {exd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3 Nf6 , Center Game: Berger Variation, Nc3 Bb4 Bd2 O-O O-O-O Re8 Bc4 d6 Nf3 Be6 Bxe6 Rxe6 Ng5 . The point we are discussing. Re8 a3 Ba5 Qg3} h6 13. h4 {.}) 6. Bc4 {. There's the problem – White does not even have to play the 'automatic' Bb5 and can play the position like a great Italian game.} Bf5 7. d3 {. Black got one of the worst versions of the Italian game.}) 5. Nc3 Qe6 {This is the critical moment of the h3 variation – now White has some choices to test Black.} 6. Be2 {The main move – White is preparing the d4 push.} Nc6 7. d4 {White is hoping to exploit their minor lead in development, but this means that the position is simplifying. Otherwise, White has no other ideas for fighting for an opening advantage.} Nxd4 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Qxd4 Ne7 {Basically, Black has to remember two maneuvers – first, the Bc8 - d7 move before developing the knight which pretty much forces the white bishop to position the passive square on e2 and this maneuver to kick off the white queen from targeting the a7 -square, so that you can castle the long side.} (9... Nf6 $2 {. One of those moments when standard developing moves give you only headaches.} 10. O-O Be7 11. Bf4 {, and White is much more active and holds a significant advantage.}) 10. Bg5 (10. O-O Nf5 {. No matter where the white queen will retreat – the pawn on a7 will no longer be under attack, and Black can safely castle the long side, achieving complete equality.}) 10... Nf5 ({More precise than} 10... h6 {, which will require Black to lead a more accurate defense.}) 11. Qd2 f6 12. O-O-O O-O-O ({The position feels very familiar from an old line in the Petroff Defense e4 e5 Nf3 Nf6 d4 exd4 e5 Ne4 Qxd4 d5 exd6} 12... Nd6 {.}) 13. Bf4 Bd6 {White still retains a small pressure, but with a couple of accurate moves, Black will neutralize it.} 14. Bg4 Qf7 15. Rhe1 Kb8 {Very accurate, walking away from pins and checks.} (15... g5 $6 {. There's no need to create weaknesses for your opponent.} 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 17. Nd5 Bxg4 18. hxg4 {. Suddenly, Black has serious problems.}) 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 17. Bxd7 Rxd7 {The position is completely symmetrical (both pawn structure and material balance); thus, the game should end with a draw.} *

