1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. Qf3 {Such moves can't be serious – unless you want to help White accelerate their development, basically any move for Black is good. However, you might already want to fight for privileges.} Nf6 4. Nc3 Qd8 {Oddly, this might be the best retreat for the queen, at least in the position. At least White can't target the black queen to rack up some extra tempos, and their queen on f3 stops White from getting something real.} 5. Bc4 Nc6 {This is one of those positions when it's better to play according to the current dynamics and try not to copy/paste standard Scandinavian moves. Black is immediately threatening to play ... Nd4 – this is not something that White has to deal with in normal Scandinavian positions.} 6. Nge2 Ne5 {And then there's another threat! Black gains the bishop pair.} 7. Qf4 Nxc4 8. Qxc4 a6 9. d3 e6 10. O-O Be7 {After Black will fianchetto the light-squared bishop on e7 , Black is entitled to fight for advantage.} *

