1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. d4 ({This is quite similar to} 3. Nf3 {, which we discussed in the two previous chapters ( #15 & #16 ) – White wants to get a position with d4 - c4 and Nc3 , avoiding the typical Scandinavian counterplay against the pawn on d4 .}) 3... Nc6 ({More accurate than the immediate} 3... e5 {.}) 4. Be3 e5 {Black's approach is the same.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Qd2 {Walking into a pin can't be a good idea – Black is not obliged to take on c3 .} Qa5 {Suddenly, White should realize that the queen on d2 is misplaced.} 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Nge2 O-O-O 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. O-O {White has seemingly escorted the king to safety, but Black's pressure on the d4 -pawn remains, along with the advantage of the two bishops.} Ne7 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 {This was played in a classical game Pavel Tregubov (2609) – Stefán Kristjánsson (2458), EU-Cup 23rd Kemer 2007. Here, Black had an easy way to secure a large advantage.} Qxc3 13. bxc3 Nf5 {Black has a massive advantage in the upcoming endgame.} *

