1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. d4 ({This is quite similar to} 3. Nf3 {, which we discussed in the two previous chapters ( #15 & #16 ) – White wants to get a position with d4 - c4 and Nc3 , avoiding the typical Scandinavian counterplay against the pawn on d4 .}) 3... Nc6 ({More accurate than the immediate} 3... e5 {.}) 4. Nf3 {The main move. Black has to continue aggressively; otherwise, White will punish the ... Nc6 move.} Bg4 {Under normal circumstances, this would be a reasonable choice, hoping that the position will transpose to the variations of the previous chapter. Unfortunately, this will require you to show much more accuracy than White needs, which is not in the spirit of our repertoire.} 5. Nc3 ({If White plays} 5. Be2 O-O-O 6. Be3 e5 {, we transpose to a variation from the previous chapter.}) 5... Qh5 6. d5 O-O-O 7. Be2 e5 {If you're a big fan of engine lines, here's what they suggest as an option.} 8. Bd2 Nb4 9. O-O Nf6 10. Nxe5 (10. h3 {is also possible.} Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Qg6 12. a3 Nbxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Re1 {. White is down a pawn, but the bishop pair gives them full compensation.}) 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Qxe2 12. Nxe2 Re8 13. Nxf7 {White has to accept the forcing sequence.} Rxe2 14. Bxb4 Bxb4 15. Nxh8 Bc5 {In an endgame where White has an extra exchange and two pawns, but Black is the one who is pushing something – somebody would call this interesting.} 16. b4 Bxb4 17. Nf7 Ne4 18. h4 Bc5 19. Ng5 Nd2 20. Rae1 Bxf2+ 21. Rxf2 Rxe1+ 22. Kh2 Nf1+ 23. Kh3 Ne3 {It somehow ends with a draw.} *

