1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. d4 ({This is quite similar to} 3. Nf3 {, which we discussed in the two previous chapters ( #15 & #16 ) – White wants to get a position with d4 - c4 and Nc3 , avoiding the typical Scandinavian counterplay against the pawn on d4 .}) 3... Nc6 ({More accurate than the immediate} 3... e5 {.}) 4. Nf3 {The main move. Black has to continue aggressively; otherwise, White will punish the ... Nc6 move.} Bg4 {Under normal circumstances, this would be a reasonable choice, hoping that the position will transpose to the variations of the previous chapter. Unfortunately, this will require you to show much more accuracy than White needs, which is not in the spirit of our repertoire.} 5. Nc3 ({If White plays} 5. Be2 O-O-O 6. Be3 e5 {, we transpose to a variation from the previous chapter.}) 5... Qh5 6. d5 O-O-O 7. Be2 e6 {It makes perfect sense.} (7... e5 $5 {. If you're a big fan of engine lines, you might take a look at this informational line .}) (7... Bxf3 $6 {. There's another idea you should be aware of.} 8. Bxf3 Qe5+ 9. Be3 e6 10. O-O Nf6 {. Just as when it seems that Black has accomplished something, White can sacrifice his queen!} 11. dxc6 Rxd1 12. cxb7+ Kb8 13. Rfxd1 Bc5 14. Rd3 {. Black's position is very dangerous.}) 8. Ng5 {But now starts a forcing line where Black is holding, which would require some high precision.} Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 Ne5 {The only move not to lose.} 11. dxe6 f6 {Another only move.} 12. Bf4 {This forces Black to solve more problems.} (12. Nf7 Nxf7 13. exf7 Ne7 {. White can't keep the extra pawn on f7 and Black eventually will equalize.} 14. Be3 Nc6 15. Rhd1 Be7 {. With equality.}) 12... Ng6 {Quite a difficult move, but the alternative might not be better.} ({Black might attempt to liquidate into an endgame immediately} 12... fxg5 {, but there's no clear path to equality.} 13. Bxe5 Re8 14. Rhe1 Rxe6 15. Kf1 Nf6 16. Nb5 $1 {As you can see, White is still creating problems.} Bc5 17. Nxc7 Rc6 18. Nb5 a6 19. Nd4 Bxd4 20. Bxd4 Rxc2 {. Black is holding on but barely.} 21. Rad1 Re8 22. Rxe8+ Nxe8 {. White keeps pressing in the endgame.}) 13. Bxc7 Re8 {More accurate than taking on c7 or g5 .} 14. Nf7 Rxe6+ 15. Kd2 Kxc7 {Black keeps fighting to keep the balance in a complex endgame, but for White, it's much easier to play, no matter the time control. We leave it up to you to decide whether it's worth it. We don't think so.} *

