1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. d4 ({This is quite similar to} 3. Nf3 {, which we discussed in the two previous chapters ( #15 & #16 ) – White wants to get a position with d4 - c4 and Nc3 , avoiding the typical Scandinavian counterplay against the pawn on d4 .}) 3... Nc6 ({More accurate than the immediate} 3... e5 {.}) 4. Nf3 {The main move. Black has to continue aggressively; otherwise, White will punish the ... Nc6 move.} e5 {The simplest and most solid continuation. There's a fair chance that we might still transpose into something from the previous chapter.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 Bxc3 {All these moves are pretty forced until this point.} 7. bxc3 {This is not a good choice for many reasons, starting with the simple fact – Black can collect the free pawn on d4 . It would give White the bishop pair, and perhaps this is what White is hoping for, but there are other good moves as well.} Nge7 {Black is also toying with the ... e4 push so that afterward, you can block White's weak squares on the queenside with moves like ... Na5 and ... Be6 .} 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Bf5 {Stronger than capturing back the pawn on e5 – now White experiences some real problems to complete the development.} 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Qxd5 Nxd5 {Black is calling the shots.} *

