1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {In this chapter we will have a closer look at rare continuations on 3rd move.} 3. d4 ({This is quite similar to} 3. Nf3 {, which we discussed in the two previous chapters ( #15 & #16 ) – White wants to get a position with d4 - c4 and Nc3 , avoiding the typical Scandinavian counterplay against the pawn on d4 .}) 3... Nc6 ({More accurate than the immediate} 3... e5 {.}) 4. Nf3 {The main move. Black has to continue aggressively; otherwise, White will punish the ... Nc6 move.} e5 {The simplest and most solid continuation. There's a fair chance that we might still transpose into something from the previous chapter.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 Bxc3 {All these moves are pretty forced until this point.} 7. Bxc3 e4 8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ne7 {This endgame has been tested in practice many times – White has nothing here, although they enjoy the bishop pair. White has three main continuations to continue testing Black.} 10. Qxd5 {White can trade queens immediately – then they must move the bishop.} Nxd5 11. Bd4 Be6 {The simplest of all choices – Black wants to castle long and then consider both ... Nb4 or ... Nf4 moves for some tactical tricks.} 12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. a3 {White can take the pawn on a7 , but then after ... Nb4 , Black will immediately win it back.} Nf4 14. g3 Nd3+ {Nice little trick that works from the b4 -square as well – Black gets rid of White's bishop pair.} 15. Bxd3 Rxd4 {With equality, but the pawn on e5 feels more vulnerable than the pawn on e4 .} *

