1. e4 d5 {In the final chapter of the course (which also will be the shortest in terms of size) let's have a look what to do if your opponent declines the Scandinavian.} 2. e5 {This continuation might seem more like the product of a mouse-slip online than a conscious choice.} c5 {Cutting off the support for the e5 -pawn.} 3. c3 Nc6 4. d4 a6 {Black gets either a perfect French Defense position or a variation from Advance Caro-Kann where they executed the ... c5 push in one go.} 5. Be2 ({This might be a more cautious move than the immediate} 5. Nf3 {, avoiding any potential pins on g4 .}) 5... Bf5 6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O Bg6 {Black plays a safe variation of the Caro-Kann with an extra tempo, meaning Black easily has equalized the game.} 8. a3 c4 {Black transfers the weight to the c3 -pawn. Trading on d4 also makes sense.} 9. Nbd2 Nh6 {A typical French Defense maneuver to avoid blocking own dark-squared bishop. Often, Black even allows White to take on h6 , even if in ruins Black's pawn structure on the kingside.} 10. g3 Be7 11. Ne1 Nf5 {Black's plan on the queenside is straightforward.} *

