1. e4 d5 {In the final chapter of the course (which also will be the shortest in terms of size) let's have a look what to do if your opponent declines the Scandinavian.} 2. e5 {This continuation might seem more like the product of a mouse-slip online than a conscious choice.} c5 {Cutting off the support for the e5 -pawn.} 3. c3 Nc6 4. d4 a6 {Black gets either a perfect French Defense position or a variation from Advance Caro-Kann where they executed the ... c5 push in one go.} 5. Nf3 (5. dxc5 Nxe5 {. White's pawn on c5 is weak; thus, one can't deny Black's advantage.}) 5... cxd4 ({Probably a little more accurate than the immediate} 5... Bg4 {since White might change their mind and capture on c5 , which is one of the core ideas against the Advance Caro-Kann Variation when Black plays 3...c5 . Then again, if Black starts with Bg4 , this gives you the option to transfer the weight of the position to the pawn on c3 with c4 and the eventual pawn march on the queenside. Either way, this is fine for Black.}) 6. cxd4 Bg4 7. Be3 e6 8. Nbd2 {White has secured the center to avoid losing a pawn, but Black has complete freedom to continue.} Bb4 ({Also} 8... Nh6 {with} 9. Z0 Be7 {to follow looks logical, offering White to take on h6 .}) 9. Be2 Nge7 10. O-O Bxd2 {A typical trade for the Caro-Kann structures – Black willingly trades the dark-squared bishop to have more space for the remaining minor pieces, but White can't exploit the weakened dark squares.} 11. Qxd2 Qa5 12. Qd3 O-O {Black has an easy game.} *

