1. e4 d5 {In the final chapter of the course (which also will be the shortest in terms of size) let's have a look what to do if your opponent declines the Scandinavian.} 2. d4 {Coffee chess works only in bullet.} dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 g6 {This is the strongest setup – you build a brick wall around your king, at the same time pressuring the d4 -pawn. The light-squared bishop will enter the game when the timing is right.} 6. Bc4 {If White is ultra-aggressive, this will work against them.} Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qe1 Nc6 9. Qh4 Bg4 {By just making normal developing moves, Black is faster at creating threats.} 10. Be3 e6 {White needs some good advice to avoid crashing and burning right after the opening. However, even with the most precise play, White's position might already be beyond saving.} 11. Ne5 Bf5 12. Rad1 Bxc2 {There are other good moves as well – this forces things.} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bg5 {All chips in the middle.} Bxd1 15. Nxd1 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qxf6 {Sadly, White has no choice; otherwise... Kg7 is incoming.} Qxf6 18. Rxf6 Rad8 {Black has a material advantage in a simple endgame.} *

