1. e4 d5 {In the final chapter of the course (which also will be the shortest in terms of size) let's have a look what to do if your opponent declines the Scandinavian.} 2. Nc3 {If, for some reason, White doesn't want to take the pawn on d5 , this is the best alternative.} dxe4 {The easiest move, avoiding unnecessary complications.} (2... d4 {. You can also aim for a more complex fight.} 3. Nce2 e5 {. Even though this objectively is the strongest continuation, this might not be the best choice for club-level players. There are several reasons: the position is not easy to understand, and what are the right choices? You will have to calculate too many complex lines, which is probably the most important thing – there is too much unnecessary theory in a sideline that will occur rarely. The rule of a simplistic approach for an opening theory is to avoid unnecessary variations where you don't need them, and better focus on simple continuations with clear plans.}) 3. Nxe4 Nc6 (3... Qd5 $5 {. If you feel your opponent wants to avoid the mainstream theory of the Scandinavian Defense, it might be a good idea to taunt them with this unusual move!} 4. Nc3 {. Everything else for White is much weaker.} Qa5 {, and we're back to the main lines !   Many players are genuinely afraid to meet the Scandinavian.}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {We're playing a version of the Tartakower variation from the Caro-Kann. The difference is that we've avoided the unnecessary move ... c6 , and substituted it with an active developing move.} 6. Bb5 Qd5 7. Qe2+ Be7 8. O-O Bg4 {You might even want to take on f3 and ruin your opponent's pawn structure.} 9. d4 a6 10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 11. Re1 Qe6 12. Qd3 Qd7 {The position remains equal, but there's a good chance that, as soon as White finishes development, they will run out of good moves. The position is balanced.   Congratulations – you made it to the very end of the theoretical part!} *

