1. e4 d5 {While writing the theoretical part for the course, Igor Kovalenko played several Scandinavian Defense games at correspondence level – this is one of the results!} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4 {This is one of the most dangerous ideas, analyzed in depth in Chapter 2 .} Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O ({The modern move – the alternative} 12. Rh3 {is slowly becoming extinct.}) 12... Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6 15. a4 {White says that castling long will have consequences – it would be dangerous to prove otherwise!} g6 (15... O-O 16. h6 g6 {is the recommended move order in the course, but it doesn't matter.}) 16. h6 O-O 17. Qf3 {White threatens Bb5 to remove the knight on d7 guarding the f6 -square.} a6 18. c3 Qd8 19. Kg2 (19. g5 {leads to a very complex engine-like game. Humans don't play like that unless they're 2800+.} f6 20. Qg4 Qe7 21. f4 e5 $1 {. Black is fighting for some serious counterplay.} 22. fxe5 fxe5 23. Bd2 e4 24. Rae1 Rae8 25. Be2 {. It might seem that White has a serious positional advantage, but...} e3 $1 26. Bc1 Rf5 $1 27. Rxf5 gxf5 28. Qxf5 Bg3 29. Qxd5+ ({(} 29. Rf1 Bf2+ 30. Kg2 Qd6 31. Rxf2 Rf8 $1 {. Black wins the queen, but White has enough material.} 32. Qxf8+ Nxf8 33. Bxe3 Qe6 34. Bd2 Ng6 35. Kg3 Qe4 36. Bf3 Qd3 37. Kg4 Qc4 38. Bg2 b5 39. Bf4 Qc8+ 40. Kg3 Qe6 {, and the game most likely will end in a draw.)}) 29... Kh8 30. Rf1 Bf2+ {. White has two extra pawns, but the engines say the position is equal. Black's counterplay is sufficient.} 31. Kh2 Qf8 $1 32. Kh3 ({(} 32. Qf3 Qe7 {)}) 32... Qe7 33. b3 Rg8 34. Ba3 $1 Qd8 35. Rxf2 exf2 36. Kh4 {. The cosmic lines continue.} Qe8 $1 37. Qf3 Qe6 38. Qxf2 Qd5 39. Qe3 Qh1+ 40. Kg3 Nf6 41. Bf3 Qxh6 42. Bc1 Qg6 {. And as you probably guessed, it will be somehow equal in the end.} 43. Qe5 h6 44. Kh4 hxg5+ 45. Bxg5 Qh7+ 46. Kg3 Qh6 47. Kf4 Qh2+ 48. Kf5 Qh3+ 49. Kxf6 Qxf3+ 50. Ke6+ Rg7 51. Bf6 Qc6+ 52. Qd6 Qe4+ 53. Be5 Kh7 {, with an unbelievable draw.}) 19... Qe7 {Black has a nasty threat – to play ... f5 and push it to f4 . It's difficult for White to properly evaluate the position, while Black charges forward and hopes for the best.} 20. Bf4 {A human move – White trades the dark-squared bishop to keep some positional pressure.} (20. Re1 f5 21. g5 f4 22. Qg4 e5 {That's the big idea – Black's initiative on the kingside starts to look pretty serious.} 23. f3 Rae8 24. Bd2 Qf7 25. Kh1 Re7 26. Re2 Rfe8 27. Rae1 Nf8 28. dxe5 {. Ultimately, the pressure at some point has to be released.} Rxe5 29. Rxe5 Rxe5 30. Rxe5 Bxe5 31. Bc2 Nd7 {With quite a wild endgame.}) 20... e5 {This starts a forcing sequence that leads Black to a slightly worse but holdable endgame.} (20... Bxf4 21. Qxf4 Qf6 22. Qe3 {. The problem with this plan is that Black's counterplay now looks less convincing, while White is threatening to squeeze Black completely. Better keep as much tension on the board as possible.}) 21. dxe5 Nxe5 22. Qg3 (22. Qxd5 {. White can accept the pawn, but only allows Black to activate the rook.} Rad8 23. Bxe5 Bxe5 24. Qf3 Qg5 {It doesn't feel that Black is risking anything here.} 25. Rae1 Qf4 26. Qxf4 Bxf4 27. Bc4 Rd2 {, with a friendly handshake soon.}) 22... Nxd3 23. Bxd6 Qe4+ 24. Kg1 Rfe8 {Both kings are exposed.} 25. Rfd1 Nxb2 26. Re1 Qd3 {Accepting two rooks for a queen with such a weak king would be dangerous for Black.} 27. Qf4 g5 {The only move, but it's enough.} 28. Qxg5+ Qg6 29. Qxg6+ fxg6 30. Reb1 Nc4 31. Bg3 b6 {The dust has settled – White is slightly better, but Black has an excellent counterplay due to the multiple pawn weaknesses.} 32. Rb4 Rac8 ({The variation starting with} 32... Re4 {also leads to a draw:} 33. Rd1 Rxg4 34. Rxd5 a5 35. Rbb5 Ne3 $1 36. Rd4 Rxd4 37. cxd4 Nf5 38. Bc7 Nxh6 39. Bxb6 Ra6 40. Bc7 Ra7 41. Bb6 Ra6 42. d5 Kf7 43. Bc5 Nf5 44. Kg2 g5 45. Kf3 h5 46. Ke4 Rf6 47. Rxa5 h4 {.}) 33. Rd1 Rc5 34. f3 Re6 35. Bf2 Ra5 {With an equal position.} *

