[GameId "2174210256827594"]

1. e4 d5 {Aryan Tari is highly regarded as a strong chess theoretician thus it was interesting to see, how a world class player would meet the Scandinavian Defense, albeit this was only a rapid game.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 {Unsurprisingly, Aryan went for one of the most principled choices.} e6 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 g6 {This is another move order that most likely will get you to the variations of Chapter 2 . There are some nuances – White might not be obliged to close the kingside just yet and meet Black's ... gxh5 with g5 . We think it makes more sense to start with a developing move ... Bd6 and keep the idea of ... g6 for later.} 15. h6 Bd6 16. Qf3 a6 {Too slow, but this goes unpunished. Black should have decided to castle; either way works fine, but we recommend a long castle.} 17. c3 {The cautious choice, keeping all the position pluses. However, the position might require a more dynamic choice.} (17. c4 $1 {looks a little more logical.} dxc4 {. The black king is still in the center and also the b-pawn is under attack.} 18. Bxc4 {.}) 17... O-O 18. Bd2 Qd8 {Now Black gets to carry out some typical kingside attack ideas. To start, ... Qh4 is a problem.} 19. Kg2 Qe7 20. Rae1 Rae8 {The engine favors White's position, but Black's ideas are simple, while White's moves are much more complex. Black is looking for ideas like creating the battery of the queen and bishop, the ... e5 break or the ... f5 break, pushing the f-pawn as far as f4 , maybe even f3 .} 21. Qh3 Qd8 22. f4 b5 {It's interesting to play the position as Carlsbad structure, but it made sense to reroute the knight to e4 since White has committed to f4 .} (22... Nf6 23. b3 ({(} 23. g5 Nd7 {would lock the kingside for good. )}) 23... Ne4 {. This is not a forcing move, and probably Black can pick a better moment, but we will show this just to illustrate the idea.} 24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Rxe4 f5 26. gxf5 Rxf5 27. Rfe1 Ref8 {. Black has counterplay on the kingside, but the engine is unimpressed. Probably you can improve the timing for ... Ne4 .}) (22... f5 $6 23. g5 b5 24. a4 bxa4 25. c4 $1 {. Black is not in time to reroute his knight to e4 .}) 23. a3 ({A positional inaccuracy – White had to keep the c4 break as an option and play} 23. b3 {. White reacted to the ... b5 push as per the typical Carlsbad plan, but the thing is – this is not your typical Carlsbad!}) 23... Qb8 (23... f5 24. g5 Nb6 {. This deserved attention, almost inevitably bringing the knight to e4 . Now, it's obvious that White's earlier a3 doesn't help them.}) 24. Qf3 Qd8 25. Kh3 Qa8 26. Re2 Qc6 {Probably around here, both players were in a time scramble as they were shuffling the pieces here and there.} 27. Be1 Qa8 28. Bg3 Qc6 29. Rfe1 Qa8 30. Qf2 Qb8 31. Qh2 Qa8 32. Re3 Qb8 33. Kg2 Qa8 34. R1e2 Qc8 35. Kf1 Qa8 36. Ke1 Qd8 37. Kd1 Nb6 {Black loses his cool.} (37... Nf6 {, and Black is still rock solid.}) 38. f5 {Finally, White decided to strike first.} Bxg3 39. Qxg3 exf5 40. gxf5 Rxe3 41. Rxe3 Qf6 {White has a large advantage, but it's not easy to convert in a time scramble.} 42. Kc2 g5 43. Qh2 Kh8 44. Qc7 Rg8 45. Re7 Rf8 46. Qb7 (46. Qe5 Qxe5 47. dxe5 {was winning on the spot.}) 46... g4 47. Re2 Qxh6 48. Qxa6 g3 49. Qxb5 Qf6 50. Qc5 Rg8 {Black is suddenly rolling the pawns forward!} 51. Rg2 h5 52. Qc7 h4 53. Qf4 Qg5 {The tables had completely turned, and Black was winning.} 54. Qe5+ f6 55. Qe6 Nc4 56. Kb1 Ne3 57. Rg1 g2 58. Be2 h3 59. Qd6 Nxf5 60. Qc7 Ng3 61. Bd3 f5 62. Qe5+ Qg7 63. Qf4 Qf6 64. Qf3 Qh6 65. Qxd5 h2 66. Qxg2 hxg1=Q+ 67. Qxg1 {Black did not win this.} Qh1 68. Qxh1+ Nxh1 69. Bxf5 Kg7 70. a4 Kf6 71. Be4 Nf2 72. Bd5 Rd8 73. c4 Nd3 74. b3 Nb4 75. Bb7 Rd7 76. Ba8 Rxd4 77. Kb2 Ke5 78. a5 Rd7 79. Ka3 Nc2+ 80. Ka4 Kd4 81. Bc6 Rc7 82. Kb5 Kc3 83. Kb6 Re7 84. a6 Nb4 85. a7 Rxa7 86. Kxa7 Nxc6+ 87. Kb6 Nd4 88. c5 Kxb3 89. c6 Nxc6 {A crazy game!} *

