1. e4 d5 {Viktor Láznička is a great positional player and a Caro-Kann practicioner and also has played his fair share of Scandinavian Defense.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6 15. a4 Qd8 {We decided to include this game in the Model games because of Láznička's interesting approach.} 16. Kg2 Qe7 17. a5 a6 18. c3 {White has a considerable space advantage on the queenside, and it feels precarious for Black to castle long, so a short castle makes more sense. And yet, here Láznička tries something else.} g6 19. h6 f5 {This is a fascinating move order! Notice that Black has not castled either way – the threat is to play ... fxg4 – what should White do?} 20. f4 {White immediately made a mistake.} (20. g5 f4 21. Qg4 O-O {. Black threatens the typical kingside attack while White has fixed some pawns on the queenside. You can sense White's hesitation to play here.} 22. Bd2 f3+ 23. Kh1 Rae8 24. Rfe1 Bc7 {. Black has a rich game.}) 20... fxg4 21. Qxg4 Nf6 22. Qg5 Rf8 {Why castle into an attack? Castling long might be an option!} 23. Bd2 Nh5 {And Black goes for the f4 -pawn.} (23... O-O-O 24. Rae1 Qd7 {was more accurate, keeping the ... Nh5 for a better moment.}) 24. Rae1 (24. Qg4 {was the only move to keep the game balanced.}) 24... Nxf4+ 25. Bxf4 Rxf4 26. Qxe7+ Kxe7 27. Rxf4 Bxf4 {Black won a pawn and eventually the entire game.} 28. c4 Kf6 29. Rf1 Kg5 30. Re1 dxc4 31. Bxc4 Rd8 32. Rxe6 Rxd4 33. b3 Rd7 34. Kf3 Bd6 35. Re4 Kxh6 {The second pawn falls; now it's a matter of technique.} 36. Rd4 Kg5 37. b4 h5 38. b5 axb5 39. Bxb5 Rf7+ 40. Kg2 Bc7 41. a6 bxa6 42. Bxa6 Rf6 43. Bc8 Bf4 44. Bd7 Rb6 45. Re4 Rd6 46. Bc8 Rd2+ 47. Kf1 Rd8 48. Rc4 Rf8 49. Kg2 Kh4 50. Rc3 Rd8 51. Rh3+ Kg5 52. Rc3 Be5 53. Rc6 Kf4 54. Rc4+ Ke3 55. Rc2 g5 56. Be6 g4 57. Ra2 Rd4 58. Ra5 Kf4 59. Rc5 Rd2+ 60. Kf1 h4 61. Ke1 Rd6 62. Bxg4 Bd4 *

