1. e4 d5 {This is another correspondence game Igor Kovalenko played to test the written analysis during the course creation.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 {The importance of the move order is described in Chapter 4 .} 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. Bb3 {White is tricky – he wants to find some pluses by changing the move order and at the same time not mix up something himself.} e6 (9... h5 $6 {. Sadly, Black can't keep the light-squared bishop alive against the Nh4 threat without seriously risking material, but maybe this idea will help you once in a while} 10. O-O-O e6 {. Black has kept the light-squared bishop, but now is falling behind in development – White should be looking for ways to punish this.} ({a. d5! . Very strong. cxd5 Nd4!} 10... Bh7 {Ndb5 Qc6} 11. Bf4 $1 {. White has a powerful initiative.} Kd8 {. The only move!} 12. Rhe1 {. With a powerful attack for White. None of the pieces are traded, but the black king is already walking. Objectively, this can't end well. Bb4 Rd4 Bxc3 Nxc3} Nc5 {The best that Black can do – trade off some attacking pieces.} 13. Bg5 Nxb3+ 14. axb3 Bg6 15. Qe5 Kd7 {Red1! Ng4} 16. Qe2 Kc8 $1 17. b4 a6 18. Nd5 {There comes the blow. exd5 Rxd5} Kb8 19. h3 {Re8 Qd2 Qxc2+ . No choice. Qxc2} Bxc2 20. Kxc2 {Nxf2 Bf4+} Ka7 21. Rf1 {Re2+ Rd2 Rxd2+ Bxd2} Rc8 22. Kb3 {Nd3 Rxf7 . Black made a lot of only moves to stay in the game, but the endgame remains complicated.})) ({b. Nh4 . White can also go for the f-pawn push, but Black keeps enough dynamic chances. Bh7 f4} 9... O-O-O {f5 . Picking up this idea for White might not be very obvious. Re8 fxe6 fxe6 That's a weak pawn, but Black is about to push it forward.} 10. Be6 {. Challenge accepted. Bg8 d5} {( Bxd7+ Qxd7 Qf2 Ng4 . White is slightly better, but Black has the bishop pair.)} Nd5 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {Qf2 Bh7 Qxa7 Bd6} 12. Nxd5 cxd5 {Nf3 Re4 . Black has compensation for the pawn, the question is – is it sufficient?}) 10. Nh4 (10. O-O-O Bb4) 10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 {Not an accurate move order, since it gives Black more options, like not being forced to castle long.} (11. O-O-O {!} O-O-O 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. h4 {. We analyze this in a few variations in Chapter 3 .}) 11... hxg6 12. g3 (12. O-O-O Rxh2 $1 {. Black can accept the pawn – the lines are complex, but Black is doing alright.} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Kd8 15. Rhe1 Rh8 16. Bg5 Bb4 17. d5 Kc8 {. With perfect play, the game will end with a perpetual check.}) ({If} 12. h4 {, Black can play} Bb4 {.}) 12... Bb4 (12... a5 {This idea looks very similar to what was played in the game.} 13. O-O-O Bb4 14. a3 Bxc3 15. Bxc3 O-O 16. Kb1 b5 {Black threatens to open the queenside.} 17. Bd2 Qb7 18. Qf3 Rfb8 19. Ba2 b4 20. a4 {. White has to keep it closed.} c5 21. Qxb7 Rxb7 22. Be3 Ng4 23. d5 {. The only reasonable thing that White can do.} Nxe3 24. fxe3 e5 25. d6 Rd8 26. Rd5 b3 $1 {. A fantastic idea.} 27. Bxb3 Rb4 28. Ka1 Rdb8 29. h3 f6 30. Ba2 Rxa4 31. Kb1 Kh7 {. The position remains double-edged, but Black's chances are not worse.}) 13. O-O-O (13. h4 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 a5 {. White's bishops on the queenside start to experience some discomfort.} 15. a4 O-O 16. O-O-O b5 17. h5 bxa4 18. Bxa4 gxh5 {. Both players are racing to the attack, but Black's chances are not worse.}) 13... a5 (13... Bxc3 {. This also looks interesting. To show you some lines, White has no advantage, and it's a game with three possible results.} 14. Bxc3 O-O 15. Kb1 ({(} 15. Rhe1 a5 16. a3 b5 17. Bd2 Rfc8 18. Kb1 Qb6 19. Ba2 c5 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21. Be3 Qc6 {)}) ({(} 15. h4 a5 16. h5 gxh5 17. Rxh5 Nxh5 18. Qxh5 Nf6 19. Qh4 Nd5 20. Rh1 f6 21. Bd2 b5 {)}) 15... a5 16. a3 b5 17. Bd2 Rfc8 {, and Black is attacking.}) 14. d5 {This looks very similar to a line from Chapter 3, but White has committed to g3 . This leads to a complex fight but not an advantage.} (14. Bf4 $5 Qc8 15. d5 Nc5 $1 {. A precise and not very difficult choice after which White can't find any hope for an initiative.} 16. dxe6 Nxb3+ 17. axb3 ({(} 17. cxb3 Qxe6 18. Rhe1 Qxe2 19. Rxe2+ Kf8 20. h4 Re8 {)}) 17... Qxe6 18. Qxe6+ fxe6 {. Black's kingside pawn structure is slightly worse, but it's not enough for White to claim an advantage.} 19. f3 Nd5 20. Be5 a4 $5 {For some excitement!} 21. Nxa4 b5 22. Nc3 Rh5 $1 23. Bxg7 Kf7 {. Black unexpectedly takes over the game.} 24. g4 Kxg7 25. gxh5 Nxc3 26. Rd7+ Kf8 27. Kd2 Ne4+ 28. Ke2 Nf6 29. Rc7 Nxh5 {,with great winning chances.}) 14... Bxc3 15. Bxc3 cxd5 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 O-O {The position clarifies – both players are looking for a direct attack against the enemy king.} 18. Rd4 (18. Rb5 a4 19. a3 Qc6 20. Re1 Nf6 21. Rb4 Nd5 22. Rc4 Qd7 23. Rd4 Qc6 {, and Black is safe.}) 18... Nb6 19. Rhd1 Nd5 20. Be1 {With such a strong knight on d5 , Black has an easy game, while White will have to play energetically not to be worse.} a4 21. a3 (21. Kb1 Rfc8 22. c4 Nf6 {is good for Black.}) 21... Rfc8 22. h4 Qc6 23. Kb1 b5 24. g4 (24. f4 Ra7) 24... Ra7 25. f4 Rac7 26. c3 {Black forces White to play c2 - c3 to weaken the light squares. Also, if the black knight departs from d5 , the white bishop can't reach the c3 -square.} Qe8 (26... Rd7 27. h5 gxh5 28. gxh5 Nf6 $1 29. Rxd7 ({(} 29. Bf2 Rxd4 30. Bxd4 Qe4+ 31. Qxe4 Nxe4 32. Rg1 f6 33. h6 g6 34. Rxg6+ Kh7 35. Rg7+ Kxh6 36. Rb7 Kh5 37. Rxb5+ Kg4 38. Rb4 Ra8 {)}) 29... Nxd7 30. h6 Nc5 $1 {. Now it's quite clear why it was such a good idea to provoke White to play c2-c3 .} 31. Qg4 Qe4+ 32. Ka2 Qc4+ 33. Ka1 ({(} 33. Kb1 Qe4+ {)}) 33... Nb3+ 34. Kb1 Qe4+ 35. Ka2 Qg6 36. Qf3 Qxh6 37. Bf2 {.}) 27. h5 gxh5 28. gxh5 Rc4 29. Rxc4 bxc4 30. h6 g6 31. Qf3 Kh7 32. Bh4 {The game finished in a draw.} *

