1. e4 d5 {And another correspondence game by Igor!} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. O-O-O e6 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. Bb3 {This is the recommendation of Anish Giri – this could be the most dangerous plan for Black in this setup.} O-O-O {The problem for Black is that now there's less room for flexibility, and the long castle is necessary.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. g3 (13. h4 {is also decent, all analyzed in Chapter 4 .}) 13... Nb6 {For starters, White needs to protect the pawn.} (13... Bd6 $6 {This 'obvious' move is unnecessary.} 14. h4 Rh5 $6 {The rook has no business here.} 15. Bg5 {White achieved a big advantage in Rauf Mamedov (2654) – Ethan Saya (2230) Ville d'Orsay online Blitz Europe Échecs INT 2021.}) 14. Bf4 ({A.} 14. Ne4 Nxe4 ({(} 14... Rxd4 $4 {. You can't take it.} 15. Ng5 Rd7 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Bxd6 Rxd6 18. Rxd6 {As seen in Aleksander Miśta (2598) – Beata Andrejczuk (2088) POL-ch rapid Zgierz 2017, Black can resign. )}) 15. Qxe4 c5 {It's necessary to seek counterplay.} ({(} 15... Nd5 {. Anchoring the knight makes sense, but White is slightly better. Unless...} 16. c4 $2 Nf6 {...White had unexpected problems with the central pawn in Francesco Agnelli (2132) – Claudio Popa (2057) Cortina d'Ampezzo op 1st 2003. )}) 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. h4 Rd7 18. Qf3 Qc6 19. Qxc6+ bxc6 20. Rhf1 Rhd8 {. White is slightly better, but Black's game is easy.}) ({B.} 14. Bg5 Be7 ({(} 14... Rd7 15. h4 a6 16. Kb1 Kb8 17. Qf3 Be7 18. g4 Nfd5 19. Ne2 {, and White keeps pressing. )}) 15. h4 Kb8 {.}) 14... Bd6 15. Bg5 {White does not want to trade the bishops.} Rd7 16. h4 {This is one of the most typical setups for White – Black needs to figure out a plan.} a6 {Black waits and prepares the ... c5 push.} (16... Nfd5 $4 17. Ne4) 17. Rd3 Kb8 18. a3 (18. Rhd1 Ka8 19. Kb1 Be7 20. a3 Rhd8 21. Na2 c5 22. dxc5 Rxd3 23. Rxd3 Nbd7 24. Bf4 Qc8 25. Bd6 Nxc5 26. Bxe7 Rxd3 27. Bxc5 Rxb3 28. Bb4 Rxb4 29. Nxb4 Nd7) 18... Ka8 {It's a good idea to bring the king as far away from the center as possible since you will be pushing ... c5 .} (18... Be7 19. Rhd1 Rhd8 20. Bf4 Bd6 21. Bd2 Be7 {. White seemingly can't make any progress without trades.} 22. Ne4 Nxe4 23. Qxe4 Nc8 {Black is rock solid.}) 19. Kb1 Be7 20. Re1 Rhd8 {Everything is ready, and Black is already aiming for the ... c5 push.} 21. Rf3 {White sets a trap and offers to take the d4 -pawn for free. It's safe to say that most humans will defend the d-pawn by doubling the rooks.} (21. Bf4 Bd6 ({(} 21... Qc8 22. Be5 c5 23. dxc5 Qxc5 24. f4 Rxd3 25. cxd3 Qa5 26. Rc1 Ne8 27. Ne4 Qb5 28. Bc4 Qd7 {. This is probably also playable – Black seems to be safe. )}) 22. Bc1 Be7 23. Red1 c5 24. dxc5 Bxc5 25. Rxd7 Rxd7 26. Bd2 Nc8 {, Black has a decent game.}) 21... Rxd4 {A principled choice – Black doesn't want to sit in a passive defense. It is not a forced choice – Black can still execute the ... c5 break.} 22. Bf4 Rxf4 (22... Qc8 23. Be3) 23. Rxf4 c5 {If White attempts to hold on to the extra exchange, Black will have sufficient compensation. Instead, White tries to give back the material and fight for the initiative.} 24. Ne4 e5 {Black enters a slightly worse endgame and can hold to a draw without much problems.} 25. Nxf6 exf4 26. Qxe7 Qxe7 27. Rxe7 fxg3 28. fxg3 c4 {The bishop is stronger than the knight.} 29. Bxc4 Rd1+ 30. Ka2 Nxc4 31. Ne8 Rg1 32. b3 Na5 33. Re3 Nc6 34. Rd3 Ne5 35. Rc3 Re1 36. Nxg7 Ng4 {Black arrests the white knight.} 37. Rc8+ Ka7 38. Ne8 Re3 39. Nd6 Rxg3 40. Rc7 Kb6 41. Rxf7 Ne3 42. Kb2 Rg2 43. Kc3 a5 44. a4 g5 45. hxg5 Rxg5 46. Nc8+ Kc6 47. Kd2 Nd5 48. Na7+ Kb6 49. Nb5 Rg2+ 50. Kc1 Nb4 51. Rf6+ Kc5 52. Rf5+ Kc6 53. Nd4+ Kb6 54. Rb5+ Ka6 55. Rh5 Kb6 56. Kd1 Na2 {The game continues, but the drawish outcome is obvious.} *

