1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {The 3...Qd6 Scandinavian. After a dozen moves, this game reveals ideas that can be applied in the Classical Scandinavian.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 Nbd7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qf3 c6 11. Be3 Nb6 12. O-O-O Nbd5 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 {This is a typical Scandinavian position that arose from a different variation. Igor played the game with Black against an uncomfortable opponent, and as Igor says, this is his first classical game in which he used the Scandinavian Defense against a grandmaster.} b5 {Clearly a typical move but still risky.} (14... e6 {is safer and also stronger.} 15. c4 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Be7 17. Bg2 f5 $1 {Important maneuver to know.} 18. Qc2 O-O-O {. Black is ready to meet any white pawn advances and, in an ideal scenario, push ... f4 to land the dark-squared bishop on d4 .}) 15. Bg2 e6 16. Bd2 (16. Bf4 $1 {White missed an opportunity to seize some advantage with a tactical trick.} Qd7 17. h4 Bd6 18. Be5 {. White is better.}) 16... Be7 17. f4 a5 18. Rhf1 Kd7 {Exclamation mark for the creativity!} (18... f5 $1 {. Again, this was stronger.} 19. Qe5 Kf7 {, and Black has solved all opening problems.}) 19. Qe5 (19. c3 f5 20. Qd3 {. Now Black has to waste more time to get the king to the better f7 square.} Ke8 {!} 21. Rde1 Kf7 22. Re2 Qd7 {. Nothing dramatic has happened, but White does control the initiative.} 23. Rfe1 Bh4 {, and the game continues.}) 19... Bf6 20. Qxd6+ Kxd6 21. c3 a4 22. Kc2 Kd7 {It's time to go after the f4 -pawn.} 23. Rg1 Be7 {Probably it was better to keep the bishop on f6 and start improving the rook first, but Igor 'calculated' and provoked White to a forced line.} (23... Rh4 $5) 24. f5 {White opens the position for his two bishops.} exf5 25. gxf5 g5 26. Bxd5 {Simplifications are incoming.} cxd5 27. Bxg5 Rxh3 28. Bxe7 Kxe7 29. Rxg7 a3 {When Igor saw this resource from afar in many versions, he realized that White doesn't have even the slightest chance to exploit Black's weaknesses.} 30. Rg2 (30. b3 Rc8 31. Rd3 Rh2+ 32. Rd2 Rh3 {, with a draw.}) 30... axb2 31. Kxb2 b4 32. cxb4 Ra4 {When Igor played Be7 , he calculated until this moment and calmed down – after all, he was forcing a draw against an opponent he had lost many times before.} 33. Kb1 Rxb4+ 34. Rb2 Ra4 {Even if White is up a pawn, Black is too active to hold this position without any problems.} 35. Rb6 Rf3 36. Re1+ Kd7 37. Rb7+ Kc6 38. Rxf7 Rxd4 39. Re6+ Kb5 40. Rb7+ Kc5 {Draw was agreed.} *

