1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {Again, the Gubinsky–Melts Defense or simply the 3...Qd6 Scandinavian.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 Nbd7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Be3 c6 11. Qf3 Nb6 12. O-O-O Nbd5 13. Bd2 e6 14. Ne2 a5 15. Kb1 b5 {Even if this game is not of the highest quality it's a blitz game after all, Black carried out many Scandinavian ideas.} 16. Ng3 a4 17. a3 Qb8 {Black opens the path for the bishop and is threatening with ... b4 .} 18. c3 Bd6 19. Bd3 Bf4 {Black wants to trade the bishops to control the weakness on f4 .} 20. Be1 g5 {Black fixes the outpost on f4 .} 21. Ne2 Qc7 22. Bc2 O-O-O {This was when Black could have safely centered the king,} (22... Kd7 $1 {, and connected the rooks.}) 23. Nxf4 Qxf4 24. Qe2 Qc7 25. c4 {White correctly senses that he should open the queenside.} Nf4 26. Qf1 Qb6 27. Bb4 ({For a blitz game, the move} 27. Bd2 $1 {is pretty difficult to pick up.} bxc4 28. Bxf4 gxf4 29. Qxc4 Qb5 30. Qxa4 Qxa4 31. Bxa4 Kc7 {, and Black has a compensation for the lost pawn.}) 27... bxc4 28. Qxc4 Qb5 {Now Black is slightly better – the knights dominate the bishops.} 29. Qa2 Kb7 30. Ka1 N6d5 31. Bc5 Nxh3 {It's time to pick up some material.} 32. Bd3 Qa5 33. b4 axb3 34. Qxb3+ Kc7 35. Rb1 Rb8 {White's attack meets a dead end.} 36. Qc2 Nhf4 37. Rxh8 Rxh8 38. Bc4 Rh3 {Unexpected counter-attack!} 39. Rb3 Rxb3 40. Bxb3 Qe1+ 41. Kb2 Qxf2 {Nice trick – Black picks up another pawn. The rest is a technique.} 42. Qxf2 Nd3+ 43. Kc2 Nxf2 44. Bf8 g6 45. a4 Nxg4 46. a5 Kb7 47. Kd2 f5 48. Bc4 Nge3 49. a6+ Ka8 50. Be2 g4 51. Bd6 f4 52. Bxf4 Nxf4 53. Kxe3 Nxe2 {An impressive victory by Kovalenko, considering that these were essentially the prime years of Grischuk, the three-time World blitz champion.} *

