1. e4 d5 {The final model game from Igor Kovalenko that he played against 5-time USA Champion Gata Kamsky, albeit it was an online rapid game. It illustrates a few more interesting Scandinavian ideas.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Nge2 {Kamsky was trying to play a system that delays the d-pawn push, which can be tricky to meet. We discuss this in Chapter 12 .} Bg4 ({Too ambitious – in the course, we're recommending} 5... Bf5 {, being more cautious of White's ideas.}) 6. h3 Bh5 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 Nc6 {If White is not playing d4 himself, you don't have to resort to the slightly passive ... c6 .} 9. d3 O-O-O 10. Bd2 Bxe2 {White was bothering the black queen; thus, it's time to seek a retreat.} 11. Nxe2 Qh5 {This queen lift is very common.} 12. b4 Bd6 {Objectively, not a good move, but Black would work out the details in a classical game.} (12... Qh4 {. It was important to stop White from playing f4 , which squeezes Black. If White now does it, Black is happy to trade off the queens for a nice middlegame.} 13. a3 Bd6 14. f4 Qxe1 15. Raxe1 a5 {, and Black is solid and also has the counterplay.}) 13. b5 {White doesn't feel the danger.} (13. f4 $1 {, and White would have a solid avantage.}) 13... Ne5 14. Bb3 {Probably, Kamsky thought that Black's initiative was leading nowhere and that White's f4 was unstoppable. Well...} Nf3+ {Apparently, White was wrong.} 15. gxf3 Qxh3 16. Bf4 Nh5 ({Also} 16... e5 {is very strong.}) 17. Bg3 g5 {Suddenly, White can't stop the ... Nf4 threat and the opening of the g-file. Kamsky resigned!} *

[Event "?"]
