[White "� Model Games"]
[Black "Efim Geller – Vasilios Kotronias, Athens 1988"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B01"]
[PlyCount "60"]
[GameId "2174210256843985"]

1. e4 d5 {With this game we'd like to illustrate that often Black can ignore White's centered knight on e5 .} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd2 c6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. O-O {This is not the best continuation against the Scandinavian, but again, it was played in 1988 when the theory looked different.} Qc7 9. Qe2 e6 10. Ne5 Bd6 {Black can ignore the white knight on e5 !} (10... Nxe5 $6 {is not a forced choice.} 11. dxe5 Nd5 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 {. This is what White wants.}) 11. Rfe1 {The famous Soviet chess legend Efim Geller decided not to touch the f-pawn.} (11. f4 O-O 12. Bb3 a6 {. Black will push ... c5 next. If White plays g4 , there's the ... Bxe5 intermezzo move. White's center suddenly becomes very shaky.} 13. g4 Bxe5 14. fxe5 Nxg4 15. h3 Nh6 16. Bxh6 gxh6 {. This is the best that White can do – the black king feels quite safe.} 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Kh8 19. Kh1 c5 20. c3 Rae8 21. Rae1 f6 {. The position is balanced.}) 11... O-O 12. g4 {Geller sensed that the opening had taken the wrong turn and tried to be aggressive.} (12. Bf4 Bxe5 {. Now it's a good moment to clarify the situation in the center.} 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Bd3 Bxd3 16. cxd3 Rac8 {. White has good odds of landing in an endgame where he has the bad bishop vs a good knight. White's kingside attack chances are not very real.}) 12... Bxe5 13. gxf5 Bxh2+ 14. Kg2 exf5 15. Qf3 {White deliberately did this, hoping the initiative would compensate the two missing pawns.} g6 16. Rh1 Bd6 17. Rh4 Rfe8 18. Rah1 Nf8 {But as it turns out, White has no real initiative here but the extra pawns stay.} 19. Bg5 Be7 20. Bf4 Qd8 21. Be5 Bd6 {Black liquidates one of White's strongest attacking pieces.} 22. Qf4 Bxe5 23. dxe5 Nd5 24. Qh2 Qg5+ (24... h5 $1 {. After this logical move, White's initiative meets an abrupt end.} 25. Bxd5 cxd5 26. Rxh5 gxh5 27. Qxh5 Ng6 {. There's no mate.}) 25. Kf1 {The game abruptly finishes right here, but Black still keeps an advantage.} f4 26. Rxh7 Qxe5 27. Rh8+ Kg7 28. Qh6+ Kf6 29. Rg8 Qg5 30. Qh8+ Ke6 {It looks a little scary, but White has no decent follow-up. Also, White's king is quite vulnerable.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
