[White "� Model Games"]
[Black "Garry Kasparov – Viswanathan Anand, New York 1995"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B01"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[GameId "2174210256843986"]

1. e4 d5 {The Scandinavian Defense is a rare occurrence in World championship matches, and yet it was a surprise choice by Vishy Anand against Garry Kasparov in his prime!} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Ne5 {Probably surprised by the opening choice, Kasparov played a sideline, attempting to avoid Bc4 , but Anand also showed good prep here.} Be6 {This is discussed in detail in Chapter 8 .} 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. f4 {Otherwise, White's approach makes no sense if he's fighting for privileges.} g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Kh1 {It's not the most accurate choice.} (10. Qe1 {is stronger, meeting Black's ... c5 with the powerful d5 , as analyzed in Chapter 8 .}) 10... Bf5 {Probably already out of prep, Anand missed a better opportunity.} (10... c5 $1 {is the key idea, which works immediately.} 11. f5 {. Anything else feels not threatening. Maybe this is what Anand didn't like or could not evaluate the arising consequences.} gxf5 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. d5 {. White has a compensation for the pawn, but not more than that.} e6 14. Bg5 O-O {. Black can also castle long and make things even more interesting.} 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Bxf5 {. Due to this small trick, White wins back the sacrificed pawn.} exf5 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. Qxd7 Rf7 {. Black has a weak pawn on f5 but a stronger bishop.} 19. Qd5 Rd8 20. Qf3 Qb4 {, with a balanced position.}) 11. Bc4 (11. Bxf5 {. This promised White a slightly better position in the middlegame.} gxf5 12. Bd2 Qb6 13. Be1 Rd8 14. Qd3 e6 15. Rd1 {. White is slightly better, but you can understand Kasparov's hesitation – the e4 square is pretty weak.}) 11... e6 12. Be2 h5 {As it turned out, White's h3 - g4 plan is never really working; thus, Black kept an amazing bishop on f5 .} 13. Be3 Rd8 14. Bg1 O-O {The verdict of the opening – due to the control of the central light squares, Black is slightly better! In the Scandinavian Defense! In a world championship match!} 15. Bf3 Nd5 (15... c5 $1 {. For some reason, Anand did not want to execute this logical plan – tactics work in his favor.} 16. Bxb7 $2 Nxe5 17. fxe5 {, and White's center collapses,} Ng4 {.}) 16. Nxd5 {Clearly damage control – by now Kasparov was already aware that the opening has gone wrong.} exd5 17. Bf2 Qc7 {The start of rerouting the knight to e4 .} 18. Rc1 f6 19. Nd3 Rfe8 {Black controls the e4 square while keeping tabs on the e5 square – White is worse.} 20. b3 Nb6 21. a4 Nc8 22. c4 Qf7 23. a5 Bf8 {While White was looking for some activity on the queenside, Black continued improving the pieces.} 24. cxd5 cxd5 25. Bh4 Nd6 {Perhaps too straightforward – it suddenly gave Kasparov a chance to complicate the matters.} (25... Rd7 26. a6 b6 27. Rc6 Nd6 {. This would make White's life quite miserable – the Ne5 trick no longer works and White would have to go on the defensive.}) 26. a6 b6 27. Ne5 {Maybe Anand miscalculated the line, which is a little strange since White's position positionally is so miserable that Ne5 is the only try.} Qe6 (27... fxe5 28. fxe5 Ne4 29. Bxd8 Rxd8 30. g4 {. Perhaps the move that Anand missed.} hxg4 31. Bxg4 {. Suddenly, White is very much in the game.} Bxg4 32. Qxg4 Nf2+ 33. Rxf2 Qxf2 34. Qxg6+ Bg7 35. Rc7 Qf1+ 36. Qg1 {. Due to the active white rook on the 7th rank and the weak a-pawn, Black can't trade the queens without risking losing.}) 28. g4 {Kasparov kept trying.} hxg4 29. Nxg4 Bg7 30. Rc7 {By now, it was quite apparent that the e4 square may not be so relevant anymore because White is very active.} Ne4 {The game slips from Anand's hands.} (30... Rc8 $1 31. Rxa7 Ne4 {would have kept the game very double-edged.}) 31. Ne3 Bh3 32. Rg1 {Suddenly, White had a serious initiative.} g5 33. Bg4 Bxg4 34. Qxg4 Qxg4 35. Rxg4 Nd6 36. Bf2 Nb5 37. Rb7 {White is better, but Black is still holding.} Re4 {It's hard to believe such an active move can be a critical mistake!} (37... Nd6 38. Rxa7 Ra8 {was the only way for Black to stay alive.} 39. Rd7 Ne4 40. Bg1 Rxa6 41. fxg5 fxg5 42. Nxd5 Ra1 {. White has a healthy extra pawn, but Black has activity and should not be lost.}) 38. f5 Rxg4 39. Nxg4 {After the smoke has cleared, White's pieces are just dominating.} Rc8 40. Rd7 Rc2 41. Rxd5 {Anand resigned.} *

