1. e4 d5 {Sergei Tiviakov is a very strong grandmaster who has been playing the Scandinavian Defense regularly. We chose this game because it illustrates some of Black's typical plans in a quiet positional game.} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 c6 6. Bd2 Qb6 {A typical grandmaster bluff! This is not the main move, but Black hints at intending to capture a pawn. The idea is worth knowing, especially if White reacts to it in the wrong way. The idea is worth knowing, especially if White reacts to it the wrong way.} (6... Bf5 {is our recommendation in Chapter 10 .}) 7. Bc1 {White immediately reacts and thus rewards Black for the chosen strategy. Remember – single pawns should not be ranked higher than the integrity of the entire position.} (7. Nf3 {. White should have called Black's bluff.} Qxb2 $2 {. It's not worth it to take such pawn, since Black loses a lot of valuable time.} ({(Then again, if Black played ... Qb6 and is not ready to take on b2 , it's not worth losing time for ... Qb6 . Most likely, Tiviakov would not dare to take it and would have continued in a worse position after} 7... Bf5 {. )}) 8. Rb1 Qa3 9. Ng5 e6 10. O-O {. Check this sample line how White easily develops an initiative. Engine says that White is already winning in all lines.} Be7 11. Re1 Qd6 {. It seems that Black is safe, will regroup, and then somehow capitalize on the extra pawn, but ...chess doesn't work like that.} 12. Nce4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qd8 14. Qh5 O-O 15. Rb3 {, with a killing attack.}) 7... Bf5 {Now Black resumes a normal development where White has wasted one tempo more on Bd2 - c1 than Black for ... Qb6 .} 8. Nf3 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Bb3 Nbd7 11. Bf4 O-O {All of this is pretty standard.} 12. Qe2 Bg4 {A maneuver worth knowing – Black creates another pin and once again presses on White's fear to lose a pawn, this time on d4 .} (12... h6 {was worth considering, preserving the strong light-squared bishop.}) 13. Rad1 Rfe8 14. h3 Bh5 15. Ne4 (15. g4 Bg6 16. Nh4 {was already necessary for White, but it would create multiple weaknesses in White's camp.} Nd5 {, and Black has a great Scandinavian position.}) 15... Nxe4 16. Qxe4 a5 17. a4 Rad8 (17... c5 {. Since White has this unpleasant pin on the d1 - h5 diagonal, this looked as an interesting option.}) 18. Qe3 Nf6 {Since White is not ready to play g4 , Black increases pressure with simple moves.} 19. Be5 Nd5 20. Qe4 Bf6 21. Rd2 {Finally, White has walked away from the pin by not playing g4 , but White's problems now escalate from mild to annoying.} Qb4 22. g4 {Only now White realizes that there's no way to play this position without pushing g4 but this already cost White a lot of time.} Bg6 23. Qe2 Bxe5 {That's a weakness to exploit on f4 .} 24. Nxe5 c5 {The maneuver is great but the timing is a little wrong.} (24... f6 25. Nxg6 hxg6 {, Black will anchor the knight on f4 and strengthen it with ... g5 . If White takes on d5 , this will cost him the b2 -pawn.}) 25. Rfd1 cxd4 26. Qc4 {Tiviakov may have missed this move and relied too much on the fork trick.} (26. Rxd4 $4 Nf4 {, with a following fork on e2 .}) 26... Rc8 27. Qxb4 Nxb4 28. Nxg6 hxg6 29. Rxd4 {Now the position is balanced again, and Tiviakov starts from scratch.} Na6 {A typical grandmaster move – keeping the position as unbalanced as possible, even in a knight vs. bishop scenario.} 30. c3 g5 {Nice move, fixing the f4 -square for the future.} 31. Kg2 Nc5 32. Bc2 Kf8 33. Kf3 Ke7 34. Ke3 Rc7 (34... Rh8 $1 {was very logical and strong.} 35. b4 Rxh3+ 36. f3 Na6 $1 {. Maybe Black did not believe that he can allow the check on d7 .} 37. Rd7+ Kf6 {, and Black is winning.}) 35. f4 gxf4+ 36. Kxf4 Rh8 {Now Black goes for the aforementioned idea.} 37. Rh1 Nd7 38. Kg3 Ne5 39. Be4 g5 {Black has another g-pawn to fix the f4 -square for the knight!} 40. h4 {Under pressure and possibly in a time scramble, White makes a big mistake – he should have refrained from making big decisions and sit tight.} gxh4+ 41. Rxh4 Rxh4 42. Kxh4 Nc4 43. b3 Nd6 {Suddenly, White's queen pawn structure deteriorates.} 44. c4 Rd7 {White can't parry White's both threats.} 45. Kh3 Nxe4 46. Rxe4 Rd3+ 47. Kh4 Rxb3 {Most likely, White is already dead lost.} 48. Re5 b6 49. c5 bxc5 50. Rxc5 Rb4 {The only way to win but it's enough.} 51. Rxa5 f5 52. Kg3 Rxg4+ 53. Kf3 Kf6 {This is technically winning.} 54. Ra6 Re4 55. Kg3 Re3+ 56. Kf2 f4 57. Ra5 Ra3 58. Ra6 Kf5 59. a5 e5 60. Ra8 Ra2+ 61. Kf1 Ke4 62. a6 Kf3 63. Kg1 e4 {White resigned.} *

